const RAW = [{"id":"botswana","n":"Botswana","f":"🇧🇼","co":"Africa","qt":["Left-hand traffic + flat dry landscape + no distinctive Google car = narrow it to the Southern Africa cluster (SA, Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini)","Black and yellow striped sign poles — some but not all signs use this, near-unique to Botswana","Green highway signs with white text and yellow highway numbers — road prefix is A (A1, A2 etc.)","High quality, well-maintained roads on main routes — unusually good for the region","Flat, dry, monotone landscape everywhere — less diverse than South Africa"],"ls":"English is the official language, Setswana widely spoken. All road signage in English. No distinctive script tells — split from South Africa by other clues, not language.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Green highway signs with yellow numbers, A prefix (e.g. A1 — the main highway through the country)","Black and yellow striped sign poles on some signs — a Botswana-specific tell not seen in neighbouring countries","Red and white chevrons on roadsides — shared with South Africa but much less frequent in Botswana","Road quality is notably high for Sub-Saharan Africa — main roads are smooth and wide","Yellow outer road lines + white centre lines — same as the whole Southern Africa cluster"],"landb":["Flat and dry throughout — this is the single biggest landscape tell. Botswana is essentially the Kalahari desert and savanna. No mountains, no lush hills, no dramatic terrain.","Brown/tan soil, sparse dry scrubby vegetation, low acacia bushes","Very open, wide horizons","Completely unlike Lesotho (mountains), Eswatini (green hills), or most of South Africa (diverse)","Occasional wildlife reserve coverage — flat bush with game fencing"],"car":"Standard Gen 3 coverage. No distinctive car meta. Coverage mainly along the main A-road network through the country and some towns. Less coverage than South Africa overall.","mu":[{"c":"South Africa","k":"biggest confusion. Both left-hand, both English, both green highway signs with yellow numbers. Splits: SA signs use N/R/M prefix, Botswana uses A prefix. SA has red/white chevrons far more commonly. SA has Gen 2 camera (halo in sky); Botswana is Gen 3 (clear sky). SA landscape is diverse; Botswana is flat and dry everywhere."},{"c":"Lesotho","k":"also Southern Africa cluster but completely different: bare rocky tabletop mountains, round thatched huts, Basotho blankets — impossible to confuse on landscape"},{"c":"Eswatini","k":"also Southern Africa but green, hilly, forested. MR road prefix."},{"c":"Namibia","k":"similar flat dry landscape but right-hand traffic, German language on signs, different road system entirely"}],"ex":["The A prefix + green signs + flat dry landscape + Gen 3 camera + no chevrons combo is the cleanest Botswana confirm","Botswana is one of the wealthiest countries in Sub-Saharan Africa (diamonds) — road quality reflects this","If you see the halo in the sky (Gen 2), it's South Africa not Botswana","Wildlife/game reserve fencing is common along roads — adds to the flat bush feel"]},{"id":"egypt","n":"Egypt","f":"🇪🇬","co":"Africa","qt":["Arabic script only — no French, no English on official signs. Pure Arabic everywhere, no bilingual text","Desert landscape — sandy, dry, barren. Either open desert, Nile Valley farmland, or dense urban Cairo/Alexandria","Coverage is extremely limited — almost entirely Cairo, Alexandria, and the Nile Valley corridor. If you're in Egypt you're almost certainly in or near a city","White license plates with Arabic numerals and Latin letters mixed, standard Arabic-world format","Right-hand traffic throughout"],"ls":"Arabic only on all official signage — no French (unlike Tunisia/Morocco), no English (unlike Jordan/Qatar). This pure Arabic-only signage is the strongest Egypt tell vs other Arabic countries. Arabic is recognisable by its calligraphic style with connected letters and horizontal baseline strokes.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Signs in Arabic only — directional signs typically green with white Arabic text","Road quality varies hugely: Cairo highways are well-developed, rural/desert roads can be basic","Coverage almost entirely urban — Cairo, Alexandria, Luxor, Aswan, Sharm El-Sheikh area","Wide, multi-lane roads in Cairo — chaotic dense urban traffic"],"landb":["Desert or Nile Valley — those are essentially your two options in Egypt coverage","Cairo: extremely dense, chaotic urban environment, yellow/beige sandstone buildings, dust everywhere","Nile Valley: green strip of farmland flanking the Nile cutting through desert, palm trees, flat irrigated fields","Pure desert: sandy/rocky with almost no vegetation","Mediterranean coast near Alexandria: slightly greener, sea visible","Architecture is beige/tan/sandstone coloured everywhere — low-rise dense blocks"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Coverage is limited — if you drop in Egypt at all it will almost certainly be Cairo or another city. Rural and desert coverage is minimal. The sheer urban density of Cairo and its distinctive yellow-beige cityscape is enough to confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Tunisia","k":"also North Africa, but Tunisia has French alongside Arabic, black license plates, and a much more Mediterranean coastal feel. Egypt = Arabic only."},{"c":"Morocco","k":"also Arabic + French bilingual. Egypt = Arabic only, no French at all."},{"c":"Jordan","k":"also Arabic only, but Jordan has bilingual Arabic/English on many signs, blue directional signs, different architecture (whiter stone buildings, more orderly)"},{"c":"Saudi Arabia","k":"similar Arabic-only signs, but Saudi plates are different and coverage is extremely limited"},{"c":"Libya/Algeria","k":"almost no GeoGuessr coverage so you won't confuse them in practice"}],"ex":["Cairo is one of the most recognisable cities in the world — once you know it, you'll never mistake it. Insane density, yellow dusty haze, Arabic signage everywhere, multi-lane chaos","The Nile farmland strip feels completely different from the desert — lush green in contrast to the surrounding beige sand","Egypt's coverage is so limited that landing there is relatively rare on the World map","Arabic numerals on plates (Eastern Arabic ١٢٣ not Western 123) — though this is hard to read through blur","No bollard meta — bollards not common enough to be useful"]},{"id":"ghana","n":"Ghana","f":"🇬🇭","co":"Africa","qt":["Black duct tape on the front-right bar of the roof rack — the single most famous Ghana tell, 100% confidence identifier, easiest way to split from Nigeria","White license plates with black text (standard plates); yellow plates on commercial vehicles — very common","English language on all official signs","Right-hand traffic","Lush tropical green landscape — similar to Nigeria's south but generally less dense urban sprawl"],"ls":"English is the official language throughout. Twi, Ga, Ewe and other local languages on informal signage but all road infrastructure is English. No French, no Swahili. English + West Africa + black tape roof rack = Ghana with very high confidence.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road quality decent on main roads, rough on rural tracks","Standard English road signage, similar conventions to Nigeria and UK","Coverage is mainly along main roads and cities — Accra, Kumasi, Cape Coast"],"landb":["Tropical green vegetation — lush, humid, palm trees common","Coastal areas near Accra have beaches and Atlantic ocean views","Central/northern Ghana gets progressively drier and more savanna-like","Red/orange laterite soil in many areas — similar to Nigeria","General West African feel — corrugated metal roofs, roadside markets, compound architecture","Less urban density than Lagos in Nigeria"],"car":"Roof rack with a distinctive piece of black duct tape on the right end of the front bar — this is the defining Ghana meta. Visible when you pan down. It is described as being on the \"front right bar\" of the roof rack. This single clue distinguishes Ghana from every other African country. No police follow-car (unlike Nigeria). No snorkel (unlike Kenya). Just the black tape. Commercial vehicles with yellow license plates are very common and easy to spot even through blur — this backs up the black tape tell.","mu":[{"c":"Nigeria","k":"most similar country in GeoGuessr. Both English, both right-hand, both West Africa, both tropical. The black tape on the roof rack is THE split. Nigeria has pickup truck + police car; Ghana has the tape. Nigeria plates have greenish tinge; Ghana plates are white (or yellow for commercial)."},{"c":"Senegal","k":"French language (immediate split from Ghana's English)"},{"c":"Côte d'Ivoire","k":"French language, minimal coverage"},{"c":"Kenya/Uganda","k":"East Africa, completely different landscape and car metas"}],"ex":["The black tape is so reliable that many players consider Ghana one of the easiest African countries to identify — if you see the tape, commit immediately","Yellow commercial vehicle plates are very common and visible — a good supporting tell when the car is visible","Accra coverage is the most common — dense, urban, coastal West African city feel","Older plates can be black with white lettering — less common but worth knowing","Ghana and Nigeria are the two main English-speaking West African countries in GeoGuessr — learning to split them by car meta is essential"]},{"id":"kenya","n":"Kenya","f":"🇰🇪","co":"Africa","qt":["Snorkel on the front-right of the Google car — the single most famous Africa car meta. 100% confidence if you see it. Installed for river crossings during rural coverage.","Left-hand traffic — rules out Tanzania, Nigeria, Ghana immediately","Yellow square rear license plates + long white front plates — very distinctive combo","Red/orange laterite soil — vivid red soil, shared with Uganda but Kenya has the snorkel car","Swahili + English on signs — MTN/Safaricom/Airtel branding everywhere"],"ls":"English and Swahili both appear on official signs. Latin script throughout. Key Swahili words: barabara (road), hospitali, shule (school), polisi (police). Safaricom (green branding) is Kenya's dominant telecom and appears constantly on buildings and signs — a strong Kenya-specific tell. MTN also present but Safaricom is the clincher.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Road quality is mixed — Nairobi and main highways are decent, rural roads can be rough or unpaved","Road numbers: A roads (national trunk roads), B roads (secondary), C roads (minor)","Standard English/Swahili road signage","Rumble strips are very common on Kenyan roads — raised strips across the road to slow traffic, a consistent Kenya tell","Coverage is densest in the southern half and northwest of the country"],"landb":["Classic East African savanna — flat-topped acacia trees, dry grassland, big sky","Red/orange laterite soil — very vivid, one of the richer reds in Africa","Coastal Kenya (Mombasa area): tropical, palm trees, Indian Ocean, Swahili architecture","Nairobi: modern city, green and hilly for a capital","Northern Kenya: arid, semi-desert, increasingly dry and harsh","Rift Valley: dramatic escarpments and flat valley floors","Flat-topped acacia + red soil + left-hand + snorkel = Kenya with near certainty"],"car":"Two distinct car types:","carb":["Older coverage: black SUV/car with a large black snorkel on the front-right fender — the most iconic Google car meta in the world. Installed for river crossings in rural Kenya.","New coverage (since 2022): different pickup truck — can appear with snorkel, with antenna, with both, or with neither. Less reliable than the old coverage.","If you see the classic big snorkel = old Kenya coverage, 100% confidence","New coverage without snorkel: rely on plates, language, landscape, and rumble strips"],"mu":[{"c":"Tanzania","k":"also East Africa, also Swahili, but Tanzania is right-hand traffic (immediate split). Tanzania has no snorkel car."},{"c":"Uganda","k":"also left-hand, also red soil, also English. Key splits: Uganda has boxy white SUV car, no snorkel. Uganda soil is even more intensely red. Uganda coverage is much more limited (Kampala + national parks only)."},{"c":"Ethiopia","k":"right-hand, Amharic script (completely different), no snorkel"},{"c":"Rwanda","k":"left-hand, but completely different car (small distinct Rwandan car), black-and-white painted curbs, much denser/hillier landscape"}],"ex":["Safaricom green branding on shops and buildings is a Kenya-exclusive telecom tell — strongest commercial clue in East Africa","Yellow square rear plates are very recognisable even at blur distance — memorise the shape","Rumble strips across the road are extremely common and a useful Kenya sub-tell","Most coverage is in the southern half — if you're in sparse northern Kenya terrain it's rarer","The snorkel is so reliable that competitive players often commit to Kenya the instant they see it — don't overthink it"]},{"id":"lesotho","n":"Lesotho","f":"🇱🇸","co":"Africa","qt":["Bare, treeless tabletop mountains with horizontal rocky ridgelines — the single most iconic Lesotho landscape tell. Unique in southern Africa.","Round thatched-roof rondavel huts scattered on hillsides — very consistent cultural tell","People wearing Basotho blankets — traditional colourful wool blankets worn as cloaks, visible on roadside locals year-round","Left-hand traffic + Southern Africa cluster (no halo = not SA)","Green highway signs with white text, A prefix road numbers — Lesotho shares A prefix with Botswana but landscape makes them unmistakable"],"ls":"English and Sesotho are both official. Road signs in English. The word \"Lesotho\" itself appears on signs and gives it away immediately if readable. No distinctive script — split is purely visual/landscape.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Green highway signs with white text and yellow road numbers — A prefix (shared with Botswana, but landscape is totally different)","Road quality is mixed — main roads reasonable, mountain passes can be rough","Yellow outer lines + white centre lines — standard Southern Africa cluster","Many signs simply show no letter prefix at all — if you see Southern Africa style green signs without a clear N/R/MR prefix, lean Lesotho"],"landb":["Entirely mountainous — Lesotho is the highest country in the world (entire country above 1,400m). Every drop is in mountains.","Mountains are bare, treeless and grassy with short grass — not lush green like Eswatini, not rocky desert like elsewhere. A distinctive bleached/golden-brown grass colour.","Tabletop and flat-topped shapes with clear horizontal rock strata lines — very distinctive and unlike any other Southern African mountain","Round stone rondavel huts on hillsides are everywhere","Wide open mountain valleys, dramatic escarpments, no forest coverage","Sky is typically big and blue with dramatic cloud formations at altitude"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Coverage is limited — mainly along the main A1 highway corridor and some towns. Very mountainous terrain means many areas have no coverage.","mu":[{"c":"South Africa","k":"most likely confusion but SA has Gen 2 camera (halo), diverse landscapes, N/R prefix signs. If you see bare tabletop mountains + left-hand + no halo, it's Lesotho."},{"c":"Eswatini","k":"also Southern Africa cluster but completely different: green, forested, hilly not mountainous, MR prefix"},{"c":"Botswana","k":"also A prefix signs but flat and dry everywhere — impossible to confuse on landscape"},{"c":"Eastern South Africa highlands (Drakensberg)","k":"can look similar from a distance but you can't be dropped in Drakensberg from the Lesotho side — if you're inside those mountains it's Lesotho"}],"ex":["Lesotho is completely landlocked inside South Africa — every single drop is in a mountainous landlocked country surrounded by SA","The Basotho blanket is one of the most culturally specific tells in all of GeoGuessr — seeing someone in a colourful blanket-cloak = commit to Lesotho","Short grass + tabletop mountain + rondavel huts = Lesotho, no need for more clues","Highest country in the world — altitude visible in landscape feel, thin air, dramatic skies"]},{"id":"madagascar","n":"Madagascar","f":"🇲🇬","co":"Africa","qt":["Boat coverage — you can be dropped on a boat on the ocean around Madagascar's islands. One of the most unique coverage types in GeoGuessr. If you're on a boat = Madagascar.","Ox/zebu cart coverage — one specific stretch of road inland from Andavadoaka on the west coast was captured from an ox cart. Completely unique in GeoGuessr.","Trekker (walking) coverage — common in the middle of the country and in Antananarivo. You can see the person walking with the camera, city visible below in Tana.","French + Malagasy bilingual signs — French infrastructure inherited from colonial era, plus local Malagasy text","Baobab trees on the west coast near Morondava — iconic \"Avenue of the Baobabs\" area"],"ls":"French and Malagasy both appear on signs. French infrastructure conventions (sign styles, road markings). Malagasy uses Latin script with long compound words. Phone numbers: landlines start 020, mobiles start 032/033/034, format XXX XX XXX XX.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French-inherited road sign conventions and styles","Road numbers use RN prefix (Route Nationale) — e.g. RN8 on the west coast","Road quality very variable — main RN roads paved, most other roads unpaved dirt","White road lines where present on main island","Cobblestone roads are memorable and appear in some areas"],"landb":["Tropical island feel — lush green highland interior, dry west coast, tropical east coast","Baobab trees on the west coast (near Morondava) — iconic and unique to this specific area","Red laterite soil very common — similar vivid red to Uganda/Kenya but island context","Coastal coverage: Indian Ocean, white sand beaches, tropical vegetation","Antananarivo (capital): dense hillside city with rice paddies in valleys","Unique biodiversity — lemurs, endemic plants visible occasionally"],"car":"Madagascar has the most diverse coverage types of any country in GeoGuessr: If you're on a boat or an ox cart you're in Madagascar, full stop.","carb":["Standard Gen 3 car: main road coverage on RN roads","Trekker (person walking): towns in the middle of the country + elevated walkways in Antananarivo","Boat coverage: around islands including Nosy Ambariovato in the north and off the west coast — you are literally on a boat on the ocean","Ox cart coverage: one specific stretch inland from Andavadoaka on RN8 — the cart and ox are visible","Beach trekker: small parts of the east coast beach"],"mu":[{"c":"Mozambique","k":"also French-influenced, also east African coast, also red soil. But Mozambique has Portuguese (not French), right-hand traffic, standard car coverage"},{"c":"Senegal","k":"also French, but completely different landscape (Sahel/West Africa vs. tropical island)"},{"c":"Réunion","k":"also French, Indian Ocean island, but Réunion has a very European feel, much more developed infrastructure, different car meta"},{"c":"Comoros","k":"also Indian Ocean, French, but minimal coverage"}],"ex":["The boat coverage is probably the most disorienting drop in all of GeoGuessr — you're literally at sea","Knowing the specific trekker locations in Antananarivo helps a lot for the World map","The ox cart road is one of the most famous ultra-niche meta locations in the game","If you see red soil + French signs + island/tropical + unusual coverage type = Madagascar","Coverage is scattered and very limited outside specific corridors — landing in Madagascar at all is relatively rare"]},{"id":"mali","n":"Mali","f":"🇲🇱","co":"Africa","qt":["Coverage is extremely limited — only a couple of trekker locations exist. Mali is essentially unmappable in normal GeoGuessr play.","Memorise the specific locations rather than general tells — this is genuinely the best strategy for Mali","French language on signs — francophone West Africa","Sahel/semi-arid landscape — flat, dry, sandy, sparse scrubby trees. Not tropical like southern West Africa.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"French is the official language. Bambara and other local languages on informal signs. All road infrastructure in French. Arabic script may appear on mosque signs given Mali's predominantly Muslim population.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French-style road signage conventions","Road quality poor — dusty, sandy, often unpaved","Very few road markings outside Bamako"],"landb":["Sahel landscape — flat, dry, sandy semi-desert with sparse acacia trees and scrubby bushes","Dusty sandy soil, brown/tan colours","Mud-brick Sudanese architecture — distinctive flat-roofed adobe buildings, common in West African Sahel","Niger River visible in some coverage areas near Bamako/Mopti","Feels dry, hot, and dusty — completely different from lush coastal West Africa"],"car":"Mali has almost no coverage — this is the critical thing to know. GeoTips explicitly states: \"There is VERY limited coverage in Mali, done by a couple of trekkers. It is probably easier to memorize the trekkers and where they exist.\" Known coverage locations: If you're dropped in what looks like Mali, you're almost certainly at one of these two locations. The Grand Mosque at Niono is architecturally distinctive — large Sudanese-style mud mosque with protruding wooden poles (torons).","carb":["Bamako area — note: some of this coverage is reportedly misplaced and doesn't actually exist in Bamako","Niono Grand Mosque — trekker coverage walking around the outside of the mosque and nearby streets"],"mu":[{"c":"Senegal","k":"also French, also West Africa, but Senegal has much more coverage and a more coastal/greener feel near Dakar. Senegal has the distinctive car metas (roof rack / silver truck)."},{"c":"Burkina Faso","k":"also French, also Sahel, also very limited coverage"},{"c":"Niger","k":"also French, also Sahel, almost no coverage"}],"ex":["The Niono Grand Mosque is one of the most visually distinctive locations in all of Africa in GeoGuessr — large mud-brick Sudanese mosque style with wooden poles sticking out of the walls (torons). If you see this architecture, it's Mali.","Sudanese mud-brick mosque architecture is a strong West African Sahel tell generally","For World map play, Mali is rare enough that most players never see it. When you do, the mosque or Bamako streetscape is your anchor.","French + Sahel + mud architecture + trekker coverage = Mali"]},{"id":"namibia","n":"Namibia","f":"🇳🇦","co":"Africa","qt":["Massive red/orange desert dunes — Namib Desert dunes are some of the tallest in the world, instantly recognisable vivid red-orange colour","German language on street signs and building names — legacy of German colonial rule, completely unique in Africa","Right-hand traffic — rules out South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho cluster immediately","Extremely sparse, open landscape — one of the least densely populated countries on Earth, wide empty roads, almost no traffic","New coverage since early 2025 — Gen 4, crisp and sharp imagery"],"ls":"English is the official language on road signs. But German appears constantly on street names, shop names, and building names — especially in Swakopmund and Lüderitz. Seeing German street names in an African context = Namibia. Afrikaans also appears. This is the only African country with significant German linguistic heritage visible on signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Standard English road signage for official signs","German street names in coastal towns — \"Kaiser-Wilhelm-Strasse\", \"Bismarckstrasse\" etc.","Roads are often wide, well-paved on main routes but surrounded by vast emptiness","Gravel roads common outside main highways","Coverage includes Windhoek (capital), Swakopmund, Lüderitz, key highways, and some desert/national park roads"],"landb":["Namib Desert coast: flat, ancient, foggy Atlantic coast with enormous red-orange dunes inland — unlike any other African landscape","Swakopmund/Lüderitz: German colonial architecture — European-style buildings in the middle of a desert. Completely surreal and unique in Africa.","Windhoek: modern city, hilly, mix of African and European-style buildings","Interior: rocky mountains (Great Escarpment), dry savanna, red gravel plains","Skeleton Coast: eerie fog, shipwrecks, whale bones, barren Atlantic coastline","Sossusvlei area: iconic massive orange dunes, dead white trees in salt pans","One of the driest countries in sub-Saharan Africa — vegetation is very sparse everywhere"],"car":"New Gen 4 coverage added in early 2025 — crisp, high-quality imagery. A pickup truck is visible in coverage. No snorkel, no distinctive tape. The landscape and German signs are the primary tells rather than car meta.","mu":[{"c":"Botswana","k":"also dry, flat in parts, southern Africa. Key split: Botswana is left-hand traffic, Namibia right-hand. No German in Botswana. No massive dunes."},{"c":"South Africa","k":"also southern Africa, also English. Key split: SA is left-hand, Namibia right-hand. SA has Gen 2 halo camera, Namibia is Gen 4."},{"c":"Angola","k":"also right-hand, also southern Africa but Portuguese language, completely different."},{"c":"Australia outback","k":"can superficially look similar (red desert, sparse roads) but completely different language, signs, road markings"}],"ex":["German colonial architecture in Swakopmund is one of the most visually distinctive and memorable location types in all of GeoGuessr — it literally looks like a Bavarian town dropped into the Namib Desert","Kolmanskop ghost town (sand-filled abandoned German houses) is in coverage — completely unique","The sheer emptiness of Namibian roads is itself a tell — you can drive for minutes in any direction and see nothing","Coverage added 2025 so it's fresh and will increasingly appear on World maps","Sun is in the north (southern hemisphere tell)"]},{"id":"nigeria","n":"Nigeria","f":"🇳🇬","co":"Africa","qt":["White police follow-car trailing the Google car in most older coverage — near-unique in the world","Large pickup truck Google car (white or red) — cab and truck bed often visible when panning down","Yellow-and-black roof rack pattern visible on Gen 3 car — unique to Nigeria","Ladder-style utility poles — many thin horizontal rungs, very common throughout the country","License plates with green/blue tinge — distinctive greenish hue visible even through blur"],"ls":"English is the official language — all official signs in English. Yoruba, Igbo, Hausa appear on informal/local signage but English dominates road infrastructure. Right-hand traffic throughout. English + West African landscape + police follow car = Nigeria.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road quality varies enormously — Lagos and Abuja have decent major roads, rural Nigeria can be very rough","Ladder-style utility poles everywhere — thin metal poles with many evenly spaced horizontal rungs, a very consistent Nigeria tell","Standard English road signage","Lagos is massive and dense; Abuja is more planned/grid-like"],"landb":["South Nigeria: tropical, lush, humid, palm trees everywhere, dense vegetation — Niger Delta area","North Nigeria (Abuja area): flatter, drier, more open with some hills around Abuja","Red/brown laterite soil in many areas","Very densely populated — lots of roadside activity, markets, hawkers visible","Flat in most covered areas, with gentle hills around Abuja","General West African feel — corrugated metal roofs, compound walls, roadside stalls"],"car":"Two distinct looks:","carb":["Gen 3: standard car, but sometimes the yellow-and-black roof rack pattern is visible — unique to Nigeria","Gen 4 / newer: large white or red pickup truck with the full cab and truck bed visible when panning down","White police follow-car trailing behind in most older coverage — this is the single most famous Nigeria meta. Can also be black police car or silver/white/red SUV. Almost always present in older coverage."],"mu":[{"c":"Ghana","k":"also English, also West Africa, also right-hand. Key split: Ghana car has black duct tape on front-right roof rack bar; Nigeria has pickup truck + police car. Ghana landscape generally less dense/urban."},{"c":"Senegal","k":"French language (immediate split)"},{"c":"Kenya","k":"English + East Africa, but Kenya has snorkel car, left-hand traffic... wait, Kenya is also left-hand. Check landscape: Nigeria is West Africa (palm trees, flat/humid south), Kenya is East Africa (acacia savanna, different feel)"},{"c":"Uganda","k":"left-hand traffic (easy split from Nigeria's right-hand)"}],"ex":["Nigeria has by far the most coverage of any West African country","The police follow-car is so consistent it's arguably the most reliable single country tell in all of Africa for older coverage","Gas stations are extremely common in Nigeria — \"Gas station density\" is a running meme for Ibadan specifically","License plate greenish tinge: visible even at blur level, helps distinguish from Ghana's white plates","Lagos coverage is chaotic and urban; Abuja coverage is cleaner and more planned — useful for city-level guessing"]},{"id":"r_union","n":"Réunion","f":"🇷🇪","co":"Africa","qt":["Black tape on the back-right bar of the roof rack — key car meta. Note: Ghana has tape on the FRONT bar, Réunion has it on the BACK bar. Easy to mix up, know the position.","French language on everything — Réunion is a French overseas department, fully French infrastructure","Volcanic tropical island — dramatic volcanic mountains, lush green vegetation, Indian Ocean visible","European-quality roads in a tropical setting — very well maintained for an Indian Ocean island, feels like driving in France but with palm trees and volcanoes","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Pure French throughout — Réunion is legally part of France (overseas department), so all signage follows French standards exactly. French road sign styles, French highway numbering (RN, D roads), French formatting on everything. Creole spoken locally but not on signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French road sign system — same blue motorway signs, same warning sign shapes, same speed limit signs as mainland France","Road numbers: RN (Route Nationale), D (Départementale) — exactly like France","Road quality is high — smooth, well-maintained European standard roads","White road markings, French conventions throughout","Tunnels common due to mountainous terrain"],"landb":["Volcanic tropical island — dramatic, lush, green. Very different from mainland Africa.","Piton de la Fournaise is one of the world's most active volcanoes — lava fields visible in coverage","Dense tropical forest on mountain slopes, sugar cane plantations on lower areas","Dramatic calderas (Cirques) — Mafate, Cilaos, Salazie — steep green mountain bowls","Coastal areas: Indian Ocean, beaches, palm trees, tropical feel","Overall: looks like France crossed with a tropical island — unique combination","Very mountainous and green — completely unlike any mainland African country"],"car":"Roof rack with bars and side mirrors visible. Black tape on the back-right bar — this is the key tell. The tape position distinguishes it from Ghana (front bar tape). The sides of the car are also visible. Standard Gen 3 quality.","mu":[{"c":"Ghana","k":"both have black tape on the roof rack. Critical split: Ghana tape is on the front bar, Réunion tape is on the back bar. Ghana looks like West African tropical; Réunion looks like a French volcanic island."},{"c":"Martinique/Guadeloupe","k":"also French overseas departments, also tropical, also French road signs. Split: those are in the Caribbean (Atlantic Ocean), Réunion is Indian Ocean east of Madagascar. Landscape feel differs — Réunion more volcanic and dramatic."},{"c":"Mauritius","k":"nearby Indian Ocean island but English language (British colonial), left-hand traffic, different look entirely"},{"c":"Madagascar","k":"nearby but French+Malagasy, much poorer infrastructure, trekker/boat coverage, very different road quality"}],"ex":["The \"France in the tropics\" feel is very strong — if you see French signs, perfect European roads, but with volcanoes, tropical plants and Indian Ocean = Réunion","Lava fields near the coast (from Piton de la Fournaise) are visually dramatic and unique — black volcanic rock right next to tropical vegetation","Despite being in the Indian Ocean near Madagascar, Réunion is legally and culturally France — EU plates, French everything","Coverage is good around the coast road and main settlements","Tape position (back vs front) is THE split from Ghana — worth memorising carefully"]},{"id":"rwanda","n":"Rwanda","f":"🇷🇼","co":"Africa","qt":["Distinctive small Google car always visible — white, black, or grey/brown, camera mount always clearly visible on top. One of the most recognisable cars in Africa.","Black and white painted kerb/curb stones — alternating black-white painted road kerbs on virtually every street. Extremely consistent and unique in Africa.","Yellow rear + white front license plates — same as Kenya and Uganda but Rwanda car is the fastest split","High-quality paved roads with yellow centre line + white sidelines — unusually good road quality for the region","Left-hand traffic + lush dense green hills"],"ls":"Kinyarwanda, French, and English are all official. English increasingly dominant after Rwanda switched from French to English-medium education in 2009. Road signs are in English. French still appears on older signs and some buildings. The English/French mix is a useful region tell but less reliable than car and road clues.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Yellow centre line + white outer lines — high quality, well maintained, clearly marked","Black and white painted kerb stones on road edges — the single most consistent Rwanda road tell, visible on almost every urban and semi-urban road","Road quality is notably high — Rwanda has invested heavily in infrastructure","Motorcyclists wearing red vests and helmets — mandatory by law, very visible on every road","High walls around most properties — compound-style housing common throughout"],"landb":["Thousand hills — Rwanda is called \"Pays des Mille Collines\" (Land of a Thousand Hills). Endless rolling green hills, terraced agriculture everywhere.","Very dense, lush, dark green vegetation — tropical highland feel","Terraced hillside farming (tea, cassava, banana) visible on every slope","No flat areas — everything is hilly and undulating","Dense population visible — lots of people walking, lots of small houses on hillsides","Feels distinctly different from flat Uganda or savanna Kenya"],"car":"Small, distinctive car — white, black, or grey/brown, always clearly visible including the camera mount on top. The car itself is the fastest Rwanda identify. It looks smaller and more compact than typical African Google cars. Almost always visible — per Geometas, it's almost always present in frame.","mu":[{"c":"Uganda","k":"both left-hand, both East Africa, both lush/green. Key splits: Uganda has boxy white SUV car; Rwanda has small compact car. Uganda has extremely red soil; Rwanda soil is less dramatically red. Rwanda has black-white kerbs; Uganda doesn't."},{"c":"Kenya","k":"both left-hand, both yellow rear plates. Key splits: Kenya has snorkel car; Rwanda has small compact car. Kenya is savanna; Rwanda is dense hills."},{"c":"Burundi","k":"adjacent country, very similar landscape and feel. Burundi has extremely limited coverage — if you're in it you'll likely be in one of very few known locations."},{"c":"Tanzania","k":"right-hand traffic (easy split)"}],"ex":["Red vest motorcyclists are everywhere and very visible — one of the most culturally specific tells in East Africa","Black-white kerbs are so consistent they're the first thing to look for after confirming the car","Rwanda is one of the safest and cleanest countries in Africa — visible in road quality, lack of litter, organised urban areas","The small Google car is really the fastest 100% confirmation — learn its shape","Property walls are high and common — less open than Uganda's compound style","Kigali (capital) has distinctive modern architecture for the region — well-planned city grid"]},{"id":"senegal","n":"Senegal","f":"🇸🇳","co":"Africa","qt":["French language on signs — only African country besides Tunisia with widespread French, but unlike Tunisia has no Arabic","Sky rifts everywhere except Dakar — camera stitching artifacts visible when panning up, same as Albania/Montenegro","Silver or white pickup truck cab visible when panning down in Gen 4 coverage","Blue license plates — distinctive blue background, very recognisable","French-style ladder poles — same thin ladder-rung utility poles as parts of France, inherited from colonial era"],"ls":"French is the dominant official language on all signage. Wolof and other local languages appear on informal signs and shop fronts but French rules official infrastructure. No Arabic script. This is the key split from Tunisia — French without Arabic = Senegal, French with Arabic = Tunisia/Morocco/Algeria.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road markings often faded — one of Senegal's consistent tells is faded or barely-visible road lines","French-inherited road sign style and conventions","Coverage concentrated along the coast and main cities — Dakar, Saint-Louis, Touba, Ziguinchor","Road quality varies; main roads decent, rural roads rougher"],"landb":["Flat, dry Sahel landscape in the north — sandy, sparse scrubby vegetation, baobab trees","More tropical/green in the south (Casamance region)","Baobab trees are iconic and very common across Senegal","Coastal areas near Dakar are urban and dense","Sandy soil, dusty atmosphere in dry season","Feels distinctly West African — different from East or Southern Africa"],"car":"Two coverage types:","carb":["Gen 3: roof rack visible on the car","Gen 4: silver or white pickup truck cab clearly visible when panning down — very distinctive, one of the most recognisable car metas in Africa","Sky rifts (camera stitching errors) visible in most of the country except Dakar — if you see rifts + French = almost certainly Senegal outside the capital"],"mu":[{"c":"Tunisia","k":"also French, but Tunisia has Arabic on signs too, black license plates, and a Mediterranean look. Senegal = French only + blue plates + West African landscape"},{"c":"Côte d'Ivoire / other francophone West Africa","k":"similar French + West African look, but those countries have very limited or no GeoGuessr coverage. If you're in a French-speaking West African country in GeoGuessr it's almost certainly Senegal"},{"c":"Nigeria/Ghana","k":"same region of Africa but English language, completely different"}],"ex":["Blue license plates are the single fastest non-car confirm for Senegal","Ladder-style utility poles (thin horizontal rungs) are a strong supporting tell — inherited directly from French infrastructure standards","Dakar has no sky rifts but the rest of the country does — if you're in a French African city without rifts, could be Dakar","Baobab trees + French signs = Senegal with very high confidence"]},{"id":"s_o_tom_and_pr_ncipe","n":"São Tomé and Príncipe","f":"🇸🇹","co":"Africa","qt":["Black license plates with white lettering — unique in Africa, instantly recognisable","Portuguese language — only African island nation with Portuguese, rules out all other African islands","Tropical island feel — lush, dense green jungle, volcanic terrain, small Atlantic island vibe","Cobblestone roads — memorable and consistent, especially on Príncipe island","Two distinct islands with different Google car metas — knowing which island you're on helps pin the location"],"ls":"Portuguese throughout — all official signs in Portuguese. This immediately rules out all English, French, and Arabic African countries. The only other African Portuguese-speaking countries are Mozambique, Angola, Cape Verde, and Guinea-Bissau — but none are islands in the Gulf of Guinea. Portuguese words to recognise: rua (street), avenida (avenue), hospital, escola (school).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road coverage is limited — mainly along the main roads of São Tomé island and some of Príncipe","White road lines on the main island where lines exist at all","Cobblestone roads are common and memorable, especially on Príncipe — one of the most distinctive road surface tells in Africa","Road quality mixed — main roads paved, others rough","Poles have no clear pattern — the more attachments on a pole, the more likely you're on the main island"],"landb":["Dense tropical jungle — lush, green, humid equatorial vegetation. Some of the most biodiverse jungle in Africa.","Volcanic island terrain — hilly, steep, dramatic","Cocoa plantations — São Tomé was historically a major cocoa producer, plantation architecture visible","Atlantic Ocean views from coastal roads","Small island feel — narrow roads, dense vegetation pressing in on both sides","Very different from mainland Africa — no savanna, no desert, no flat plains"],"car":"Two separate car metas for the two islands:","carb":["São Tomé (main island): black/green truck, mostly blurred but parts visible","Príncipe (smaller island): blue truck visible, with a distinctive black antenna sticking off the side","Both are unusual and distinctive — coverage also includes some unofficial/Ari contributor sections (~30% of what the map shows)"],"mu":[{"c":"Cape Verde","k":"also Portuguese-speaking African island, but Cape Verde is in the Atlantic off West Africa, drier/less lush, different architecture"},{"c":"Mozambique","k":"also Portuguese but mainland, completely different landscape"},{"c":"Equatorial Guinea","k":"adjacent mainland/island territory but Spanish language, minimal coverage"}],"ex":["Black plates with white lettering are shared with Tunisia in Africa — but Tunisia is Arabic + North Africa desert, impossible to confuse","The cobblestone roads on Príncipe are one of the most memorable specific road surfaces in all of GeoGuessr Africa","Coverage is limited enough that landing here is relatively rare — but the combination of black plates + Portuguese + jungle island is so distinctive you should recognise it quickly","The blue truck antenna on Príncipe is one of the more niche car metas in Africa — worth knowing for dedicated players"]},{"id":"eswatini","n":"Eswatini","f":"🇸🇿","co":"Africa","qt":["Green highway signs with white text and yellow numbers, MR prefix — the MR prefix is unique to Eswatini in the Southern Africa cluster, the fastest sign-based confirm","Green, hilly, heavily forested landscape — the lushest and most tree-covered of the Southern Africa cluster. Unlike Lesotho (bare), Botswana (flat/dry), or most of SA.","Left-hand traffic + Southern Africa cluster feel","Wooden utility poles with three insulators on the side — simple design, consistent throughout the country","Blue-green tinted license plates — subtle but distinctive vs South African plates"],"ls":"English and siSwati both official. All road signs in English. Same language as South Africa effectively — the split is entirely visual/landscape and sign prefix, not linguistic.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Green highway signs with white text and yellow road numbers — same colour scheme as South Africa and Botswana, but MR prefix is unique to Eswatini (e.g. MR3, MR8)","Yellow outer lines + white centre lines — standard Southern Africa cluster road markings","Road quality reasonable on main routes","Wooden utility poles with three insulators on the side — simple, consistent, different from SA's more varied poles","Grass by the roadside is notably longer and thicker than in Lesotho"],"landb":["Green, hilly, forested — this is the defining Eswatini landscape tell. Much more tree coverage than any other country in the Southern Africa cluster.","Rolling hills covered in trees and tall grass — subtropical feel","Sugarcane plantations in lower valley areas","Pine plantations on some hillsides","No dramatic tabletop mountains like Lesotho, no flat desert like Botswana","Small country — coverage is limited to main roads through this compact landlocked territory"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Eswatini is identified by landscape, sign prefix, and poles rather than car.","mu":[{"c":"Lesotho","k":"the most common confusion in the cluster. Both hilly, both left-hand, both green highway signs. Key split: Lesotho mountains are bare and treeless with short grass and tabletop shapes; Eswatini is **green and forest"}]},{"id":"tunisia","n":"Tunisia","f":"🇹🇳","co":"Africa","qt":["Black license plates — the single strongest Tunisia tell. Only African country on GeoGuessr with black plates","Arabic + French bilingual signs — Arabic script alongside Latin French text on the same sign","Dark green Mazda follow-car in central and southern Tunisia (south of Hammamet) — with a red and black license plate","Bright blue sky + white Mediterranean architecture — almost always sunny, whitewashed buildings","Metallic wire-style utility poles — distinctive thin wire construction poles"],"ls":"Arabic is official but French appears everywhere alongside it — on road signs, shop fronts, and official signs. This Arabic+French combo on the same sign is characteristic of the Maghreb (Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia). Distinguishing from Morocco/Algeria: check the black plates. Arabic script looks calligraphic with letters connected and a line-like baseline.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Roundabouts very common at intersections — often have directional signs around them","Road signs follow French/European style conventions given French colonial history","Coverage is mostly limited to the east coast — Tunis, Sousse, Sfax, Hammamet, Djerba area. Almost no coverage inland or in the Sahara","Road quality decent in coastal urban areas"],"landb":["Mediterranean coastal feel — white/blue architecture, palm trees, warm dry climate","Intense bright blue sky almost always visible — one of the most consistently sunny countries in GeoGuessr","White cubic/Mediterranean buildings with flat or domed roofs, often blue window trims","Palm trees very common","Sahara desert starts in the south but has no coverage","Overall vibe is \"Middle Eastern meets Mediterranean\" — lighter and more Mediterranean than Egypt or Jordan"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. Key meta: dark green Mazda follow-car visible in central and southern coverage (south of Hammamet). This follow car also has a distinctive red and black license plate. In northern/Tunis area coverage, no follow car. The follow car is one of the most reliable Tunisia confirms when spotted.","mu":[{"c":"Morocco","k":"also Arabic + French, also Mediterranean, also right-hand. Key split: Morocco plates are white, Tunisia plates are black. Morocco has more varied landscape and Moroccan Arabic dialect differs on informal signs."},{"c":"Algeria","k":"also Arabic + French. Algeria plates are also white/different. Less GeoGuessr coverage than Tunisia."},{"c":"Egypt","k":"Arabic only (no French), different architecture, Arabic-only plates, different Google car"},{"c":"Libya","k":"Arabic only, almost no GeoGuessr coverage"},{"c":"Jordan/Lebanon","k":"also Arabic but no French, completely different architecture style"}],"ex":["Black plates are THE fastest single Tunisia confirm in all of Africa — memorise this","The green follow-car appears roughly south of Hammamet, so its presence narrows you to central/southern Tunisia specifically","Djerba island coverage has a very distinct island/resort feel","Phone numbers on signs often in French format","Most coverage is clustered on the eastern coastal strip — if you see Tunisia, you're almost certainly near the coast"]},{"id":"tanzania","n":"Tanzania","f":"🇹🇿","co":"Africa","qt":["Swahili language on signs — Latin script, but with unique words like \"barabara\" (road), \"mji\" (town), \"kata\" (ward)","Right-hand traffic — rules out Kenya, Uganda, and other left-hand East African neighbours","White license plates with black text, often starting with T prefix","Flat-topped acacia savanna landscape — classic East African look","Swahili coastal architecture near the coast — ornate carved wooden doors, whitewashed buildings"],"ls":"Swahili (Kiswahili) is the dominant language on signs, alongside English. Latin script throughout — no Arabic, no Cyrillic. Key words: barabara (road), njia (path/way), hospitali, shule (school), kanisa (church), msikiti (mosque). Bilingual Swahili/English signage is common. MTN and Vodacom telecom branding appears frequently.","rb":["Right-hand traffic (unlike Kenya which is also right-hand — check other clues)","Road markings are often faded or poorly maintained outside major cities","Road numbers use T prefix for trunk roads","Directional signs are generally blue or green with white text","Road quality varies hugely — Dar es Salaam has decent roads, rural Tanzania can be unpaved dirt tracks"],"landb":["Savanna with flat-topped acacia trees — classic East Africa","Mount Kilimanjaro visible in the north (near Moshi/Arusha) — snow-capped peak in the tropics is very distinctive","Zanzibar island coverage: coastal, white sand, tropical, Swahili architecture with ornate doors","Baobab trees appear in central and western Tanzania","Vegetation is drier than Uganda — more open savanna than dense jungle","Red/orange laterite soil in many areas"],"car":"Mix of Gen 3 coverage. Coverage is mainly along major roads and in cities like Dar es Salaam, Arusha, Moshi, and Zanzibar. Rural and interior coverage is very limited. No distinctive special car like Kenya's snorkel — standard Gen 3 white car.","mu":[{"c":"Kenya","k":"also right-hand, also Swahili, very similar landscape. Key splits: Kenya car has a snorkel, Kenya plates are yellow rear/white front (square yellow rear), Tanzania plates are white. Kenya has more coverage."},{"c":"Uganda","k":"also East Africa but left-hand traffic, very red soil, boxy white SUV car"},{"c":"Mozambique","k":"Portuguese language (not Swahili), right-hand traffic, similar landscape"},{"c":"Rwanda","k":"much smaller, denser, hillier, black-and-white curbs, distinctive Google car"}],"ex":["Zanzibar coverage feels very different from mainland — coastal, touristy, distinct Swahili stone-town architecture","\"Duka\" (small shop/kiosk) signs are everywhere — East Africa tell","MTN, Vodacom, Tigo, Airtel telecom branding on buildings is common across East Africa but confirms the region"]},{"id":"uganda","n":"Uganda","f":"🇺🇬","co":"Africa","qt":["Extremely red soil — one of the most vivid red laterite soils in the world, brighter red than Kenya or Brazil","Boxy white SUV Google car with distinctive square side mirrors — unique in Africa","Left-hand traffic — rules out Tanzania, Rwanda, most of East Africa","White front + yellow rear license plates — same as UK style","Armed soldier/security guard following the Street View car in some locations — near-unique tell"],"ls":"English is the official language — signs are in English throughout. Luganda and other Bantu languages appear on informal signage. No French, no Swahili dominance on official signs. English-only official signage distinguishes Uganda from francophone neighbours.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Road quality is mixed — Kampala has reasonable roads, rural areas can be rough","Standard English-language road signs","Coverage is very limited — mainly Kampala city and western national parks (Bwindi, Queen Elizabeth)","In national park coverage: visible black metal bull bar/grill guard on the front of the car"],"landb":["Dense equatorial vegetation — lush, green, tropical. Much greener and denser than Tanzania or Kenya","Extremely red laterite soil — the single most distinctive visual tell of Uganda. Brighter and more saturated red than elsewhere","Hilly terrain — Uganda is called \"the Pearl of Africa\" for its lush rolling hills","Banana/matoke plantations very common roadside","No dramatic mountains in coverage areas (Rwenzori range is remote/uncovered)"],"car":"Boxy white SUV with square side mirrors — very distinctive shape, looks older and boxier than a standard Gen 3 car. In national park coverage, there's a visible black metal bull bar on the front bumper. In some locations, an armed soldier or security guard is visible following the Street View car — a famous Uganda meta moment, near-unique in the world.","mu":[{"c":"Kenya","k":"also has red soil in some areas, but Kenya drives on the left too... actually both are left-hand. Key split: Kenya has a snorkel on the car; Uganda has the boxy SUV. Kenya coverage is far more extensive."},{"c":"Rwanda","k":"also left-hand, also lush/hilly, but Rwanda has black-and-white painted curbs, high-quality roads, and a completely different distinctive Google car"},{"c":"Tanzania","k":"right-hand traffic (easy split)"},{"c":"DRC","k":"no Google coverage; if you see it, it's not DRC"}],"ex":["Coverage is so limited (Kampala + 2-3 national parks) that location-guessing within Uganda is actually not that hard","White front / yellow rear plates — same format as UK, shared with Kenya","Banana trees and matoke (cooking banana) plantations are a strong Uganda sub-tell","Boda-boda (motorcycle taxis) are everywhere on Kampala roads — visible cultural tell"]},{"id":"south_africa","n":"South Africa","f":"🇿🇦","co":"Africa","qt":["Gen 2 camera — halo in the sky + circular blur beneath the car, blurrier image quality","Left-hand traffic — rules out most of Africa instantly","Yellow traffic light poles — very consistent across all major cities","Red and white chevrons on roadsides — extremely common, near-unique to SA (Botswana has them too but far less)","Green highway signs with yellow road numbers — distinct sign colour combo"],"ls":"English and Afrikaans dominate signage. Afrikaans looks like Dutch — double vowels, words like \"straat\", \"dorp\", \"pad\", \"ingang\", \"uitgang\". Seeing both English and Afrikaans on the same sign is a near-certain South Africa tell. 11 official languages total but English/Afrikaans overwhelmingly on road signs.","rb":["Yellow sidelines + white centre lines — unique combo shared with Botswana, Lesotho, Eswatini","Road numbers: N = national (N1–N20), R = provincial/regional","Green highway signs with yellow route numbers — consistent national standard","Wide, well-paved roads on main routes; rural roads can be gravel/dirt","Wooden utility poles common in both rural and developed areas, multiple styles"],"landb":["Karoo = dry, flat, sparse scrub, red/brown soil","Western Cape = Mediterranean, vineyards, dramatic mountains (looks almost European)","KwaZulu-Natal coast = tropical, sugarcane plantations, lush green","Drakensberg = dramatic rocky mountains","Highveld = flat grassy plateau, Johannesburg area","Baobab trees in the north (Limpopo)"],"car":"Gen 2 coverage throughout. Key signs: visible halo ring in the sky when panning up, circular blur/black dot beneath the car when panning down, overall softer/blurrier image quality than Gen 3/4. One of the most reliable Gen 2 countries in the world alongside Australia and Japan.","mu":[{"c":"Botswana","k":"also left-hand, also has chevrons, also Gen 2. Botswana is flat and dry everywhere, uses black & yellow striped signposts, roads are high quality but landscape is monotone"},{"c":"Lesotho","k":"bare treeless tabletop mountains, round thatched-roof huts, people wearing Basotho blankets, green signs but different feel"},{"c":"Eswatini","k":"very green, hilly, forested, small country — less road coverage"},{"c":"Zimbabwe","k":"right-hand drive (different!), worse road quality, different signs"},{"c":"Namibia","k":"right-hand drive, German language appears on signs, extremely sparse/desert"}],"ex":["Regional license plates exist per province but hard to read through blur","Spaza shops (small informal kiosks) are very common roadside — South African cultural tell","Seeing both English + Afrikaans text = almost certainly South Africa, not Botswana/Lesotho","Sun is in the north (southern hemisphere) — useful for compass orientation"]},{"id":"antarctica","n":"Antarctica","f":"🇦🇶","co":"Antarctica","qt":["All coverage is trekker (on foot) — if you're in a car, you're NOT in Antarctica. No roads, no vehicles.","Snow, ice, bare rock, glaciers — the landscape is unmistakable. Nothing else on Earth looks like this.","Penguins — sometimes visible in coverage. If you see penguins waddling around you, you're in Antarctica (or possibly South Georgia).","No signs, no license plates, no infrastructure — nothing man-made except research station buildings","McMurdo Station area is the main coverage cluster — US research base, visible industrial/scientific buildings"],"ls":"None. No road signs anywhere. If you see a sign, it'll be in English (US/UK research stations) but signs are extremely rare.","landb":["Rocky coastline near McMurdo — bare volcanic black rock meeting ice and sea. Not always white — coastal Antarctica near McMurdo is surprisingly barren brown/black rock.","Ice shelves and glaciers — vast flat white expanses of ice","Antarctic Peninsula coverage (south of Chile) — narrow rocky peninsula jutting north, more mountainous","Absolutely no vegetation — not even grass. Completely barren.","Sky is often overcast and grey, or intensely blue on clear days","Feels utterly alien — no trees, no buildings, no roads, nothing"],"carb":["Trekker only — person on foot carrying camera","Main coverage clusters:","McMurdo Station — largest US Antarctic research base, most coverage","Antarctic Peninsula — trekker paths along the peninsula","Penguin colony coverage — official penguin encounter coverage, you are literally surrounded by penguins","No car is ever visible. If you see a car, you're not in Antarctica."],"mu":[{"c":"South Georgia","k":"also cold, also rocky, also penguins, also no roads. Key split: South Georgia has tussock grass and more dramatic mountain/fjord scenery. Antarctica is more barren rock and ice."},{"c":"Iceland/Norway/Svalbard","k":"also cold and rocky, but those have roads, cars, and signs. Antarctica has none."},{"c":"Falkland Islands","k":"also sub-Antarctic feel but has roads and vehicles"}],"ex":["Penguin coverage is one of the most memorable drops in all of GeoGuessr — you are at eye level with hundreds of penguins","McMurdo Station has distinctive yellow and red research buildings — if you see those colours on industrial-looking structures in a frozen landscape, it's McMurdo","The Antarctic Peninsula coverage near Chile is more mountainous and icy than McMurdo","No license plates, no language to read, no bollards — pure visual geography only","Sun position is NOT useful here — the sun circles the horizon rather than rising/setting normally in Antarctic summer"]},{"id":"south_georgia_south_sandwich_islands","n":"South Georgia & South Sandwich Islands","f":"🇬🇸","co":"Antarctica","qt":["Trekker coverage (on foot) — no roads, no cars, all walking POV like Antarctica","Tussock grass — tall, dense, golden-brown tussock grass covering hillsides. This is the single biggest split from Antarctica which has NO vegetation at all.","Penguins + elephant seals + fur seals visible on beaches — extraordinary wildlife density, often thousands of animals in one shot","Dramatic mountain/glacier/fjord scenery — steeper, more dramatic and greener than Antarctica's flat ice","Grytviken whaling station ruins — rusting industrial whale processing equipment, historic wooden church, Ernest Shackleton's grave — completely unique location"],"ls":"English — British Overseas Territory. Any visible signs are in English. Very few signs exist outside the research station at King Edward Point and Grytviken. No road infrastructure.","landb":["Tussock grass — the defining South Georgia tell vs Antarctica. Tall, dense tussocks of golden grass covering coastal slopes, sometimes head-height. Nothing like this in Antarctica.","Fjords and dramatic mountains — glacier-carved valleys, steep peaks, blue glacier ice calving into the sea","Beaches absolutely packed with wildlife — king penguins in colonies of thousands, elephant seals lying in piles, fur seals everywhere","King penguins are the dominant species — tall, orange-and-yellow chest markings, spectacular. Huge colonies at places like Gold Harbour and Salisbury Plain.","Sub-Antarctic vegetation — patches of green on lower slopes where tussock grows","Weather-beaten, dramatic, remote feel — stormy skies, crashing waves, extraordinary isolation"],"carb":["Trekker only — person on foot","Main coverage areas:","Grytviken — whaling station ruins, historic church (built in Norway, assembled by whalers 1913), Shackleton's grave, museum","Penguin and seal colony beaches — walking among thousands of animals","Coastal paths around the island","No cars, no roads, no infrastructure except at Grytviken"],"mu":[{"c":"Antarctica","k":"most obvious confusion. Key split: South Georgia has tussock grass and much more dramatic mountain/fjord scenery. Antarctica is flatter, more icy, and has zero vegetation. South Georgia also has more obvious wildlife on beaches."},{"c":"Falkland Islands","k":"also British, also sub-Antarctic, also penguins. But Falklands has roads, cars, English signs, and sheep farms — very different."}],"ex":["Grytviken is one of the most atmospheric and historically unique drops in GeoGuessr — rusting whale oil tanks, old machinery, a working church, and Shackleton's grave all in the same area","The wildlife density is genuinely staggering — you can see hundreds of king penguins in a single panorama","Ernest Shackleton is buried at Grytviken — his gravestone is sometimes visible in coverage","South Georgia is a British Overseas Territory administered from Stanley, Falkland Islands","No permanent civilian population — only researchers and government staff at King Edward Point","The tussock grass is absolutely the fastest Antarctica vs South Georgia split — learn it"]},{"id":"uae","n":"UAE","f":"🇦🇪","co":"Asia","qt":["White Google Street View car — almost always visible when panning down. Jordan has a black car; UAE has white. This is the fastest UAE vs Jordan split.","Arabic + English bilingual signs everywhere — both scripts on all official signage","Extreme wealth visible — skyscrapers, perfect roads, luxury cars, immaculate landscaping. Far wealthier looking than any other Arabic-speaking country in GeoGuessr.","Black and white striped utility poles — one of only a few countries in the world with these, very distinctive","Dubai coverage dominant — Burj Khalifa (world's tallest building) sometimes visible in the background"],"ls":"Arabic and English both appear on all official signs — bilingual is the standard throughout the UAE. Road signs, street names, directional signs all have Arabic above and English below. This is shared with Qatar but UAE is much more recognisable by its visual wealth and car meta.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Wide, multi-lane, extremely well maintained highways — some of the best road infrastructure in the world","Arabic/English bilingual directional signs — green motorway signs with both scripts","White license plates with black text as standard; Abu Dhabi plates have a distinctive horizontal red strip along the top","Green commercial vehicle plates also common","UAE area codes: all phone numbers begin with 0","Roundabouts common in older residential areas"],"landb":["Desert nation — sandy, arid, flat in most coverage areas","Dubai is predominantly urban — massive skyscrapers, glass towers, mall complexes","Eastern UAE (near Fujairah) has dramatic rocky mountains — the Hajar range, looks completely different from Dubai","White flat-topped houses in residential areas","Palm trees everywhere in urban areas (planted, not natural desert)","Burj Khalifa visible in background of much Dubai coverage","Off-shore island near Dubai coast has coverage with a unique Google car"],"car":"White car always visible when panning down — this is the single fastest UAE tell, particularly for splitting from Jordan (black car). Standard Gen 3/4 quality. Very clean, sharp imagery reflecting the wealth of the country. An island off the Dubai coast has a distinct car for that coverage.","mu":[{"c":"Jordan","k":"also Arabic+English, also Middle East. Key split: Jordan has black car, UAE has white car. Jordan looks noticeably poorer, less modern. Jordan has blue directional signs; UAE has green motorway signs."},{"c":"Qatar","k":"also Arabic+English, also very wealthy, also white truck car. Qatar has a white truck beneath you (similar to UAE). Qatar feels slightly less dramatically urban than Dubai specifically."},{"c":"Saudi Arabia","k":"also Arabic, also desert, but SA has very limited GeoGuessr coverage and no distinctive white car meta"},{"c":"Tunisia","k":"Arabic but also French, not English. Completely different feel."}],"ex":["Abu Dhabi plates with the red top strip are a strong regional tell within the UAE","The wealth gap between UAE and every other Arabic-speaking GeoGuessr country is dramatic — if it looks absurdly rich and modern with Arabic script, it's UAE","Black-and-white striped poles appear in some urban areas — shared with Malaysia, Sri Lanka, and Peru but combined with Arabic script = UAE","White water tanks on rooftops are common in UAE and Jordan — helps distinguish both from Tunisia which doesn't have them","Uniquely styled ornate street lights visible in some areas — another UAE-specific infrastructure detail"]},{"id":"bangladesh","n":"Bangladesh","f":"🇧🇩","co":"Asia","qt":["Bengali script — horizontal line (matra) running along the TOP of letters, connecting them. Looks like letters hanging from a clothesline. Distinct from Hindi (similar but slightly different character shapes — Bengali sometimes has small left-pointing triangles ◁).","Rickshaws everywhere — cycle rickshaws with two wheels at the back are ubiquitous on every road, including city streets. Left-hand traffic with rickshaws = Bangladesh or India, but rickshaw density in Bangladesh is extreme.","Red and white striped bollards shaped like chimneys — very consistent and distinctive, often lined up along bridges and roadsides","Multiple Google car types — very distinctive variety including a car with roof bars, red mirrors, and yellow+green doors in some areas","Left-hand traffic throughout"],"ls":"Bengali (Bangla) script — key recognition feature is the horizontal line (matra) running along the top of characters, connecting them into word groups. The letters hang below this line. Bengali looks similar to Hindi/Devanagari but Bengali has small left-pointing triangle shapes (◁-like) in some characters. Both are distinct from Chinese/Japanese/Korean scripts. Bengali is also the official script in parts of northeast India (West Bengal, Assam) but those areas rarely appear in GeoGuessr.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","All white road lines — varying degrees of fading on older roads, but white throughout","Road markings often faded or barely visible on secondary roads","Red/white striped chimney-shaped concrete bollards — extremely common near bridges and along roadsides, a very reliable tell","Red and white fencing near water bodies","Coverage is extensive — most of the country has been covered by official Street View"],"landb":["Extremely flat and densely populated — Bangladesh is one of the most densely populated countries on Earth. Roads are always busy, people everywhere.","Lush, green, tropical — rice paddies, rivers, dense vegetation","Rivers and water bodies everywhere — the country is essentially a river delta","Very wet-looking landscape, lots of water visible","Dense urban areas (Dhaka especially) are chaotic and crowded","Rural areas: flat green fields, palm trees, bamboo houses, dirt tracks off main roads"],"car":"Multiple coverage types — Bangladesh has several distinct cars:","carb":["Most common: standard white-reared car","Distinctive variety: car with roof bars, red mirrors, and yellow+green door — near-unique globally, appears in some areas","White-reared car: also common","Person on back: a car with a gentleman on the back seat visible, located around Sylhet in the northeast","Boat coverage: the Sundarbans mangrove forest in the southwest has boat coverage","Trekker coverage: some areas","Gen 4 black car: newer coverage uses this","India cam appearance: also appears around Dhaka"],"mu":[{"c":"India","k":"most obvious confusion. Both left-hand, both Bengali script possible (West Bengal/Assam), both chaotic urban environments. Key splits: India has a massive circular blur when panning down; Bangladesh has various distinctive cars. Bengali script in Bangladesh vs Devanagari (Hindi) or other scripts in India."},{"c":"Nepal","k":"also left-hand, also South Asia, but Nepal uses Devanagari script (different from Bengali), more mountainous"},{"c":"Myanmar","k":"also left-hand, but uses its own unique Burmese script (completely different)"}],"ex":["Rickshaw density is the fastest visual tell — if every road is packed with cycle rickshaws, it's Bangladesh","The chimney bollards (red/white striped, short concrete cylinders) near bridges are very reliable and consistent","Sundarbans boat coverage is one of the more unusual drops — mangrove forest, water everywhere, clearly a boat POV","Dhaka is one of the most chaotic and dense cities in all of GeoGuessr — if you're dropped into extreme urban chaos with Bengali script, guess Dhaka","The distinctive yellow+green door car with red mirrors is one of the most unusual Google cars in the world — instant Bangladesh if you see it"]},{"id":"bhutan","n":"Bhutan","f":"🇧🇹","co":"Asia","qt":["Most mountainous country in GeoGuessr — if you see tall, steep, heavily forested mountains everywhere with no flat land in sight, Bhutan is the top candidate","Red license plates — one of very few countries in GeoGuessr with red plates. Visible even through blur at a distance.","Dzongkha script (Tibetan alphabet) on signs — acute lines and vertical straight strokes, looks similar to Tibetan. Combined with Latin script on the same signs.","Distinctive stone milestone/signpost slabs — small stone posts showing distance to nearest town, road number, and kilometre marker. Common on major roads.","Elaborate traditional architecture — white walls, flat roofs extending beyond walls, arch windows, detailed wooden elements on houses and government buildings"],"ls":"Dzongkha is the official language and uses the Tibetan alphabet — characterized by acute lines and vertical straight strokes. Signs often show both Dzongkha and Latin/English text together, which helps. The Tibetan-style script is very distinctive and unlike any other script in South/Southeast Asia. If you see something that looks like Tibetan writing, think Bhutan (or possibly Tibet/China border regions).","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Stone milestone posts — small stone slabs at roadsides showing distance to nearest town on both sides, road number on top, km marker on the side. Rare elsewhere, very common in Bhutan on major roads.","Road numbers aren't shown on the GeoGuessr map so learning them specifically has limited value","Roads are curvy, narrow mountain roads — winding through dramatic terrain, no motorways","Stone bollards on roadsides — near-unique styling along mountain road edges","No dirt roads in covered areas — paved throughout despite mountainous terrain","Road quality reasonably good given the extreme terrain"],"landb":["Extremely mountainous and forested — the entire country is defined by steep, densely tree-covered Himalayan mountain ranges","Deep river valleys cutting between mountain ridges","Dense broadleaf and conifer forest covering slopes up to high altitude","Bhutanese dzongs (fortress-monasteries) visible from roads — white-walled, multi-storey traditional buildings, often on hilltops or cliff edges","Prayer flags (colourful horizontal flags strung between poles) visible frequently","No desert, no flat plains — entirely montane environment"],"car":"Left-hand traffic, standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Bhutan is identified entirely by landscape, script, red plates, and architecture rather than car.","mu":[{"c":"Nepal","k":"also left-hand, also Himalayan mountains, also Tibetan-ish script influences. Key splits: Nepal uses Devanagari script (rounder, different from Tibetan-style Dzongkha). Nepal is generally less green and forested at road level. Bhutan has the distinctive red plates; Nepal plates are white."},{"c":"China (Tibet/Yunnan regions)","k":"also mountainous, also near Tibetan script areas. Key split: China drives on the right; Bhutan left-hand. Chinese signs use Simplified Chinese characters alongside Tibetan script in Tibet."},{"c":"India (northeastern states)","k":"also left-hand, also forested hills. But India uses various local scripts and Hindi, not Dzongkha/Tibetan. India has the massive circular blur when panning down."}],"ex":["Red plates are genuinely visible at GeoGuessr blur distance — the colour is strong enough to read","The stone milestone posts are very specific to Bhutan — if you see small stone slabs with road information on a winding mountain road, commit to Bhutan","Dzong architecture is one of the most visually stunning and distinctive building types in GeoGuessr — if you see a massive white fortress on a cliff with a red roof, you're in Bhutan","Prayer flags (colourful horizontal cloth flags on strings or poles) are a strong Himalayan region tell — appears in Bhutan, Nepal, and Tibet","Coverage is limited to main roads — rural and high-altitude areas have no coverage"]},{"id":"china","n":"China","f":"🇨🇳","co":"Asia","qt":["Simplified Chinese characters — complex characters with many strokes, but in simplified (Mainland China) form. No Japanese kana (curvy simple strokes) mixed in, no Korean circles. Pure Chinese = complex, square, high-stroke-count characters.","Right-hand traffic — rules out Hong Kong immediately","Green highway signs with white text — standard motorway/expressway signage throughout China, similar to US interstate style","Blue license plates with white characters — standard private vehicle plate across all of China, very consistent","Massive country with extreme regional diversity — landscape ranges from tropical south to snowy north, desert west to coastal east"],"ls":"Simplified Chinese — the key is learning to distinguish Chinese from Japanese and Korean: In China, Tibetan script also appears in Tibet/Qinghai regions, Arabic script in Xinjiang, and Mongolian in Inner Mongolia — these are regional tells within China.","lb":["Chinese: complex characters, many strokes, no curvy simple symbols mixed in, no circles. Examples: 路 (road), 街 (street), 市 (city), 省 (province)","Japanese: mixes complex kanji (same/similar to Chinese) WITH simple curvy hiragana/katakana characters (ノ, シ, い, ア) — the mix of simple and complex is the tell","Korean: dominated by Hangul — rounded, blocky characters with circles (ㅇ, ㅎ) — very distinctive"],"rb":["Right-hand traffic","Green expressway signs with white text — national expressways (G prefix, e.g. G1, G2) and provincial expressways (S prefix)","Blue standard road signs for national highways","Blue license plates with white characters for private vehicles; yellow plates for commercial/trucks; green plates for electric vehicles (increasingly common)","White road lines throughout","Road quality excellent on main roads and expressways — one of the world's largest modern highway networks","Chinese characters on road signs are always Simplified (not Traditional — that's Taiwan/Hong Kong)"],"landb":["East coast / Yangtze Delta: dense urban, skyscrapers, modern infrastructure, humid subtropical","North China Plain: flat agricultural, wheat fields, hazy/polluted atmosphere common","Northeast (Manchuria): forested, cold, birch trees, feels similar to Russia/Korea","South China (Guangdong, Fujian): subtropical, lush green, tropical trees, karst mountains","Yunnan: dramatic mountain landscapes, ethnic minority villages, diverse vegetation","Tibet/Qinghai: high plateau, Tibetan script, prayer flags, bare high-altitude landscape","Xinjiang: arid desert/steppe, Arabic script and mosques, feels like Central Asia","Karst formations (Guilin/Guizhou area): dramatic limestone peaks rising from flat ground — one of the most distinctive landscapes in all of GeoGuessr"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. China is enormous and coverage is extensive throughout. The sheer variety of landscapes means you need language + road signs + regional landscape to pin a location within China.","mu":[{"c":"Taiwan","k":"also Chinese characters but Taiwan uses Traditional Chinese (more complex than Simplified), left-hand traffic, and green signs with distinctive flower-shaped freeway numbers"},{"c":"Hong Kong","k":"also Chinese but left-hand traffic, Traditional Chinese + English bilingual, very urban/dense, distinctive red-green taxis"},{"c":"Japan","k":"also uses Chinese-looking characters but mixes in simple curvy kana. Right-hand traffic."},{"c":"South Korea","k":"Hangul is completely different (circles/blocks). Right-hand traffic."},{"c":"Vietnam","k":"Latin script, no Chinese. Right-hand traffic."}],"ex":["The green expressway G/S prefix signs are extremely consistent and a reliable China tell on any major road","Blue plates with white characters — memorise this as the standard China plate colour","Electric vehicle green plates are increasingly common in cities — a sign of modern urban China","Tibet region feels completely different from rest of China: Tibetan script, prayer flags, high barren plateau, yaks","Xinjiang feels like Central Asia with Chinese government infrastructure overlaid — Arabic mosque architecture next to Chinese green highway signs","Haze/smog is often visible in eastern Chinese cities — a sub-tell for urban northern/eastern China","Karst limestone peaks are one of the most visually unique and beautiful landscapes in GeoGuessr — if you see surreal vertical rocky hills rising from flat ground with Chinese signs, it's Guilin/Guizhou"]},{"id":"hong_kong","n":"Hong Kong","f":"🇭🇰","co":"Asia","qt":["Red and green taxis everywhere — abundant on every road, very distinctive colour scheme. Red taxis in urban Kowloon/Hong Kong Island, green in New Territories. One of the most reliable HK tells.","Traditional Chinese + English bilingual signs — all official signage has both scripts, English below Chinese. Traditional Chinese (more complex) not Simplified.","Left-hand traffic — rules out mainland China immediately","Extremely dense urban skyscrapers crammed onto steep hillsides — the most intense urban density in GeoGuessr","Yellow shield road signs with numbers for major roads — distinctive yellow-background number shields"],"ls":"Traditional Chinese + English on all official signs. Traditional Chinese has more complex, complete characters than Simplified Chinese used in mainland China — some characters are noticeably more elaborate. The English+Chinese bilingual combo on every sign is a hard tell for Hong Kong (vs mainland China which is Chinese only or Chinese+Pinyin). If you can read \"香港\" (Heung Gong) anywhere = confirmed HK.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Yellow road number shields — the major Hong Kong road routes are indicated by a yellow background with a number inside. Very distinctive.","English + Traditional Chinese on all directional signs","Almost square-shaped license plates — HK plates are more square/compact than typical rectangular European plates","Road markings are white, British-style (left-hand)","Roads are often narrow, steep, and winding due to hilly terrain","Excellent road quality throughout — well-maintained British-inherited infrastructure"],"landb":["Incredibly dense urban environment — towering skyscrapers on impossibly steep hillsides, almost no flat land","Victoria Harbour visible from many vantage points — water between Hong Kong Island and Kowloon","Very hilly — roads constantly climbing and descending","Surprisingly green in some areas — country parks and steep hillside vegetation between urban areas","Some coverage in the New Territories is more suburban/rural but still distinctly HK","Lantau Island: less dense, some rural coverage, airport visible"],"car":"Standard Gen 3 quality. No distinctive car meta. The taxis and bilingual signs are the primary tells.","mu":[{"c":"Mainland China","k":"biggest confusion. Key splits: China is right-hand; HK is left-hand. China has Simplified Chinese only; HK has Traditional Chinese + English. China has blue plates; HK has compact near-square plates. China has no red-green taxis everywhere."},{"c":"Macau","k":"adjacent territory, also dense, also Traditional Chinese. Key splits: Macau has Portuguese as second language (not English), black license plates, and Gen 2 camera (halo). HK has English signs and Gen 3."},{"c":"Taiwan","k":"also Traditional Chinese, also left-hand. Key splits: Taiwan is less urban-dense, has green highway signs with flower-shaped numbers, different plate style."},{"c":"Singapore","k":"also English + Chinese bilingual, also very dense, also left-hand. But Singapore has Malay and Tamil too, different architecture style, no red-green taxis."}],"ex":["The red/green taxi combination is unmissable — if you see them you're in HK, commit immediately","Macau vs HK: Macau = Portuguese on signs + black plates + Gen 2 halo camera. HK = English on signs + compact plates + Gen 3.","Hong Kong is technically a SAR (Special Administrative Region) of China but counts as a separate territory in GeoGuessr","The density of skyscrapers on steep hillsides is globally unique — nowhere else in GeoGuessr has this exact combination","Night market culture and dense street-level signage (neon signs, vertical Chinese character signs on buildings) is very characteristic of HK urban coverage","Coverage is very good throughout the territory including outlying islands"]},{"id":"israel_west_bank_palestine","n":"Israel & West Bank (Palestine)","f":"🇮🇱","co":"Asia","qt":["Hebrew script — angular, right-to-left letters with no vowels written. Completely unique in the world. If you see Hebrew, you're in Israel or the West Bank.","Trilingual signs (Hebrew + Arabic + English) — Israel's official road signs show all three scripts. This triple-language combo is unique globally.","Yellow license plates with a blue strip on the left — looks similar to EU plates but yellow background. West Bank/Palestinian plates are white.","Color-coded road signs — Israel has a unique system: blue = national roads, red = inner city, green = regional, black = local. Each road category has its own sign colour.","Black and white stripes on street light bases — very consistent throughout Israel"],"ls":"Hebrew is the primary official language — appears on all road signs. Arabic is also official and appears alongside Hebrew. English appears as a third language on most road signs. The Hebrew + Arabic + English trilingual combination on directional signs is unique and immediately identifiable. Hebrew looks angular and blocky, right-to-left, with square-ish letterforms. Arabic is more cursive and flowing. If you see one script that looks very angular and square alongside cursive Arabic = Israel. In the West Bank (Palestinian territories), Arabic dominates on local signage. Palestinian plates are white rather than yellow. Coverage is more limited.","rb":["Right-hand traffic throughout","Colour-coded road number system — blue shields for national roads, red for inner-city, green for regional, black for local. Road numbers visible on these coloured shields.","Directional signs show Hebrew + Arabic + English","Black and white striped street light bases — very consistent throughout the country","Road quality is excellent — well-maintained modern infrastructure","White road markings throughout"],"landb":["Diverse for such a small country:","Coastal plain (Tel Aviv area): Mediterranean, flat, urban, beachside","Jerusalem hills: rocky limestone terrain, ancient stone buildings, olive trees","Negev desert (south): arid, dusty, sandy desert — majority of the country's land area","Galilee (north): greener, hills, Mediterranean vegetation, more European feel","Dead Sea area: extreme desert, lowest point on Earth, white salt flats visible","West Bank: hilly limestone terrain, olive groves, Palestinian villages with distinctive architecture"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. A version of the black car with a long visible antenna on the back appears in some Israel and Palestine coverage — shared with Russia and Donetsk. No other distinctive car meta. Identification is primarily through language and sign system.","mu":[{"c":"Jordan","k":"also Middle East, Arabic on signs. Key split: Jordan has no Hebrew at all. Jordan has a black camera car, Israel has standard. Jordan's directional signs are blue with white text; Israel's are colour-coded by road type."},{"c":"UAE","k":"also Arabic, but UAE has no Hebrew, has white camera car and extreme modern wealth"},{"c":"Palestine/West Bank","k":"technically same GeoGuessr region but Palestinian areas: Arabic dominant (no Hebrew), white plates instead of yellow, generally poorer infrastructure, coverage is more limited"}],"ex":["Yellow plates = Israel. White plates = Palestinian/West Bank territories. This split is visible at blur distance.","The trilingual sign system (Hebrew+Arabic+English) is the fastest single confirm in the region","Black-white striped light poles are very consistent and appear throughout the country","Jerusalem's old stone architecture (cream/golden limestone buildings) is very distinctive","The Dead Sea area drop is one of the most extreme-looking landscapes in GeoGuessr — bone-dry, white salt, hazy horizon, clearly below sea level feel"]},{"id":"india","n":"India","f":"🇮🇳","co":"Asia","qt":["White Google car in a South Asian chaotic urban context = India","Distinctive utility poles — the most reliable India tell. The most common type has three branches splaying out from the top like a mountain/anchor shape. Chaotic wiring draping between them. Nothing like European or East Asian poles.","Tuk-tuks (auto-rickshaws) everywhere in urban coverage — three-wheeled yellow-green vehicles. Globally unique density to India.","Coverage is entirely urban — if you're on a rural road, it's almost certainly not India (could be Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Pakistan etc.)","English appears on virtually all signs alongside the local script"],"car":"White car — consistent across Indian coverage. Slightly lower quality imagery than standard Gen 3. Heavy blur on faces and vehicles. Coverage is entirely from 2022 onwards in city environments.","mu":[{"c":"Bangladesh","k":"Also Bengali script, also chaotic, also left-hand. Key splits: Bangladesh is much less urban, more rural flooding-prone landscape; India coverage is city-only. Rickshaw density extremely high in Bangladesh."},{"c":"Sri Lanka","k":"Also left-hand, also tropical. Key splits: Sri Lanka uses Sinhala script (curvy C-shapes, different from any Indian script) + Tamil. Smaller island, less chaotic."},{"c":"Pakistan","k":"Right-hand traffic (key split from India's left-hand). Urdu/Arabic script dominant."},{"c":"Nepal","k":"Also Devanagari script. Key splits: Nepal has Himalayan mountain context + different plates + road quality very different. Nepal plates have distinct format."}],"ex":["India coverage is rapidly expanding — new cities are being added regularly since 2022","The most common spawns are Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, Chennai, Kolkata, Hyderabad, Jaipur, Ahmedabad","Learning to distinguish the 4 major South Indian scripts is the single highest-value skill for India pinpointing — it immediately narrows you to one of four states","Goa is visually the most distinctive Indian state — Portuguese colonial architecture + Christian symbols + tropical lushness = immediately recognisable","Rajasthan is the second most distinctive — the dry desert + ornate sandstone/painted buildings are unique in India","Kolkata (West Bengal) has a distinct colonial British atmosphere unlike any other Indian city — grand 19th century buildings, yellow taxis, more decayed European-style streets"]},{"id":"british_indian_ocean_territory_biot_diego_garcia","n":"British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT / Diego Garcia)","f":"🇮🇴","co":"Asia","qt":["Tropical atoll island — flat, low-lying coral island, turquoise Indian Ocean water, dense tropical vegetation, white sand","English signs — British Overseas Territory, all signage in English","Military base infrastructure — Diego Garcia is a joint UK/US military base. You may see military-style buildings, fencing, restricted area signs, American-style infrastructure on a tropical island.","Extremely limited coverage — one of the rarest drops in all of GeoGuessr. Almost exclusively Diego Garcia.","Left-hand traffic (British territory)"],"ls":"English throughout. British Overseas Territory so all official signage follows British conventions. American English also appears given the large US military presence. No other languages.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","British-style road signage","Military base signage — restricted area signs, US military conventions mixed with British","Roads are flat and simple — coral atoll with no elevation change whatsoever","Very limited road network"],"landb":["Flat tropical atoll — Diego Garcia is essentially a V-shaped coral atoll barely above sea level","Dense tropical coconut palm vegetation throughout","Turquoise Indian Ocean lagoon on the inside of the atoll","White sandy beaches, coral reef visible in shallow water","Very hot, humid tropical climate","No mountains, no hills, entirely flat","The lagoon is enormous — the atoll encloses a massive protected harbour used by the military"],"car":"Coverage is extremely limited — almost entirely Diego Garcia island roads. This is one of the rarest countries to encounter in GeoGuessr on the World map. Standard car coverage on the island's road network.","mu":[{"c":"Maldives","k":"also flat Indian Ocean atoll, also tropical, but Maldives has Dhivehi script (unique curved script) and trekker-only coverage"},{"c":"Cocos (Keeling) Islands","k":"also flat tropical atoll, also Australian/British administration, but those are Australian territory"},{"c":"Seychelles","k":"Indian Ocean islands but Seychelles is much more hilly/volcanic, has French+English+Creole signage"},{"c":"Guam/Pacific atolls","k":"similar US military + tropical feel but those are in the Pacific, not Indian Ocean"}],"ex":["Landing here on the World map is extremely rare — BIOT is almost never included in standard World maps","The combination of flat tropical atoll + English signs + military infrastructure + Indian Ocean is unique enough that if you get here, there's essentially nothing else it could be","Diego Garcia has been a controversial territory — the original Chagossian population was forcibly removed in the 1960s-70s to make way for the military base. The island has no civilian population.","Coverage is entirely on Diego Garcia — the other Chagos islands have no Street View","The American military presence means you may see US-style yellow road markings or signs mixed with British conventions"]},{"id":"iraq","n":"Iraq","f":"","co":"Asia","qt":["Arabic script only — no English, no French, no Hebrew. Pure Arabic on all signage.","Flat, dry, dusty Mesopotamian landscape — the Tigris-Euphrates river plain is extremely flat, brown, and arid. Very different from Jordan's rocky mountains or UAE's modern desert.","Very limited coverage — Iraq has minimal GeoGuessr coverage. Most drops will be in Baghdad or major cities along the main roads.","Right-hand traffic","Poorer infrastructure than UAE/Jordan — visible wear, older buildings, less modern feel"],"ls":"Arabic only throughout. No English on official road signs (unlike Jordan or UAE which have bilingual signs). Pure Arabic-only signage is the key language tell — if you see Arabic with no other script present and the setting looks like Mesopotamia/Iraq, commit to Iraq.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Arabic-only road signs — no English translation unlike in Jordan or UAE","Road quality varies — main Baghdad roads reasonable, elsewhere can be poor","Coverage is very limited and mostly around Baghdad and a few other urban areas","Flat, wide roads in urban areas"],"landb":["Extremely flat — the Mesopotamian plain (Tigris-Euphrates valley) is one of the flattest landscapes in the world. Nothing like Jordan's rocky mountains.","Brown, dusty, dry semi-arid landscape","Date palm trees are common — Iraq is one of the world's largest date producers, palm trees visible everywhere","Flat agricultural land with irrigation channels","Baghdad: dense urban, wide boulevards, older Soviet-era style government buildings, Arabic signage everywhere","No dramatic mountains in covered areas (Kurdish north has mountains but minimal coverage)","Rivers (Tigris/Euphrates) visible in some coverage"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Very limited coverage overall — Baghdad is the primary source of drops.","mu":[{"c":"Jordan","k":"Arabic, Middle East, but Jordan has Arabic+English bilingual signs, black camera car, and much more mountainous/rocky terrain"},{"c":"UAE","k":"Arabic, but UAE has English alongside Arabic, white car, and extreme modern wealth"},{"c":"Saudi Arabia","k":"Arabic only, also flat desert, but SA has almost no GeoGuessr coverage"},{"c":"Syria","k":"also Arabic only, also flat in some areas, but Syria has almost no coverage"}],"ex":["Date palms are a consistent Iraq tell — they're everywhere and distinctive","The extreme flatness of the landscape is the clearest visual tell vs Jordan (mountains) or UAE (modern city)","Baghdad coverage is the main source — if you're in a large Arabic-only city with wide boulevards and older infrastructure on an extremely flat plain, it's Baghdad","Coverage is sparse enough that Iraq is relatively rare on World maps","Kurdish region (north Iraq) has different feel — more mountainous, Kurdish language (Kurmanji/Sorani, Latin alphabet in Kurmanji) may appear on signs"]},{"id":"jordan","n":"Jordan","f":"🇯🇴","co":"Asia","qt":["Black Google Street View car — pan down and see a black car beneath you. UAE has white; Jordan has black. The single fastest Jordan vs UAE split.","Arabic + English bilingual signs — directional signs in both scripts, but less English than UAE","Blue directional signs with white text — Jordan's primary directional sign colour is blue with white lettering","Rocky, mountainous, arid landscape — Jordan is mostly desert and rocky hills, dramatically different from the flat UAE desert","White license plates with black text — wide/short format, occasionally tall/narrow variant"],"ls":"Arabic is the dominant language on signs. English appears on most official directional signs alongside Arabic, but less prominently than in UAE. Pure Arabic-only on smaller local signs. No Hebrew (immediate Israel split). The Arabic+English combo on blue signs is the standard Jordan directional sign look.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Blue directional signs with white text — Arabic and English both shown","Green highway shields with yellow numbers for standard national highways","Road quality reasonable on main roads, poorer on rural routes","White water tanks on rooftops — very common in Jordan (and UAE) but not Tunisia","White license plates, wide-short format standard, occasional tall-narrow variant","Occasional black-and-white striped poles in some areas (rarer than UAE)"],"landb":["Mountainous and rocky — Jordan's landscape is defined by dramatic rocky desert hills and wadis (dry valleys). Completely unlike UAE's flat sandy desert.","Beige/tan limestone and sandstone terrain — ancient carved rock formations","Wadi Rum area: dramatic red-orange sandstone desert with towering rock formations, used in countless films. One of the most spectacular landscapes in GeoGuessr.","Dead Sea area: extremely low elevation, dry salt flats, hazy atmosphere","Petra area (Wadi Musa): carved rose-red rock architecture, ancient city","Amman: modern city, white stone buildings on rolling hills, very distinctive skyline","Generally sparse vegetation — desert scrub, olive trees in some areas"],"car":"Black car — visible when panning down. This is the primary Jordan meta. The black car in Jordan contrasts directly with UAE's white car. Standard Gen 3 quality. Coverage is decent throughout the country including tourist sites.","mu":[{"c":"UAE","k":"biggest confusion. Both Arabic + English, both Middle East. Key split: Jordan = black car, UAE = white car. Jordan is poorer and more mountainous; UAE is ultra-modern and flat. Jordan has less English on signs."},{"c":"Israel","k":"both right-hand traffic, both in same region. Key split: Israel has Hebrew on signs (Jordan has none), Israel has yellow plates (Jordan has white), Israel has trilingual signs."},{"c":"Saudi Arabia","k":"Arabic only (no English), almost no coverage, flat desert not rocky mountains"},{"c":"Iraq","k":"Arabic only (no English), flat not mountainous, different landscape entirely"}],"ex":["The black car is the fastest single Jordan confirm — learn it","White water tanks on rooftops distinguish Jordan (and UAE) from Tunisia which doesn't have them","Wadi Rum is one of the most visually stunning and recognisable landscapes in GeoGuessr — if you see massive red sandstone towers rising from a rust-coloured sandy desert, it's Wadi Rum, Jordan","Jordan has surprisingly good coverage including many rural and desert roads","Amman is one of the most recognisable Middle Eastern cities — white stone buildings cascading down multiple hills, very distinctive topography"]},{"id":"japan","n":"Japan","f":"🇯🇵","co":"Asia","qt":["Yellow license plates — Japanese kei cars (small boxy cars) use distinctive yellow plates. Even standard white plates are recognisable. Yellow plates are effectively unique to Japan in East Asia.","Low camera mount — Japan's Google car has a lower-than-usual camera position, making roads look wider, the car look bigger, and producing a distinctive large circular blur at the bottom. The camera height is visibly different from other countries.","Boxy kei cars everywhere — small, tall, boxy micro-cars that aren't sold anywhere else in the world. Very distinctive vehicle shape.","Japanese script — mix of kanji (complex Chinese-origin characters) + hiragana/katakana (simple curvy symbols like ノ, シ, い, ア). The mixing of complex and simple scripts is unique.","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"Japanese — three scripts used simultaneously: The key tell: Japanese text mixes complex kanji WITH simple curvy/angular kana symbols. If you see complex Chinese-looking characters mixed with simple symbols like ノ, シ, ア, ン = Japanese. Chinese/Taiwanese has only complex characters. Korean has Hangul (circles/blocks).","lb":["Kanji: complex characters borrowed from Chinese (same as Chinese characters)","Hiragana: simple curvy characters — ひらがな (flowing, rounded)","Katakana: simple angular characters — カタカナ (sharp, angular)"],"rb":["Left-hand traffic","Blue directional signs with white lettering (motorways and national routes)","Yellow diamond-shaped warning signs — Japan uses American/Oceanian-style yellow diamond warnings, shared with USA, Australia, New Zealand. Unusual for East Asia.","Yellow and black vertical stripes on utility poles — these vertical stripes are the key Japan vs Taiwan pole split. Japan = vertical stripes. Taiwan = diagonal stripes reaching ground. Korea = diagonal not reaching ground.","Small circular road mirrors on winding roads for seeing around corners — very common in Japan on mountain/rural roads","Small plates on utility poles indicating region — best tool for regional guessing within Japan"],"landb":["Incredibly diverse for a relatively small country:","Hokkaido: northern island, cold, snowy in winter, wide roads, agricultural, feels almost Canadian","Honshu (main island): enormous variety from Tokyo megalopolis to rural rice paddies to dramatic mountain passes","Kyushu/Okinawa: subtropical south, tropical in Okinawa, volcanic landscapes","Rice paddies surrounded by mountains are iconic Japan rural","Vending machines on every rural road — a Japan cultural tell visible roadside","Torii gates (red Shinto shrine gates) visible in some coverage","Immaculate road quality and infrastructure throughout"],"car":"Low camera mount — the camera is mounted lower than standard, creating: Older coverage may show Japan's Gen 2 characteristics in some areas.","carb":["Roads appear wider than usual","The car beneath appears larger","Large circular blur at the bottom of the screen","This low camera height is distinctive and shared with Switzerland (which also has low cam but different look)"],"mu":[{"c":"Taiwan","k":"both left-hand, both East Asian. Key splits: Japanese mixes simple kana with complex kanji; Taiwan has Chinese characters only. Japan has yellow plates; Taiwan has white plates. Japan poles have vertical stripes; Taiwan poles have diagonal stripes."},{"c":"South Korea","k":"both right-hand... wait, Korea is right-hand, Japan is left-hand. Easy split. But if confused: Korea has Hangul (circles), Japan has mixed scripts."},{"c":"China","k":"also complex Chinese characters but China is right-hand, Japan is left-hand. Very different camera quality and infrastructure feel."}],"ex":["Yellow kei car plates are the fastest Japan confirm at blur distance — bright yellow small square plate","Boxy kei cars are incredibly distinctive — if you see lots of tiny cube-shaped cars, you're in Japan","Vending machines on rural roads are a famous Japan-specific commercial tell","The low camera mount making roads look extra wide is subtle but recognisable once learned","Regional pole plates (small information plates on utility poles) have different designs per region — a deep Japan meta rabbit hole for pinpointing","Okinawa looks very different from mainland Japan — tropical, flat, US military infrastructure, feels closer to Taiwan","Japan has exceptional coverage nationwide including very remote mountain roads"]},{"id":"kyrgyzstan","n":"Kyrgyzstan","f":"🇰🇬","co":"Asia","qt":["Visible side mirrors + bars under the car — Kyrgyzstan's Google car shows bars and black/white side mirrors. Shared only with Guatemala — and those two look nothing alike.","Mirror reflection meta — in southwestern Kyrgyzstan (Osh area), you can see ~90% of the silver car reflected in the left side mirror. In the rest of the country, only ~60% is visible. This can help narrow down region.","Red stripe on the left of license plates — distinctive red vertical band on the left side of the white plate","Dramatic mountain landscape — Kyrgyzstan is one of the most mountainous countries in GeoGuessr, covered in high Tian Shan peaks","Cyrillic script — Russian and Kyrgyz (both Cyrillic) on signs throughout"],"ls":"Cyrillic script throughout — both Russian and Kyrgyz use Cyrillic. Signs often in both languages. Kyrgyz Cyrillic has a few unique letters (ң, ү, ö, ä) not found in Russian. The Cyrillic + dramatic mountain landscape + Central Asian feel is the core identification combo. Unlike Russia (flat/forested) or Ukraine (flat agricultural), Kyrgyzstan is mountainous and Central Asian in character.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Cyrillic-only road signs — no Latin script on official signage","Road quality varies enormously — main roads in Bishkek and between cities are paved, rural mountain roads can be very rough gravel","Roads often wind dramatically through mountain passes","White road lines where present","Coverage is mainly along main roads — remote mountain areas have very limited or no coverage"],"landb":["Extremely mountainous — the Tian Shan range dominates. Snow-capped peaks, deep gorges, high-altitude valleys. One of the most dramatic landscapes in all of GeoGuessr.","High-altitude grasslands (jailoo) — green meadows at altitude surrounded by bare rocky peaks","Occasional yurts (traditional round felt tents) visible in rural areas — a strong Central Asian tell","Very sparse population outside cities","Bishkek: relatively modern post-Soviet city, wide Soviet-era boulevards, Cyrillic signs, backdrop of Tian Shan mountains","Rivers and gorges cut through mountain valleys","Feels distinctly Central Asian — Soviet infrastructure + dramatic mountains + steppe/grassland"],"car":"Silver car with visible bars and black/white side mirrors — distinctive setup shared globally only with Guatemala. The mirror reflection percentage meta: ~90% car reflected in Osh/southwest, ~60% everywhere else. This is a niche but real meta for regional guessing within Kyrgyzstan.","mu":[{"c":"Russia","k":"also Cyrillic, but Russia is mostly flat with forests or steppe. Mountains immediately suggest Kyrgyzstan over Russia. Russia has no side mirror car meta."},{"c":"Kazakhstan","k":"also Cyrillic, also Central Asia, but Kazakhstan is mostly flat steppe. Mountains = Kyrgyzstan not Kazakhstan."},{"c":"Mongolia","k":"also Central Asia + mountains + yurts but Mongolia has its own unique script (Mongolian vertical script) appearing alongside Cyrillic, plus the very distinctive camping gear under the car"},{"c":"Georgia","k":"also Caucasus mountains, but Georgia has its own completely unique Georgian script (rounded, like no other alphabet)"},{"c":"Guatemala","k":"also shows bars + side mirrors car meta but Spanish language + Central American landscape makes confusion impossible"}],"ex":["The visible bars + side mirrors is a reliable car meta — if you see this in an Asian mountainous context, commit to Kyrgyzstan","Red stripe on license plates is visible at blur distance — memorise it","Yurts on hillsides are one of the most culturally specific tells in GeoGuessr — Central Asia + yurt = Kyrgyzstan or Mongolia (check script and car to split)","Bishkek has a very classic post-Soviet feel — wide tree-lined boulevards, Soviet architecture, Cyrillic","The mountain scenery is spectacular and unique — if you see towering bare rocky Tian Shan peaks with Cyrillic signs, it's Kyrgyzstan","Coverage is decent along main roads but gaps in remote mountain areas"]},{"id":"cambodia","n":"Cambodia","f":"🇰🇭","co":"Asia","qt":["Khmer script — small hooks on the top of almost every character, pointing to the RIGHT. Very distinctive and unlike Thai (circles at tops) or Lao (similar but different). If you see right-pointing hooks on script, commit to Cambodia.","Right-hand traffic — rules out Thailand (left-hand) immediately","Red and white striped bollards — very consistent across the country","Angkor and Ganzberg beer advertisements — both featuring RED signs, absolutely everywhere. If you see red beer ads with these brands, you're in Cambodia.","Wooden houses on stilts — traditional architecture with multiple roof sections, red-brown, light-blue or orange wall colors"],"ls":"Khmer script — the defining Cambodia tell. Key recognition feature: small hooks pointing RIGHT at the top of most characters. This is different from Thai (which has more circular/looping elements) and Lao (similar hooks but slightly different). Khmer looks ornate and complex with lots of vertical strokes topped by those right-pointing hooks. Once you recognise the hook direction, Cambodia vs Thailand/Laos becomes much easier.","rb":["Right-hand traffic (unlike Thailand which is left-hand)","Stop signs show Khmer script + the English word \"STOP\" — bilingual stop signs","Road markings vary — yellow centre lines on some roads, white on others","Red and white bollards — striped or divided into two sections, very consistent","Road quality mixed — main roads paved, rural roads can be rough","Two types of utility poles: square ladder-style poles (indents not extending to top/bottom) and round poles with small holes"],"landb":["Flat lowlands in central Cambodia (Mekong/Tonle Sap basin) — very flat agricultural landscape","Rice paddies everywhere — flooded fields with emerald green young rice","Tonle Sap lake area: floating villages, water everywhere","Angkor Wat area (Siem Reap): jungle temples, massive tourist infrastructure","Hills and mountains in the northeast and southwest borders","Tropical, lush, humid — palm trees and tropical vegetation throughout","Wooden houses on stilts with distinctive multiple-section roofs in rural areas"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Cambodia is identified by language, bollards, beer ads, and architecture.","mu":[{"c":"Thailand","k":"most similar feel but Thailand is left-hand traffic and uses a different script (Thai has more circles). Thai script has circular/looping elements; Khmer has right-pointing hooks."},{"c":"Laos","k":"also right-hand, also Southeast Asian, Lao script is similar to Khmer but hooks are slightly different. Laos has very limited coverage; Cambodia has much more. Laos has yellow plates, distinctive pinecone utility poles."},{"c":"Vietnam","k":"also right-hand, but Vietnam uses Latin script (Chữ Nôm/Quốc ngữ with diacritics) — completely different from Khmer"},{"c":"Myanmar","k":"also Southeast Asia but left-hand traffic, completely different Burmese script"}],"ex":["Angkor and Ganzberg red beer signs are everywhere — one of the most reliable commercial tells in Southeast Asia","The right-pointing hooks on Khmer script are the single fastest script identification tell","Wooden stilt houses with brightly coloured walls (orange, light blue, red-brown) and multi-section roofs are very distinctive architecture","Coverage is decent throughout the country including rural roads","Phnom Penh: dense urban, French colonial architecture mixed with modern buildings, Khmer signage"]},{"id":"south_korea","n":"South Korea","f":"🇰🇷","co":"Asia","qt":["Hangul script — Korean characters dominated by circles and blocky/rigid shapes (ㅇ, ㅎ, ㅡ, ㅣ). Completely unique script, unmistakable once learned.","Utility poles with a long sharp pointed spike extending upward from the top — very distinctive compared to other East Asian poles","Yellow and black diagonal stripes on lower section of utility poles — not extending all the way to the ground, distinct pattern","Green highway signs with white text — expressway shields look similar to US Interstate shields","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Hangul — the Korean alphabet. Key recognition feature: circular/rounded elements mixed with blocky rigid strokes. The letters ㅇ (circle), ㅎ (circle with stroke), ㄱ (right angle), etc. give Hangul a distinctive blocky-yet-circular appearance. Unlike Chinese (complex, many strokes, no circles), unlike Japanese (mixes simple curvy kana with Chinese kanji), Korean Hangul is consistently blocky with circles. If you see script dominated by circles and right angles = Korean = South Korea.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Green highway expressway signs with white text — expressway number shields look like US Interstate shields (similar shield shape). Expressway numbers visible on map if zoomed in.","Warning signs: triangle with red border and yellow fill — South Korea and Vietnam are the ONLY Asian countries with this European-style warning sign format","Road markings white throughout","Good road quality — South Korea has excellent modern infrastructure"],"landb":["Mountainous country — about 70% of Korea is mountains, but coverage is mostly in populated valleys and cities","Dense urban areas (Seoul, Busan, Incheon): modern high-density cities, concrete apartment blocks everywhere","Rural areas: rice paddies, mountain valleys, traditional tiled-roof houses (hanok) in some areas","Cherry blossom trees in spring — very recognisable pink blossom lined streets (seasonal)","Coast: dramatic rocky coasts, especially on Jeju island","Jeju Island: volcanic landscape, stone walls, tangerine orchards — very distinctive sub-location"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. South Korea is identified by language, poles, and signs.","mu":[{"c":"Japan","k":"most common confusion. Both East Asian, both highly developed, both right-hand. Key splits: Japanese uses a MIX of Chinese kanji + simple curvy kana (hiragana/katakana); Korean is pure Hangul with circles and blocks. Japan has yellow license plates; Korea has white plates. Japan's poles have yellow-black stripes extending ALL THE WAY to the ground; Korea's stripes don't reach the ground."},{"c":"China","k":"Chinese uses complex characters only, no circles. Right-hand. China is much larger and more diverse."},{"c":"Taiwan","k":"also uses Chinese characters (Traditional), right-hand, but Taiwan has green signs with flower-shaped freeway numbers"}],"ex":["The spiked tops of utility poles are very distinctive — if you see poles with a long upward spike, it's South Korea","Yellow-black diagonal stripes on poles that DON'T reach the ground: Korea. Same stripes that DO reach the ground: Japan. This is a key Japan vs Korea pole split.","European-style triangular warning signs (red border, yellow fill) are shared only with Vietnam in Asia — confirms you're not in Japan or China","Seoul is absolutely massive — if you're in a gigantic Asian city with Hangul signs and green highway shields, it's Seoul","Jeju Island is recognisable by its volcanic black rock walls and subtropical feel — very different from mainland Korea"]},{"id":"kazakhstan","n":"Kazakhstan","f":"🇰🇿","co":"Asia","qt":["Cyrillic script + vast flat steppe landscape — the combination of Cyrillic and endless flat grassland/semi-desert is Kazakhstan's signature. Russia also has Cyrillic but is more forested; Kazakhstan is predominantly flat open steppe.","Enormous flat, open landscape — Kazakhstan is the world's largest landlocked country. Roads stretch to the horizon across flat steppe with almost nothing visible for miles.","White sedan with tall camera mast — the Google car in Kazakhstan (and parts of Russia/Central Asia) uses a white sedan with a noticeably tall/long camera mast","Right-hand traffic","Very sparse, wide roads with almost no traffic in rural areas"],"ls":"Cyrillic throughout — both Russian and Kazakh (both use Cyrillic in Kazakhstan). Kazakh Cyrillic has some unique letters (ә, ғ, қ, ң, ө, ұ, ү, і, һ) not found in Russian. Signs are often bilingual Kazakh/Russian. Kazakhstan is also transitioning to a Latin-based script for Kazakh, so newer signs may show Latin-alphabet Kazakh alongside Cyrillic. This transitional bilingual Cyrillic+Latin (for Kazakh specifically) is a growing tell.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road quality varies enormously — main highways between cities can be decent, but rural roads are often poor, damaged, or unpaved","Very long straight roads across flat terrain — you can often see the road stretching absolutely straight to the horizon","White road lines where present","Coverage is mainly along main highways and in cities (Almaty, Astana/Nur-Sultan, Shymkent)","Vast distances between settlements — if you see a straight road with nothing on either side for miles, Central Asian steppe = Kazakhstan"],"landb":["Vast flat steppe — the dominant landscape. Semi-arid grassland, brown/tan/grey earth, sparse vegetation, enormous sky","Semi-desert in the south — more arid, drier, sandy/dusty","Mountains only in the very southeast (Tian Shan near Almaty) and northeast (Altai)","Almaty: modern city at the foot of dramatic snow-capped Tian Shan mountains — very distinctive backdrop","Astana (Nur-Sultan): futuristic modern capital city on flat steppe — bizarre architecture visible (Bayterek tower, distinctive modern buildings)","Extremely sparse population outside cities — you can drive enormous distances without seeing a building"],"car":"White sedan with a tall camera mast — shared with parts of Russia and other Central Asian countries. No single unique meta like Kyrgyzstan's mirrors. Coverage is mainly along main routes.","mu":[{"c":"Russia","k":"also Cyrillic, but Russia has more forests (taiga), birch trees, and a more European feel in western areas. Eastern Russia can look similar to Kazakhstan steppe. Check for Kazakh-specific Cyrillic letters on signs."},{"c":"Kyrgyzstan","k":"also Cyrillic, also Central Asia, but Kyrgyzstan is mountainous while Kazakhstan is flat. Kyrgyzstan has the visible side mirrors car meta."},{"c":"Mongolia","k":"also flat steppe, but Mongolia uses Mongolian vertical script alongside Cyrillic, and has the camping gear car meta"},{"c":"Ukraine","k":"also Cyrillic, also flat in east, but Ukrainian has specific characters (і, ї, є, ґ) and Ukraine has red car with long antenna"}],"ex":["The sheer emptiness and flatness is Kazakhstan's most reliable tell — if roads stretch to the horizon with nothing around and Cyrillic signs, it's Kazakhstan","Almaty backdrop (snow-capped Tian Shan behind a modern city) is one of the most dramatic city landscapes in GeoGuessr","Astana's bizarre futuristic architecture (Bayterek tower, Khan Shatyr tent, mirrored skyscrapers) on a flat steppe is completely unique","The Kazakh transition to Latin script means some newer signs have Latin Kazakh — a growing regional tell","Soviet-era apartment blocks (Khrushchyovka) are very common in cities — Central/Eastern European Soviet aesthetic","Summer in western and central Kazakhstan.","Autumn in the northeast.","Winter in the southeast."]},{"id":"laos","n":"Laos","f":"🇱🇦","co":"Asia","qt":["Very limited coverage — Laos has almost no Street View. Coverage is mainly in a few urban areas. When you see the car bars and mirrors in Laos, they're visible.","Yellow license plates — distinctive, shared with very few other Southeast Asian countries. In Southeast Asia, yellow plates = Laos (or commercial vehicles in Thailand)","Asymmetric \"pinecone\" utility poles — two pinecone-shaped insulators on one side, one on the other. Also have small holes. Very distinctive shape.","Lao script — similar to Khmer but with slightly different hook direction and letter shapes. Also similar to Thai. Right-hand traffic.","Stop signs: Lao script + English \"STOP\" — bilingual stop signs"],"ls":"Lao script — similar to Thai and Khmer but distinct. Lao has fewer letters than Thai, the script is slightly more rounded than Khmer. Distinguishing Lao from Thai: both have curved/circular elements, but Thailand is left-hand traffic while Laos is right-hand. If the script looks like Thai but traffic is on the right = Laos. Lao and Khmer both have right-hand traffic, but Lao is less hook-dominated than Khmer.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow license plates — this is the fastest single Laos confirm visible at blur distance","Stop signs show Lao script + \"STOP\" in English","Road quality poor — Laos is one of Southeast Asia's poorer countries, roads often rough","Coverage is extremely limited — Vientiane (capital) and a handful of other towns only. Many areas have no coverage at all.","When the car IS visible, bars and side mirrors are visible in coverage"],"landb":["Urban coverage (Vientiane): flat, low-rise, French colonial architecture mixed with traditional Lao buildings","Mountains and hills visible in the background even from urban coverage — Laos is a landlocked mountainous country but coverage is mostly in the valleys","Lush tropical vegetation","Mekong River visible near Vientiane (border with Thailand)","Rural Laos: very remote, forested mountains, almost no coverage"],"car":"Coverage shows bars and side view mirrors visible — a relatively unusual car setup. Coverage is so limited that car meta is less useful than yellow plates and script.","mu":[{"c":"Thailand","k":"most similar script, similar feel. Key split: Thailand is left-hand traffic; Laos is right-hand. Thailand has white plates; Laos has yellow plates. Thailand has far more coverage."},{"c":"Cambodia","k":"also right-hand, also Southeast Asia. Key splits: Khmer script has more pronounced right-pointing hooks than Lao. Cambodia has red/white bollards. Cambodia has far more coverage than Laos."},{"c":"Myanmar","k":"left-hand traffic, completely different Burmese script"},{"c":"Vietnam","k":"right-hand, but uses Latin script with diacritics — completely different"}],"ex":["Yellow license plates are the single fastest Laos confirm — if you're in Southeast Asia with right-hand traffic and yellow plates, it's Laos","The pinecone utility poles are very distinctive — asymmetric with two pinecones on one side, one on the other","Coverage is so limited that landing in Laos on the World map is rare — most drops will be Vientiane","French colonial architecture in Vientiane (white/yellow buildings with arched windows, French street layout) is a supporting cultural tell","Laos is landlocked and shares borders with Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam, China, and Myanmar — all of which look different"]},{"id":"lebanon","n":"Lebanon","f":"🇱🇧","co":"Asia","qt":["Arabic + French and/or English trilingual signs — Lebanon is one of very few Arabic countries with prominent French. Signs often show Arabic + French or Arabic + English or all three. French colonial heritage is strong.","Dramatically mountainous Mediterranean landscape — steep rocky limestone mountains right behind a Mediterranean coastal strip. Unlike Jordan (rocky desert), unlike UAE (flat desert), unlike Tunisia (flat Mediterranean).","Stone construction everywhere — Beirut and Lebanese cities are built from local beige/cream limestone. The stone colour and texture is very distinctive.","Right-hand traffic","Very chaotic, dense urban areas — Beirut is famous for its dense, visually complex urban environment with mixture of old and new architecture"],"ls":"Arabic dominates all official signage. French appears prominently alongside Arabic — on street names, shop signs, restaurant menus, and sometimes official signage. English also common in Beirut's commercial districts. This Arabic+French combo is shared with Tunisia/Morocco/Algeria but Lebanon's mountainous Mediterranean landscape immediately distinguishes it. The Lebanese dialect of Arabic also appears on informal signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Arabic + French (and sometimes English) on signs","Road quality very variable — main Beirut roads can be decent, but infrastructure generally poor due to decades of conflict and economic crisis","Traffic is chaotic — Beirut has almost no functional traffic lights in some areas","Mountain roads: winding, steep, sometimes very narrow","No distinctive bollard or pole meta"],"landb":["Mountains immediately behind the coast — the Lebanon Mountain range rises dramatically from the Mediterranean coastal plain. You can see sea AND snowy mountains in the same view in winter/spring.","Rocky limestone terrain — grey/white rocky outcrops and cliffs throughout","Mediterranean coast: beaches, turquoise sea, dense coastal development","Bekaa Valley: flat agricultural valley between Lebanon Mountains and Anti-Lebanon range — fertile farmland, vineyards","Cedars (in high mountain areas): iconic cedar trees, symbol of Lebanon","Stone-built villages on steep mountain slopes","Beirut: dense urban, mix of French colonial architecture, war-damaged buildings, gleaming new towers — visually chaotic"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Lebanon is identified by language, mountain landscape, and stone architecture.","mu":[{"c":"Jordan","k":"Arabic, Middle East, mountainous. Key splits: Jordan has no French. Jordan's black camera car vs Lebanon's standard. Jordan landscape is more desert-rocky; Lebanon is more Mediterranean-green with snow-capped peaks."},{"c":"Tunisia","k":"Arabic + French, Mediterranean. Key splits: Tunisia is flat coastal; Lebanon is dramatically mountainous. Tunisia has black plates and a follow car."},{"c":"Morocco","k":"Arabic + French, Mediterranean. Key splits: Morocco has more diverse landscape, different architecture, different plates. Morocco is much larger with more coverage."},{"c":"Syria","k":"Arabic only (no French), similar landscape, but Syria has almost no GeoGuessr coverage"},{"c":"Greece","k":"also Mediterranean mountains + coast but Greek script (completely different), left-hand traffic"}],"ex":["Arabic + French on the same sign immediately narrows to Lebanon, Tunisia, Morocco, or Algeria — then use landscape to split (Lebanon = dramatic mountains right behind coast)","Beirut's architecture is uniquely chaotic — French Art Deco buildings next to glass towers next to bombed-out ruins. If you see that mix with Arabic+French signs, it's Beirut.","The Bekaa Valley has a very different feel from Beirut or the coast — flat agricultural, vineyards, mountains on both sides","Cedar forests in the high mountains are a strong Lebanon sub-location tell","Lebanon has decent coverage throughout the country including mountain roads and the Bekaa Valley","Economic crisis visible in coverage — many buildings look dilapidated, infrastructure worn, which distinguishes Lebanon from wealthier UAE/Qatar"]},{"id":"sri_lanka","n":"Sri Lanka","f":"🇱🇰","co":"Asia","qt":["Gen 3 car: white with red blur on RIGHT side, blue blur on left — unique in all of GeoGuessr. Only Sri Lanka has this. The red blur on the right is the defining car tell.","Gen 4 car: low-cam — camera mounted lower than usual, making roads look wider, car looks bigger, large wide circular blur at bottom","Yellow rear license plates + white front — like UK/Kenya/Uganda style but in a South Asian context","Sinhala script — looks very \"C\"-like, with many letters resembling C forwards, backwards, or upside down. Very curvy and rounded.","Left-hand traffic + tropical island"],"ls":"Sinhala is the primary script — characterised by extremely curvy, circular letterforms. Many letters look like variations of the letter \"C\" (forwards, sideways, upside down). Tamil also appears in northern Sri Lanka (looks more angular than Sinhala). English appears on some signs. The combination of Sinhala script + tropical island + left-hand traffic is unmistakable.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Black-and-white striped signposts — very common, shared with Malaysia but Sri Lanka context is different","Small white and black stone bollards — distinct low stone post style","Road markings: yellow or white, variable","Road quality varies — main roads decent, rural roads rough","Coverage is good throughout the island"],"landb":["Tropical island — lush, green, humid, palm trees everywhere","Reddish/laterite soil — similar to Uganda/Kenya but island context","Diverse landscape: southern coast (beaches, palm trees), central highlands (tea plantations on steep green hills), northern dry zone (flatter, drier)","Tea plantations on steep terraced hillsides in the central highlands — one of the most distinctive landscapes in GeoGuessr, bright green rows of tea bushes on dramatic slopes","Dense tropical vegetation throughout","Tuk-tuks (auto-rickshaws) everywhere on roads"],"car":"Two distinct generations: Both are Sri Lanka-exclusive. The Gen 3 red-right-blur is 100% confidence.","carb":["Gen 3: white car with distinctive red blur on the right side and subtle blue blur on the left — resembles the French flag horizontally. This is completely unique to Sri Lanka. Instantly identifiable.","Gen 4: low-cam setup — camera mounted lower, roads appear wider, large circular blur beneath, different look from Gen 3"],"mu":[{"c":"India","k":"also left-hand, also South Asia, also tropical in south. Key splits: India has foggy unofficial camera (very different quality), India has no yellow rear plates standard. Sri Lanka is an island — no land borders."},{"c":"Bangladesh","k":"also left-hand, also South Asia, Bengali script vs Sinhala. Bangladesh has distinctive chimney bollards; Sri Lanka has stone bollards."},{"c":"Thailand","k":"also tropical, similar feel in south. Key split: Thailand is left-hand too, but uses Thai script (circles) vs Sinhala (C-shapes). Thailand has yellow/white poles with painted bases; Sri Lanka has black-white striped poles."},{"c":"Malaysia","k":"also left-hand, also tropical, also black-white striped poles. Key splits: Malaysia uses Malay (Latin script), completely different plates (two-section white/black format)."}],"ex":["The red blur on the Gen 3 car is THE fastest Sri Lanka confirm — if you see it, commit immediately","Tea plantation hillsides are one of the most beautiful and distinctive landscapes in GeoGuessr — rows of bright green tea bushes on steep terraced slopes = central Sri Lanka","Tuk-tuks are extremely common and add to the South Asian visual identity","Yellow rear plates in a tropical left-hand island context = Sri Lanka (Kenya/Uganda are the only other yellow-rear left-hand countries but those are African savanna)"]},{"id":"mongolia","n":"Mongolia","f":"🇲🇳","co":"Asia","qt":["Camping equipment on top of the Google car — tents, sleeping bags, spare tyres strapped to the roof. The drivers literally camped out in the steppe while covering the country. One of the most iconic and unique car metas in GeoGuessr.","Also: snorkel on the car — Mongolia and Kenya are the ONLY two countries with snorkel cars. The snorkel distinguishes from other Central Asian Cyrillic countries.","Cyrillic script + vast empty steppe — but unlike Russia (forests), Mongolia is open treeless grassland","Full-width white license plates with black lettering — no red stripe (unlike Kyrgyzstan)","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Cyrillic for Mongolian — plus the traditional Mongolian vertical script (written top-to-bottom) appears on some official signs and newer government signage. The vertical script is completely unique — it looks like columns of connected curves flowing downward. If you see vertical text flowing downward alongside Cyrillic, you're in Mongolia. The Cyrillic alone + steppe landscape is usually enough.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Cyrillic road signs","Road quality extremely variable — Ulaanbaatar has decent roads, rural Mongolia often has no roads at all, just dirt tracks across the steppe","Coverage is surprisingly extensive given the landscape — Google drove thousands of km of dirt tracks","Stop signs exist but are sometimes missing entirely in rural areas"],"landb":["Vast open steppe — the defining Mongolia landscape. Flat or gently rolling grassland stretching to the horizon, almost no trees, enormous sky","Gobi Desert in the south — sandy/rocky desert, even more sparse than the steppe","Mountains in the north and west — forested taiga in north, rocky peaks in west","Yurts (gers) visible on the landscape — traditional round felt dwellings, white domes in the steppe. One of the most culturally distinctive tells in GeoGuessr.","Almost no fences, almost no buildings outside Ulaanbaatar","Extreme weather visible — snow-covered steppe in winter coverage, dust in summer"],"car":"Two variants, both unique:","carb":["Camping equipment car — bars on roof PLUS tents, sleeping bags, spare tyres, camping gear piled on. Western Mongolia and Ulaanbaatar: bars filled with black rubber. Eastern Mongolia: bars NOT filled with black rubber. This regional split helps narrow location within Mongolia.","Bars + red side view mirrors — second variant without camping gear but with red mirrors","Snorkel — Mongolia and Kenya are the only two countries with snorkel cars. Mongolia's snorkel distinguishes it from other Cyrillic countries (Russia, Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan all lack snorkel)."],"mu":[{"c":"Kyrgyzstan","k":"also Cyrillic, also Central Asian mountains, also has bars visible on car. Key splits: Kyrgyzstan has red stripe on license plates (Mongolia has none). Kyrgyzstan has visible side mirrors + bars; Mongolia has camping gear. Kyrgyzstan is more mountainous."},{"c":"Russia","k":"also Cyrillic, also vast landscape. Key splits: Russia has forests (taiga) in most of its coverage; Mongolia is open treeless steppe. Russia has red car with antenna in many areas."},{"c":"Kazakhstan","k":"also Cyrillic, also steppe. Key splits: Kazakhstan has no camping gear car, no snorkel. Kazakhstan plates are different."}],"ex":["The camping equipment car is one of the most famous and beloved metas in all of GeoGuessr — learn the image and you'll never miss Mongolia again","Yurts/gers on the open steppe are the most culturally specific tell — if you see white dome structures in a treeless grassland with Cyrillic signs, commit to Mongolia","The bar rubber fill meta (black rubber = west/UB, no rubber = east) is a niche but real regional guessing tool","Ulaanbaatar is a dense city with Soviet architecture backdrop of mountains — very distinctive capital","Mongolia's coverage of remote steppe roads is extraordinary — you can literally be dropped in the middle of nowhere with no roads visible"]},{"id":"macau","n":"Macau","f":"🇲🇴","co":"Asia","qt":["Traditional Chinese + Portuguese bilingual signs — Macau is the ONLY place in GeoGuessr with Chinese + Portuguese together. This combination is completely unique globally.","Black license plates with white lettering — the fastest single Macau confirm. Shared with Tunisia in Africa but context makes confusion impossible.","Gen 2 camera — halo visible in sky, blurrier image quality. Most HK coverage is Gen 3; Macau is mostly Gen 2.","Entirely urban — Macau is 100% built-up city, no rural or natural areas in coverage","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"Traditional Chinese + Portuguese on every official sign — this is globally unique. No other territory combines these two languages on road signs. If you see Chinese characters alongside Portuguese words like \"Rua\" (street), \"Avenida\" (avenue), \"Travessa\" (lane), or \"Largo\" (square) — you're in Macau. The Portuguese street naming convention (Rua de X, Avenida de Y) is immediately recognisable.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (Portuguese colonial convention maintained)","Chinese + Portuguese bilingual signage on all street signs and directional signs","Road markings: white lines or white centre with yellow shoulders","Parking meters very common — Macau is known for having many parking meters","Dense urban road network — tiny territory, everything packed tightly","Road quality good"],"landb":["100% urban — Macau is one of the most densely populated territories on Earth. There is no nature, no countryside, no open land in coverage.","Casino resort architecture — massive casino hotels (visible Venetian, MGM, Lisboa hotels)","Portuguese colonial architecture on the Macau Peninsula — pastel-coloured buildings, cobblestone streets, colonial-era churches and forts","Cotai Strip: massive casino resort complex on reclaimed land between Taipa and Coloane islands","The famous ruins of St. Paul's Cathedral facade is a landmark visible in some coverage"],"car":"Gen 2 — halo visible in sky, blurrier image quality. This directly contrasts Hong Kong which has Gen 3. The Gen 2 halo + Chinese+Portuguese signs = immediate Macau confirm. Standard car otherwise.","mu":[{"c":"Hong Kong","k":"most obvious confusion. Both dense Chinese cities, both left-hand. Key splits: Macau has Portuguese on signs (HK has English). Macau has black plates (HK has compact rectangular plates). Macau has Gen 2 halo (HK has Gen 3 clear sky)."},{"c":"Portugal","k":"also Portuguese language, but Portugal is in Europe with completely different architecture and Latin script only (no Chinese)"},{"c":"Brazil","k":"also Portuguese, but Brazil is right-hand traffic, Latin script only, completely different look"}],"ex":["Chinese + Portuguese is the single fastest Macau confirm in the world — the moment you see \"Rua\" or \"Avenida\" next to Chinese characters, it's Macau","Black plates visible at blur distance — memorise this","The Gen 2 halo is very reliable — HK and Macau look similar but the halo immediately confirms Macau","Casino architecture (The Venetian, MGM Grand, etc.) is sometimes visible — confirms Cotai Strip area specifically","Cobblestone streets in old Macau Peninsula feel distinctly Portuguese-European","Macau is tiny — the whole territory fits in a few square kilometres, so coverage area is very limited"]},{"id":"oman","n":"Oman","f":"🇴🇲","co":"Asia","qt":["Yellow license plates — private vehicles in Oman use yellow plates, unique in the Arabian Peninsula. Red plates for commercial vehicles, white for state/diplomatic. Yellow plates + Arabic = Oman.","Arabic + English bilingual signs — standard throughout the country","Black and white striped sign poles — most signs in Oman are mounted on black and white striped poles, very consistent","White truck Google car with closely-spaced bars on the back and an antenna on the front","Dramatically mountainous for a Gulf country — the Hajar mountains are steep, rocky, and dramatic. Unlike UAE or Qatar which are flat."],"ls":"Arabic is the official language, appearing on all official signs. English appears alongside Arabic on most road signs and directional signs. The Arabic+English bilingual setup is similar to UAE and Qatar, but yellow plates distinguish Oman immediately.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Black and white striped sign poles — the most consistent Oman road infrastructure tell","Yellow side lines with some white — paved roads predominantly use yellow outer lines","Road quality decent on main roads; some rural roads unpaved","Guard rails with red-only reflectors — distinguishes from most countries that use red+yellow or red+white combinations","Coverage is reasonable along main roads and cities but large rural sections have no official coverage or use unofficial Ari contributors"],"landb":["Hajar Mountains — dramatic, rocky, steep limestone mountains in northeast Oman. Very different from the flat Gulf states. Dramatic wadis (dry river valleys) cutting through the mountains.","Muscat area: coastal city between mountains and sea, very modern infrastructure, white/beige buildings, palm trees","Salalah (south): completely different — monsoon-influenced, green, tropical-feeling in summer. Unique in Arabia.","Desert interior: sandy/rocky desert, vast and empty","Most houses surrounded by walls matching the house colour scheme — very modern squared-off architecture","Very clean and well-maintained for the region"],"car":"White truck with bars on the back supporting the camera, with the bars positioned closely together. Also has an antenna on the front. Various levels of blur visible on the truck. This truck is distinctive and relatively unusual — not a standard sedan.","mu":[{"c":"UAE","k":"also Arabic+English, also Gulf region. Key splits: UAE has no yellow plates (white plates), UAE has extreme modern wealth/skyscrapers, UAE is flat. Oman has yellow plates and mountains."},{"c":"Jordan","k":"also Arabic, also mountainous. Key splits: Jordan has a black camera car; Oman has a white truck. Jordan has no yellow plates. Jordan landscape is more desert-rocky beige; Oman has more dramatic limestone mountains."},{"c":"Saudi Arabia","k":"also Arabic, also Arabian Peninsula, but SA has almost no GeoGuessr coverage and no yellow plates"},{"c":"Qatar","k":"also Arabic+English Gulf state, but Qatar is completely flat and has a white truck car similar to UAE/Senegal. No yellow plates in Qatar."}],"ex":["Yellow plates are the single fastest Oman confirm in the Middle East — they're visible even at blur distance","Black-and-white striped sign poles are extremely consistent throughout the country","The Hajar Mountains coverage is dramatically different from any other Gulf country — if you see steep rocky limestone canyons with Arabic signs, it's Oman","Salalah (southern Oman) is unique — it has monsoon climate and looks almost tropical, completely unlike the rest of Oman or any other Gulf state","Oman was added to GeoGuessr relatively recently (2024) — coverage is growing but still has large gaps","Red-only guardrail reflectors are a useful supporting tell on mountain roads"]},{"id":"philippines","n":"Philippines","f":"🇵🇭","co":"Asia","qt":["Jeepneys — brightly decorated elongated jeep-style buses with colourful artwork. Completely unique to the Philippines. If you see a jeepney, you're in the Philippines.","Tricycles (motorbike + sidecar) — motorbike taxi with a covered sidecar attached. Extremely common on every road.","Wooden crucifix-style utility poles — the most common pole type in the Philippines is a wooden pole shaped like a cross/crucifix. Very distinctive.","English language on signs — the Philippines is the only country in Southeast Asia where English is an official language and appears prominently on road signs","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"English + Filipino (Tagalog) — both official languages. English appears on virtually all official road signs, making the Philippines the only predominantly English-signage country in Southeast Asia. Filipino/Tagalog uses Latin script with similar words to Spanish in many cases. You may see Spanish loanwords on signs (barangay, plaza, etc.). If you're in Southeast Asia and see primarily English on signs = Philippines.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","English on all official signage — this immediately distinguishes from every other Southeast Asian country","Rectangular concrete block roads — many roads are built with rectangular concrete paving blocks rather than asphalt. Very common and distinctive texture.","European-style warning signs with thin red borders — triangular red-border warning signs","Red and white chevrons on some roads — shared with Sri Lanka in Asia","Varied road quality — main roads decent, rural roads often rough or unpaved"],"landb":["Tropical archipelago — 7,000+ islands, tropical everywhere. Lush green vegetation, palm trees, rice paddies","Very mountainous on larger islands — volcanic peaks, dramatic terrain","Coastal areas: tropical beaches, turquoise water, fishing villages","Very densely populated — busy roads, lots of people, street commerce everywhere","Basketball courts/hoops visible on virtually every street and barangay (neighbourhood) — Philippines is obsessed with basketball. A basketball hoop by a road = Philippines.","Election posters/campaign signs plastered everywhere during election season","Dense tropical vegetation mixed with chaotic urban development"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Philippines is identified by jeepneys, tricycles, English signs, and wooden poles.","mu":[{"c":"Indonesia","k":"also right-hand, also tropical archipelago, also Southeast Asia. Key splits: Indonesia uses Indonesian language (Latin script, different from English). Indonesia has different utility poles (3-upward-bulb style). No jeepneys in Indonesia."},{"c":"Malaysia","k":"also right-hand in peninsular Malaysia. Key splits: Malaysia uses Malay (BERHENTI on stop signs, not STOP), black-white striped poles vs wooden crucifix poles."},{"c":"Guam/CNMI","k":"also English, also right-hand, also Pacific. But those are tiny US territories with different infrastructure."},{"c":"Sri Lanka","k":"both have red-white chevrons in Asia. Key split: Sri Lanka is left-hand traffic; Philippines is right-hand."}],"ex":["Jeepneys are 100% confidence Philippines — no other country has them. Learn the shape (elongated, colourful, decorative).","Tricycles (motorbike + sidecar) are also very consistent — they appear on virtually every road in every town","Basketball hoops by roads is a famously specific Philippines sub-tell — the country plays basketball everywhere","Jollibee fast food restaurants (red-and-yellow, bee mascot) are extremely common — a strong commercial tell","The concrete block road texture is very distinctive if you notice it — much more common here than anywhere else in Southeast Asia","English signs in a tropical Southeast Asian context = Philippines with very high confidence"]},{"id":"pakistan","n":"Pakistan","f":"🇵🇰","co":"Asia","qt":["Trekker coverage (person on foot) — Pakistan's coverage was NOT captured by a Google car. You pan down and see the outline of a person walking. No car visible anywhere.","Coverage is almost exclusively religious monuments and historic sites — mosques, temples, forts, Mughal architecture. Almost all coverage in Lahore.","Urdu/Arabic-style script — Urdu uses Nastaliq Arabic script, flowing right-to-left with distinctive diagonal strokes","Very limited coverage — only about two dozen historical sites, mostly in Lahore","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Urdu uses the Nastaliq variant of Arabic script — very flowing, calligraphic, with dramatic diagonal strokes going from upper-left to lower-right. This distinctive diagonal flow distinguishes Urdu/Nastaliq from standard Arabic (which is more horizontal). Signs also appear in English in some locations. Urdu + trekker POV + Mughal/Islamic architecture = Pakistan.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Coverage is trekker-only — no road coverage at all","Occasional concrete or metal poles visible in the parking lot/approach areas of monuments","Some parking lot coverage shows license plates occasionally"],"landb":["Mughal/Islamic architecture — the coverage is almost entirely ornate mosques, mausoleums and Mughal-era buildings. Lahore Fort, Badshahi Mosque, Shalimar Gardens etc.","Red brick and sandstone construction typical of Mughal architecture","Ornate tilework, arched gateways, formal gardens with fountains","Lahore is a dense, hot, dusty city — some glimpses of urban environment around monument edges"],"car":"Trekker (person walking) — when panning down you see the person's outline/silhouette rather than a car. This is the defining Pakistan meta. Coverage is almost entirely within or immediately around historical sites in Lahore. Only a handful of other locations exist nationally.","mu":[{"c":"India","k":"also South Asian, also uses unofficial/trekker-style coverage. Key splits: India's unofficial camera has a distinctive foggy quality; Pakistan's trekker shows a clear walking person outline. India has much more coverage; Pakistan has almost none outside Lahore monuments."},{"c":"Bangladesh","k":"also uses Bengali/Urdu-adjacent script region. But Bangladesh has car coverage and very different landscapes."},{"c":"Iran","k":"also Nastaliq/Arabic script but Iran has far more road coverage and Persian language."}],"ex":["If you're dropped in what looks like an ornate Islamic/Mughal monument with trekker POV and Urdu-style script = Lahore, Pakistan, almost certainly","The Badshahi Mosque and Lahore Fort are iconic and recognisable if you study them","Pakistan's coverage is so limited that memorising the ~24 specific locations is genuinely a valid strategy for competitive play","Some parking lots outside monuments have car coverage and show plates","Coverage areas include: Lahore (majority), plus a few scattered sites elsewhere"]},{"id":"qatar","n":"Qatar","f":"🇶🇦","co":"Asia","qt":["White truck visible when panning down — similar to UAE and Senegal. Qatar features a white truck beneath you when you pan down.","Arabic + English bilingual signs — all official signs in both languages","Black and white freshly-painted curbs — Qatari roads are consistently surrounded by very neat black-and-white painted kerb stones. One of the most reliable Qatar tells.","License plates with a narrow maroon band on the left — Qatar plates are long and elongated with this distinctive maroon/dark-red strip","Extreme wealth and modernity — Qatar is one of the richest countries per capita on Earth. Infrastructure is immaculate."],"ls":"Arabic and English both on all official signage. Signs in Qatar are typically written in both Arabic and English — this includes street signs, stop signs, and directional signs. The bilingual Arabic+English setup is shared with UAE and Jordan, but Qatar is distinguished by car meta, plates, and extreme wealth.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Arabic + English on all signs including stop signs","Black and white freshly-painted curb stones — very consistent throughout the country, look neat and recently maintained","Road quality excellent — some of the best road infrastructure in the world","Very wide roads with multiple lanes","Roundabouts common in older residential areas of Doha"],"landb":["Entirely flat — Qatar is a small peninsula with essentially no elevation change. Completely flat desert.","Doha dominates the coverage — massive modern skyline, glass skyscrapers, luxury developments","Desert outside Doha — flat sandy/gravelly semi-desert","Palm trees in urban areas (planted)","Overall feel: extremely modern, clean, wealthy, very flat — similar to UAE but smaller and more compact","The Doha skyline (West Bay area) with its distinctive skyscrapers on the waterfront is recognisable"],"car":"White truck visible when panning down — same general type as UAE. Qatar, UAE, and Senegal all share this white truck appearance, but context and other clues distinguish them easily. Qatar = Arabic+English signs, black-white kerbs, maroon plate strip, flat desert, extreme wealth.","mu":[{"c":"UAE","k":"most similar. Both Arabic+English, both Gulf, both very wealthy, both white truck. Key splits: UAE has black-and-white striped poles (Qatar doesn't). UAE plates are plain white; Qatar plates have maroon strip. UAE coverage centres on Dubai (massive, diverse); Qatar centres on Doha (compact, recognisable skyline)."},{"c":"Bahrain","k":"also tiny Gulf state, also Arabic+English, but Bahrain has minimal GeoGuessr coverage"},{"c":"Kuwait","k":"also Gulf, also Arabic+English, but very limited coverage"},{"c":"Jordan","k":"Arabic but has black car, different landscape (mountains), not flat"}],"ex":["The black-and-white freshly-painted kerbs are the fastest Qatar ground-level confirm — very consistent","Maroon plate strip is subtle but visible at blur distance if you look carefully — long, elongated plate with dark band on left","Qatar is tiny — the whole country is smaller than Connecticut. Coverage is predominantly Doha.","The 2022 FIFA World Cup infrastructure is visible — new stadiums, roads, metro system","Qatar feels slightly less dramatically wealthy than Dubai specifically — Doha is impressive but not the same scale as Dubai's skyscrapers"]},{"id":"singapore","n":"Singapore","f":"🇸🇬","co":"Asia","qt":["Pale green street name signs with spaced-out bold font — Singapore's street signs have a completely unique pale/mint green background with distinctive wide-spaced bold lettering. Unmistakable once learned.","Four official languages on signs — English, Chinese, Malay, and Tamil all appear. Quadrilingual signage is essentially unique.","Extremely clean, modern, wealthy — Singapore is one of the wealthiest and most orderly cities in the world. Immaculate infrastructure, no litter, everything looks maintained.","Square warning signs — Singapore's warning signs look like standard European triangular signs but in square shape. Unique in the world.","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"English + Chinese + Malay + Tamil — four official languages. English dominates street names and official signs. Chinese (Traditional), Malay (Latin script), and Tamil all appear on various signs and shop fronts. This quadrilingual mix is essentially unique to Singapore (occasionally seen in urban Malaysia but far less common). If you see four different scripts on the same sign — you're in Singapore.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Pale/mint green street name signs with bold, spaced-out font — this is the single fastest Singapore confirm","Square warning signs (not triangular like everywhere else) — unique in the world","Road quality is flawless — Singapore maintains some of the best roads on Earth","Signal poles punched with holes — holey signal poles","Traffic lights often arch horizontally over roads — overhead gantry traffic lights","White/yellow plates — can have black plates too. Front and rear plates white or yellow.","Black-white striped curbs in some areas"],"landb":["100% urban — Singapore is a city-state. There is no countryside, no agriculture, no wilderness in coverage.","Extremely green despite being urban — Singapore plants trees on every road and building, tropical trees lining every street","Ultra-modern architecture, glass towers, luxury shopping malls","Hawker centres (open-air food courts) visible roadside — cultural tell","Perfectly maintained tropical urban environment — feels like the cleanest city in the world","Some coverage in nature reserves (Bukit Timah, Sungei Buloh) but mostly urban roads"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Singapore is identified by signs, language, and infrastructure quality.","mu":[{"c":"Malaysia","k":"most similar. Both left-hand, both tropical, both English+Malay on signs. Key splits: Malaysia uses \"BERHENTI\" on stop signs; Singapore uses \"STOP\". Malaysia has black-backed plates (two white sections); Singapore has white/yellow plates. Malaysia's road signs are different colour/style. Singapore's pale green street signs don't appear in Malaysia."},{"c":"Hong Kong","k":"also dense, also left-hand, also multilingual. Key splits: HK has Traditional Chinese + English (no Malay/Tamil). HK has red-green taxis. HK has yellow road number shields."},{"c":"Australia","k":"also left-hand, also English, also modern. But Australia has completely different landscape and very different signage style."}],"ex":["The pale mint green street signs with spaced-out bold font are absolutely the fastest Singapore confirm — memorise that colour and font","Square warning signs (not triangular) are a strong supporting tell — if you see a square warning sign, you're in Singapore","Singapore is so small and so consistently urban that once you know what Singapore looks like, you'll never miss it","The quadrilingual signage (English + Chinese + Malay + Tamil) sometimes appears on the same sign — very distinctive","Coverage is excellent throughout the island-state","Everything feels impossibly clean and ordered compared to any other Southeast Asian country"]},{"id":"thailand","n":"Thailand","f":"🇹🇭","co":"Asia","qt":["Thai script — abundance of small circles at the ends of characters. The circular tail/loop at the end of most Thai letters is the key recognition feature. Very flowing, looping script. Unique to Thailand.","Left-hand traffic — rules out Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam (all right-hand) immediately","Yellow road lines — dashed yellow inner lines with solid yellow outer lines on most roads. Left-hand + yellow lines + Thai script = Thailand.","Square black-and-white alternating bollards — distinctive shape, different from other Southeast Asian bollards","Wooden signposts painted white with a black section at the base — very consistent across the country"],"ls":"Thai script — the key recognition feature is circles at the ends of characters. Most Thai letters have a small circular loop/tail. This is more pronounced and complete circles than Lao (which looks similar but has fewer circles). Thai is only used in Thailand. Once you can recognise the circular tails, you'll never confuse Thai with anything else. Thai + left-hand = Thailand with very high confidence.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Yellow centre lines — dashed yellow inner line, solid yellow outer lines. Left-hand traffic with yellow lines is rare globally and almost unique to Thailand.","White wooden signposts with black painted base — very consistent roadside post style","Blue directional signs for directions","Road markings can also be white on some roads","Road quality varies — highways very good, rural roads rough","Thai milestones — white posts with script on 3 sides; side facing road shows a bird with road number"],"landb":["Tropical — lush, humid, palm trees everywhere, thick vegetation","Rice paddies very common — flooded paddy fields are one of the most iconic Thailand landscapes","Varied terrain: flat central plains (rice paddies), mountainous north (Chiang Mai area), tropical south (peninsula towards Malaysia)","Buddhist temples (wats) everywhere — ornate gold spires visible from roads","Very thin and long street light poles — distinctive tall thin streetlights throughout urban areas","Tropical fruit trees, rubber plantations, oil palm in south"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Thailand is identified by script, road markings, bollards, and landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Cambodia","k":"most difficult split. Khmer script looks similar to Thai but Khmer has right-pointing hooks while Thai has circles/loops. Cambodia is right-hand; Thailand is left-hand. This traffic direction split is the fastest confirm."},{"c":"Laos","k":"also similar script (Lao looks like Thai), but Laos is right-hand traffic, has yellow plates, and has very limited coverage"},{"c":"Malaysia","k":"also left-hand, also tropical. Key splits: Malaysia uses Malay (Latin script, BERHENTI signs), different bollards, no yellow road lines."},{"c":"Sri Lanka","k":"also left-hand, also tropical. Key splits: Sri Lanka uses Sinhala (C-shaped letters, not circles), yellow rear plates, red blur on Gen 3 car."}],"ex":["Circles in Thai script + left-hand traffic = immediate Thailand confirm","Yellow road lines on left-hand roads are very rare globally — Thailand is the primary example","Buddhist temple gold spires (prangs, chedis) are culturally distinctive and visible from roads in many areas","The square black-white bollards are distinctive and reliable","Thin, very tall street light poles are a strong urban Thailand tell","Thailand has excellent coverage nationwide including rural areas"]},{"id":"turkey","n":"Turkey","f":"🇹🇷","co":"Europe","qt":["Turkish language with distinctive characters: ş, ç, ğ, ı, ö, ü — Turkish uses a modified Latin alphabet. The most distinctive characters: ş (s with cedilla hook underneath), ğ (g with breve — looks like g with a u-shape on top), and ı (dotless i — looks like a lowercase l). These appear constantly in common words. ş or ğ on a sign = Turkey.","White Google car (or no car visible) — Turkey's Street View car is white, unlike the standard coloured cars of Europe.","Red and white road arrows/chevrons — Turkish road curve arrows are red and white. Distinctive colour combination.","EU-style white plates with blue strip — Turkey uses EU-format plates (despite not being EU) with a blue strip. The country code shows TR.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Turkish — Turkic language, Latin script since 1928 (Atatürk's reform). Unique characters: Street vocabulary: cadde/caddesi (avenue), sokak/sokağı (street), mahalle (neighbourhood), köy (village).","lb":["ş — s with cedilla (very common: şehir = city, şimdi = now)","ç — c with cedilla (shared with Romanian/Albanian but very common in Turkish: çok = many)","ğ — g with breve (silent/lengthening letter: dağ = mountain, bağ = vineyard)","ı — dotless i (looks like l: ılık = lukewarm)","ö, ü — shared with German but context is different"],"rb":["Right-hand traffic","White Google car (or in some areas no visible car)","Red/white road arrows on curves — distinctive","EU-format white plates with TR blue strip","Blue directional signs with white text (similar to EU standard)","Road quality highly variable — Istanbul/major cities excellent; rural Anatolia rough"],"car":"White car — Turkey's Street View car is white. Supporting meta when visible. Some older coverage has no car visible.","mu":[{"c":"Greece","k":"neighbouring, similar Mediterranean landscape in western Turkey. Key splits: Greece uses Greek alphabet; Turkey uses Latin with ş/ğ/ı. Turkey drives on the right; Greece also drives on the right — language is the split."},{"c":"Albania","k":"also Latin, also uses ç. Key splits: Albania has sky rifts; Turkey doesn't. Albanian language very different (has ë, xh, gj); Turkish has ş, ğ, ı."},{"c":"Romania","k":"also Latin, also uses ş (though Romanian ș has a comma below not cedilla). Key splits: Romanian landscape and architecture very different. Romanian also has ă, ț."}],"ex":["ş or ğ on any sign = Turkey, immediately — these characters do not appear in any other GeoGuessr country","ı (dotless i) is the fastest single-character Turkey confirm — it appears constantly and is visually unique","Turkey spans Europe and Asia — Istanbul has European and Asian sides separated by the Bosphorus","Turkey has excellent nationwide coverage including rural Anatolia","The Cappadocia region (central Anatolia) is one of the most visually extraordinary landscapes in all of GeoGuessr — impossible to mistake once you know it"]},{"id":"taiwan","n":"Taiwan","f":"🇹🇼","co":"Asia","qt":["Traditional Chinese + English OR Traditional Chinese only on green signs — green directional signs with white text, sometimes bilingual Mandarin/English","Flower-shaped freeway number shields — National Freeways numbered 1–10 are shown inside a distinctive white flower/plum blossom shape on green signs. Completely unique globally.","Diagonal black and yellow stripes running ALL THE WAY to the ground on utility poles — key split from Japan (vertical stripes) and South Korea (diagonal but NOT reaching ground)","Blue rectangle with letter+number code on utility poles — the first letter (e.g. K, E, N) indicates which region of Taiwan you're in. Massive regional guessing tool.","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"Traditional Chinese — same complex characters as Hong Kong and Macau, but Taiwan uses Traditional (not Simplified like mainland China). Signs are either Chinese-only or bilingual Chinese+English. Very little English relative to Hong Kong. Chinese characters are complex with many strokes. Key distinguisher from Japan: Japanese mixes simple curvy kana symbols (ノ, シ, い) with complex kanji — Taiwan/Chinese has complex characters only, no simple curvy symbols.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (unlike mainland China which is right-hand)","Green directional signs with white text and English subtitles on major roads","Flower/plum blossom freeway number shield — white flower shape on green background with a number inside","Cylindrical utility poles with diagonal black-and-yellow stripes extending all the way to the ground — distinctive diagonal pattern, reaching ground (Japan's are vertical, Korea's diagonal but stop before ground)","Blue rectangle on poles with letter+number grid coordinate — first letter tells you the region","Full-width white plates with black text"],"landb":["Mountainous island — the Central Mountain Range runs north-south through the island, dramatic high peaks","Western plains: flat agricultural, rice paddies, dense urban areas","Eastern coast: dramatic cliffs dropping straight to Pacific Ocean, very spectacular","Tropical in south (Kaohsiung area), subtropical in north (Taipei)","Dense tropical vegetation, palm trees in south","Taipei: modern dense city with distinctive 101 skyscraper visible in some coverage"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Taiwan is identified by pole stripes, signs, and language.","mu":[{"c":"China (mainland)","k":"also Traditional Chinese characters but mainland uses Simplified. Key splits: China is right-hand; Taiwan is left-hand. Green freeway signs in China don't have flower shields. Different pole styles."},{"c":"Hong Kong","k":"also Traditional Chinese, also left-hand. Key splits: HK has English prominently + red-green taxis + yellow road shields. Taiwan has far less English, flower freeway shields, diagonal pole stripes."},{"c":"Japan","k":"both left-hand, both East Asian. Key splits: Japanese mixes simple kana with complex kanji — Taiwan has Chinese characters only. Japan has yellow plates; Taiwan has white plates. Japan poles have vertical stripes; Taiwan poles have diagonal stripes all the way to ground."}],"ex":["The flower/plum blossom freeway shield is one of the most distinctive road signs in all of GeoGuessr — learn it","The blue rectangle letter code on poles is an incredible regional tool: K=Kaohsiung area, E=Eastern, N=Northern, etc. — a whole geography system encoded in the poles","Left-hand traffic in Taiwan is often surprising given the mainland China connection — always check traffic direction","Taiwan has excellent coverage nationwide","The diagonal full-ground pole stripes are the fastest Japan vs Taiwan split when you can't read the script"]},{"id":"vietnam","n":"Vietnam","f":"🇻🇳","co":"Asia","qt":["Motorbike coverage — all of Vietnam's official Street View was captured on a motorbike. You can see the rider's crash helmet above the blur when panning up. The motorbike outline or blur is visible below. Completely unique in GeoGuessr.","Vietnamese language — Latin script with heavy diacritics (tone marks and vowel modifiers stacked above and below letters). Looks like: Thành phố, đường, phường. Multiple marks on single letters. Unmistakable once seen.","LEGACY STATUS — Vietnam has officially requested removal of its coverage from Google Maps. Coverage may be unavailable or very limited in current GeoGuessr depending on map updates.","Right-hand traffic","European-style triangular warning signs with red border and yellow fill — shared only with South Korea in Asia"],"ls":"Vietnamese (Chữ Quốc ngữ) — Latin script but with extensive diacritical marks. Letters can have TWO marks simultaneously (e.g., ộ = o + circumflex + dot below). The density of accent marks on every word is the key recognition feature. Unlike any other Latin-script language — if you see Latin text with stacked diacritics on almost every vowel, it's Vietnamese. Key words: đường (road/street), phố (street), quận (district), thành phố (city), phường (ward).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","European-style warning signs (red border, yellow fill triangle) — shared only with South Korea in Asia. Distinguishes Vietnam from most Southeast Asian countries.","White road lines throughout","Road quality varies — Ho Chi Minh City and Hanoi have decent roads, provincial areas rough","Coverage was mainly in Ho Chi Minh City, Hanoi, Hue, Hai Phong, Ha Long, and a few other cities — very limited","White full-width license plates with black lettering"],"landb":["Dense urban for most coverage — Ho Chi Minh City and Hanoi are the dominant drops","Ho Chi Minh City: massive, chaotic, dense, tropical, motorbikes everywhere on every road","Hanoi: slightly older feel, more French colonial architecture, also dense","Halong Bay area: dramatic limestone karst islands rising from the sea — one of the most spectacular landscapes in GeoGuessr","Tropical throughout — palm trees, humid, lush vegetation","French colonial architecture visible in both major cities — ornate yellow buildings, wide boulevards"],"car":"Motorbike — the coverage was captured from a motorbike not a car. When panning around you can see:","carb":["The rider's crash helmet above the blur at the top of the screen","The blurred motorbike outline beneath","Sometimes the motorbike is completely blurred out","Different helmet colours and styles were used in different cities — helmet colour was used by the GeoGuessr community to identify which city you were in"],"mu":[{"c":"Cambodia","k":"also right-hand, also Southeast Asia, similar urban feel. Key splits: Khmer script vs Vietnamese Latin+diacritics. Cambodia has standard car coverage; Vietnam has motorbike."},{"c":"Laos","k":"also right-hand, also Southeast Asia. Key splits: Lao script (similar to Thai) vs Vietnamese. Laos has very limited coverage."},{"c":"Taiwan","k":"also uses triangular red-border warning signs (in Asia). Key splits: Taiwan has Traditional Chinese script, left-hand traffic, motorbike vs car."}],"ex":["CRITICAL: As of 2025, Vietnam has requested removal of all official Google Maps coverage. Check whether Vietnam still appears on GeoGuessr World maps before studying it heavily — it may be a legacy country.","The motorbike camera is iconic — the helmet is the fastest Vietnam confirm if coverage still exists","Vietnamese Latin diacritics are very distinctive — ộ, ắ, ề, ụ are good examples of the stacked marks","Ho Chi Minh City's motorbike density on streets is one of the most visually intense urban environments in GeoGuessr","French colonial architecture (yellow buildings, arched windows, wide tree-lined boulevards) is a strong Ho Chi Minh City/Hanoi tell"]},{"id":"andorra","n":"Andorra","f":"🇦🇩","co":"Europe","qt":["Andorran plates — narrow, no EU strip, large red and yellow crest on left — the most reliable Andorra confirm. Plates are slightly narrower than standard EU plates, have no EU blue strip, and instead have a large distinctive red-and-yellow Andorran coat of arms on the left side. Very visible and unique.","Pyrenean mountain valley landscape — Andorra sits entirely within the Pyrenees mountains. All roads are in steep mountain valleys between dramatic peaks. If you see a mountain valley between France and Spain (Pyrenees character) with distinctive plates = Andorra.","Tax-free shopping visible — Andorra is a major tax-haven shopping destination. Duty-free shops, tobacco shops, electronics stores, alcohol shops line main roads. Heavy commercial density in valleys.","Snow poles — green/white or reddish-brown/white striped snow poles mark road edges in mountainous areas. Very common in Andorran mountain coverage.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Catalan — Andorra's sole official language. Catalan looks like a French-Spanish hybrid: carrer (street), avinguda (avenue), plaça (square). French and Spanish are also widely used given Andorra's position between the two countries. The combination of Catalan + Pyrenean mountains + distinctive plates = Andorra.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Andorran plates with red/yellow crest on left, no EU strip","Catalan (+ French + Spanish) on signs","Snow poles (green/white striped) on mountain road edges","French and Spanish cars with EU blue strips also visible (many tourists)","Road quality good — Andorra invests in infrastructure given tourist traffic"],"landb":["Entirely mountainous — Andorra is one of Europe's most mountainous countries. All roads are in valleys between steep peaks.","Pyrenees character — dramatic, rocky, snowy in winter, green alpine meadows in summer","Dense commercial development in main valleys (particularly the capital Andorra la Vella)","Ski resort infrastructure visible — Andorra is a major ski destination","Small country (~468 km²) — all coverage is within a few narrow valleys"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Andorra is identified by plates and mountain valley landscape.","mu":[{"c":"France (Pyrenees)","k":"same mountain range, similar landscape. Key splits: Andorra has distinctive crest plates with no EU strip; French cars have standard EU plates. Andorran signs have Catalan (not French)."},{"c":"Spain (Pyrenees / Catalonia)","k":"similar landscape, similar Catalan language. Key splits: Spanish cars have standard EU plates; Andorran plates have the crest. Very similar feel otherwise."}],"ex":["Andorran plates with the red/yellow crest are unmistakable once you know them — the fastest Andorra confirm","The heavy duty-free commercial signage (tobacco shops, electronics, alcohol) is a very strong cultural tell — nowhere else in Europe has this density of tax-haven retail on main roads","Andorra la Vella (capital) is one of the highest capitals in Europe at ~1,023m elevation","Coverage is very limited — a handful of main valley roads"]},{"id":"albania","n":"Albania","f":"🇦🇱","co":"Europe","qt":["Sky rifts — visible camera stitching errors in the sky, shared only with Montenegro and Senegal","License plates with blue vertical stripes on BOTH left and right edges (most of Europe only has left)","Latin script with ë and ç — unique in the Balkans, rules out all Cyrillic neighbours","Loads of old Mercedes-Benz on the roads — unusually dominant for one car brand","Unfinished brick/concrete houses everywhere alongside the road — very consistent poverty tell"],"ls":"Latin alphabet. Key unique letters: ë, ç, q, j, k appear very frequently. Word for street is rrugë/rruga. Road numbers use prefix SH (Rruga Shtetërore). Bold, rounded-corner font on street signs is distinctive. Rules out all Slavic/Greek neighbours immediately.","rb":["Road markings mostly white, but yellow solid lines can split traffic (unusual for Europe)","Directional signs: blue background, white text, arrow forms the side of the sign","Warning signs: standard red/white triangles","Road prefixes: SH for national roads, E for European routes","Roads vary hugely — main roads fine, rural roads can be very poor quality"],"landb":["Dramatic high mountains and deep valleys, rocky but lush","South Albania feels Mediterranean — palm trees, dry rocky hills, can resemble Turkey/Jordan","Many unfinished brick or concrete buildings under construction along roadsides","One of the poorer-looking countries in Europe visually — rough infrastructure is a consistent tell"],"carb":["Mix of Gen 3 (white car) and Gen 4 (white or red pickup truck — white = July coverage, red = August coverage)","Coverage is limited — stick to main roads, rural areas often have no coverage","Sky rifts (camera stitching artifacts visible when panning up) are the single most famous Albania tell"],"mu":[{"c":"Montenegro","k":"also has sky rifts, but uses Cyrillic script (rules out instantly with any text visible)"},{"c":"North Macedonia","k":"similar poverty level and landscape, but Cyrillic script and different bollards"},{"c":"Greece","k":"similar Mediterranean south, but Greek alphabet"},{"c":"Italy","k":"both have blue stripes on both sides of plates, but Italy is far wealthier looking and uses Italian"},{"c":"Turkey/Jordan","k":"southern Albania landscape can feel similar, check for Latin script with ë/ç"}],"ex":["Taxi plates in Albania are orange/amber coloured — unique identifier","Taxis come in many colours (yellow, green, black, silver) with a sign on top; green taxis = Tirana electric fleet","Bollards: black diagonal stripe extending all the way to the top with a red vertical rectangle inside on front, white rectangle on rear — described as \"Italy-style\" but with the black going to the top","Coverage is unofficial/limited in many areas — you may land on photospheres"]},{"id":"austria","n":"Austria","f":"🇦🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Dark/black reflector bollards with a black \"hat\" on top — Austrian bollards have dark (nearly black) or very dark red reflectors on the front AND a distinctive black rounded top cap. This combination — dark reflector + black hat — is unique to Austria globally. No other country has both features.","ß in text but NOT in a major city — if you see German + ß + rural/alpine landscape = Austria (Germany only has urban coverage; Austrian coverage includes countryside and mountains)","\"EINBAHN\" on blue signs in cities — Austrian one-way street signs say \"EINBAHN\" (German for one-way). Very common in Vienna and other Austrian cities.","Alpine landscape — dramatic mountain peaks, green alpine meadows, wooden chalets, ski infrastructure","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"German throughout — same as Germany, including ä, ü, ö and ß. Key split from Switzerland: Austria uses ß (Switzerland uses \"ss\"). Key split from Germany: Austria has rural/alpine coverage (Germany has only major city coverage). Austrian-specific vocabulary occasionally visible: Gasse (alley), Gürtel (ring road).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Dark/black bollards with black hat and dark reflector — the fastest Austria bollard confirm","EINBAHN one-way signs in cities — blue signs with white EINBAHN text","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Autobahn vignette stickers visible on windshields — Austria requires a motorway sticker","Green motorway signs; blue/white for other routes","Road quality excellent"],"landb":["Alpine — Austria is heavily dominated by the Alps. Dramatic mountain coverage is the norm.","Green alpine meadows (Alm), mountain streams, wooden chalets (Almhütte)","Ski infrastructure visible in many areas — ski lifts, piste signs, resort villages","Wine country in east (Burgenland, Wachau valley along Danube) — vineyards on hillsides","Vienna: grand imperial city, ornate Baroque architecture, Ring road, classical buildings","Eastern Austria (Burgenland, Styria): flatter, more Central/Eastern European feel"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Austria is identified by bollards, landscape, and language context.","mu":[{"c":"Germany","k":"same language, same ß. Key splits: Germany has ONLY city coverage; Austria has extensive rural/alpine coverage. Austrian bollards dark + black hat; German bollards white vertical strip. Alpine landscape = Austria, not Germany."},{"c":"Switzerland","k":"also alpine, also German in most areas. Key splits: Switzerland uses \"ss\" not ß. Swiss plates have NO EU blue strip; Austria has blue strip. Swiss bollards are curved-cylindrical; Austrian are dark with black hat."},{"c":"Slovenia","k":"similar alpine landscape in northwest. Key splits: Slovenia uses Slovenian (Slavic language, not German)."}],"ex":["Dark bollard + black hat combination = Austria, no exceptions — the most reliable single-bollard country confirm in Europe","EINBAHN signs visible on virtually every one-way street in any Austrian city","Alpine landscape + German text + ß = Austria with very high confidence","Vienna is one of the most recognisable cities in GeoGuessr — imperial Ringstraße, Baroque palaces, Rathaus, Opera House","Austrian Tyrol (Innsbruck area): extremely dramatic alpine coverage — some of the most spectacular mountain scenery in European GeoGuessr","Austria has excellent nationwide coverage including remote alpine valleys"]},{"id":"belgium","n":"Belgium","f":"🇧🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Red lettering on EU-format plates — Belgian license plates use the standard European white/blue format BUT the letters and numbers appear in a distinctive red colour (not black). Through blur this appears as a faint red wash on the plate text area. The fastest Belgium plate confirm in Europe.","Bilingual signs — Belgium has three official languages. In Brussels: French + Dutch on same sign. In Flanders: Dutch only. In Wallonia: French only. In the east: German. Bilingual signs (French + Dutch) are a very strong Brussels/Belgium tell.","City name on street signs — in Belgian cities it's common to see the city name printed on street name signs (e.g. \"LIÈGE\" written on the sign). Unusual in Europe.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Three official languages: Brussels: bilingual French/Dutch on all official signs. The bilingual sign combination (Rue / Straat, Avenue / Laan) is a very strong Brussels indicator.","lb":["Dutch (Flemish) — northern Belgium (Flanders). Same as Netherlands Dutch.","French — southern Belgium (Wallonia) and half of Brussels.","German — small eastern area (Eupen-Malmedy)."],"rb":["Right-hand traffic","Red-lettered plates — the defining Belgium plate tell","Standard EU white plates with blue strip (but red text, not black)","Road quality: Belgian roads are famously poor by Western European standards — bumpy, cracked surfaces are a sub-tell","Green directional signs on main routes","No car visible in Google car — Belgium's coverage has no visible car (completely blurred out)"],"landb":["Flat in Flanders (north): looks similar to Netherlands — flat, agricultural, brick housing","Rolling in Ardennes (south): forested, hilly, more dramatic — similar to Luxembourg or eastern France","Dense urban coverage throughout","Red-brick housing very common in Flemish areas","Medieval city centres: Bruges, Ghent, Brussels — distinctive Gothic/Flemish architecture with ornate guild halls"],"car":"No car visible — Belgium's Google car is completely blurred out. When you pan down you see just blur. This is a supporting meta.","mu":[{"c":"Netherlands","k":"also flat in north, also Dutch-speaking in Flanders. Key splits: Netherlands has yellow plates; Belgium has white plates with red text. Netherlands is flatter overall."},{"c":"France","k":"also French-speaking in Wallonia. Key splits: French bollards are distinctive; Belgian infrastructure looks different. Belgian plates have red text; French have black text."},{"c":"Luxembourg","k":"small neighbour, also trilingual. Key splits: Luxembourg has yellow plates; Belgium has white with red text."}],"ex":["Red plate text is THE fastest Belgium confirm — if you can see any plate and notice the text has a reddish tint = Belgium","No visible car (complete blur) is a supporting but not definitive tell","Belgian roads being notably bumpy/potholed is a famous sub-tell — if Western European roads look terrible = Belgium","Brussels bilingual French/Dutch signs are unmistakable once you know them","Belgium has excellent nationwide coverage"]},{"id":"bulgaria","n":"Bulgaria","f":"🇧🇬","co":"Europe","qt":["Cyrillic script — Bulgaria uses Cyrillic alphabet. In the European context this narrows to Russia, Ukraine, Bulgaria, Serbia, Montenegro, North Macedonia, or Belarus. But Bulgaria is the ONLY EU member using Cyrillic. Settlement signs often show place names in BOTH Cyrillic AND Latin scripts.","No distinguishing Cyrillic letters unique to Bulgarian — Bulgarian Cyrillic looks identical to Russian Cyrillic. Use other tells (landscape, bollards, road signs, context) to distinguish Bulgaria from Russia/Ukraine/etc.","Bulgarian bollards: red rectangle on front, white rectangle on rear (centred) — same as Hungarian bollards but in a different country context","Settlement signs in both Cyrillic and Latin — bilingual settlement name signs (Latin + Cyrillic) are a Bulgaria-specific tell (Russia/Ukraine only use Cyrillic)","Blue and green directional signs with bilingual Cyrillic/Latin text","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Bulgarian — South Slavic language using Cyrillic script. No unique Cyrillic characters compared to Russian — the same Cyrillic letters appear. Bulgarian-specific words on signs: улица (ulitsa = street), площад (ploshtad = square), бул. (bul. = boulevard). The key split from Russia: settlement signs in Bulgaria often show names in BOTH scripts (Latin underneath Cyrillic or side by side). Russia never does this.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Bilingual Latin/Cyrillic settlement signs — critical Bulgaria vs Russia split","Blue/green directional signs with Latin AND Cyrillic text","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Bulgarian bollards: red centred rectangle on front","Warning signs: standard European triangular"],"landb":["Varied terrain:","Northern plains (Danube valley): flat, agricultural — can look similar to Romania or Ukraine","Balkan Mountains (central): forested mountain range crossing east-west","Southern Bulgaria (Thrace): warm, dry plains and valleys","Black Sea coast: beach resorts, flat coastal areas","Rhodope Mountains (southwest): beautiful forested mountains, traditional villages","Generally feels like a poorer Southeastern European country — mix of communist-era blocks and older traditional architecture","Mediterranean-adjacent climate in south — drier, sunnier"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Bulgaria is identified by Cyrillic script, bilingual signs, and landscape context.","mu":[{"c":"Russia","k":"most similar Cyrillic. Key splits: Russia uses ONLY Cyrillic on signs (no Latin); Bulgaria has Latin + Cyrillic. Russia has Gen 2 halo in older coverage. Russia is enormous and coverage often looks very different. Russian plates white with no EU strip; Bulgarian plates have EU strip."},{"c":"Serbia","k":"also South Slavic Cyrillic but Serbia also uses Latin in parallel. Key splits: Serbia often uses yellow directional signs; Bulgaria uses blue/green. Serbian bollard has red rectangle off-centre (to left); Bulgarian has centred red rectangle."},{"c":"North Macedonia","k":"also Cyrillic + Latin. Key splits: North Macedonia has yellow directional signs with Cyrillic above Latin; Bulgaria has blue/green signs. North Macedonia uses white elongated plates."},{"c":"Ukraine","k":"also Cyrillic. Key splits: Ukraine has yellow+blue strip on plates; Bulgaria has standard EU strip."}],"ex":["Bilingual Latin+Cyrillic on settlement signs = Bulgaria (not Russia, not Ukraine) — this is the fastest Bulgaria vs Russia split","EU blue strip on plates confirms this is an EU country (Bulgaria, not Russia/Ukraine/Serbia)","Bulgaria has decent nationwide coverage including mountain and coastal areas","Sofia (capital) has good urban coverage — Soviet-era and older mixed architecture"]},{"id":"belarus","n":"Belarus","f":"🇧🇾","co":"Europe","qt":["Cyrillic only, no Latin — same as Russia. Signs are purely Cyrillic, no bilingual Latin translations (unlike Bulgaria, Serbia, North Macedonia).","Standard white EU-format plates with green strip on left — Belarus plates are white with a distinctive green vertical strip on the left (not the standard EU blue). This green strip is unique in Europe and immediately separates Belarus from Russia (plain white) and Ukraine (yellow/blue strip).","Very limited coverage — essentially Minsk only — Belarus has almost no rural coverage. If you're in a flat Eastern European city with Cyrillic-only signs, green-strip plates, and Soviet-era architecture = Minsk, Belarus.","Flat landscape, Soviet architecture — Belarus is extremely flat. Cities dominated by wide Soviet-era boulevards, identical residential tower blocks, and monumental Stalinist architecture.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Belarusian and Russian — both official. Both use Cyrillic. Belarusian has unique letters Ў (short u, looks like u with a breve) and І (dotted i, same as Ukrainian). In practice, Russian is dominant on most signage. The script looks identical to Russian — rely on plates rather than language alone.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","White plates with green strip on left — the primary Belarus plate meta","Cyrillic-only signs","Soviet-era road infrastructure: wide lanes, long straight boulevards","Road quality decent on main roads (Minsk is well-maintained)"],"landb":["Extremely flat — Belarus sits on the East European Plain with almost no elevation change","Dense mixed forest (birch/pine) similar to western Russia","Coverage almost entirely limited to Minsk — one of the best-preserved Soviet-era capitals","Minsk: extraordinarily wide Stalinist boulevards, identical massive apartment blocks, impressive monumental Soviet architecture. Unlike any Western European city.","Very little rural road coverage"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Green-strip plates are the primary confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Russia","k":"most similar Cyrillic country. Key splits: Belarus has green strip on plates; Russia has plain white plates. Russia has black car with long antenna; Belarus has standard car."},{"c":"Ukraine","k":"also Cyrillic, also flat. Key splits: Ukraine has red car + yellow/blue plate strip; Belarus has standard car + green plate strip. Ukrainian unique letters Ї, Є visible on signs."}],"ex":["Green plate strip = Belarus, the fastest single confirm in an Eastern European Cyrillic context","Coverage is extremely limited — if you're somewhere rural and Cyrillic, it's almost certainly Russia or Ukraine, not Belarus","Minsk is one of the most architecturally distinctive Soviet capitals — massive scale, monumental buildings, perfectly preserved Stalinist streetscapes"]},{"id":"switzerland","n":"Switzerland","f":"🇨🇭","co":"Europe","qt":["Low-cam — the single most reliable instant tell. The camera sits noticeably lower than in other countries, causing a larger car blur and making roads appear wider. Only Switzerland, Japan, and Liechtenstein always use low-cam.","License plates are fully white, no EU blue strip — instantly distinguishes Switzerland from all EU neighbors (Germany, France, Austria, Italy all have the blue strip). Front plates are unusually short.","Yellow pedestrian crossings — unique to Switzerland and Liechtenstein in all of Europe.","Long dashed yellow center lines on roads.","Black-and-white bollards — wedge-shaped or cylindrical with a rounded top."],"ls":"Switzerland has four official languages — which one you see immediately narrows your region: Critical: Swiss German never uses ß (unlike Germany and Austria). Seeing German text without ß is a strong CH signal.","lb":["Bilingual areas: Biel/Bienne (DE+FR), parts of Fribourg and Graubünden. Signs show both names.","Romansh place names (e.g. \"Cuira,\" \"Val,\" \"Ova\") are an immediate giveaway — extremely rare in Street View.","Direction signs near borders often show city names in two languages (e.g. \"Bern / Berne\")."],"rb":["Direction sign colors: Blue for main/national roads, white for side roads and local streets.","Round grey metal border frames most Swiss road signs — distinctive compared to neighboring countries.","Town entry signs: White or blue, with a metal frame. Canton abbreviation often visible on the bottom near borders.","Speed limit signs show text in the regional language (e.g. German in the north, French in the west) — useful to confirm language zone.","Chevrons: Black body with a white arrow. Austrian chevrons are red-and-white, so color is a quick differentiator.","Pedestrian crossing signs: 7 stripes, tall blue rectangle (rest of Europe uses a square).","Dashed yellow center lines — long dashes, distinctly yellow.","Yellow pedestrian crossings painted on the road surface.","Bus stop signs: Thick metal frame/signpost wrapping around the sign — unique to Switzerland.","Motorway signs: Green (Germany uses blue).","Postal codes: 4 digits, increasing from west to east (e.g. 1200s in Geneva → 9000s in St. Gallen).","Canton abbreviations (ZH, BE, GE, TI, GR…) appear on town signs and unblurred plates."],"landb":["North/Central (Mittelland): Rolling farmland, gentle hills, densely settled. Forested ridges visible in the distance. This is the most common Street View landscape.","South: Dramatic Alps — steep valleys, snow-capped peaks, glaciers. Long thin valleys between high mountains.","Northwest (Jura): Rounded forested ridges with exposed limestone. Lower than the Alps. Rockwalls along roads are common here.","Ticino: Mediterranean feel — palm trees, terracotta roofs, ochre/yellow plastered walls, Italian-style architecture. Dramatically different from the rest of Switzerland.","Architecture (German CH): Stone buildings in light warm colors, wooden shutters opening in two horizontal halves, tiled gable roofs. Windows always have shutters.","Ticino architecture: Smooth plaster walls (orange-yellow), multi-story, green/brown Italian-style shutters, flatter roofs with terracotta tiles.","Bern area: Large houses with roofs shaped like an arch underneath. Elaborate medieval arcaded streets in the old town.","Northeast (Appenzell): Living house + long barn joined at 90° angle. Facade divided into neat squares, one window per square.","Graubünden: Stone houses with decorative white painted details (Sgraffito) around windows and edges — unmistakable in the Engadin valley.","Northeast: Elaborate red timber frames on houses.","Valais: Thick wooden bollards (square or cylindrical) instead of the standard black-and-white ones."],"carb":["Always low-cam. This is the defining camera characteristic — a noticeably larger car blur and a lower viewing angle vs. standard European coverage.","Gen 2 coverage is extremely limited (a few short stretches near Bern/Valais border and Schaffhausen). Essentially all coverage is Gen 3+.","Trekker (backpack) coverage exists on mountain trails and ski resorts — if you're on a hiking path with a low/tilted POV, likely Switzerland or Austria.","Train trekker: Unique Bernina Express rail coverage exists in Graubünden."],"mu":[{"c":"Liechtenstein","k":"Near-identical: same low-cam, same bollards, same yellow crossings, same pedestrian signs. Check plates (FL prefix in LI). Liechtenstein is tiny — if coverage seems rural/Alpine and all roads feel like one valley, suspect LI."},{"c":"Germany","k":"Blue EU strip on plates; blue motorway signs; uses ß in German text; 5-digit postal codes."},{"c":"Austria","k":"Blue EU strip on plates; red-and-white chevrons; different sign typography; no yellow road lines."},{"c":"France (Romandy confusion)","k":"Blue EU strip on plates; French national road signs are blue/white, not Swiss white."},{"c":"Italy (Ticino confusion)","k":"Italian plates have EU strip; Swiss signs in Ticino still follow CH formatting (white direction signs, metal borders, yellow crossings)."}],"ex":["Yellow PostBus (PostAuto): Bright yellow buses with a black-circle/yellow-horn logo. Ubiquitous in rural Switzerland. If you see one, you're in Switzerland (or possibly Liechtenstein).","SBB/CFF/FFS: Swiss Federal Railways — white arrow on red background. Appears on train station signs.","Yellow hiking trail signs: Distinctive fingerposts showing walking times in hours/minutes. These are everywhere — even in villages — and are a strong Switzerland-specific clue.","Basel-Landschaft: Olive-green infrastructure (signposts, sign borders, sign backs) — distinct from rest of Switzerland.","Geneva/Lake Geneva corridor: Bike path markings use a simplified person on two disconnected wheels — unique to this region.","Glarus: Road reflectors attached directly to fences instead of bollards.","Fruit trees: Highest density in the Martigny valley; also common near Lake Constance.","Lake Geneva: From the north shore — hilly terrain with flat lake and high Alps on the far side.","Lake Constance (Bodensee): Flat, low-lying landscape to the northeast.","Cantonal road divider types vary by canton — plonkit has a detailed map if you want to region-guess from divider style."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_1.png"},{"l":"Language zones","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_6.png"},{"l":"Direction signs","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_4.png"},{"l":"Road lines","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_8.png"},{"l":"Yellow crossing","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_5.png"},{"l":"Bollards","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_7.png"},{"l":"Low-cam example","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_2.png"},{"l":"License plates","f":"Europe_ch_Switzerland_3.png"}]},{"id":"cyprus","n":"Cyprus","f":"🇨🇾","co":"Europe","qt":["Left-hand traffic + Greek alphabet + Mediterranean island — Cyprus is the only country in the world with this combination. Left-hand traffic (British legacy) + Greek script + dry Mediterranean landscape = Cyprus immediately.","Greek alphabet on signs — same script as Greece. Road signs show place names in both Greek and English (bilingual). The Greek alphabet on signs in a left-hand traffic context = Cyprus only (Greece drives on the right).","Standard EU white plates with blue strip — Cyprus is an EU member. Plates are standard European white with blue EU strip.","Dry, rocky Mediterranean landscape — Cyprus is noticeably drier and more rugged than Greece. Rocky limestone hills, sparse scrubby vegetation, very sunny. Troodos mountain range visible in interior.","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"Greek — same alphabet as mainland Greece. Signs are bilingual Greek + English (British influence). Greek alphabet characters: α, β, γ, δ, ε, etc. The combination of Greek script + English bilingual signs + left-hand traffic = Cyprus. Key difference from Greece: Cyprus drives on the left.","rb":["Left-hand traffic — the primary Cyprus vs Greece split","Bilingual Greek + English on most signs","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","British road sign influences (yellow road markings in some areas, similar to Ireland/UK)","Road quality good on main roads"],"landb":["Mediterranean island — dry, rocky, very sunny. Average 300+ sunshine days per year.","Troodos Mountains (centre): up to 1952m — surprisingly dramatic for a Mediterranean island. Forested with pine trees at altitude.","Coastal areas: dry limestone cliffs, clear blue Mediterranean sea, sandy beaches","Mesaoria Plain (north/centre): flat dry agricultural plain","More arid and rocky than mainland Greece — less lush, more bleached dry look","Split island: southern Cyprus (Republic) has GeoGuessr coverage; northern Cyprus (Turkish-occupied) has limited/no coverage"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Left-hand traffic is the primary confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Greece","k":"same Greek alphabet, same Mediterranean landscape. Key splits: Cyprus is left-hand; Greece is right-hand. This single difference is the definitive split."},{"c":"Malta","k":"also left-hand, also Mediterranean island. Key splits: Malta uses Latin script (Maltese/English); Cyprus uses Greek alphabet. Malta is limestone-flat; Cyprus has mountains."}],"ex":["Left-hand + Greek alphabet = Cyprus only, no other country in the world","The English bilingual signs (British colonial legacy) are very consistent — Greek + English on every road sign","Limassol, Nicosia, Paphos, Larnaca all have good coverage","The Troodos mountain roads are among the most scenic coverage in Cyprus"]},{"id":"czech_republic","n":"Czech Republic","f":"🇨🇿","co":"Europe","qt":["Large arrow-shaped directional signs — Czech directional signs are unique: the sign itself is shaped like a large arrow (the sign's border forms the arrowhead pointing in the direction of travel). No other country has this distinctive arrow-shaped sign format.","Czech bollards with fluorescent orange stripes on a black section — Czech bollards have distinctive bright/fluorescent orange diagonal stripes on a black upper section. The fluorescent orange is very visible.","Czech language — uses č, š, ž, ř (c/s/z with háček — inverted circumflex above), á, é, í, ó, ú, ů (long vowels). The ř character (a unique sound combining r and zh) is found ONLY in Czech — no other language uses ř.","Town name signs with thick black outline — Czech town entry/exit signs have a noticeably thick black outline around the border","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Czech — West Slavic language. Uses Latin script with háček diacritics: č, š, ž, ř, ě, ď, ť, ň. The ř is unique to Czech — it appears in common words: řeka (river), ředitel (director), řidič (driver). Other common Czech words on signs: ulice (street), náměstí (square), most (bridge), město (city). Czech looks similar to Slovak but has ř and different vocabulary.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Arrow-shaped directional signs — the sign IS the arrow. This format is unique in Europe.","Fluorescent orange bollard stripes on black — bright, visible from a distance","Thick black outlined town name signs — thicker outline than Slovakia (Slovakia uses thinner outline)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Highway route markers: red oval (expressway) or blue oval","Warning signs: yellow background with red border"],"landb":["Central European: rolling hills, mixed deciduous forest, agricultural plains","Bohemia (west): rolling forested hills, river valleys, historic spa towns","Moravia (east): flatter, more agricultural, vineyards in south (Moravian wine country)","Prague: iconic skyline with castle and Charles Bridge — recognisable if you know it","Czech architecture: mix of medieval, Baroque, and typical Central/Eastern European communist-era blocks","Generally green and well-wooded"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Czechia is identified by arrow signs, bollards, and language (ř character).","mu":[{"c":"Slovakia","k":"most similar. Both West Slavic, both Central European, similar landscape and infrastructure. Key splits: Czech directional signs are arrow-shaped (Slovakia's are rectangular with small white arrows). Czech town signs have thicker black outline (Slovakia thinner). Czech bollards have fluorescent orange (Slovakia bollards have fluorescent orange stripes too but slightly different shade). ř character = Czech only."},{"c":"Poland","k":"also Slavic, also Central European. Key splits: Polish uses different diacritics (ą, ę, ó, ń, ź, ż) — no háčeks; Czech has č, š, ž, ř. Polish bollards have diagonal red stripe."},{"c":"Austria","k":"also sometimes similar rolling landscape. Key splits: Austria uses German (ß, umlauts); Czech uses Czech with háčeks."}],"ex":["Arrow-shaped directional signs are THE fastest Czechia confirm — they appear at every junction","The ř character = Czech only, globally — if you see ř on any sign = Czechia, commit immediately","Fluorescent orange bollard stripes are very visible and distinctive","Czech Republic has excellent nationwide coverage including rural and border areas","Prague is recognisable from the castle (Hradčany) on the hill above the river — distinctive silhouette","Czech beer brands (Pilsner Urquell, Budvar, Kozel) occasionally visible on commercial signs"]},{"id":"germany","n":"Germany","f":"🇩🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["ß (Eszett/sharp S) — the letter ß appears in German and Austrian text. If you see ß on a sign = Germany or Austria (Switzerland uses \"ss\" instead of ß). Combined with landscape/other tells to split Germany from Austria.","Very limited coverage — Germany has almost no rural or small-town coverage due to strong privacy laws. Coverage is mostly major city centres and photospheres. If you appear to be in a German-speaking dense urban environment with old city architecture = Germany.","German bollards — white post with a vertical white strip on the front and two white dots on the rear. The vertical strip is distinctive.","German language — ä, ü, ö umlauts + ß. Words: Straße (street), Weg (way/path), Platz (square), Hauptstraße (main street). German place name suffixes: -burg, -berg, -dorf, -furt, -hausen.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"German uses Latin script with ä, ü, ö (umlauts) and ß (Eszett). The ß appears in many common German words: Straße, heiß, Fußgänger. Key split: Germany/Austria use ß; Switzerland uses ss. German is also spoken in Austria, most of Switzerland, northern Italy (South Tyrol), and a small part of Belgium. German place names ending in -burg, -berg, -dorf, -furt are reliable confirms on any directional sign.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","White bollards with vertical white strip front, two white dots rear","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Autobahn (motorway) signs: blue with white text","Standard European white/blue/green directional signs","Coverage is mostly Gen 4 in major cities (very crisp quality)"],"landb":["Coverage is extremely limited to city centres — you won't see the German countryside in GeoGuessr","Major cities: Berlin (flat, wide boulevards, mix of historic and Soviet-era + modern), Munich (southern, more alpine feel), Hamburg (port city, canals), Frankfurt (skyscrapers), Cologne (cathedral), etc.","City architecture: mix of pre-WWII historic buildings, post-WWII reconstruction (often plainer), and modern","Very clean, well-maintained urban environments","Essentially NO rural coverage"],"car":"Gen 4 in most coverage — very crisp, high quality images in city centres. The extremely high image quality combined with German language in a dense urban environment is itself a clue.","mu":[{"c":"Austria","k":"also German, also ß. Key splits: Austria has much more rural/countryside coverage; Germany has only urban. Austria has distinctive dark-reflector bollards; Germany has white vertical strip bollards. Austrian landscape is alpine/mountainous; German city coverage is flat (Berlin/Hamburg) or varied."},{"c":"Switzerland","k":"also German in most areas. Key splits: Switzerland uses \"ss\" not ß; Switzerland has no EU blue strip on plates; Swiss mountain landscape is extreme."},{"c":"Belgium (east)","k":"small German-speaking area. Key splits: Very rare spawn; Belgian plates have red lettering."}],"ex":["ß = Germany or Austria (never Switzerland) — memorise this split completely","Germany's limited coverage is itself a meta: if you see very limited urban-only coverage in German = Germany","Berlin is flat and has distinctive Soviet-era Plattenbau (concrete panel buildings) in some areas","Munich has a more alpine/Bavarian feel with ornate buildings","The Autobahn (no speed limit sections) doesn't help much since you can't tell from coverage","German is one of Europe's most common languages — don't confuse German-speaking = Germany"]},{"id":"denmark","n":"Denmark","f":"🇩🇰","co":"Europe","qt":["White directional signs with metal/chrome border — Danish direction signs have a distinctive white background with what looks like a metallic frame/border. Completely unique in Europe.","Red and white directional signs — the other major Danish sign type: white background with red text and red arrows. This red-on-white combination for directional signs is unique to Denmark.","Short-dashed white edge lines on roads — Denmark uses distinctively short dashes for road edge markings, shorter than Norway (long dashes) or Sweden (medium dashes)","Yellow commercial vehicle plates (front AND rear) — regular cars have standard EU plates, but commercial vehicles have yellow plates on both ends. Unique in Scandinavia.","Flat landscape — Denmark is one of the flattest countries in Europe. No mountains, no hills over ~170m. If it's Scandinavian but completely flat = Denmark."],"ls":"Danish uses Latin script with å, æ, ø — same special characters as Norwegian. Written Danish and Norwegian are nearly identical visually. Danish-specific vocabulary: vej (road/way), gade (street), plads (square), skov (forest), by (town). The suffix -vej on road names (vs Norwegian -vei) is a subtle written split. Rely on non-language tells to distinguish Denmark from Norway.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","White directional signs with metal border — the fastest Denmark sign confirm","Red-and-white directional signs — secondary direction sign type, also unique","Short-dashed white edge lines — the shortest dash length in Scandinavia","Black-on-white settlement signs with a small village illustration — towns marked with a unique pictographic sign showing a small house/church","Warning signs: red border, white background, NO additional outline (different from Norway which has an outline)","Standard EU white plates; yellow commercial plates on both axles","Abundant bollards — Denmark uses bollards more than any other Nordic country; they have a distinctive yellow front section (yellow on front, grey/white on rear)"],"landb":["Completely flat — the defining Danish landscape. Rolling gently at most, but genuinely flat by European standards. Zero mountains.","Agricultural, with orderly fields, hedgerows, and windbreaks","Deciduous trees (beech forests are iconic in Denmark — smooth grey trunks, very distinctive)","Coastal — Denmark is a peninsula + islands, always near the sea","Red-brick farmhouses and traditional Danish architecture","Wind turbines very common — Denmark is a world leader in wind energy","Generally looks like a very tidy, prosperous flat European farming country"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Denmark is identified by signs, road lines, flat landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Norway","k":"same script, same special characters. Key splits: Norway is mountainous; Denmark is flat. Norway has yellow directional signs; Denmark has white/metal border + red-white signs. Norway has long-dashed edge lines; Denmark has short-dashed."},{"c":"Netherlands","k":"also very flat, also prosperous Northern European. Key splits: Dutch uses different language (geen, straat, weg); Danish uses æ/ø. Different road sign styles."},{"c":"Germany (northern)","k":"also flat in some areas, also German-adjacent. Key splits: German uses different language (Straße, no æ/ø)."}],"ex":["White sign with metal border = Denmark, immediately — the most reliable single-sign confirm in all of Scandinavia","Red-on-white directional signs are equally unique — if you see red text directional signs, it's Denmark","Short road edge dashes are a strong supporting tell (requires seeing road markings clearly)","Yellow commercial plates on vans = fast Denmark confirm when a commercial vehicle is visible","Denmark is one of the most densely covered countries in GeoGuessr — excellent nationwide coverage","The beech forests (smooth grey-barked trees with green canopy) are very distinctive in spring/summer"]},{"id":"estonia","n":"Estonia","f":"🇪🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Estonian language — closest to Finnish in Europe. Distinctive features: Õ (o with tilde — unique to Estonian) and Ä combined with double letters. Street names end in -tee (road) or -tänav (street). The Õ character appears nowhere else.","Red-on-white chevrons — Estonia uses red background with white arrows for chevrons. Unique in the Baltics (Latvia and Lithuania use different styles).","Blue/white wrappers on signpost bases — Estonian sign poles are sometimes wrapped in a blue-and-white pattern at their base. Distinctive once seen.","Cylindrical bollards with rectangular reflector in front, two circular reflectors on the back","Dirt roads — Estonia has many dirt/gravel roads, similar to Finland. Best default when on a Baltic dirt road with no other clear clues."],"ls":"Estonian — Finno-Ugric, completely unrelated to Latvian and Lithuanian (which are Baltic Indo-European). Key distinguishing feature: Õ (tilde-o) — found ONLY in Estonian. Also uses Ä, Ö, Ü. Double letters common. Street suffix -tee (similar to Finnish -tie). Words look somewhat Finnish but different: tee (road/tea), linn (city), küla (village). If you see Õ on a sign = Estonia immediately.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Red chevrons (red background, white arrows) — unique in the Baltics","Blue/white wrapped signpost bases in some areas","Warning signs: red border, thin, WITHOUT additional outer outline (different from Finland which has an outline, different from Latvia which has a thick border)","Kilometre markers perpendicular to the road — Estonian km markers face the road perpendicularly (at 90° to road direction)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","No guardrail reflectors — Estonia uniquely does not use reflectors on guardrails"],"landb":["Northern European: birch and pine forests, many lakes","Relatively flat — Estonia is one of the flatter countries in Europe","Dense patches of small white flowers at roadsides in rural areas — a flora tell for Estonia vs other Baltics","Narrower dirt roads than Latvia and Lithuania — Estonian rural tracks feel tighter","Coastal areas: flat, rocky, juniper scrubland (western Estonia/islands)","Tallinn area: medieval old town (recognisable if you know it), mix of Soviet-era and modern buildings"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Estonia is identified by language (Õ), chevrons, and sign tells.","mu":[{"c":"Finland","k":"most similar language family. Key splits: Finnish roads end in -tie; Estonian in -tee. Finland has different bollards. Very similar landscape — forest/flat/dirt roads. Õ character is Estonian only."},{"c":"Latvia","k":"neighbouring Baltic state. Key splits: Latvian is a Baltic language (completely different from Estonian); Latvian has thick red border on warning signs; Latvian bollards are thin planks. Estonian has thin warning sign border + Õ in language."},{"c":"Lithuania","k":"also Baltic but different language. Key splits: Lithuanian has ė (e with dot below); Estonian has Õ. Different bollard styles."}],"ex":["The Õ character is THE fastest Estonia language confirm — it appears in very common words (põhi = north, õlu = beer, tõde = truth)","Red chevrons are reliable when a road bend is visible","Dirt road + Nordic/Baltic European context + no clear clues = lean Estonia","Estonia is EU/Schengen — standard EU plates with blue strip","Estonia's coverage is extensive including remote forest roads and island coverage (Saaremaa, Hiiumaa)","Soviet-era architecture visible in Tallinn and other cities — typical former USSR concrete blocks"]},{"id":"spain","n":"Spain","f":"🇪🇸","co":"Europe","qt":["\"CALLE\" on street signs — Spanish for street, visible on virtually every urban street sign. \"Calle + name\" format is consistent throughout Spain (and Latin America, but landscape context separates them).","Wedge bollards with orange rectangular front reflector + two white circular rear reflectors — Spanish bollards are hollow wedge-shaped posts with orange on front and two white circles on back. The hollow/open-sided wedge shape is distinctive.","Yellow-orange guardrail reflectors — Spain has distinctive yellow-orange reflectors attached to guardrails every few metres. No other European country uses this colour on guardrails.","Red road signs with borders extending to sign edge — on Spanish warning and regulatory signs the red border goes all the way to the edge with no gap/outline. Other countries have a small gap between the border and sign edge.","Pedestrian crossing signs with 8 stripes — Spain has the highest number of crossing stripes on pedestrian signs in Europe (8 stripes vs typically 4-5 elsewhere).","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish (Castilian) throughout most of the country. Regional languages visible in specific areas: Spanish words: calle, avenida, plaza, camino, carretera. Words often end in -a, -o, -ión.","lb":["Catalan (Catalonia, Valencia, Balearics): looks like French-Spanish hybrid — words like carrer (street), avinguda (avenue)","Basque/Euskara (Basque Country): completely unique language with very unusual consonant clusters — kalea (street), abundant k and x","Galician (Galicia, northwest): very similar to Portuguese — rúa (street)"],"rb":["Right-hand traffic","Red signs with border to edge (no gap outline) — consistent on all warning signs","8-stripe pedestrian crossing signs","Yellow-orange guardrail reflectors","Hollow wedge bollards with orange front, two white circles rear","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Ladder-style utility poles very common — poles with rung-like indents running up them","National road prefix: N- (carretera nacional), A- (autovía/autopista)"],"landb":["Enormous regional diversity:","Meseta (central plateau): vast flat/rolling dry plateau, brown/golden, sparse scrub, hot. Most of inland Spain looks like this — very different from anywhere in Northern Europe.","Mediterranean coast: dry, rocky, scrubby maquis, olive/almond trees, blue sky, terracotta","Pyrenees/Cantabrian mountains: green, alpine, dramatic","Andalucía: very hot, dry, white villages, olive groves","Galicia/Basque coast: rainy, green — looks almost like Ireland","Canary Islands: volcanic, subtropical, dramatically different","Sunflower and olive groves are strongly Spanish landscape tells in inland areas"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Spain is identified by language, bollards, and landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Portugal","k":"most similar language (done separately). Key splits: Portuguese uses ã, ç; Spanish doesn't have ã. Portugal uses yellow on right side of plates (old) or different plate style."},{"c":"Latin America (various)","k":"also \"calle\" on signs, also Spanish. Key splits: Spain has European landscape; Latin America has tropical/Andean/etc. landscape. Spain has EU plates."},{"c":"Italy","k":"also Mediterranean, also warm landscape. Key splits: Italian words end in vowels (molto, strada); Spanish uses different vocabulary. Different bollards."}],"ex":["Yellow-orange guardrail reflectors are the fastest Spain road infrastructure confirm — no other European country has them","\"Calle\" on any sign = Spanish-speaking, then use landscape to confirm Spain vs Latin America","Canary Islands (Spanish territory but off Africa coast) look very different from mainland — volcanic desert with palm trees but Spanish signs/plates","Ceuta and Melilla (Spanish enclaves in Morocco) exist but are extremely rare spawns"]},{"id":"finland","n":"Finland","f":"🇫🇮","co":"Europe","qt":["Dirt/gravel roads — Finland is the best default guess when you're on an unpaved road in a Nordic country with no other clear clues. Finland has more dirt roads than any other Nordic country.","Finnish language — completely unlike Danish/Norwegian/Swedish. Finnish has ä, ö + distinctive double vowels (aa, oo, ee, uu) and double consonants. Street names end in -katu (street) or -tie (road). Finnish words look very different from Scandinavian — longer, more unusual letter combinations.","Cylindrical bollards — Finnish bollards appear cylindrical from the front (round cross-section), unlike the wedge-shaped bollards of Norway/Sweden/Lithuania","Blue directional signs (minor roads) — smaller directional signs have white text on blue background with a bold arrow. Highway signs are green.","Warning signs with yellow background + additional outer outline — Finnish warning signs have a thin additional outline just outside the red border. This outline distinguishes Finland from Sweden (which also has yellow warning signs but NO outer outline)."],"ls":"Finnish (Suomi) — totally unrelated to Scandinavian languages. Part of the Finno-Ugric family (related to Estonian and distantly to Hungarian). Key features: ä and ö but NOT å (å = Danish/Norwegian/Swedish). Double vowels very common: katu, tie, kaupunki (city), järvi (lake), metsä (forest). Street suffixes: -katu (street in urban areas), -tie (road in rural areas). If you see -katu or -tie on road signs = Finland. Bilingual signs (Finnish + Swedish) in western/coastal areas — both languages on the same sign.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Dirt/gravel roads — more common than in any other Nordic country","Blue minor direction signs with bold arrow (similar to Sweden but bolder arrow style)","Green highway direction signs","Warning signs: yellow background, red border, with thin additional outer outline — unique feature","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Solid white outer edge lines (when present) — less dashed than Norway"],"landb":["Boreal forest (taiga) everywhere — vast, dense, dark conifer forests (spruce and pine). The most forested country in Europe by percentage. If you see endless dark conifer forest in a Nordic context = lean Finland.","Thousands of lakes — Finland has ~188,000 lakes. Roadside lakes and reflective water visible constantly in coverage.","Flat to gently rolling terrain — not mountainous like Norway. Flatter than Sweden in many areas.","Dense birch and pine forests, often no visibility beyond the treeline","White flower patches at roadsides in rural areas — dense small white flowers common in Estonian and Finnish rural verges","Very sparse population density — roads can feel extremely isolated even in summer"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Finland is identified by language, dirt roads, forest density, and bollard/sign tells.","mu":[{"c":"Estonia","k":"most similar language (Finno-Ugric family, both use ä/ö). Key splits: Estonian roads end in -tee (vs Finnish -tie). Estonia has different bollards (cylindrical with rectangular reflector in front, two circular on back). Estonia has narrower dirt roads than Finland. Visually the countries look very similar — language endings are the most reliable split."},{"c":"Sweden","k":"also forested, also Nordic. Key splits: Swedish uses å/ä/ö (Finland's Finnish has no å); Swedish warning signs have yellow background but NO outer outline (Finland has outer outline). Swedish directional signs have white-on-blue with thin arrow."},{"c":"Russia (northwest)","k":"also boreal forest, also flat. Key splits: Russia uses Cyrillic; Finland uses Latin."}],"ex":["Dirt roads + Nordic European context = Finland as default — this heuristic works very often","Finnish -katu (urban street) is the fastest language confirm — nothing else uses this suffix","Yellow warning signs with outer outline = Finland; yellow without outer outline = Sweden. Memorise this.","Bilingual Finnish/Swedish signs appear on the western coast and in Helsinki area — distinctive when seen","Finland has excellent coverage including many remote forest roads","The sheer density and darkness of Finnish boreal forest is characteristic — trees crowd right up to road edges"]},{"id":"faroe_islands","n":"Faroe Islands","f":"🇫🇴","co":"Europe","qt":["Grey roof racks and grey side mirrors on Google car — the Faroe Islands Google car has plain grey (not black) roof rack bars and plain grey side mirrors. This is the primary car meta. No colour, no distinctive features — just plain grey bars and mirrors.","Jagged green mountains with NO trees — the Faroe Islands landscape is completely unique: intensely green, grass-covered jagged mountain peaks rising directly from the sea. No trees anywhere, but lush green (unlike Iceland's volcanic black). Dramatic fjords between green peaks.","Dramatic overcast Atlantic atmosphere — the Faroe Islands is almost always overcast, foggy, grey. The light is soft and grey-white constantly.","Sheep on roofs — turf-roofed houses with grass growing on them. Sheep sometimes graze on rooftops. Globally iconic and completely unique.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Faroese — a North Germanic language descended from Old Norse, related to Icelandic and Norwegian. Uses special characters ø, æ, á, í, ó, ú, ý, ð — notably the ð (eth) which also appears in Icelandic. Faroese place names: Tórshavn, Klaksvík, Streymoy, Eysturoy. Faroese looks somewhat like a mixture of Icelandic and Norwegian. The combination of ð + the dramatic treeless green mountain landscape = Faroe Islands.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Road quality good — well-maintained despite remote location","Standard European-style road sign conventions","Tunnels very common — the islands have an extensive undersea tunnel network connecting islands","Road lines standard European white","Very few signs overall — limited signage in such a small, remote territory"],"landb":["Green jagged mountains — steep, dramatic, grass-covered peaks. The mountains have a characteristic jagged/serrated profile when seen against the sky. Intensely, saturated green.","No trees — like Iceland, completely treeless. But unlike Iceland's volcanic black, Faroe is all grass.","Fjords and sea inlets — narrow channels between mountain walls, dark blue-green Atlantic water","Turf-roofed houses — traditional Faroese buildings have grass-covered roofs. Some also have brightly coloured wooden walls (red, yellow, blue) beneath green turf roofs. Iconic architecture.","Grey sky and fog — the Faroe Islands is one of the cloudiest places on Earth. Coverage is almost always in grey, overcast, foggy conditions.","Waterfalls pouring directly into the sea from cliff edges (hanging valleys)","Very dramatic coastal scenery — sea cliffs, stacks, bird colonies"],"car":"Plain grey roof rack bars and plain grey side mirrors — no colour, no distinctive features. Just grey. This is the Faroe Islands car. When combined with the green mountain landscape it's a complete confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Iceland","k":"also treeless North Atlantic island. Key splits: Iceland is volcanic (black rock, lava fields); Faroe Islands is all green grass. Faroe Islands has grey car meta; Iceland has aerial visible. Iceland has yellow bollards; Faroe Islands rarely has bollards."},{"c":"Scotland (Highlands)","k":"also dramatic, also green, also Atlantic. Key splits: Scotland has some trees/heather; Faroe has none. Scottish road signs are in English; Faroese use their own language."},{"c":"Norway (coastal)","k":"also fjords, also dramatic. Key splits: Norway has extensive forests; Faroe Islands has zero trees. Norway has yellow directional signs; Faroe Islands has standard white signs."}],"ex":["Grey car bars + grey mirrors = Faroe Islands, immediately — the most reliable single-car meta in Scandinavia","The green jagged mountains with no trees is globally unique — nothing looks quite like the Faroe Islands","Turf roofs are iconic — if you see a grass-covered roof, you're almost certainly in the Faroe Islands","The islands are an autonomous territory of Denmark — hence Danish administrative influence visible in some signs","Coverage includes most main roads on Streymoy (Tórshavn) and other main islands","Undersea tunnel entrances visible in coverage — unique infrastructure for island-hopping"]},{"id":"france","n":"France","f":"🇫🇷","co":"Europe","qt":["Very long white road edge dashes — France has the longest road edge dash markings in Europe. Nowhere else has dashes this long on road edges. If you see unusually long white dashes on both sides of the road = France.","French bollards — two types, both unique shape: rounded/mushroom-top post with either a grey reflector strip running around it OR a red reflector strip. The rounded, somewhat chubby shape is unlike any other European bollard.","\"Rue\" on street signs — French for street, appears on virtually every urban intersection sign. In a blue/white enamel format.","Yellow \"D\" road number signs — minor roads in France are called D-roads (departmental). The yellow rectangle with \"D\" followed by a number is visible everywhere on rural roads.","French cars everywhere — Renault, Peugeot, Citroën, Dacia. High density of these brands is a strong supporting tell."],"ls":"French throughout. Latin script with ç (c-cedilla), é, è, ê, à, ù, â, î, ô accent marks. Key words: rue (street), avenue, chemin (path/road), D-route numbers on yellow signs. French is also spoken in Belgium and Switzerland — but French bollards + French D-road signs = France specifically. Note: if you see ß or German = not France.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Very long white edge dashes — the longest in Europe, completely consistent","Yellow D-road number signs (rectangular yellow with \"D\" + number) on virtually all minor roads","Standard EU white plates with blue strip; pre-2009 plates can have yellow background with EU strip","Newer plates have a thin blue strip on the RIGHT side as well (not just left) — a French plate quirk","Green motorway signs (autoroute)"],"landb":["Enormous country with massive regional diversity:","Normandy/Brittany: green, wet, hedgerow-divided fields, stone buildings","Loire Valley: flat, wide river valley, château architecture","Provence/Côte d'Azur: Mediterranean, lavender fields, dry stone villages, olive trees, blue sky","Alps/Pyrenees: dramatic mountains, ski infrastructure","Alsace: German-influenced architecture (half-timbered), vineyards","Corsica: Mediterranean island, mountains, shorter road dashes","Generally: green agricultural landscape in most of the country"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Gen 2 (halo visible) appears in some older French coverage.","mu":[{"c":"Belgium","k":"also French-speaking in south (Wallonia). Key splits: Belgium has red-lettered plates; France has standard white plates. French bollards are very distinctive from Belgian roads."},{"c":"Switzerland","k":"also partly French-speaking. Key splits: Switzerland has no EU blue strip on plates (non-EU); French plates have blue strip. Swiss mountain scenery dramatically different from most of France."},{"c":"Luxembourg","k":"also partly French-speaking. Key splits: Luxembourg very small, distinctive yellow directional signs."}],"ex":["Long road edge dashes are THE fastest France road meta — visible within seconds on any rural road","French bollards (rounded mushroom shape with wrap-around reflector strip) are a global one-clue identifier","Germany has very limited GeoGuessr coverage (major cities only). If you see German language in what looks like city coverage = Germany, but if you see countryside in similar language = possibly Alsace, France","France has excellent nationwide coverage including remote mountain roads and island coverage (Corsica, overseas territories)","Corsica has shorter road dashes + Mediterranean mountain landscape — distinctive within France"]},{"id":"united_kingdom","n":"United Kingdom","f":"🇬🇧","co":"Europe","qt":["White front plate + yellow rear plate — UK vehicles have a white plate on the front and yellow plate on the rear. The ONLY country in Europe with asymmetric white/yellow plates. If you see a yellow rear plate in Europe = UK immediately.","No EU blue strip on plates — UK left the EU. Plates may have a GB identifier or Union Jack but no EU blue strip. This splits UK from Ireland.","Left-hand traffic + English — narrowed to UK, Ireland, Gibraltar. Yellow rear plate confirms UK over Ireland.","\"Give Way\" triangular signs and black-on-white bollards with large red rectangle on top — UK bollard style is distinctive.","Miles on speed signs (not km/h) — UK uses mph. \"30\" on a round white/red sign = mph."],"ls":"English throughout. Wales: Welsh/Cymraeg bilingual signs (Welsh looks like: Croeso y Cymru, very double-l heavy: llwyn, llan, afon). Scotland: English predominantly, occasional Scottish Gaelic in Highlands (Taigh, Abhainn). Northern Ireland: English + occasional Irish Gaelic. The appearance of Welsh (abundant ll, ff, ch, ng combinations) = Wales specifically.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","White front / yellow rear plates — most reliable UK confirm globally","No EU blue strip on plates (or UK flag/GB identifier instead)","Speed signs in mph — round white signs with red circle border","\"Give Way\" on inverted triangle give-way signs (not \"Yield\" or \"Cédez\")","Road quality variable — major roads excellent, rural lanes very narrow","Black-and-white bollards with large red rectangle at top — distinctive UK bollard","Cats' eyes (reflective road studs) in centre of roads — very common in UK"],"landb":["England: varied — south is rolling chalk hills (white cliffs), Midlands is industrial/suburban, north has moorland (Yorkshire Dales, Lake District), coastline","Scotland: dramatic Highland mountains, lochs (lakes), heather moorland, glens — some of the most dramatic scenery in GeoGuessr","Wales: green hilly valleys, slate quarries, sheep on hillsides","Northern Ireland: green rolling hills, Antrim Coast dramatic basalt cliffs (Giant's Causeway)","Generally: green, temperate, often overcast","Red post boxes — Royal Mail red post boxes are a strong cultural tell","Terraced red-brick houses — very common in English towns and cities"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Left-hand traffic is the primary confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also English, also green. Key splits: Ireland has EU blue strip on plates (UK doesn't). Ireland has yellow outer road lines (UK has white). Ireland has bilingual English/Irish signs (UK doesn't, except Wales/Scotland). UK has yellow rear plate (Ireland has white rear EU plate)."},{"c":"Australia","k":"also left-hand, also English, also drives on left. Key splits: Australia has eucalyptus trees (UK doesn't). Very different landscapes."},{"c":"Malta","k":"also left-hand, also English. Key splits: Malta is Mediterranean island (completely different landscape)."}],"ex":["White front + yellow rear plates = UK, always — globally unique plate combination in Europe","No EU blue strip is a fast supporting tell (plates may show GB or Union Jack)","Welsh road signs (double-l words, Croeso y Cymru) = Wales specifically","Scottish Highlands coverage is among the most dramatic in Europe — lochs, mountains, heather","Cats' eyes road studs are a strong UK road meta once you notice them","Red phone boxes (older coverage) and red double-decker buses (London) are iconic cultural tells","UK has excellent nationwide coverage including remote Scottish island roads"]},{"id":"georgia","n":"Georgia","f":"🇬🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Georgian script (Mkhedruli) — one of the most visually distinctive and beautiful scripts in the world. Georgian characters are rounded, curving, with many loops and tails. No other language uses Georgian script. If you see it = Georgia, immediately.","Bilingual Georgian + Latin/Cyrillic on road signs — official signs show both Georgian script and often English or Russian transliteration alongside.","Dramatic Caucasus mountain landscape — Georgia has some of the most spectacular mountain scenery in GeoGuessr. The Greater Caucasus range forms the northern border with Russia.","Mix of post-Soviet and traditional architecture — Soviet-era blocks everywhere, but also traditional Georgian stone tower houses (especially in Svaneti region).","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Georgian — South Caucasian language, completely unrelated to anything else. The Mkhedruli script is unique to Georgian (and related Mingrelian/Svan languages). Characters are rounded with flowing curves, loops and hanging strokes — unlike the angular geometry of Cyrillic or Latin. Some key visual identifiers: many characters have a circular body with a tail or stroke. Once you can recognise that this is Georgian script, you will never confuse it with anything else. Road signs show Georgian script prominently with English or Russian underneath.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Bilingual Georgian + English on newer signs; older signs may have Georgian + Russian","Standard European-style road sign shapes but with Georgian text","White plates with EU-style formatting (Georgia uses similar plate dimensions)","Road quality highly variable — main highways decent, rural mountain roads rough or unpaved","Coverage includes main highways and some mountain roads"],"landb":["Greater Caucasus (north): some of the most dramatic mountains in GeoGuessr — towering peaks, deep gorges, alpine meadows. Higher than the Alps.","Tbilisi area: hilly, semi-arid, mix of older stone buildings and Soviet blocks. The old town (Narikala) has distinctive balconied wooden houses.","Eastern Georgia (Kakheti): wine country, rolling vineyard-covered hills, drier","Western Georgia (Adjara, Imereti): lush, green, subtropical near Black Sea coast","Svaneti (northwest): extremely remote alpine valleys with distinctive medieval stone towers (Svan towers) — one of the most architecturally unique landscapes in the world","Black Sea coast (Batumi area): subtropical, palm trees, resort architecture"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Georgia is identified entirely by the unique Georgian script — it is one of the easiest country identifications in GeoGuessr once you can recognise the script.","mu":[{"c":"Armenia","k":"neighbouring Caucasus country. Key splits: Armenian uses the Armenian script (distinct from Georgian — more angular, different letter shapes). Both scripts are unique but to a trained eye, Georgian has more circular forms, Armenian more angular."},{"c":"Russia","k":"neighbour to the north, also in this region. Key splits: Russia uses Cyrillic; Georgia uses Georgian script. Completely different scripts."},{"c":"Turkey","k":"also Caucasian region, borders Georgia. Key splits: Turkey uses Latin with Turkish characters (ş, ç, ğ); Georgia uses Georgian script."},{"c":"Azerbaijan","k":"also Caucasus. Key splits: Azerbaijan uses Latin script with Azerbaijani characters; Georgia uses Georgian script."}],"ex":["Georgian script is the absolute fastest Georgia confirm — one of the most immediately recognisable scripts in all of GeoGuessr","Georgia has reasonable coverage including city coverage in Tbilisi and some mountain roads","Svaneti towers (medieval stone defensive towers in alpine villages) are among the most distinctive architectural features in all of GeoGuessr","Tbilisi old town with its balconied wooden houses is distinctive once you know it","Georgia is geographically in the Caucasus — technically at the border of Europe and Asia"]},{"id":"gibraltar","n":"Gibraltar","f":"🇬🇮","co":"Europe","qt":["The Rock of Gibraltar always visible — Gibraltar is dominated by its famous 426m limestone rock. The Rock is visible from virtually every point in Gibraltar. If you see a massive grey limestone cliff/mountain directly adjacent to a small city = Gibraltar.","White front + yellow rear plates with EU blue strip — Gibraltar plates follow UK format (white front, yellow rear) but unlike the UK, Gibraltar has the EU blue strip on the left (Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory with a special relationship with the EU). This white/yellow + EU strip combination is unique.","Unique Google car antenna with white tip — Gibraltar's Street View car has a distinctive antenna with a white tip. Supporting car meta.","English + Spanish bilingual — English is official but Spanish is widely spoken given the border with Spain. Signs may appear in both languages.","Left-hand traffic (British territory)"],"ls":"English throughout (official). Spanish also common due to daily cross-border commuting with Spain. British road sign conventions. The combination of English + left-hand traffic + Mediterranean climate = Gibraltar (or Malta, but the Rock is unmistakable).","rb":["Left-hand traffic (British)","White front plates + yellow rear plates with EU blue strip on left","British road sign conventions (GIVE WAY, speed in mph)","Distinctive antenna with white tip on Google car"],"landb":["The Rock — an enormous limestone monolith rising 426m straight up. Completely dominates every view.","Tiny territory (~6.7 km²) — you are always within sight of either the Rock, the sea, or Spain","Mediterranean climate — warm, dry, scrubby vegetation on the Rock's slopes","Dense urban area at the base of the Rock: British-style town with Spanish influences","Barbary macaques (monkeys) visible in some coverage near the top of the Rock — unique in Europe","Spanish border and La Línea de la Concepción (Spanish city) visible in some coverage"],"car":"Antenna with white tip — distinctive when visible. Coverage is from 2010 (Gen 2) — halo visible in sky is a supporting tell.","mu":[{"c":"UK","k":"also left-hand, also English, also yellow rear plates. Key splits: Gibraltar has EU blue strip on plates; UK doesn't. The Rock is always present and unmistakable."},{"c":"Malta","k":"also left-hand, also Mediterranean. Key splits: The Rock = Gibraltar immediately. Malta has limestone buildings everywhere; Gibraltar has the Rock + dense urban at its base."},{"c":"Spain (Andalucía)","k":"neighbouring, similar climate. Key splits: Gibraltar is left-hand; Spain is right-hand. The Rock makes Gibraltar unmistakable."}],"ex":["The Rock of Gibraltar is THE most recognisable single landmark in GeoGuessr — if you see that massive grey limestone cliff, it's Gibraltar, immediately","Coverage is very limited given the tiny size — the main road up the Rock (Europa Road) and town streets","Gibraltar is one of the easiest pinpoints in GeoGuessr — the Rock acts as a permanent landmark"]},{"id":"greece","n":"Greece","f":"🇬🇷","co":"Europe","qt":["Greek alphabet — completely unique writing system. Greek letters: Α, Β, Γ, Δ, Ε, Ζ, Η, Θ, Ι, Κ, Λ, Μ, Ν, Ξ, Ο, Π, Ρ, Σ, Τ, Υ, Φ, Χ, Ψ, Ω. Key visual identifiers: Ξ (looks like a capital E rotated), Ψ (trident/pitchfork shape), Ω (horseshoe shape), Σ (Greek sigma), Λ (upside-down V), Π (two vertical lines with crossbar). Once you can recognise Greek script = Greece or Cyprus only.","Yellow warning signs with red border — Greece uses yellow background warning signs (unlike most of Europe which uses white). Shared with Finland/Sweden/others but combined with Greek script = Greece.","Wedge bollards with red front and white rear reflectors — Greece-specific bollard design","Yellow taxi plates — taxis in Greece have yellow plates (not the standard EU white). All other vehicles use standard white EU plates.","No car visible in some coverage — Greece's Gen 4 car is black and has no antenna (antenna = never Greece)","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Greek — uses the Greek alphabet, which is ancestral to Latin but completely different in appearance. Common Greek letters on signs: ΟΔΟΣ (odos = road/street), ΛΕΩΦΟΡΟΣ (leofotos = boulevard), ΠΛΑΤΕΙΑ (plateia = square). Road signs often bilingual Greek + Latin transliteration. The Greek alphabet is visually unmistakable — it's one of the most immediately identifiable scripts in GeoGuessr.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow warning signs with red border","No antenna on car (Gen 3 + Gen 4) — if you see a European car with no antenna = Greece (antenna is absent in nearly all Greek coverage)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip; yellow plates on taxis","Greek bollards: wedge-shaped, red rectangular reflector on front, white on rear","Bilingual Greek + Latin transliteration on many directional signs"],"landb":["Mediterranean and Aegean — the defining Greek landscape","Rocky, dry, sparse vegetation — phrygana (low thorny scrub), maquis (low aromatic shrubs)","White cubic architecture — traditional Greek islands: brilliant white cube buildings with blue accents (especially Cyclades)","Dramatic mainland mountains (Olympus, Pindos range)","Olive groves and cypress trees very common","Mainland Greece: hilly to mountainous, rocky, dry","Coastlines: dramatic rocky cliffs, turquoise Aegean/Mediterranean sea","Very blue skies, harsh sunlight — strong Mediterranean light quality"],"car":"No antenna visible on either Gen 3 or Gen 4 car — this is a reliable secondary tell. Gen 4 coverage is black car. Black car without antenna in European Mediterranean context = Greece.","mu":[{"c":"Cyprus","k":"also Greek alphabet, also Mediterranean. Key splits: Cyprus is left-hand traffic (British influence); Greece is right-hand. Coverage is limited in Cyprus but context splits it."},{"c":"Bulgaria","k":"also Southern European. Key splits: Bulgaria uses Cyrillic, not Greek alphabet — completely different scripts."},{"c":"Turkey","k":"also Mediterranean/Aegean, neighbouring. Key splits: Turkey uses Latin with Turkish characters (ş, ç, ğ); Greece uses Greek alphabet."}],"ex":["Greek alphabet = Greece or Cyprus only. Learn to recognise Ω, Ψ, Ξ, Σ, Λ, Π, Θ — these letters look nothing like Latin.","No antenna on the car is a supporting tell — if the car has no visible antenna in a European context, consider Greece","Yellow taxi plates are very visible in urban Greek coverage","Yellow warning signs + Greek script = Greece immediately","Greece has extensive coverage including islands (Crete, Rhodes, Corfu, the Cyclades etc.) — island coverage feels very different from mainland","Greek islands: brilliant white cubic buildings, blue domes, very photogenic — among the most recognisable architecture in GeoGuessr"]},{"id":"croatia","n":"Croatia","f":"🇭🇷","co":"Europe","qt":["Blue fire hydrants — Croatia is essentially the only GeoGuessr country with blue-painted fire hydrants as standard. Narrow, distinctive blue posts on roadsides. Once you know this, it's one of the fastest single-object confirms in Eastern Europe.","Croatian language — uses Latin script with č, š, ž, ć, đ. The ć (c with acute accent) is shared with Serbian but the đ (d with stroke) is more common in Croatian than elsewhere. Street suffix: ulica (street), shown on blue street name signs.","Blue street name signs with white lettering — Croatian street signs are blue with white text. Very consistent.","Wide plates without EU strip (older coverage) — pre-2016 Croatian plates were white and wide without the EU blue strip. Newer coverage has EU strip. The old-style wide plates were distinctive.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Croatian — South Slavic, Latin script. Key characters: č, š, ž (same as Slovenian/Serbian Latin) + ć (c-acute) and đ (d with stroke). Croatian vocabulary on signs: ulica (street), trg (square), cesta (road/highway). Croatian and Serbian are mutually intelligible but use different scripts on official signs — Croatia uses Latin exclusively.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Blue street name signs with white lettering","Croatian bollards: red rectangle on front, white rectangle on rear (centred) — same family as Serbia/Slovenia/Montenegro bollards","Gen 4 coverage has blue cars with antenna (Mediterranean European)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip (newer); old wide plates without strip (older coverage)","Blue fire hydrants — the fastest single-object Croatia confirm"],"landb":["Adriatic coast (Dalmatia): dramatic rocky coastline, brilliant blue Adriatic sea, islands, Mediterranean vegetation (olive trees, stone pines, maquis). Very beautiful — some of the most distinctive coastal coverage in GeoGuessr.","Istria peninsula (northwest): Italian-influenced, rolling hills, vineyards, medieval hill towns","Inland Croatia: flat agricultural (Slavonia), similar to Hungary/Serbia","Dubrovnik area: iconic walled medieval city, orange rooftiles, dramatic cliffs","The karst limestone landscape of Dalmatia is very distinctive — white/grey bare rock, sparse scrub"],"car":"Gen 4 blue cars with antenna in newer coverage. Side mirrors with yellow sticker in some older coverage (pre-2019 Croatia tell). No single dominant car meta.","mu":[{"c":"Slovenia","k":"most similar. Both South Slavic Latin script, both former Yugoslavia. Key splits: Slovenian directional signs are yellow with black text (Croatia uses standard European green/blue). Slovenian km markers have yellow rectangle with road number at top-left. Blue fire hydrants = Croatia (rare in Slovenia)."},{"c":"Montenegro","k":"also South Slavic, also Adriatic coastal. Key splits: Montenegro has rifts in sky. Language nearly identical but Montenegro is much smaller and coverage context differs."},{"c":"Serbia","k":"related language. Key splits: Serbia sometimes uses Cyrillic; Croatia always Latin. Serbian bollard red rectangle is off-centre (left side); Croatian is centred."}],"ex":["Blue fire hydrants are THE fastest Croatia confirm — globally unique in GeoGuessr","Blue street name signs are very consistent and fast when you reach any intersection","Dalmatian coast coverage is visually stunning — white rock, turquoise Adriatic, Mediterranean vegetation = unmistakably Croatia","Croatia has good nationwide coverage including islands and coastal roads"]},{"id":"hungary","n":"Hungary","f":"🇭🇺","co":"Europe","qt":["Holey poles with holes going ALL THE WAY TO THE GROUND — Hungarian concrete utility poles have large holes punched through the full length of the pole, from top to the base. This full-length \"holey pole\" is shared with Romania but NOT Poland (which stops 0.5m above ground).","Hungarian language with ő and ű — unique double-accent characters. ő (o with double acute accent — two lines above) and ű (u with double acute) are found ONLY in Hungarian. If you see a vowel with two accent lines above it = Hungarian.","Green directional signs with white inner border + green outer border — Hungarian highway signs have a distinctive double-border (white inside, green outside). Blue on motorways (M-roads).","Sign poles attached with FOUR bolts in tall rectangular arrangement — Hungarian road signs are fastened to their posts with four visible bolts arranged in a tall rectangle. Very distinctive once noticed.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Hungarian (Magyar) — Finno-Ugric language, completely unrelated to any neighbouring Slavic or Germanic language. Unique characters: ő (o with double acute = two ´ marks above), ű (u with double acute). Also á, é, í, ó, ú, ö, ü (standard accented vowels). Street suffix utca (street) — extremely common on all urban street signs. Words: utca (street), út (road), tér (square), körút (ring road). The ő and ű appear in everyday words: főváros, tőkés, műszaki, győzelem.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Holey poles with holes running FULL LENGTH to ground !","Green directional signs with double border (white inner + green outer)","Blue directional signs on M-roads (motorways)","Four-bolt sign attachment in tall rectangular pattern","Hungarian bollards: red rectangle on front, white rectangle on rear (centred)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Road number codes: M (motorway), number only (national road)"],"landb":["Central European: relatively flat Pannonian Plain (Alföld) in east — one of the flattest parts of Europe","Hilly in the west (Transdanubia) — rolling forested hills","Budapest: dramatic capital — Buda hills on west bank with castle, Pest flat on east bank, connected by famous bridges over Danube","Architecture: beautiful Austro-Hungarian Habsburg era buildings in Budapest, Soviet-era blocks elsewhere","Agricultural flatlands, sunflower fields in summer"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Hungary is identified by holey poles, ő/ű language, and sign border style.","mu":[{"c":"Romania","k":"also full-length holey poles! Key splits: Romanian has ă, ș, ț characters (Latin with cedilla-like marks); Hungarian has ő, ű (double accent). Romanian town signs have a distinctive yellow speed limit section at top. Different bollards."},{"c":"Poland","k":"also holey poles but Polish holes stop 0.5m above ground; Hungarian go all the way to ground."},{"c":"Czech Republic/Slovakia","k":"also Central European. Key splits: Czech has ř; Slovak has ľ; Hungarian has ő, ű — all unique characters making the split clean."}],"ex":["ő and ű are the fastest Hungary language confirms — two acute accent marks above a single vowel. Globally unique to Hungarian.","Full-length holey poles = Hungary or Romania (then use language to split)","Budapest is one of the most recognisable and beautiful capital cities in GeoGuessr — the Parliament building and Chain Bridge are iconic","Four-bolt sign attachment is a reliable supporting tell once you notice it","Hungary has good nationwide coverage"]},{"id":"ireland","n":"Ireland","f":"🇮🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Bilingual English + Irish Gaelic on all road signs — every Irish road sign shows BOTH English AND Irish (Gaeilge). The Irish text is immediately distinctive: words like Baile Átha Cliath (Dublin), Bóthar (road), Sráid (street). If you see English road signs with a second line of unusual-looking text underneath = Ireland.","Yellow dashed outer road edge lines — Ireland has yellow dashes on the outer edges of roads. This is very rare in Europe — most European countries use white. Yellow outer lines + left-hand traffic = Ireland almost certainly.","EU blue strip on plates — Ireland is EU, so plates have standard blue strip on left. This splits Ireland from UK (no blue strip on UK plates).","Left-hand traffic + English + EU plates"],"ls":"English (primary) + Irish/Gaeilge on signs. Irish uses Latin script with distinctive features: á, é, í, ó, ú (fadas — long accent marks), and unusual consonant combinations like bh, mh, dh, gh (which make different sounds). Place names in Irish look very unusual to non-Irish speakers: Cill Dara (Kildare), Gaillimh (Galway), Port Láirge (Waterford). If you see English + what looks like strange Celtic-looking Latin text on the same sign = Ireland.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Yellow dashed outer edge lines — very rare in Europe, very consistent in Ireland","Bilingual English/Irish signs on all road signs (motorways, local roads, street signs)","EU white plates with blue strip (unlike UK which has no EU strip)","Road quality: Irish roads are variable — major routes good, rural roads can be very narrow","Green directional signs for major routes; blue for motorways","Speed in km/h (not mph like UK)"],"landb":["Intensely green — Ireland earns its \"Emerald Isle\" nickname. Rolling green hills, green fields, green hedgerows. Some of the greenest landscape in GeoGuessr.","Hedgerow-divided fields — stone walls and dense hedgerows dividing fields. Very characteristic of rural Ireland.","Rolling hills, no extreme mountains (except in Kerry/Connemara/Donegal)","Stone walls visible in western Ireland (Connemara, Aran Islands) — distinctive dry stone construction","Atlantic coast: dramatic cliffs, rugged coastline (Cliffs of Moher area)","Generally overcast, wet, green — similar to UK but even greener","Peat/bog landscapes in Midlands — flat, brown, treeless"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. Electric Google car sometimes visible in cities. No distinctive car meta beyond left-hand perspective.","mu":[{"c":"UK","k":"most similar. Both left-hand, both English, both temperate green landscape. Key splits: Ireland has EU blue strip on plates; UK does NOT. Ireland has yellow road edge lines (UK has white). Ireland has bilingual English/Irish signs (UK doesn't, unless Wales/Scotland). UK uses mph; Ireland uses km/h."},{"c":"Scotland","k":"also green, also hilly, also English + Gaelic. Key splits: Scottish plates have EU strip sometimes but no Irish text. Scottish Gaelic looks different from Irish Gaelic."}],"ex":["Yellow outer road lines = Ireland, always — this is the fastest Ireland vs UK road split","Bilingual signs with Irish Gaelic text are very consistent — learn to recognise the Irish fada (á, é, í, ó, ú)","EU plates with blue strip = Ireland (not UK). This is extremely reliable.","Irish Gaelic place names ending in -more (big), -beg (small), -knock (hill), -kil (church) are very consistent","Ireland has excellent nationwide coverage including scenic western roads","Irish pubs, Guinness signs, and Catholic church architecture are cultural tells in some coverage"]},{"id":"isle_of_man","n":"Isle of Man","f":"🇮🇲","co":"Europe","qt":["Red strip on left side of license plates — Isle of Man plates follow UK format (white front, yellow rear) but have a distinctive small vertical red stripe on the left side. No other European territory has a red strip on UK-format plates. This is the single fastest Isle of Man plate confirm.","Gen 2 coverage — Isle of Man, like Jersey and Gibraltar, has only Gen 2 coverage from 2010. Halo/rift visible in sky when panning up. Combined with British landscape = Isle of Man.","Very few speed limit signs — the Isle of Man famously has no national speed limit on many roads. Coverage has noticeably fewer speed limit signs than mainland UK or Ireland.","British road signs + English only — standard UK road sign conventions, English only (Manx language is extremely rare in public signage).","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"English throughout. Manx (the indigenous Celtic language) is spoken by only ~300 people and almost never appears on road signs. Standard British road sign vocabulary: GIVE WAY, STOP, speed limits in mph (when present).","rb":["Left-hand traffic","White front + yellow rear plates with red strip on left","British road sign conventions","Notably fewer speed limit signs than UK (national speed limit is unlimited on many roads)","Gen 2 coverage throughout"],"landb":["British-feeling island — green, rolling, similar to parts of England or Wales","Relatively quiet rural roads and small towns","TT (Tourist Trophy) motorcycle race course runs through the island — some barrier/signage infrastructure visible","Coastal cliffs and beaches","Small (~572 km²) — limited coverage","Douglas (capital): small British-style town on a bay"],"car":"Gen 2 only — halo visible in sky. The same Gen 2 quality as Jersey and San Marino, but the landscape and plates distinguish them.","mu":[{"c":"UK","k":"most similar. Key splits: Isle of Man plates have red strip on left; UK plates don't. Isle of Man is Gen 2 only; much of UK has Gen 3/4. Fewer speed limit signs on IOM."},{"c":"Jersey","k":"also Gen 2, also Crown Dependency, also British plates. Key splits: Jersey plates have no red strip; IOM plates have red strip. Jersey has bilingual English/French; IOM is English only. Jersey was captured on sunny blue-sky days; IOM has more typical grey overcast."},{"c":"Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also island near UK. Key splits: Ireland has EU plates with blue strip; IOM has UK format with red strip."}],"ex":["Red strip on plates is THE fastest IOM confirm — completely unique in Europe","Gen 2 quality is a supporting tell against mainland UK","The TT race course infrastructure (hay bales, barriers, course signage) is visible in some coverage near the race circuit route","Limited coverage — knowing Douglas, Ramsey, Peel, and Castletown (main towns) helps pinpointing significantly"]},{"id":"iceland","n":"Iceland","f":"🇮🇸","co":"Europe","qt":["No trees — only grass, moss, lava rock, and tundra — Iceland has essentially zero native forest. The entire country is open landscape: grass, black lava fields, green moss, rocky tundra, volcanic mountains. If you see Scandinavian-feel with zero trees = Iceland.","Yellow bollards with yellow top edge — Iceland's bollards are distinctively all-yellow with a slightly different shaped top. Completely unlike any other European bollard.","No EU blue strip on license plates — Iceland is not EU, so its plates are plain white/elongated without the blue EU identification strip on the left. In an otherwise European-looking context, missing the blue strip = Iceland.","Yellow directional signs with black text — same yellow as Norway but Iceland also has this. Context (treeless volcanic landscape) resolves the Norway/Iceland split instantly.","Visible aerial on Google car + sometimes a section painted white/red/blue"],"ls":"Icelandic — unique characters Þ/þ (thorn, sounds like \"th\") and Ð/ð (eth, also \"th\"). These two characters are found essentially nowhere else in the world (medieval English had them but modern English doesn't). If you see Þ or ð on a sign = Iceland, commit immediately. Also uses á, é, í, ó, ú, ý, ö, ü, æ. Icelandic place names: Reykjavík, Akureyri, Selfoss, Ísafjörður — the ð and Þ are visible in many place names.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs with black text (shared style with Norway, but context is completely different)","Yellow background pedestrian crossing signs — Iceland is the ONLY European country with yellow background behind pedestrian crossing signs","Warning signs: yellow background, red border, NO additional outer outline (different from Finland which has an outer outline; same background as Sweden/Finland but no outline)","Dark-coloured roads — Icelandic roads are often noticeably darker than typical tarmac due to the volcanic rock aggregate used","White dashed edge markings with grass growing right to the road edge — very rural, raw feel","No EU blue strip on plates — plain white elongated plates"],"landb":["Volcanic — black lava fields, volcanic craters, geothermal steam rising from the ground, obsidian rock","No trees — this is the single fastest Iceland landscape confirm. Scandinavia has dense forests. Iceland has none. Open, treeless, windswept.","Grass and moss covering lava fields — bright green or golden-brown grass rolling over black rock","Glaciers visible — white ice caps on flat-topped mountains (Vatnajökull etc.)","Geothermal features — steam rising from ground, hot springs, sulphur smell (occasionally visible as steam plumes)","Dramatic volcanic mountains — flat-topped or conical, often snow-capped","Waterfalls everywhere — Iceland has hundreds of waterfalls visible from roads","The Ring Road (Route 1) circles the island and contains most coverage"],"car":"Aerial/antenna often visible on the Google car. Sometimes a section of the car is painted white, red, and blue (Icelandic flag colours). This antenna is a supporting tell when the treeless landscape doesn't make it obvious enough (it usually does).","mu":[{"c":"Norway","k":"also yellow directional signs, also dramatic landscape. Key splits: Norway has extensive forest; Iceland has NO trees. Norway has yellow bollards? No — Norway barely uses bollards. Iceland has distinctive yellow bollards. The treeless landscape settles this split immediately."},{"c":"Faroe Islands","k":"also treeless North Atlantic island, also dramatic. Key splits: Faroe Islands has green jagged mountains with a completely different lush-grass feel; Iceland has more barren volcanic black landscape. Faroe Islands has grey roof rack car meta. Language differs."},{"c":"Scottish Highlands","k":"also dramatic, also sometimes sparse. Key splits: Scotland has heather/bracken and occasional trees; Iceland is completely treeless volcanic. Different language."}],"ex":["Þ and ð on any sign = Iceland, immediately — globally unique characters","The absence of trees is the fastest landscape confirm for Iceland — once you notice it, you'll never miss it","Yellow bollards are consistent and distinctive once memorised","No EU blue strip on plates is a supporting tells for European context","Iceland uses yellow centre lines — one of very few European countries to do so (shared with Norway)","The Ring Road has excellent coverage; interior F-roads have some trekker coverage at highland areas","Geothermal steam visible in some coverage (especially around Reykjavík, Geysir area)"]},{"id":"italy","n":"Italy","f":"🇮🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Blue vertical stripes on BOTH sides of license plates — Italian plates have a light blue vertical strip on the LEFT (EU identifier) AND an additional blue strip on the RIGHT side. This double-blue-strip is shared only with Albania (and rarely France). If you see blue on both sides of a plate = Italy (or Albania — but landscape/language resolves this instantly).","\"VIA\" on street signs — Italian for street, visible on virtually every urban street sign on building walls (not just on posts — Italian street names are typically on small rectangular plaques mounted on building corners).","Italian bollards — white post with a vertical red rectangle inside a black diagonal strip on the front, with the black section extending all the way to the top of the bollard. Rear has white rectangle. The \"black top\" feature is globally unusual.","Words ending in vowels — virtually every Italian word ends in a vowel. This makes Italian text immediately recognisable: via, piazza, corso, lungofierno, uscita, entrata.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Italian — Latin script, all words end in vowels: via (street), piazza (square), corso (boulevard), viale (avenue), lungomare (seafront). Regional languages: German in South Tyrol/Alto Adige (bilingual Italian/German signs), French in Aosta Valley. Italian accents: à, è, é, ì, ò, ù but these are less frequent. Italian is also spoken in southern Switzerland (Ticino) but Swiss plates have no EU strip.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Double blue strip plates (left EU strip + right blue strip) — the fastest Italy plate confirm","Blue directional arrows pointing to towns — Italian town directional signs use blue arrows with white pointed end. Similar to Czech style but distinctly Italian.","\"VIA\" plaques on building walls at street corners — not on poles like most countries, but on building-mounted ceramic/metal plaques","Standard EU white plates with blue strip on left + additional strip on right","Road numbers: SS (Strada Statale), SP (Strada Provinciale), A (Autostrada)"],"landb":["Huge regional diversity:","North Italy (Po Valley): flat agricultural, foggy in winter, industrial, Alps backdrop","Italian Alps/Dolomites: dramatic vertical rock towers (Dolomites), ski resorts, stunning","Tuscany: rolling hills, cypress trees, olive groves, vineyards, terracotta farmhouses (podere)","Central Italy: rugged Apennine mountains, medieval hilltop towns","South Italy: drier, warmer, more worn infrastructure, resembles Greece","Sicily: Mediterranean island, very dry, volcanic (Etna)","Red/terracotta rooftiles very common outside of northern plain","Hilltop medieval villages visible in many coverage areas"],"car":"Blue car sometimes visible in Gen 4 coverage (Italy had Gen 4 blue cars with antenna in Mediterranean areas). No single distinctive car meta — plates and language are primary tells.","mu":[{"c":"Albania","k":"also double blue strip on plates! Key splits: Albanian uses different language (Shqip — rrugë for street, very different vocabulary). Albanian landscape looks poorer/more rural. Albanian bollards have black section going all the way to top (same as Italy) — this is the hardest split; use language."},{"c":"France","k":"also Romance language. Key splits: French \"rue\" vs Italian \"via\". French bollards are round/mushroom; Italian have black-top vertical strip."},{"c":"Greece","k":"also Mediterranean, also southern European feel. Key splits: Greece uses Greek alphabet (completely different script); Italian uses Latin."}],"ex":["Double blue strip plates = Italy or Albania only — memorise this two-country club","VIA on building-wall plaques is a very consistent and distinctive sign format","Italian words ending in vowels makes the language instantly recognisable even without knowing Italian","Italy has excellent nationwide coverage including remote Alpine valleys and island coverage (Sicily, Sardinia)","South Tyrol (Alto Adige): bilingual German/Italian signs — if you see German + Italian = South Tyrol, Italy"]},{"id":"jersey","n":"Jersey","f":"🇯🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Gen 2 coverage with notably blue skies — Jersey's entire coverage is Gen 2 (halo visible in sky). The coverage was captured on sunny blue-sky days, which contrasts with the typically grey Gen 2 coverage of mainland UK and the Isle of Man.","Solid yellow outer lines + single dashed white inner line — Jersey has a completely unique road marking system. The outer edge lines are solid yellow (like Ireland but different inner line) combined with a dashed white centre line. This combination is described as looking like South Africa but in a European context — unique in Europe.","Bilingual English + French on signs — Jersey is a Crown Dependency close to Normandy, France. Signs mix English and Norman French: place names like La Rocque, Grouville, Mont à l'Abbé, Rue des Prés. English/French bilingual signs in a non-tropical island = Jersey.","White front + yellow rear plates — same as UK. Jersey is a British Crown Dependency.","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"English (primary) + Norman French / Jèrriais on some signs and place names. French-sounding place names are everywhere: La Hocq, Rue de la Croix, Les Ruettes. The combination of UK-style roads + English + French place names + blue sky = Jersey.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (British Crown Dependency)","Solid yellow outer lines + dashed white centre line — unique road marking combination in Europe","White front + yellow rear plates (UK format, no EU strip)","Standard British-style road signs","Gen 2 coverage throughout — halo visible in sky"],"landb":["Channel Island — small island between England and France","Green, gently rolling countryside — similar to southern England but slightly warmer/sunnier","Sandy beaches, rocky coastline, small bays","Very English feel in infrastructure but with French place names everywhere","Small (~120 km²) — limited coverage"],"car":"Gen 2 only — sky halo always visible. Captured on blue-sky days — brighter and sunnier than typical Gen 2 UK coverage.","mu":[{"c":"UK","k":"most similar. Key splits: Jersey has unique yellow/white road markings; UK has white only. Jersey has bilingual English/French place names; UK doesn't (except Wales). Both have yellow rear plates."},{"c":"Isle of Man","k":"also Gen 2, also Crown Dependency, also British. Key splits: Isle of Man has red strip on plates; Jersey has standard UK plates. Isle of Man is greyer; Jersey was captured on blue-sky days. Different road markings."},{"c":"Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also island near UK. Key splits: Ireland has EU plates with blue strip; Jersey has UK-format plates (no EU strip). Ireland has bilingual English/Irish signs; Jersey has English/French."}],"ex":["Unique yellow outer + white dashed centre road markings are the fastest Jersey road confirm — nothing else in Europe has this","Blue sky Gen 2 quality is a supporting tell against mainland UK (grey) and Isle of Man","French place names on every road sign are very distinctive for a British territory","Jersey is known for its finance sector — large number of bank and finance company signs visible in St. Helier (capital)"]},{"id":"liechtenstein","n":"Liechtenstein","f":"🇱🇮","co":"Europe","qt":["German language + Alpine landscape + no EU blue strip on plates — Liechtenstein is not an EU member. Plates are white but without the EU blue strip. Combined with German language and a narrow Rhine valley Alpine setting = Liechtenstein.","Tiny Rhine valley sandwiched between Switzerland and Austria — Liechtenstein is one of the smallest countries in the world (~160 km²). All coverage is in the narrow Rhine valley and the hills above it. If you're in a very small German-speaking Alpine country with non-EU plates = Liechtenstein.","Uses Swiss franc, looks very Swiss — infrastructure, architecture, and landscape are virtually identical to neighbouring Switzerland. German without ß (uses ss like Switzerland, not Austria).","Very limited coverage — a handful of roads in Vaduz and surrounding towns.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"German — Alemannic dialect identical to Swiss German in sound, but standard German on signs. No ß (uses ss like Switzerland). Key vocabulary: Strasse (written as Strasse not Straße), Weg (way), Gasse (alley). Looks identical to Swiss German signage.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","White plates, no EU blue strip (Liechtenstein is not EU — uses Swiss Customs Union)","Swiss-style road signs and conventions","Very well-maintained roads (wealthy small state)","No highway (Autobahn) — too small"],"landb":["Narrow Rhine valley — the entire country sits in a valley between the Rhine River and the Alpine foothills. Very constrained geography.","Alpine character — forested hillsides, alpine meadows at altitude, similar to eastern Switzerland","Vaduz (capital): small town on valley floor with a distinctive castle (Vaduz Castle) on the hillside above — if you can see a castle on a hill above a small German-speaking Alpine town = Vaduz","Extremely green, well-kept countryside"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Non-EU plates + Swiss-style landscape + German = Liechtenstein.","mu":[{"c":"Switzerland","k":"most similar. Key splits: Switzerland has its own distinctive Swiss plates (white with red cross canton identifier on left); Liechtenstein has plain white plates with no strip or identifier. Coverage area is also tiny for Liechtenstein."},{"c":"Austria","k":"also Alpine, also German. Key splits: Austria has ß on signs and EU blue strip on plates. Liechtenstein uses ss and has no EU strip."}],"ex":["Vaduz Castle on the hillside is one of the most recognisable Liechtenstein landmarks — very distinctive if visible","Liechtenstein is one of only two doubly-landlocked countries in the world (surrounded by landlocked countries Switzerland and Austria)","Coverage is extremely limited — mainly Vaduz and a few surrounding villages","Functionally identical to Switzerland in look and feel — the plate is the key distinguisher"]},{"id":"lithuania","n":"Lithuania","f":"🇱🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Warning signs with thin red border AND thin white outer outline — Lithuanian warning signs have a thin red border PLUS a separate thin white outline running just outside the red border. This double-line effect is unique in the Baltics (Estonia has thin border but NO outline; Latvia has thick border but NO outline).","ė character (e with dot below) — a unique Lithuanian letter. Also uses š, ž, č, ų, ū, į. The ė with its dot below is the fastest Lithuanian language confirm.","Wedge-shaped bollards with orange rectangular reflectors on the front — Lithuanian bollards are wedge-shaped (like a wedge of cheese) with orange reflectors. Orange front = Lithuania (Estonia has rectangular, Latvia has thin plank).","Street suffix -g. or -gatvė — Lithuanian for \"street\". Very consistent on all street signs.","\"Detached head\" pedestrian crossing signs — Lithuanian pedestrian signs show a walking person with the head visually separated from the body (3-stripe crossing). Unique quirk."],"ls":"Lithuanian (Lietuvių) — Baltic Indo-European, closely related to Latvian but distinct. Unique character: ė (e with dot below, not to be confused with anything in Latvian or Estonian). Also š, ž, č, ų, ū, į (consonants with caron; vowels with ogonek). Street suffixes: -gatvė or abbreviated g. (street), -kelias (road/highway). Words: gatvė (street), miestas (city), Lietuva (Lithuania). If you see ė = Lithuanian, immediately.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Warning signs: thin red border + thin white outer outline — the double-line effect","Wedge bollards with orange front reflectors — orange is the key colour (vs Estonia's rectangular reflector, Latvia's white plank)","Orange guardrail reflectors — when present (not always)","Kilometre markers in V-shape — Lithuanian km markers have two sides arranged at 45° angle toward the road, forming a V-shape when viewed from above","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Green directional signs on main routes"],"landb":["Central Baltic landscape — mixed forest (pine, birch, oak), rolling terrain","More rolling/hilly than Estonia or Latvia in some areas, especially in eastern Lithuania","Curonian Spit — dramatic narrow sand dune peninsula (UNESCO heritage, shared with Russia's Kaliningrad). Distinctive landscape of sand dunes and pine forests if you're near the coast.","Vilnius: the capital has a beautiful medieval old town with distinctive Baroque churches visible in coverage","Agricultural areas with open fields typical of Northern Europe","Generally slightly warmer feel than Estonia/Latvia — more central European in some areas"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Lithuania is identified by language (ė), bollard colour (orange), and warning sign double-outline.","mu":[{"c":"Latvia","k":"most confusable. Both Baltic languages, similar landscape, similar infrastructure. Key splits: Lithuanian warning signs have thin border + outer outline; Latvian have thick border no outline. Lithuanian has ė (dot below e); Latvian has ē (bar above e). Lithuanian bollards have orange reflectors; Latvian bollards are thin white planks. Lithuanian street suffix = gatvė; Latvian = iela."},{"c":"Poland","k":"also uses diacritics, also central/eastern European. Key splits: Polish has ą, ę, ó, ń (different diacritics); Lithuanian has ė, š, ž. Different sign styles."},{"c":"Estonia","k":"also Baltic region. Key splits: Estonian is Finno-Ugric (with Õ); Lithuanian is Baltic (with ė). Very different language families despite geographic proximity."}],"ex":["ė (e with dot below) = Lithuania, always — appears in extremely common words (gatvė, Lietuva, etc.)","Orange bollard reflectors are a fast colour-based Baltic split when a road edge is visible","The detached head on pedestrian crossing signs is a fun/memorable tell once you know it","Lithuania is the southernmost Baltic state — slightly more continental feel than Estonia","Vilnius old town is one of the largest surviving medieval old towns in Northern Europe","Lithuania has good nationwide coverage including forests, farmland, and coastal areas"]},{"id":"luxembourg","n":"Luxembourg","f":"🇱🇺","co":"Europe","qt":["Yellow license plates (front AND rear) + EU blue strip — Luxembourg is one of only two European countries with yellow plates on both ends (the other is the Netherlands). The critical split: Luxembourg plates ALSO have the EU blue strip on the left (Netherlands plates may or may not). Yellow plates + EU strip = Luxembourg; yellow plates + no EU strip would be unusual.","Yellow directional signs with black ALL-CAPS text, surrounded by a complete rectangular frame — Luxembourg's road direction signs are yellow with black uppercase text and a full border frame around the entire sign. Distinctive and consistent.","Trilingual country — Luxembourgish, French, and German all appear on signs. Street names may appear in any of the three languages on the same sign or in different areas.","Hilly, green, rolling landscape — Luxembourg has undulating terrain throughout. Never flat, rarely steep. Gentle green hills and valleys.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Three official languages visible on signs: Signs can mix all three. The combination of German-looking text + French-looking text on the same sign = Luxembourg or Switzerland (Switzerland is much more mountainous and has no EU plates).","lb":["Luxembourgish (Lëtzebuergesch) — Germanic language with French influences. Distinctive: words like Strooss (street), Wee (way/road), Gare (train station).","French — used in much of the south and official contexts.","German — used in the east (Moselle region)."],"rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs with complete rectangular frame and ALL-CAPS black text","Yellow plates (front + rear) with EU blue strip on left","Standard European-style road markings","Road quality excellent — well-maintained"],"landb":["Gently rolling hills throughout — the Ardennes plateau in the north, Moselle valley in the east, central plateau","Green farmland, deciduous forest, vineyard slopes along the Moselle River","Small but densely covered — Luxembourg City (capital) has extensive coverage","Luxembourg City: dramatic fortifications on cliffs above river valleys — recognisable if you know it"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Luxembourg is identified by yellow plates + yellow framed signs.","mu":[{"c":"Netherlands","k":"also yellow plates (front + rear). Key splits: Luxembourg has EU strip + hilly landscape + French/German/Luxembourgish text; Netherlands is completely flat + Dutch language only."},{"c":"Belgium","k":"nearby, also trilingual. Key splits: Belgium has white plates with red text; Luxembourg has yellow plates."},{"c":"France","k":"also French language in much of Luxembourg. Key splits: French road signs very different style; Luxembourg has yellow directional signs with full frame; France has standard green/blue signs."}],"ex":["Yellow plates + yellow framed directional signs = Luxembourg two-clue confirm — very fast","Luxembourg is tiny (~2,600 km²) and very densely covered — you will rarely be far from a recognisable road junction","The Moselle wine region (eastern Luxembourg) has beautiful riverside vineyard coverage"]},{"id":"latvia","n":"Latvia","f":"🇱🇻","co":"Europe","qt":["Thick red border on warning signs — Latvia's warning signs have a noticeably thicker red border than Estonia or Lithuania. The thickness is clearly visible and consistent — the fastest Baltic warning sign split.","Latvian language — Baltic language with distinctive macron characters: ā, ē, ī, ū (vowels with horizontal line above). Also uses š, ž, ģ, ķ, ļ, ņ, č. The macrons (horizontal line above vowel) are key recognition features.","Thin flat bollards with a white rectangle on the front and two white circles on the back — very distinctive shape (thin plank-like, not wedge or cylindrical)","Blue directional signs with slightly stylised diagonal arrow edge — more stylised arrow than Estonia or Lithuania's straighter arrows","Bus stop signs with 5 windows — Latvian bus stop signs show 5 window-like rectangles"],"ls":"Latvian (Latviešu) — Baltic Indo-European language. Distinctive: ā, ē, ī, ū (vowels with macron/bar above — looks like a line drawn over the letter). Also š (sh), ž (zh), č (ch), ģ, ķ, ļ, ņ (consonants with cedilla-like marks below). Street suffix iela (street) — very consistent and recognisable. Words: iela (street), ceļš (road), pilsēta (city). If you see vowels with macrons (ā, ē, ī, ū) = Latvian.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Thick red-bordered warning signs — the thickest red border in the Baltics","Blue directional signs with slightly stylised diagonal arrow","5-window bus stop signs — visible at any bus stop","Pedestrian crossing signs with 5 stripes on the zebra pattern (vs Lithuania's 3-stripe)","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","White and red guardrail reflectors — Latvia uses these on guardrails"],"landb":["Northern European mixed forest — birch and pine, similar to Estonia and Lithuania","Slightly more rolling terrain than Estonia in some areas","Riga (capital): large Baltic city, beautiful Art Nouveau architecture in the city centre — if you recognise Art Nouveau buildings with elaborate facades, lean Riga","Sandy beaches on the Baltic coast — flat, sandy, pine-forested coastline (Jūrmala area)","Agricultural areas: open fields, flat, similar to other Baltic states"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Latvia is identified by language macrons, thick warning sign border, and bollard shape.","mu":[{"c":"Lithuania","k":"most similar. Both Baltic languages, similar landscape. Key splits: Lithuania has thin warning sign border with outer outline; Latvia has thick border without outline. Lithuanian has ė (e with dot below); Latvian has ē (e with macron/bar above). Lithuanian bollards are wedge-shaped with orange reflector; Latvian bollards are thin planks. Lithuanian street suffix = g./gatvė; Latvian = iela."},{"c":"Estonia","k":"neighbouring. Key splits: Estonian is Finno-Ugric (completely different language family) with Õ; Latvian is Baltic with macrons. Different warning sign borders (Latvia thick, Estonia thin without outline)."},{"c":"Poland","k":"also uses some diacritics. Key splits: Polish has ą, ę, ó not macrons. Polish landscape is different."}],"ex":["Macrons (ā, ē, ī, ū) are the fastest Latvia language confirm — if you see a vowel with a flat bar over it = Latvian","iela (street suffix) appears on every street sign — learn to recognise it","Thick red warning sign border is very reliable when a warning sign is visible","Latvia has good nationwide coverage including rural and coastal areas","Riga's Art Nouveau district is one of the most distinctive urban streetscapes in the Baltics","The thin flat bollard shape is distinctive — plank-like vs the cylindrical Estonian or wedge Lithuanian bollards"]},{"id":"monaco","n":"Monaco","f":"🇲🇨","co":"Europe","qt":["Ultra-dense luxury cityscape on steep cliffs above the Mediterranean — Monaco is immediately recognisable from its unique urban character. A tiny city-state crammed onto steep cliffs with the Côte d'Azur below. No other place on Earth looks like this.","Yachts everywhere — the harbour (Port Hercules) is full of superyachts. If you see a dense marina packed with luxury yachts in a steep coastal city = Monaco.","Mountains directly behind the city — dramatic cliffs and rocky Alpine foothills rise immediately behind the densely-built urban area.","Extreme wealth visible — luxury car showrooms, designer boutiques, immaculate streets, palatial buildings. Arguably the most visually expensive streetscape in GeoGuessr.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"French throughout — Monaco's official language. Same signs as France. Street suffix: rue, avenue, boulevard. The city is so small and distinctive that language alone is rarely needed — the visual character of Monaco is unmistakable.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French road sign conventions throughout","Monaco plates: white with standard EU formatting but very rare","Most cars visible are high-end luxury brands (Ferrari, Lamborghini, Rolls-Royce) — a cultural tell","Roads are extremely steep and narrow in many areas (built into cliff faces)"],"landb":["Completely urban — Monaco has essentially no undeveloped land. The entire principality is city.","Steep cliffs dropping to the Mediterranean","Lush planted gardens and parks (Exotic Garden on cliff face)","Formula 1 circuit runs through the streets — trackside barriers visible in some coverage","The Rock of Monaco (old town/palace) on a promontory overlooking the harbour"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. Monaco is one of the smallest countries in the world (~2 km²) — coverage is very limited and entirely urban. The luxury urban density is the primary identify.","mu":[{"c":"France (Côte d'Azur)","k":"Monaco is completely surrounded by France. Key splits: The extreme density, luxury, and cliff-face urban character is unique. French Riviera towns nearby (Nice, Cannes) are less dense and less dramatically built into cliffs."},{"c":"Italy (Italian Riviera)","k":"similar Mediterranean coastal feel nearby. Key splits: Monaco is French-language; Italian Riviera is Italian. Monaco's urban density is extreme."}],"ex":["Monaco is one of the easiest country identifications in GeoGuessr — the combination of ultra-luxury, extreme density, steep cliffs, and Mediterranean harbour is globally unique","The F1 circuit (Circuit de Monaco) has street-level barriers and trackside infrastructure visible in some coverage","Coverage is very limited given the tiny size — knowing the main areas (Port Hercules, Casino Square, La Condamine, Monte-Carlo) helps with pinpointing","Second smallest country in the world after Vatican City — but Vatican has no GeoGuessr coverage"]},{"id":"montenegro","n":"Montenegro","f":"🇲🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Rifts/sky tears visible when panning up — Montenegro has distinctive sky rift artefacts visible in older Gen 2 coverage. When you pan upward you can see circular or jagged rift patterns in the sky. Shared with Albania. In a Balkan context, rifts = Montenegro or Albania.","Yellow directional signs with black text — Montenegro uses yellow directional signs (same colour as Serbia's signs but Montenegro is a separate small country)","Brown signs with white lettering for tourist/scenic routes — common throughout Montenegro","Latin script more common on signs despite being related to Serbian — Montenegro's GeoGuessr coverage tends to show more Latin than Cyrillic, though both exist","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Montenegrin — virtually identical to Serbian, uses both Cyrillic and Latin. Latin Montenegrin characters: č, š, ž, ć, đ (same as Croatian/Serbian). In practice, Latin is more commonly seen on GeoGuessr signs. Montenegro is so small and coverage so limited that the landscape context + rifts is often more useful than language alone.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs","Brown tourist signs with white text","Standard European plates with EU-style blue strip","Montenegrin bollards: similar to Serbian family (centred red rectangle)","Road quality variable — coastal and main roads good, mountain roads rough"],"landb":["Dramatically beautiful — Montenegro is one of the most scenic small countries in GeoGuessr","Bay of Kotor: dramatic deep fjord-like bay surrounded by steep mountains — one of the most recognisable landscapes in the Balkans","Durmitor mountains (north): dramatic alpine peaks, glacial lakes, very rugged","Adriatic coast: narrow coastal strip, Mediterranean vegetation, clear blue sea","Overall extremely mountainous — Montenegro means \"Black Mountain\" aptly","Some of the most vertical, dramatic terrain in European GeoGuessr"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. Sky rifts in older Gen 2 coverage are the primary Montenegro car-era meta.","mu":[{"c":"Serbia","k":"nearly identical language, similar bollards. Key splits: Montenegro has rifts in sky; Serbia doesn't. Montenegro is coastal/alpine; Serbia is inland/flatter."},{"c":"Albania","k":"also has sky rifts! Key splits: Albania uses Latin-only with Albanian language (very different from Montenegrin). Albanian landscape different. Key split: rifts = Montenegro OR Albania → use language to confirm."},{"c":"Croatia","k":"also Adriatic coastal, also similar language. Key splits: Croatia has blue fire hydrants; Montenegro doesn't. Croatian directional signs are standard colour; Montenegro uses yellow."}],"ex":["Sky rifts = Montenegro or Albania in the Balkans → language/landscape splits the two","The Bay of Kotor coverage is breathtaking and immediately recognisable once you've seen it","Montenegro is tiny (~14,000 km²) — coverage is limited, so the distinctive landscape helps enormously","Montenegro has applied for EU membership — plates have EU-style formatting"]},{"id":"north_macedonia","n":"North Macedonia","f":"🇲🇰","co":"Europe","qt":["No antenna on the Google car — shared with Serbia and Greece. In a Macedonian context (Cyrillic + Balkans + yellow signs) this confirms North Macedonia.","Yellow directional signs with Cyrillic text on top, Latin translation below — North Macedonia's directional signs are yellow with black text, bilingual Cyrillic/Latin with Cyrillic on top. This specific format (yellow + Cyrillic above + Latin below) is distinctive.","Unique Cyrillic letters: Ѓ (Gje) and Ќ (Kje) — these two letters are unique to Macedonian Cyrillic and do not appear in Russian, Bulgarian, or Serbian Cyrillic. If you spot Ѓ or Ќ on a sign = North Macedonia.","White elongated plates (some) — North Macedonia has a mix of EU-style plates AND some older white elongated plates without EU strip.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Macedonian — South Slavic, Cyrillic script. Unique letters: Ѓ (Gje — g with acute) and Ќ (Kje — k with acute). These are found ONLY in Macedonian. Also shares Љ, Њ, Џ with Serbian. Signs are bilingual Cyrillic/Latin — Cyrillic on top, Latin transliteration below (road signs especially). Street suffix: улица (ulica), булевар (bulevar).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs with Cyrillic top, Latin bottom","No antenna on Google car","Mix of EU-style and older non-EU plates","Utility poles with distinctive lamps — North Macedonian poles often have unusual lamp attachments","Warning signs with yellow background in some areas"],"landb":["Balkan inland: rolling hills, mountains, river valleys","Vardar River valley runs through the country — flat fertile valley with mountains on both sides","Mountains: Šar Planina range (northwest), Baba/Pelister (southwest)","Lake Ohrid (southwest): one of the oldest and deepest lakes in Europe — very beautiful, UNESCO heritage","Generally: feels similar to southern Serbia or northern Greece in landscape but with Macedonian signs","Mix of agricultural flatlands (around Skopje) and dramatic mountains"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No antenna visible — same as Serbia and Greece. Use yellow signs + bilingual Cyrillic/Latin to confirm North Macedonia over the other two.","mu":[{"c":"Serbia","k":"also bilingual Cyrillic/Latin, also no antenna. Key splits: North Macedonia has yellow directional signs with Cyrillic above Latin; Serbia's signs vary in colour. Ѓ and Ќ characters = only Macedonia. Different bollards."},{"c":"Bulgaria","k":"also Cyrillic, also Balkans. Key splits: Bulgaria has bilingual Cyrillic+Latin settlement signs; North Macedonia's directional signs are specifically yellow with Cyrillic above Latin. Bulgarian plates always EU strip; Macedonian mixed."},{"c":"Greece","k":"also no antenna. Key splits: Greece uses Greek alphabet (completely different); North Macedonia uses Cyrillic/Latin."}],"ex":["Ѓ and Ќ on any sign = North Macedonia only — globally unique Cyrillic characters","Yellow directional signs with Cyrillic top/Latin bottom are the fastest non-language sign confirm","Lake Ohrid coverage is beautiful and distinctive — deep blue lake surrounded by mountains","North Macedonia has reasonable nationwide coverage","Skopje has notable coverage — distinctive \"Skopje 2014\" neoclassical/baroque government buildings"]},{"id":"malta","n":"Malta","f":"🇲🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Left-hand traffic + Mediterranean landscape — Malta is the ONLY EU country with EU-format plates that drives on the left (besides Ireland, which looks nothing like the Mediterranean). Left-hand traffic + Mediterranean dry rocky landscape = Malta immediately.","Cream/honey-coloured limestone buildings — Maltese architecture is built almost entirely from the local golden limestone. Every building is the same warm cream/honey colour. Flat roofs, thick walls, ornate carved stone details. No render, no brick — all bare limestone.","Extremely dry and sparse vegetation — Malta is one of the driest countries in Europe. Almost no trees. Low scrubby plants, patches of grass, bare rock. Very arid feel for a European country.","Distinctive plates — mix of standard EU plates and shorter/less-elongated plates with blue section in upper-left corner (not full left-strip like normal EU).","Left-hand traffic"],"ls":"Maltese + English — both official. Maltese is unique: it's a Semitic language (Arabic-based) written in Latin script. Maltese words look unusual for a European language — many Arabic-root words: triq (street), belt (city), djar (houses), sqaq (alley). English appears on most road signs. The combination of English + Arabic-looking Latin words + Mediterranean limestone island = Malta.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Standard European road sign shapes but all in English","Mixed plate types: standard EU-style and shorter plates with blue upper-left section","Road quality reasonable — small island, well-maintained main roads","Very dense coverage for such a small island"],"landb":["Arid Mediterranean island — bare, rocky, very dry. Almost no trees outside of planted areas.","Limestone landscape — flat to gently hilly, all bare pale limestone rock","Golden stone buildings everywhere — the most distinctive Malta visual. Every building is the same warm honey-limestone colour with flat roofs and ornate carved stone details.","Narrow winding streets in villages — medieval layout, very narrow, sometimes the Google car barely fits","Turquoise Mediterranean sea visible from coastal roads","No dramatic mountains — Malta is relatively flat with gentle rises"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Left-hand traffic is the primary confirm.","mu":[{"c":"Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also EU plates. Key splits: Ireland is green and rainy; Malta is dry and sunny. Ireland has bilingual English/Irish signs; Malta has English + Maltese. Completely different landscapes."},{"c":"Cyprus","k":"also Mediterranean island, also left-hand (British influence). Key splits: Cyprus uses Greek alphabet (Malta uses Latin). Cyprus is more mountainous and lush."},{"c":"UK/Gibraltar","k":"also left-hand, also English. Key splits: UK landscape is temperate green; Malta is dry limestone. Gibraltar has the Rock of Gibraltar."}],"ex":["Left-hand + dry Mediterranean limestone landscape = Malta, no other option in Europe","The golden limestone buildings are the single most distinctive Malta visual tell — once seen, never forgotten","Malta is tiny (~316 km²) — the whole island is covered and you're always near the coast","Valletta (capital): dramatic fortified city on a peninsula, UNESCO heritage, recognisable from the fortification walls and baroque churches","Gozo (second island): slightly more rural and quieter feel than main Malta island"]},{"id":"netherlands","n":"Netherlands","f":"🇳🇱","co":"Europe","qt":["Yellow license plates — both front AND rear — Netherlands is one of very few countries in the world with yellow plates on both ends. If you see yellow plates in a European context = Netherlands (or Luxembourg). Very fast confirm.","Completely flat — the Netherlands is one of the flattest countries on Earth. Zero hills. If it looks like Western Europe but is genuinely flat with no elevation = Netherlands.","Dutch language — abundance of z and w letters, double letters (aa, ee, oo), and ij combination. Words: weg (road/way), straat (street), laan (lane/avenue), dijk (dyke).","Cycling infrastructure everywhere — dedicated cycle paths (fietspad) alongside every road, often with their own markings. The Netherlands has more cycle paths per capita than anywhere. Red-surface cycle lanes visible on road edges.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Dutch — Latin script with abundant z, w, double vowels (aa, ee, oo, uu), and ij digraph. Words like straat, weg, plein, gracht (canal). Dutch is also spoken in Belgium (Flemish) and Suriname, but yellow plates + flat landscape = Netherlands specifically. German is similar but Dutch has distinctive letter patterns (geen, zijn, zijn — common Dutch words).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow plates front and rear — most reliable Netherlands confirm globally","Red cycle lane surfaces on road edges — dedicated cycling infrastructure","Standard EU white plates do appear on some vehicles but yellow is dominant","Green directional signs for main routes","Weg, straat suffixes on road signs"],"landb":["Perfectly flat — arguably the flattest country in GeoGuessr. Polders (reclaimed land below sea level), open flat agricultural land, windmills (though rare now), long straight roads.","Windmills occasionally visible in some areas","Open skies, big cloud formations over flat landscape — classic Dutch painting sky","Canals and ditches alongside roads everywhere — water management infrastructure","Dense suburban/urban development throughout — the Netherlands is the most densely populated EU country","Flat fields, ordered farms, brick housing","Rotterdam/Amsterdam areas: dense urban, canal-side architecture, narrow tall houses"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Netherlands is identified by yellow plates and flat landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Belgium (Flanders)","k":"also Dutch-speaking (Flemish), also flat in north. Key splits: Belgium has red-lettered EU white plates; Netherlands has yellow plates. Belgian landscape slightly less flat than Netherlands."},{"c":"Luxembourg","k":"also yellow plates! Key splits: Luxembourg has French/German/Luxembourgish language (not Dutch). Luxembourg is hilly (not flat). Very small country."},{"c":"Denmark","k":"also flat in some areas. Key splits: Denmark uses Danish language (æ, ø); Netherlands uses Dutch. Denmark has white/metal-border directional signs."}],"ex":["Yellow plates front AND rear = Netherlands or Luxembourg — two-country club globally. Flat + yellow = Netherlands immediately.","The cycling infrastructure (red road surface lanes) is visible on virtually every Dutch road","The Netherlands is extremely densely covered in GeoGuessr — even very small villages have coverage","Canal-side coverage in cities (Amsterdam, Utrecht, Leiden) is architecturally distinctive — tall narrow brick houses with hoisted beam at roof gable","The Dutch word ij appears constantly in place names and street names (Amsterdam = Amstel + dam, IJsselmeer, etc.)"]},{"id":"norway","n":"Norway","f":"🇳🇴","co":"Europe","qt":["Yellow directional signs — Norway uses yellow background with black text for directional/road signs. Most of Europe uses green or blue. Yellow directional signs = Norway (or Iceland, but Iceland has additional tells)","Yellow centre lines + dashed white outer edge lines — Norway is one of the few European countries using yellow centre lines. Combined with long-dashed white outer lines = Norway immediately","Green commercial vehicle plates — regular cars have standard EU white plates with blue strip, but commercial vehicles (vans, trucks) have distinctive dark green plates. If you spot a green plate on a van = Norway","Street names ending in -vei, -veien, -gate, -gata — Norwegian street suffix vocabulary, very consistent","Dramatic fjord/mountain landscape — fjords, dramatic cliffs, dark green forested slopes, snow-capped peaks"],"ls":"Norwegian uses Latin script with special characters å, æ, ø. Shared with Danish — the two are nearly identical in written form. Key Norwegian words: vei/veien (road), gate/gata (street), kommune (municipality), sentrum (centre). The -vei and -gate suffixes on street signs are very reliable. Norwegian vs Danish: practically impossible to distinguish from script alone — rely on other tells.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs — unique in mainland Scandinavia","Yellow centre lines — rare in Europe, shared with Iceland","Long-dashed white outer edge lines — longer dashes than Sweden (medium) or Denmark (short)","Warning signs: red border, white background, with additional outline outside the border","Standard EU white plates with blue strip; green plates on commercial vehicles","Tunnel signage common — Norway has more road tunnels than any other country in the world"],"landb":["Fjords — deep, narrow sea inlets carved by glaciers, with steep forested or rocky walls. The most iconic Norway landscape. If you see a deep blue-green water channel between dramatic cliff walls = Norway","Steep forested mountains — dark green conifer forests covering mountain slopes","Snow-capped peaks year-round in many areas","Rocky coastline — exposed granite rocks, islands, skerries","Western Norway: dramatic, steep, wet, green. Eastern Norway (around Oslo): flatter, more continental feel, drier","North Norway: subarctic tundra, midnight sun, sparse birch forests, very remote"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. Good quality newer coverage in many areas. No distinctive car meta. Norway is identified by yellow signs, yellow road lines, and landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Denmark","k":"same script (å, æ, ø), similar language. Key splits: Denmark is flat (no mountains); Norway is very mountainous. Denmark uses white directional signs with metal border + red writing; Norway uses yellow signs. Denmark uses short-dashed edge lines; Norway uses long-dashed."},{"c":"Sweden","k":"also Scandinavian, similar landscape in some areas. Key splits: Sweden uses white-on-blue directional signs; Norway uses yellow signs. Sweden has yellow-blue chevrons. Swedish script uses ä, ö not æ, ø."},{"c":"Iceland","k":"also yellow centre lines, also dramatic landscape. Key splits: Iceland has no trees at all; Norway has forests. Iceland has yellow bollards; Norway barely uses bollards."}],"ex":["Yellow directional signs are the single fastest Norway confirm — look for any road junction sign","Green commercial plates on vans/trucks are extremely reliable when visible","The tunnel entrances (blue rectangular portals with yellow border) are very distinctive Norway infrastructure","Norway has more road tunnels than any other country — if you drive into a long tunnel, you're likely in Norway or Switzerland","Bergen/western coast area: very rainy, extremely dramatic steep fjord landscape","Oslo area: more urban, less dramatic, could be confused with Sweden near the border"]},{"id":"poland","n":"Poland","f":"🇵🇱","co":"Europe","qt":["Concrete utility poles with holes NOT reaching the ground — Polish \"holey poles\" have large holes punched through them but the holes stop about half a metre above the ground (unlike Romanian and Hungarian holey poles where holes go all the way to the ground). This height split is the fastest Poland vs Romania/Hungary pole confirm.","Red diagonal stripe on bollards — Polish bollards have a single broad diagonal red stripe wrapping around the post. Very distinctive.","Polish language — unique characters ł (barred l, sounds like English \"w\") and ż/ź (z with dot/accent). Words: ulica (street), aleja (avenue), plac (square). The ł character appears extremely frequently in Polish text.","Thin red border on warning signs — Poland uses warning signs with a thin red border (thinner than Serbia or other Balkan countries)","Pedestrian crossing signs with ONE horizontal line behind the person — unique in Europe","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Polish — West Slavic language with distinctive characters: ł (looks like l with a diagonal stroke through it), ż (z with dot above), ź (z with accent), ą (a with ogonek/tail below), ę (e with ogonek), ó (o with accent), ś, ź, ć, ń (consonants with acute accent). The ł appears in extremely common words: ulica, plac, Polska, łódź, wrocław. If you see a letter that looks like a strikethrough-l = Polish, immediately.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Holey poles with holes NOT going to ground (stop ~0.5m above) — key split from Hungary/Romania","Diagonal red stripe bollards","Thin red border warning signs","One-horizontal-line pedestrian crossing signs — unique in Europe","Green directional signs with white lettering","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Double centre lines common on main roads"],"landb":["Central European: flat to gently rolling agricultural land, mixed deciduous forest","Wide flat plains in much of the country — Poland is geographically one of the flatter European countries","Birch forests visible in northeast","Architecture: mix of medieval old towns (Kraków, Warsaw's rebuilt old town), Soviet-era blocks, modern","Warsaw: large dense capital — rebuilt after WWII destruction, mix of styles","Kraków: beautiful well-preserved medieval old town"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Poland is identified by holey poles, bollards, and ł character.","mu":[{"c":"Hungary","k":"also holey poles. Key splits: Hungarian holes go ALL THE WAY TO THE GROUND; Polish holes stop 0.5m above ground. Hungarian language has ő, ű (double-accent vowels); Polish has ł, ą."},{"c":"Romania","k":"also holey poles. Key splits: Romanian holes go all the way to ground (like Hungary); Polish holes stop higher. Romanian has ă, ș, ț characters; Polish has ł, ą."},{"c":"Czech Republic","k":"also Central European, also Slavic. Key splits: Czech has ř (unique to Czech); Polish has ł. Czech directional signs are arrow-shaped; Polish are normal rectangular green signs."}],"ex":["Ł (barred-l) = Polish only in Europe — appears in very common words, unmissable on any sign","Holey poles stopping 0.5m above ground = Poland; holes to ground = Hungary or Romania","Diagonal red stripe bollards are distinctive and consistent","Poland has excellent nationwide coverage including rural areas and mountain regions (Tatras)","The Tatra mountains (south Poland/Slovakia border) have dramatic alpine coverage"]},{"id":"madeira_portugal","n":"Madeira (Portugal)","f":"🇵🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Portuguese language + dramatic volcanic mountain island — Madeira is an autonomous region of Portugal. Same language, same plates, same poles as mainland Portugal. The key identifier is the dramatic volcanic landscape.","Extremely steep and dramatic terrain — Madeira is a volcanic island with very sharp, tall mountains dropping steeply to the sea. Roads are extremely winding, often cut into cliff faces. Tunnels and viaducts everywhere.","Laurel forest (Laurisilva) — Madeira's unique UNESCO-listed ancient laurel forest. Dark, dense, mossy subtropical forest at higher altitudes. Very distinctive — nothing else in Europe looks like it.","Levadas (irrigation channels) — narrow stone-lined water channels running along cliffsides. Unique to Madeira.","Portuguese plates + yellow right-side strip — same as mainland Portugal. Plates are white EU-format with yellow section on the right side (unique in Europe — mainland Portugal is the only European country with yellow on the right).","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Portuguese — same as mainland. Signs: Rua (street), Estrada (road), Caminho (path/lane). Blue-and-white azulejo tile street signs visible in some areas. Madeira uses the same plate conventions as mainland Portugal including the yellow right-strip.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Portuguese plates — white EU-format with yellow section on the right side","Extremely narrow winding mountain roads","Many tunnels cut through volcanic rock","Viaducts spanning deep valleys","Same road sign conventions as mainland Portugal"],"landb":["Volcanic mountain island — very tall, very steep, very dramatic. The central mountains reach 1862m (Pico Ruivo). Extremely vertical terrain.","Lush but dramatic — greener than the Canary Islands but drier than the Azores at lower altitudes. More subtropical lushness at higher elevations.","Laurisilva — ancient UNESCO laurel forest at altitude: dark, atmospheric, mossy. Very distinctive.","Coastal cliffs — dramatic black volcanic rock cliffs dropping straight to the Atlantic","Funchal (capital): terraced city on south coast hillside, colourful buildings, cable car infrastructure visible","Black volcanic rock walls lining roads throughout the island"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Landscape + Portuguese plates are the primary confirms.","mu":[{"c":"Azores","k":"also Portuguese volcanic Atlantic islands. Key splits: Azores is much greener and flatter on lower ground, with vivid hydrangea hedgerows lining roads; Madeira is steeper and drier at low altitude with more dramatic cliffs. Azores has visible crater lakes; Madeira has Laurisilva forest."},{"c":"Canary Islands (Spain)","k":"also Atlantic volcanic islands. Key splits: Canary Islands use Spanish language and Spanish plates (EU format, no yellow right strip). Madeira uses Portuguese + yellow-right plates."},{"c":"Mainland Portugal","k":"same language and plates. Key splits: Mainland Portugal is mostly flat to hilly; Madeira is dramatically mountainous and obviously an island."}],"ex":["The steep cliff-face roads, tunnels, and viaducts are the fastest Madeira landscape confirm — nowhere in mainland Portugal or the Azores has this level of vertical drama","Yellow strip on the right side of plates = Portugal (mainland + Madeira + Azores) — unique in all of Europe","Funchal cable car pylons and infrastructure visible in some coastal coverage","Levadas (narrow i"]},{"id":"azores_portugal","n":"Azores (Portugal)","f":"🇵🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["Portuguese language + intensely green rolling volcanic island landscape — The Azores are the greenest islands in the Atlantic. Vivid emerald green hills, lush pastures, dense subtropical vegetation. More intensely green than even Ireland.","Hydrangea hedgerows lining roads — blue and purple hydrangeas grow wild everywhere along roadsides, used as field boundaries. This is the single most distinctive Azores visual — nothing else in GeoGuessr looks like a road lined by walls of blue hydrangeas.","Portuguese plates with yellow right-strip — same as mainland Portugal and Madeira.","Volcanic crater lakes — visible in some coverage: perfectly round blue/green crater lakes in the centres of old volcanoes (Sete Cidades, Lagoa das Sete Cidades on São Miguel are iconic).","Cows everywhere — the Azores is a major dairy region. Green pastures with black-and-white Friesian cattle on virtually every hillside.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Portuguese — same as mainland. Signs: Rua, Estrada, Caminho. Same plate conventions as mainland Portugal (white EU-format + yellow right-strip). The combination of Portuguese + extreme lush green + hydrangeas = Azores.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Portuguese plates — yellow right-strip (unique in Europe)","Roads winding through intensely green landscape","Some roads lined with hydrangea hedgerows","Well-maintained but often narrow"],"landb":["Intensely green and lush — the Azores sit in the mid-Atlantic with high rainfall year-round. The result is extraordinary lushness — greener than Ireland, greener than Madeira's low altitudes.","Rolling hills and volcanic peaks — gentle to moderate terrain on most islands. Less dramatically steep than Madeira.","Hydrangea hedgerows — blue/purple hydrangeas line roads as field boundaries. Unique and unmistakable.","Crater lakes — circular lakes in old volcanic craters visible on higher ground","Hot springs and geothermal features — steaming fumaroles, thermal pools (visible in some coverage near Furnas, São Miguel)","Black sand beaches — volcanic black sand at some coastal areas","Dairy cattle on green hillsides everywhere","Islands are scattered across the mid-Atlantic — São Miguel (largest, most coverage), Terceira, Faial, Pico etc."],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Landscape + hydrangeas + Portuguese plates are the primary confirms.","mu":[{"c":"Madeira","k":"also Portuguese volcanic Atlantic island. Key splits: Azores is much greener and flatter with hydrangea hedgerows; Madeira is steeper and drier at low altitude with dramatic cliffs and Laurisilva forest. Azores has crater lakes; Madeira doesn't."},{"c":"Ireland","k":"also intensely green, also Atlantic island. Key splits: Ireland uses English/Irish + EU blue-strip plates; Azores uses Portuguese + yellow-right-strip plates. Hydrangea hedgerows = Azores not Ireland."},{"c":"Mainland Portugal","k":"same language and plates. Key splits: Mainland is generally drier/flatter; Azores is volcanic island with extreme lushness."}],"ex":["Hydrangea hedgerows = Azores, immediately — no other GeoGuessr location has this as a consistent roadside feature","Yellow-right plate strip = Portugal family (mainland + Madeira + Azores) — unique in Europe","The Azores are spread across 9 islands — coverage is mostly São Miguel (Ponta Delgada area) and Terceira","Geothermal steam visible near Furnas village is one of the most dramatic landscape features in GeoGuessr"]},{"id":"portugal","n":"Portugal","f":"🇵🇹","co":"Europe","qt":["License plate yellow strip — Portuguese plates have a blue strip on the left AND a unique yellow strip on the right. No other European country has this. (Discontinued 2020 — Gen 4 coverage may show only the blue strip.)","Eucalyptus trees — extremely common across Portugal, especially the northwest. Rare elsewhere in Europe (only northern Spain has some). Tall, pale-barked, aromatic-looking trees.","Concrete ladder poles with tall steps — utility poles have very tall ladder rungs, often with a small see-through hole in each step. Spain/France have short steps.","Red guardrail reflectors — Portugal uses A-type guardrails with red reflectors. Spain uses yellow. Instantly distinguishable.","Black-and-yellow chevrons — unique among Mediterranean countries. Spain uses white-and-yellow, France uses red-and-white."],"lb":["Portuguese is closely related to Spanish but has unique letters: Ã, Õ, Â, Ê, Ç — none of which are Spanish (except Ç in Catalan). Crucially, Portuguese has no Ñ — if you see Ñ, you're in Spain.","The word for street is \"Rua\" (Spanish: Calle; Galician: Rúa with accent). \"Rua\" without accent = Portugal.","Common Portuguese words on signs: \"Saída\" (exit), \"Entrada\" (entrance), \"Câmara Municipal,\" \"Farmácia,\" \"Pastelaria.\"","Azulejo tile street signs — blue-and-white ceramic tile panels mounted directly on building walls instead of metal posts. Extremely characteristic of Portugal.","Azores and Madeira are Portuguese territory — same language and sign conventions.","French Guiana, Cape Verde, Brazil are also Portuguese-speaking but have completely different visual contexts."],"rb":["Guardrail reflectors: red (Spain: yellow) — one of the fastest Portugal vs. Spain tells at speed.","Chevrons: black body with yellow arrow — unique in Mediterranean Europe.","Road signs have a white border — most Spanish signs lack this white border.","Directional signs: white background with black arrows that don't touch the sign border. Spanish directional signs use coloured road-number boxes and thin black borders only.","Stop signs: large font. Spanish stop signs use a distinctly small, compact font.","Pedestrian crossing signs: 5 stripes, and the figure wears a high belt. Spain: 8 stripes. Italy: no belt. Greece: dotted lines.","Hunting signs: red-and-white, diamond or rectangular shape. Spanish hunting signs are black-and-white.","Kilometre markers: wide rectangles with a coloured section on the left divided diagonally from the white part. Square km signs appear every km showing road number in coloured top half.","Black-and-white waystones (kilometre stones) are common along older roads.","Cobblestone roads: very common, typically square stones arranged diagonally to the road direction.","Cobblestone sidewalks made of bright white/grey stones (calçada portuguesa) — distinctive Portuguese pavement art pattern.","Porto: lime green street signs (unique to the city)."],"landb":["Architecture: White painted stone houses with orange/terracotta tiled roofs are the dominant style. Blue or yellow painted trim around windows, doors, and wall edges is very common.","Decorative azulejo tiles (blue-and-white or coloured mosaic tiles) cover many building facades — a hallmark of Portuguese architecture.","Northern Portugal: Houses often built of square concrete blocks with white mortar (similar just over the border in Galicia, but usually without the mortar).","Algarve (south/Faro district): Distinctive decorative chimneys — round or square with small spire-shaped tops. The round chimney is a very strong regional tell.","Northwest: Dense eucalyptus forests. Also maritime pine (grey bark with red undertones, fluffy upward-pointing branches, bare lower trunk).","Southeast (Alentejo): Open fields with sparse holm oaks and cork oaks (montado). Cork oaks often have their lower trunk stripped of bark, revealing a vivid reddish-orange surface — very visible and distinctive. Flat, golden landscape with long straight roads. Village houses are whitewashed with a horizontal blue or yellow stripe at mid-wall height.","Douro Valley (east of Porto): Steep terraced vineyards carved into hillsides along the river.","Northeast + south: Olive plantations in dense rows.","South coast: Citrus plantations.","Serra da Estrela: Rocky mountainous highland with yellow-and-black snow poles.","Near Setúbal–Sines coast: Pine forest on strikingly white sandy soil.","Far southwest: Flat, dry, almost no trees — only low scrub."],"carb":["Gen 4 Smallcam coverage is common — lower-mounted than standard Gen 4, big circular blur with a small front protrusion. Blur can be fully transparent, making it harder to spot.","No distinctive car artifacts unique to Portugal vs. Spain — rely on road/environment clues.","Coverage quality is generally good across mainland Portugal.","Azores and Madeira have their own separate plonkit guides."],"mu":[{"c":"Spain","k":"Red guardrail reflectors (PT) vs yellow (ES); yellow strip on plate (PT, pre-2020); eucalyptus trees (PT >> ES); tall ladder pole steps (PT) vs short (ES); black-yellow chevrons (PT) vs white-yellow (ES); stop sign font large (PT) vs small (ES); white sign border (PT); pedestrian sign 5 stripes + belt (PT) vs 8 stripes (ES); \"Rua\" not \"Calle\"; no Ñ"},{"c":"Galicia (NW Spain)","k":"Very similar landscape and concrete block houses; check plate (ES has EU blue strip but no yellow right strip), \"Rúa\" with accent vs \"Rua\" without, hunting sign colour (PT red-white vs ES black-white)"},{"c":"Brazil","k":"Portuguese language but: yellow center lines (Portugal uses white/European standard), tropical vegetation, completely different architecture, Brazilian plates are yellow rectangles"},{"c":"Italy","k":"Both have orange roofs and Mediterranean feel; check language (Portuguese Ã/Õ vs Italian), chevron colour, guardrail reflector colour"}],"ex":["Area codes: Portuguese landlines start with 2 + regional digit. Numbers starting with 29x = Azores or Madeira.","Azores (west of mainland) and Madeira (southwest) count as Portugal for GeoGuessr. Both have distinct island geography — see their dedicated plonkit guides.","Bollards: Wedge-shaped with thin white top, or flat with wide reflector (white or orange). Darker than Spain's yellow reflectors.","Holm oak / cork oak (montado): Cork oaks often have their lower bark stripped, revealing a distinctive reddish-brown trunk — very visible and unique to Portugal/southwest Spain.","Flattened landscape: Much of the Alentejo is very flat and open, with low scrub and wheat fields — can feel desolate. Combined with the orange rooftops of occasional villages, very distinctly Portuguese."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_1.png"},{"l":"Language clues","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_3.png"},{"l":"License plate","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_2.png"},{"l":"Ladder pole","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_4.png"},{"l":"Guardrail","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_5.png"},{"l":"Chevrons","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_6.png"},{"l":"White houses","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_7.png"},{"l":"Cobblestone","f":"Europe_pt_Portugal_8.png"}]},{"id":"romania","n":"Romania","f":"🇷🇴","co":"Europe","qt":["Holey poles with holes going ALL THE WAY TO THE GROUND — same as Hungary. Romanian concrete utility poles also have full-length large holes. Many Romanian holey poles also have white-painted bottoms and/or yellow markings on them — an additional distinguishing detail.","Romanian language — unique characters ă (a with breve), â (a with circumflex), î (i with circumflex), ș (s with comma-below), ț (t with comma-below). These cedilla/comma-below characters ș and ț are unique to Romanian.","Town entry signs with yellow section showing speed limit + town skyline silhouette at top, white section with name below — very distinctive Romanian sign design.","Directional signs: white text on blue background — Romanian directional signs are blue with white text.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Romanian — Romance language (Latin-derived), unlike its Slavic neighbours. Special characters: ă (a-breve), â/î (a/i with circumflex), ș (s with comma-below — looks like ş but the mark is a comma not a cedilla), ț (t with comma-below). These comma-below characters ș and ț are found only in Romanian. Street suffix: stradă (street), strada, bulevardul (boulevard). Words end in vowels frequently, similar to Italian.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Holey poles — full length to ground, sometimes with white-painted base and yellow markings","Blue directional signs with white text","Town entry signs with yellow speed limit section + skyline silhouette at top","Roadside markers in various colours (blue, red, white) showing road numbers and distances","Romania barely uses bollards — if you don't see bollards in an Eastern European context, lean Romania","Standard EU white plates with blue strip"],"landb":["Very diverse:","Carpathian mountains: dramatic forested mountains — the Carpathians arc through Transylvania. Dense dark forests, mountain villages, dramatic peaks.","Transylvania (central): hilly, forested, Germanic/Saxon architectural influence (Sibiu, Brasov)","Wallachia (south): flat Danube plain, agricultural, Soviet-era feel","Moldova (east): rolling hills, agricultural","Black Sea coast: flat, resort towns (Constanța area)","Architecture ranges from beautiful Saxon villages to heavy Soviet-era blocks in cities"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Romania is identified by holey poles, ș/ț language, and town sign design.","mu":[{"c":"Hungary","k":"also full-length holey poles. Key splits: Hungarian has ő, ű (double accent); Romanian has ș, ț (comma below). Very clean language split once you know the characters."},{"c":"Moldova","k":"also Romanian language, similar landscape. Moldova has almost no official GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Bulgaria","k":"neighbouring, similar landscape in some areas. Key splits: Bulgaria uses Cyrillic script; Romania uses Latin. Very easy script split."}],"ex":["ș and ț (comma below, not cedilla) = Romanian ONLY — if you see these characters = Romania immediately","Holey poles = Romania or Hungary → use ș/ț vs ő/ű to split","Town entry signs (yellow + skyline) are very consistent and fast confirms at any town","Romania has extensive coverage including remote mountain villages in the Carpathians","Bucharest (capital): large, mix of communist-era mega-buildings (Palace of Parliament is the world's largest civilian building) and older architecture"]},{"id":"serbia","n":"Serbia","f":"🇷🇸","co":"Europe","qt":["No antenna on the Google car — Serbia is one of very few Eastern European countries where the Google car antenna is absent. Most of Eastern Europe has a visible antenna. No antenna in a Cyrillic/Latin Balkan context = Serbia (shared with Greece and North Macedonia — but context separates these easily).","Serbian bollard with red rectangle positioned to one side (left) — Serbian bollards look similar to Croatian/Slovenian but the red rectangle is always off-centre, positioned to the LEFT side of the front face. This side-positioning is unique to Serbia.","Bilingual Cyrillic and Latin — Serbia uses both scripts. Road signs can appear in either or both. Serbian Cyrillic has unique letters: Ј (j), Љ (lj), Њ (nj), Ћ (ć), Ђ (đ), Џ (dž). Latin Serbian uses č, š, ž, ć, đ.","Yellow road signs with black text in some areas — Serbian signs often yellow-background with black lettering.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Serbian — South Slavic, uses BOTH Cyrillic AND Latin scripts (officially both are standard). Serbian Cyrillic unique letters: Ј, Љ, Њ, Ћ, Ђ, Џ. Latin Serbian: č, š, ž, ć, đ (same as Croatian). When you see Cyrillic in the Balkans context (not Russia/Ukraine/Bulgaria) = Serbia or North Macedonia or Montenegro. Serbian vs Bulgarian: Bulgarian always Cyrillic only; Serbian is bilingual. Street suffix Cyrillic: улица (ulica) or Latin: ulica.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","No antenna on Google car — very reliable car meta","Yellow signs with black text common on Serbian roads","Off-centre (left-side) red rectangle bollards","Standard EU-style white plates with blue strip","Road quality variable — highways good, rural roads often poor","Brown tourist directional signs with white text also common"],"landb":["Central Balkan landscape: rolling hills, deciduous forest, agricultural plains","Vojvodina (north): flat Pannonian plain — very flat, agricultural, similar to Hungary","Central Serbia: rolling hills, mixed forest, river valleys (Morava, Drina)","Southern Serbia: more mountainous, approaching Balkans proper","Belgrade: large Balkan capital, mix of Austro-Hungarian legacy, communist blocks, and modern buildings. Fortress (Kalemegdan) at confluence of Sava and Danube.","Generally: feels poorer than Western Europe but with rich urban character"],"car":"No antenna visible — this is one of the most reliable Serbia car metas. In Eastern Europe where most cars have visible antennas, the absence of an antenna strongly points to Serbia (or Greece in a different context, or North Macedonia).","mu":[{"c":"Bulgaria","k":"also Cyrillic. Key splits: Bulgaria has bilingual Latin+Cyrillic settlement signs; Serbia uses both scripts on all signs. Bulgarian plates have EU strip and are full EU member; Serbian plates also have EU-style strip but Serbia is not EU. Landscape context also helps."},{"c":"Montenegro","k":"nearly identical language, similar landscape, also Cyrillic/Latin. Key splits: Montenegro has rifts in sky; Serbia doesn't. Montenegro is coastal/alpine; Serbia is inland. Very hard split otherwise."},{"c":"Croatia","k":"same Latin script characters (č, š, ž, ć, đ). Key splits: Croatia never uses Cyrillic; Serbia does. Croatian street signs are blue; Serbian are various. Blue fire hydrants = Croatia not Serbia."},{"c":"North Macedonia","k":"also no antenna! Key splits: North Macedonia has yellow directional signs with Cyrillic above Latin; Serbia has various sign styles. North Macedonia bollards are different."}],"ex":["No antenna is the fastest Serbia car meta — the moment you look down and see no antenna in a Balkan Cyrillic context = Serbia","Off-centre (left-side) red bollard rectangle is very distinctive once you know the Serbia/Slovenia/Croatia bollard family","Serbia has excellent nationwide coverage","Novi Sad (second city): attractive Austro-Hungarian architecture on the Danube"]},{"id":"russia","n":"Russia","f":"🇷🇺","co":"Europe","qt":["Black Google car with long visible rear antenna — THE primary Russia car meta. Long antenna extending from the rear. No other major European country has this. Black car + long rear antenna + Cyrillic = Russia.","Purely Cyrillic signs — Russia almost never uses Latin on road signs. Purely Cyrillic with no Latin separates Russia from Bulgaria (bilingual), Serbia/Montenegro (both scripts), North Macedonia (bilingual yellow signs).","White elongated plates with no EU blue strip — Russian plates are white, elongated, no EU formatting.","White signposts with small black section at base — very consistent Russian sign pole painting style.","Blue distance marker posts on highways (small blue posts showing km distances).","Right-hand traffic in western Russia."],"rb":["М (M) roads — federal motorways, radiating from Moscow (М1 to Minsk, М4 to Sochi/Krasnodar, etc.)","А (A) roads — federal roads not starting from Moscow","Р (R) roads — regional federal roads"],"car":"Black car with long visible rear antenna — consistent in western Russia. In eastern Russia the car may vary as coverage was done by local contractors. The right-hand drive cars visible on the road (parked or passing) are more useful than the Google car itself for eastern Russia identification.","mu":[{"c":"Ukraine","k":"most similar western appearance. Key splits: Ukraine has red car; Russia has black car with long antenna. Ukrainian plates have yellow+blue strip; Russian plates plain white. Ukrainian unique Cyrillic letters Ї, Є (not in Russian)."},{"c":"Kazakhstan","k":"also vast, also Cyrillic, also flat steppe in southern Russia border area. Key splits: Kazakhstan signs often bilingual Cyrillic (Kazakh) + Latin; Russian signs are Cyrillic only. Kazakhstan has its own plate style. The steppe in southern Russia vs Kazakhstan can look very similar — check signs carefully."},{"c":"Belarus","k":"also Cyrillic, but essentially no GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Finland/Scandinavia","k":"also birch forests, also flat. Key splits: Finland uses Finnish/Latin; Russia uses Cyrillic. Completely different scripts."}],"ex":["Russia is one of the most common spawns in GeoGuessr World maps — you will see it constantly. Investing in regional knowledge pays off enormously.","Moscow-region coverage is most common — the dense road network around Moscow means a disproportionate amount of Russian spawns are in the greater Moscow area.","Road quality is a supporting regional tell: western Russia major highways reasonable; rural Russia rough; Siberian roads can be very rough/unpaved.","Industrial infrastructure (oil rigs, factories, Soviet-era industrial plants) is visible in many regions — the Urals and Siberia have distinctive heavy industry.","Soviet-era architecture is everywhere: standard 5-storey Khrushchyovka blocks in all mid-size cities across the country."]},{"id":"sweden","n":"Sweden","f":"🇸🇪","co":"Europe","qt":["Blue chevrons with yellow arrows — unique in Europe. No other country uses this combination (Norway uses white-on-brown, Finland white-on-black).","All road lines are white — Norway and Finland both use yellow center lines. If every line on the road is white, lean Sweden strongly.","Blue-and-white wooden electricity markers near utility poles — a thin wooden post with blue and white stripes at the top. Found nowhere else in the Nordic countries.","Red-and-yellow road infrastructure — warning signs have a red border on a yellow background; signposts have red-and-yellow stripe markings; even road barriers and roadwork signs use red and yellow. This colour scheme is pervasive and uniquely Swedish.","Gen 3 white car with long antenna — very common in Sweden, also appears in Iceland, but extremely rare in Norway, Denmark, and Finland."],"lb":["Swedish uses Å, Ä, Ö — all three. Key distinction: Norwegian and Danish use only Å (not Ä or Ö); Finnish uses Ä and Ö but treats Å as Swedish. Seeing Ä or Ö alongside Å points to Sweden (or Finland — use other clues).","Finnish words are distinctively long with frequent double vowels (e.g. \"kauppakeskus,\" \"liikennöidään\"). Swedish words are shorter with no double vowels — easy to tell apart once you know.","Street name suffixes: Swedish uses -vägen or -gatan (often shortened to \"v\" and \"g\" on signs). Norway uses -veien/-vei/-gate; Denmark uses -vej/-gade; Finland uses -tie/-katu.","Sámi bilingual signs appear inland in the far north — a strong tell for northern Sweden.","Meänkieli (a Finnish-related language) appears near the Finnish border; river names ending in -väylä are a distinctive clue. Finnish-sounding place names = close to Finnish border."],"rb":["Chevrons: yellow arrow on blue background — only Sweden in Europe (Luxembourg extremely rarely).","All road lines white — outer lines on small roads are white dashed, distinctly shorter dashes than Norway's. Highway outer lines appear solid from a distance but are divided into small sections (not solid like Finland/Norway; Denmark has similar but sections are rectangular).","Warning signs: red border + yellow background. Finnish signs add a thin yellow outer border outside the red.","Directional signs: blue with white font and thin white border + thin arrow. Norway: yellow or white signs. Finland: white signs with a filled white arrow (not outline).","Signpost markings: blue-and-white or red-and-yellow stripes on the post itself. Red-and-yellow is essentially unique to Sweden.","\"Mötesplats\" signs: small blue sign with a large white M (passing place on narrow roads). Norway has similar but the M's middle point reaches the bottom. No equivalent in Finland.","Snow poles: orange with a wide white reflector positioned slightly above the middle. Finland: very thin reflector close to top. Norway: reflectors placed differently, often at middle.","Electricity markers: thin wooden post, blue and white stripe at top — found only in Sweden among Nordic countries.","Bollards: black-and-white, various shapes (wedge, round, thin-curved). Grey reflector normally; orange at intersections.","Utility poles: wooden with small black metal cap on top (shared with other Nordics). Lamp attached slightly below the top with double bolting (Finland: lamp at the very top, straighter).","Pedestrian signs: 4 stripes (Finland/Denmark: 5; Norway: usually 4 but sometimes 5).","Railway crossing sign backs: yellow sticker with 5-digit ID — first digit indicates region (increases northeast)."],"landb":["Falun red houses — dark red wooden houses are the dominant rural style. Also exists in Norway and Finland but is most prevalent and iconic in Sweden, especially in Dalarna.","Boreal forest (spruce, pine, birch) dominates. Large flat expanses of forest with many lakes throughout.","South (Skåne): Most open agricultural landscape in Sweden — open fields with few trees, reminiscent of Denmark. Half-timbered houses, red brick buildings, diamond-tiled roofs.","West coast: Smooth, rounded exposed rocks along shore with low vegetation. White and light yellow houses common near Norwegian border.","North: Trees get shorter and thinner. Mountains above treeline only in the far northwest. Sandy/mossy soil in the far north. Orange snow poles common.","Dalarna: Red dirt roads (and slightly red asphalt), dense thin pines, strong woodcraft tradition in architecture.","Gotland: Limestone houses with dirty-white facades; white sand beside roads; small juniper bushes on Fårö; wooden windmills.","Öland: Extremely flat, barren south half with small bushes; stone brick walls; uneven stone houses.","Traditional wooden fence (gärdsgård) — thin spaced vertical trunks + diagonal logs stacked on top; most common in Sweden, rarer in Norway near the border.","Volvo makes up ~30% of all passenger cars — by far the most if you can read the badge.","Swedish church flag: red cross on yellow background with a crown in the middle — commonly seen near churches."],"carb":["Gen 3: White car with a long antenna — very common in Sweden. Same car covers all of Iceland and is somewhat common in Finland, but extremely rare in Norway and Denmark. Seeing it strongly suggests Sweden or Iceland.","Gen 4: Three car colors exist in Sweden — red, white, and blue. Only the blue car also appears in Norway, Finland, and Denmark. A red or white Gen 4 car = Sweden only.","Gen 4 Smallcam: Lower-mounted, big circular blur, small front protrusion. Common across Northern Europe.","West coast / Skåne: A white Gen 3/4 car with a blue stripe on the back — almost never found outside Sweden."],"mu":[{"c":"Norway","k":"Yellow center lines (NO) vs all-white (SE); yellow/white directional signs (NO) vs blue (SE); chevrons white-on-brown (NO) vs yellow-on-blue (SE); Norwegian street names end in -veien/-vei; longer road line dashes (NO)"},{"c":"Finland","k":"Finnish has very long words with double vowels; yellow center line (FI); filled white arrow on directional signs (FI); snow pole reflector near top (FI); lamp at top of pole, straighter (FI); street suffix -tie/-katu (FI)"},{"c":"Denmark","k":"No Ä or Ö in Danish (only Å); street names end in -vej/-gade; red brick towns look similar to Skåne — check language and signs"},{"c":"Iceland","k":"Also has Gen 3 white car with antenna — but Iceland has no trees above a certain altitude, very volcanic landscape, no road line markings on many roads"}],"ex":["Road number geography: National roads 9–99; regional roads 100–404. Numbers generally increase northeast — useful for rough region-guessing.","Place name endings are region-specific — plonkit has a detailed map (e.g. -bo, -sta, -by, -åker all concentrate in different areas).","Area codes: First 2–4 digits of landlines indicate region; first two digits increase northeast. Mobile numbers always start with 07.","Bus stop signs are region-specific — each of Sweden's 21 regions has its own design. City-specific too: Gothenburg has unique blue street signs; Stockholm street signs have two rows divided by a black line; Malmö has white signs with black corners.","Snowmobile trail markers: Small red crosses on poles, found in northern half of the country.","Green snow poles occasionally near Umeå — unusual vs the standard orange.","Sámi bilingual signs inland in the far north; Meänkieli near Finnish border."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_1.png"},{"l":"Blue-yellow chevrons","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_2.png"},{"l":"White road lines","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_3.png"},{"l":"Road signs: red border, yellow background","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_6.png"},{"l":"Directional signs: blue with white","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_7.png"},{"l":"Electricity markers","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_4.png"},{"l":"Falun red architecture","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_5.png"},{"l":"Gen 3 white car with antenna","f":"Europe_se_Sweden_8.png"}]},{"id":"slovenia","n":"Slovenia","f":"🇸🇮","co":"Europe","qt":["Yellow directional signs with black text — Slovenian directional signs have a yellow background with black text. Very few European countries use yellow for directional signs (Norway uses yellow too but context is completely different). In a Central/Eastern European context, yellow directional signs = Slovenia.","Kilometre markers with road number in a yellow rectangle at top-left — Slovenian km posts have a distinctive yellow box containing the road number in the top-left corner. Very consistent and recognisable.","Slovenian bollards — front has red centred rectangle; rear has white centred rectangle. Similar family to Serbia/Croatia but Slovenia-specific shape.","Slovenian language — uses č, š, ž with Latin script. Street suffix: ulica (street), cesta (road). Words: pot (path), vas (village). Slovene is closely related to Croatian/Serbian.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Slovenian (Slovene) — South Slavic, Latin script. Characters: č, š, ž (same as Croatian but Slovene uses fewer of ć and đ). Key Slovene words: ulica (street), cesta (road), vas (village), pot (path). Slovene looks very similar to Croatian in written form — rely on directional sign colour (yellow = Slovenia) and km marker style rather than language alone.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow directional signs with black text — fastest Slovenia sign confirm","Km markers with yellow road number rectangle top-left","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","Slovenian bollards: centred red rectangle on front","Road quality excellent — Slovenia is one of the wealthier former Yugoslav states"],"landb":["Alps in the northwest — Julian Alps with dramatic peaks (Triglav, highest in former Yugoslavia). Very alpine — can look similar to Austria or Switzerland.","Karst (southwest): limestone plateau with underground caves (Postojna Cave area) — bare white rock, sparse scrub","Mediterranean coast (very short, near Piran): small Adriatic coastline","Central/eastern plains: agricultural, more Central European feel","Generally: very green, forested, mountainous in most of the country","Small and compact country — great variety in a tiny area"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. Blue car with antenna visible in Gen 4 (Mediterranean European). No single distinctive car meta.","mu":[{"c":"Croatia","k":"most similar. Both South Slavic Latin, both former Yugoslavia. Key splits: Slovenia has yellow directional signs; Croatia has standard green/blue directional signs. Slovenia has yellow km marker box; Croatia doesn't. Blue fire hydrants = Croatia, not Slovenia."},{"c":"Austria","k":"also alpine, also good roads. Key splits: Austria uses German (ß, umlauts); Slovenia uses Slovenian (č, š, ž). Austrian bollards have dark reflector + black hat; Slovenian are standard centred red rectangle."},{"c":"Montenegro","k":"also uses similar language/characters. Key splits: Montenegro has rifts in sky; Slovenia doesn't. Montenegro is Mediterranean coastal; Slovenia is alpine."}],"ex":["Yellow directional signs = Slovenia in a Central/Eastern European context — the fastest non-language Slovenia confirm","The yellow road number rectangle on km posts is very reliable once you recognise it","Slovenia has excellent full-coverage including mountain roads (Vršič Pass is one of the most spectacular mountain roads in GeoGuessr)","Ljubljana (capital): compact, charming Central European city with a castle on a hill","Slovenia is the most prosperous of the former Yugoslav states — infrastructure feels noticeably better than Serbia/Montenegro"]},{"id":"svalbard_norway","n":"Svalbard (Norway)","f":"🇸🇯","co":"Europe","qt":["Arctic tundra landscape with no trees whatsoever — Svalbard is above the treeline. Absolutely no trees anywhere. Bare tundra, rock, snow/ice, glaciers. If you see a completely treeless Arctic landscape with Norwegian signs = Svalbard.","Norwegian language on signs — Svalbard is Norwegian territory. Signs are in Norwegian. But the landscape alone is usually enough — no other GeoGuessr location looks like this.","Glaciers visible — over 60% of Svalbard is covered by glaciers. Dramatic white glacier tongues descending from mountains to sea are visible in some coverage.","Extreme northern sun angle — in summer coverage, the sun is very low on the horizon even at midday, casting long shadows. In winter coverage, almost no light.","Longyearbyen — the only town with coverage. Small Arctic settlement with colourful wooden buildings, snowmobile trails, coal mining infrastructure.","Right-hand traffic (same as Norway)"],"ls":"Norwegian — same as mainland Norway. Signs use Norwegian vocabulary: vei/veg (road), gate (street). Standard Norwegian road sign conventions. The key is that language + landscape together = immediate Svalbard confirm.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Norwegian road signs","Very few roads — coverage is limited to Longyearbyen and a handful of roads","Norwegian plates (same as mainland)","Polar bear warning signs — distinctive yellow warning signs with polar bear silhouette visible near the edge of settlement. Unique to Svalbard.","No national speed limit road signs on many stretches"],"landb":["High Arctic — Svalbard sits between 74°–81°N, halfway between mainland Norway and the North Pole","Completely treeless — tundra biome. Low mosses, lichens, hardy grass only","Glaciers — dramatic white ice masses covering 60% of the land","Dramatic fjords — deep Arctic fjords with ice-reflected water","Mountains and bare rock — jagged, rocky, snow-capped peaks","Midnight sun / polar night — summer coverage shows sun low on horizon at all hours. Winter coverage is dark or very low light.","Arctic foxes, reindeer, and polar bears inhabit the area (signs warning of polar bears visible)"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. Coverage limited to Longyearbyen and immediate surroundings. The landscape is so extreme and unique that car meta is irrelevant — you will immediately recognise Svalbard from the environment.","mu":[{"c":"Iceland","k":"also treeless, also dramatic Arctic/sub-Arctic island. Key splits: Iceland has some low scrub vegetation and moss-covered lava fields; Svalbard has true bare Arctic tundra + glaciers + snow even in summer. Iceland has no polar bear signs. Iceland road signs use Þ/ð characters; Svalbard uses standard Norwegian."},{"c":"Northern Norway (mainland)","k":"also Norwegian signs, also dramatic landscape. Key splits: Mainland Norway has some trees (birch/pine at lower latitudes); Svalbard has zero trees. Svalbard has glaciers directly visible; mainland Norway does not typically."},{"c":"Greenland","k":"also Arctic, also treeless. But Greenland has almost no official road coverage in GeoGuessr."}],"ex":["Zero trees + Norwegian signs = Svalbard, no other option","Polar bear warning signs are globally unique to Svalbard in GeoGuessr","Coverage is extremely limited — almost entirely Longyearbyen town streets and the road to the airport","Longyearbyen has a distinctive look: colourful wooden houses on stilts (built above permafrost), coal mining machinery, very small and remote","One of the most immediately recognisable locations in all of GeoGuessr once you know it"]},{"id":"slovakia","n":"Slovakia","f":"🇸🇰","co":"Europe","qt":["Ľ (L with caron/háček) — the letter ľ (lowercase) and Ľ (uppercase) is unique to Slovak. It sounds like a palatalised \"ly\". If you see this character = Slovakia only. Also uses ô (o with circumflex) — another Slovak-specific character.","Rectangular directional signs with small white arrows — Slovak directional signs are rectangular with small arrows on them. This contrasts directly with Czech arrow-shaped signs (where the whole sign IS an arrow).","Thinner black outline on town name signs vs Czech Republic (thicker outline). Slovakia and Czechia are very similar — this town sign border thickness is one of the most used splits.","Fluorescent orange bollard stripes — same as Czech Republic but Slovak bollards sometimes differ slightly in shade; use language as the primary split","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Slovak — West Slavic, very similar to Czech. Unique characters: ľ (l with caron), ô (o with circumflex), Ä (a with diaeresis in some uses), ŕ (r with acute). Also uses č, š, ž, á, é, í, ó, ú like Czech. The ľ is the fastest Slovak confirmation — it appears in very common words: ľudia (people), ľahký (easy), ulica (street). Slovak also uses ŕ which Czech doesn't. Absent: Czech-unique ř character — if you see ř = Czech, not Slovak.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Rectangular directional signs with small arrows (not arrow-shaped like Czech)","Thinner black outline on town name signs (Czech has thicker outline)","Borders on road signs directly at sign edge (Czech borders are set in slightly from edge)","Fluorescent orange bollard stripes on black section","Standard EU white plates with blue strip","National highways: D (diaľnica = motorway), R (rýchlostná = expressway)"],"landb":["Mountainous — Slovakia has some of the most dramatic mountains in Central Europe","High Tatras (north): spectacular sharp alpine peaks, shared with Poland. One of the most distinctive mountain landscapes in European GeoGuessr.","Low Tatras/Fatra/Beskydy: gentler forested mountains in central/west","Danube plain (south): flat agricultural, similar to Hungary","Dense mixed forest throughout most of the country","Traditional Slovak villages: wooden folk architecture in mountain areas"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Slovakia identified by ľ character, rectangular directional signs, and mountain landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Czech Republic","k":"most similar. Both West Slavic, very similar languages and landscapes. Key splits: Czech directional signs are arrow-shaped (Slovakia rectangular). Czech town signs have thicker black outline. Czech unique character is ř (Slovakia doesn't have ř). Slovak unique character is ľ (Czech doesn't have ľ). Clean splits once you know both characters."},{"c":"Poland","k":"also Slavic, also mountainous in south. Key splits: Polish has ł (barred l, different from Slovak ľ); different bollards; Polish holey poles visible."},{"c":"Hungary","k":"neighbouring, similar southern flat areas. Key splits: Hungarian has ő, ű (double accent); Slovak has ľ, ô."}],"ex":["ľ (l with háček) = Slovakia only — globally unique character. If you see it on any sign = commit to Slovakia.","Rectangular directional signs = Slovakia; arrow-shaped = Czech Republic. This is the fastest non-language infrastructure split.","The High Tatras (Vysoké Tatry) are dramatically distinctive — sharp granite peaks rising from forested valleys","Slovakia has good nationwide coverage including mountain areas","Bratislava (capital): sits right on the Austrian/Hungarian border — can look almost Austrian or Hungarian in some areas; rely on language to confirm"]},{"id":"san_marino","n":"San Marino","f":"🇸🇲","co":"Europe","qt":["Black Google car + Gen 2 coverage (halo visible) — San Marino has a black car and old Gen 2 coverage. The circular halo/rift visible in the sky when panning up is the primary camera tell. Gen 2 + looks like Italy = San Marino.","Italian language + Italian-looking landscape but different plates — San Marino looks exactly like rural/hilly central Italy. The key difference is the plates: San Marino plates are white with light blue font and an emblem on the left, without the EU blue strip. Completely different from Italian plates (which have double blue strips). Many Italian-registered cars are also visible in San Marino.","Hilltop fortress — San Marino's capital is built on top of Monte Titano, a distinctive rocky peak with three medieval towers (Guaita, Cesta, Montale) visible on the ridgeline. If you can see three towers on a dramatic rocky hilltop = San Marino city.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Italian throughout — San Marino is an Italian-speaking enclave entirely surrounded by Italy. Road signs identical to Italian conventions. Street suffix: via, strada, corso. Language alone cannot distinguish San Marino from Italy — rely on plates and camera generation.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Italian road sign conventions","San Marino plates: white with light blue lettering and national emblem on left. No EU blue strip.","Many Italian-registered cars also visible (most vehicles in San Marino are Italian)","Gen 2 camera coverage — halo visible in sky"],"landb":["Monte Titano: the distinctive rocky mountain on which the capital is built. Three medieval tower silhouettes on the ridgeline are iconic.","Surrounding countryside: rolling hills, vineyards, olive groves — classic central Italian landscape","Very small (~61 km²) — coverage is limited to the main roads around and up to the capital","The view from the towers down to the surrounding Italian countryside is distinctive"],"car":"Black car + Gen 2 coverage (sky halo visible). This is the primary San Marino camera meta. Italy has Gen 3/4 coverage; San Marino has old Gen 2. If you see Italian-looking landscape with Gen 2 quality + black car = San Marino.","mu":[{"c":"Italy","k":"looks identical in landscape and language. Key splits: Italy has Gen 3/4 coverage (crisp); San Marino has Gen 2 (halo in sky). Italian plates have double blue strips; San Marino plates have light blue font with emblem, no EU strip. Black car = San Marino."},{"c":"Vatican City","k":"also Italian enclave. But Vatican has no GeoGuessr coverage."}],"ex":["Gen 2 halo + black car + Italian-looking landscape = San Marino, commit","The three medieval towers on Monte Titano's ridge are among the most recognisable landmarks in GeoGuessr for anyone who knows them","San Marino is the world's oldest constitutional republic (founded 301 AD)","Coverage is very limited — the main road up to the capital and a few surrounding roads"]},{"id":"ukraine","n":"Ukraine","f":"🇺🇦","co":"Europe","qt":["Red Google car — Ukraine's Google Street View car is distinctively red. This is the primary and most reliable Ukraine car meta. A red Google car in an Eastern European Cyrillic context = Ukraine immediately.","Unique Ukrainian Cyrillic letters: І, Ї, Є, Ґ — these letters are found in Ukrainian but NOT in Russian: І (dotted i), Ї (i with diaeresis — looks like ï), Є (Cyrillic ye — looks like a backwards 3), Ґ (g with upturn). If you see Ї or Є on a Cyrillic sign = Ukrainian, not Russian.","Yellow and blue painted objects — in many areas fences, poles, kerbstones, and other street objects are painted in Ukrainian flag colours (blue and yellow). Very common and culturally deliberate.","Ukrainian plates: yellow+blue strip on left — the EU-style blue strip on Ukrainian plates has a yellow upper section and blue lower section (Ukrainian flag colours). Standard EU plates have all-blue strip.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Ukrainian — East Slavic Cyrillic. Unique characters: І (dotted i, looks like Latin i), Ї (i-diaeresis, ï-like shape), Є (backwards-3 shape), Ґ (g with upturn). Ukrainian street vocabulary: вулиця (vulytsia = street, abbreviated вул.), бульвар (boulevard), проспект (prospect/avenue). Ukrainian looks broadly similar to Russian but these four unique characters appear in common words: їжак (hedgehog), єдиний (only), Україна (Ukraine).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow+blue left strip on plates (Ukrainian flag colours)","Blue directional signs with white text (similar to Russian but Ukrainian context)","White-painted pole bases — many Ukrainian utility poles have white-painted lower sections","Wide Ukrainian bollards with a larger/wider red rectangle on front than Croatia/Serbia/Hungary (and often appear worn/run-down)","Yellow plates on public transport vehicles"],"landb":["Flat steppes (east/south): vast agricultural plains — some of the most fertile farmland in the world. Flat, open, endless fields. Very similar to Russian southern coverage.","Carpathian mountains (west): beautiful forested mountains, traditional Hutsul wooden architecture","Kiev/Kyiv area: large modern city, mix of Soviet-era and older architecture, famous golden-domed Orthodox churches","Black Sea coast (south): flat, resort areas","Generally: a country of contrasts — flat eastern steppes vs western mountains"],"car":"RED car — this is THE Ukraine meta. The Google car in Ukraine is red (not white/silver/blue like most of Europe). When you pan down and see a red car in an Eastern European context = Ukraine, commit immediately.","mu":[{"c":"Russia","k":"most similar Cyrillic country. Key splits: Ukraine has RED car (Russia has black car with long antenna). Ukrainian plates have yellow+blue strip (Russian plates have white strip, no EU format). Ukrainian unique letters Ї, Є (not in Russian)."},{"c":"Bulgaria","k":"also Cyrillic, also Eastern European. Key splits: Bulgaria has EU strip on plates (standard blue); Ukraine has yellow+blue strip. Bulgarian settlement signs bilingual Cyrillic+Latin; Ukrainian usually Cyrillic only."},{"c":"Belarus","k":"also Cyrillic, also flat Eastern European. But Belarus has essentially no GeoGuessr coverage."}],"ex":["Red Google car = Ukraine, always — no other European country has a red car","Ї and Є are the fastest Ukrainian language confirms — visually unmistakable characters","Blue+yellow painted objects (kerbstones, fences, poles) are very common and culturally significant","Ukraine has extensive coverage including rural steppes, western mountains, and major cities","Note: coverage may reflect pre-2022 invasion state in some areas — some western cities have newer coverage"]},{"id":"bermuda","n":"Bermuda","f":"🇧🇲","co":"North America","qt":["Distinctive white roofs on every house — Bermuda's most iconic visual. ALL houses have brilliant white stepped/tiered roofs. This is functional (rainwater collection for drinking water) but creates an immediately recognisable skyline. If you see a bright white stepped roof = Bermuda.","Pastel-coloured house walls — houses are painted in semi-faded bright pastels (pink, yellow, blue, peach) with those white roofs. The combination of white roof + pastel walls is completely unique.","Black truck Google car — a black truck is visible when panning down. Sometimes it's blurred into a jagged dark shape; sometimes clearly a black truck. Bermuda also has boat coverage.","Left-hand traffic — British Overseas Territory","English language + British conventions"],"ls":"English throughout — British Overseas Territory. UK road sign conventions, left-hand traffic. Bermuda is geographically isolated in the North Atlantic (not Caribbean), but feels like a very wealthy British tropical island.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","Single yellow centre line — Bermuda's roads characteristically have a single yellow centre line","British road sign conventions","Roads are notably narrow — Bermuda limits car sizes due to tiny road network","Road quality excellent — well-maintained British-standard infrastructure","Very small road network (island is only 21 sq km)"],"landb":["Isolated North Atlantic island — not Caribbean despite the tropical feel. Located ~1,070 km off North Carolina, USA.","Lush subtropical vegetation — cedar trees, palms, tropical flowers","Beautiful turquoise/blue water visible from roads — pristine beaches","Coral pink sand beaches in some areas","Dense, small-scale suburban feel — the entire island is essentially one large connected community","No rivers or lakes — hence the reliance on white roofs for rainwater collection","Some boat coverage in eastern harbours"],"car":"Black truck — when panning down you see either a clearly visible black truck OR a jagged, blurred black car-like shape. The same vehicle, just differently processed. Some coverage is from boats. This black truck is distinctive — combined with the white-roofed pastel houses, Bermuda is one of the most immediately recognisable places in GeoGuessr.","mu":[{"c":"Curaçao","k":"also colourful houses, also left-hand, also Caribbean-ish. Key splits: Curaçao has Dutch language + Dutch gabled architecture; Bermuda has English + stepped white roofs. Very different architecture styles."},{"c":"Cayman Islands / Bahamas","k":"also tropical British. But those have much less coverage and different infrastructure."},{"c":"Hawaii","k":"also tropical, also English. Key splits: Hawaii is volcanic, mountainous, and American (right-hand); Bermuda is flat, tiny, and British (left-hand)."}],"ex":["White stepped roofs are THE single fastest Bermuda confirm in GeoGuessr — nothing else looks like this globally","The white roof system exists because Bermuda has no natural freshwater — rainwater is collected from rooftops into underground tanks","Bermuda is one of the wealthiest places on Earth per capita — very well-maintained, extremely clean","The island is so small (~34 km² total) that coverage can feel like you're always near the coast","Black truck car meta is reliable when visible","Bermuda is in the North Atlantic, not the Caribbean — closer to North Carolina than to any Caribbean island"]},{"id":"costa_rica","n":"Costa Rica","f":"🇨🇷","co":"North America","qt":["Footpath/trekker only — you cannot leave the path — Costa Rica's coverage was captured by a person walking, not a car. You are locked to a footpath. You cannot turn onto roads. This is the single most important Costa Rica meta: if you're in Spanish-speaking Central America and you literally cannot move off the sidewalk, it's Costa Rica.","Coverage concentrated around San José and Heredia — almost all coverage is on university campuses, parks, and pedestrian areas around the capital city and nearby Heredia","Spanish language + tropical urban environment","Right-hand traffic (visible from the footpath)"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Standard Central American Spanish. Key words visible on buildings and signs: Universidad (university), parque (park), calle. Costa Rican colloquial term \"Tico\" sometimes visible on local branding. The urban environment around San José is chaotic, colourful, dense — typical Central American city feel.","rb":["Right-hand traffic (seen from footpath perspective)","You cannot access roads — footpath only. This is the meta.","Standard Spanish signage where visible","Costa Rica does NOT have a distinctive Google car — there is no car at all"],"landb":["Urban San José / Heredia — the vast majority of coverage is on university campuses and city parks. You will typically see:","University buildings (Universidad de Costa Rica is common)","City parks with tropical trees and benches","Urban streets viewed from the footpath","Lush tropical vegetation where present","Dense urban environment with colourful commercial signage","Some surrounding countryside visible from footpaths"],"car":"No car — trekker/footpath only. The coverage was captured by a person walking. When you pan around you see a standard pedestrian perspective. You CANNOT click to move onto roads — you are limited to the footpath network. This coverage restriction is globally unique to Costa Rica among Spanish-speaking countries (Pakistan is trekker-only but completely different context).","mu":[{"c":"Panama","k":"also Central American, also Spanish, also tropical. Key splits: Panama has full road car coverage with unique antenna; Costa Rica has footpath only."},{"c":"Guatemala","k":"also Central American Spanish. Key splits: Guatemala has full car coverage with visible bars + black mirrors; Costa Rica has no car at all."},{"c":"Colombia","k":"also tropical Spanish. Key splits: Colombia has full road coverage; Costa Rica is footpath only."}],"ex":["The inability to move off the footpath is the meta — if you're stuck on a pavement in tropical Spanish Central America, stop immediately and guess Costa Rica","Coverage is limited to a handful of university campuses and parks in and around San José and Heredia","The Universidad de Costa Rica campus is the most common spawn point — recognisable once you've seen it","Costa Rica has excellent biodiversity but you won't see much of it in coverage — it's mostly urban university environments","If you see tropical university architecture with Spanish + pedestrian-locked movement = Costa Rica, commit"]},{"id":"dominican_republic","n":"Dominican Republic","f":"🇩🇴","co":"North America","qt":["Black strip running down the middle of the grey roof rack bars — the DR's Google car has a very specific feature: the roof rack bars have a black strip running lengthwise down the centre of the grey metal. This is shared ONLY with Mongolia — two countries that are otherwise very unlikely to be confused.","Green street signs with white border and white lettering — DR street name signs have a distinctive bright green background with a white outer border and white text. Unique style in the Caribbean/Latin America.","\"PARE\" on stop signs — DR uses \"PARE\" (not \"STOP\" or \"ALTO\"). Shared with some other Caribbean countries but useful confirmation.","Extremely limited coverage — only two cities: Santo Domingo (capital) and Santiago de los Caballeros","Spanish language + Caribbean tropical urban"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Dominican Spanish is notable for its rapid pace and distinct accent (reflected in signage style). Standard Latin American road conventions. Key words: calle, avenida, PARE on stop signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","PARE stop signs — not STOP, not ALTO","Green street name signs with white border and white lettering — very distinctive, found consistently throughout coverage","Rear plates white with slight yellowish tinge; cars rarely have front plates","Road quality variable — Santo Domingo main roads decent, some rough urban areas","Santiago de los Caballeros utility poles: painted medium grey at the bottom. Santo Domingo poles: no paint. This splits the two covered cities."],"landb":["Urban only — coverage is entirely within Santo Domingo and Santiago de los Caballeros. No rural, no beaches, no countryside.","Santo Domingo: large, chaotic, dense Caribbean city. Mix of colonial old town (Zona Colonial — UNESCO heritage, oldest European city in the Americas) and modern sprawl.","Santiago de los Caballeros: second largest city, somewhat more compact","Tropical Caribbean urban — palm trees, colourful buildings, busy streets"],"car":"White blur visible at rear + bars visible — standard bars configuration but with the distinctive black strip running down the centre of each grey bar. This is the fastest DR car confirm. No visible side mirrors (distinguishes from Guatemala which also has bars but WITH black mirrors).","mu":[{"c":"Guatemala","k":"also has bars on the car. Key splits: Guatemala has black side mirrors visible; DR does NOT have visible side mirrors. Guatemala is Central American mountainous; DR is Caribbean urban."},{"c":"Curaçao","k":"also Caribbean Spanish-adjacent. Key splits: Curaçao has Dutch language; DR has Spanish. Curaçao has black car bonnet (no strip on bars); DR has white car with black-strip bars."},{"c":"Puerto Rico","k":"also Caribbean Spanish, also US-influenced. Key splits: PR has no front plates + front antenna + \"Clasificados Online\" signs; DR has PARE signs + green street signs + bar meta."},{"c":"Mongolia","k":"also has black strip on bars. These two countries are otherwise nothing alike — context resolves this immediately."}],"ex":["The black strip on the roof rack bars is globally shared only with Mongolia — memorise this","Green street name signs with white border are extremely consistent and a fast confirm on any street corner","Coverage is so limited (2 cities) that memorising what each looks like is a viable strategy","Zona Colonial in Santo Domingo is recognisable — Spanish colonial stone buildings, cobblestone streets","\"PARE\" on stop signs is a small but useful supporting confirm"]},{"id":"greenland","n":"Greenland","f":"🇬🇱","co":"North America","qt":["Brightly coloured houses on barren Arctic/subarctic landscape — Greenland's towns consist of vividly coloured wooden houses (red, yellow, blue, green, orange) set against bare rocky hillsides, snow, ice, and grey sea. The contrast is immediately distinctive.","Greenlandic language (Kalaallisut) — Latin script with many Qs and -aq suffixes. Place names are long, vowel-heavy, and end in -aq (like Nuuk, Sisimiut, Ilulissat, Qaqortoq). Many Qs visible on any sign.","Coastal only — all coverage is in small towns on the west coast. No inland coverage (most of Greenland is ice sheet). You will always be near the sea.","Right-hand traffic (Danish convention)","White plates with thin red border — the plate design is distinctive"],"ls":"Kalaallisut (Greenlandic) — Latin script but looks very different from any European language. Extremely long words, many Qs (Q appears far more than in any European language), suffix -aq on many words, vowel-heavy. Danish also appears on some signs. The Q-heavy text is the fastest Greenlandic script confirm. Place names: Nuuk, Sisimiut, Aasiaat, Qaqortoq, Ilulissat — once you recognise the pattern, the script is unmistakable.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","White plates with thin red outer border — unique plate design","Very limited road infrastructure — Greenland has NO roads between towns (you can only travel between settlements by boat, helicopter, or dogsled)","Coverage is confined to within individual towns — roads dead-end quickly","Danish road sign conventions where applicable","Very few signs overall — signage is sparse"],"landb":["Arctic/subarctic barren landscape — rocky hillsides with almost no vegetation (maybe some low Arctic tundra plants in summer). Brown/grey rock, snow and ice in winter/spring.","Bright coloured wooden houses against this barren backdrop — the defining visual. Houses painted in red, yellow, blue, green, orange to combat the grey monotony.","Cold grey sea visible from almost all coverage — fjords, icebergs sometimes visible","Icebergs visible offshore in some locations (especially Ilulissat area — one of the world's largest iceberg nurseries)","Most of the world's second-largest island is permanently covered by the Greenland Ice Sheet","Summer: brief green tundra, midnight sun. Winter: snow everywhere, dark."],"car":"Various vehicles used across different towns — car meta varies by location. The coverage type itself (small isolated Arctic town, no roads connecting to anywhere) is more useful than any specific car meta. Most towns have their own distinct coverage vehicle.","mu":[{"c":"Iceland","k":"also North Atlantic, also volcanic/rocky, also sparse. Key splits: Iceland has Icelandic (ð, þ characters); Greenland has Kalaallisut (many Qs). Iceland has roads connecting everywhere; Greenland coverage dead-ends at town boundaries. Iceland has more lush green vegetation."},{"c":"Norway/Faroe Islands","k":"also cold, also coloured houses. Key splits: Norwegian/Faroese use their own languages (no Qs); Greenlandic has many Qs."},{"c":"Alaska/Canada","k":"also Arctic, also remote. Key splits: Those have English American/Canadian signs; Greenland has Kalaallisut + Danish."}],"ex":["The Q-heavy text is the fastest Greenland language confirm — if you see -aq, -aaq, -ooq endings and lots of Qs on signs, commit to Greenland","The brightly coloured house + bare grey Arctic rock combination is one of the most striking visual contrasts in GeoGuessr","Nuuk (capital) is the largest city — looks slightly more developed but still small by global standards","Ilulissat area: famous for massive icebergs — if you see huge white icebergs floating in a fjord with coloured houses on rocky hills = almost certainly Ilulissat, Greenland","Greenland is technically an autonomous territory of Denmark — hence Danish influence on some signs","The isolation of each town (no connecting roads) means pinpointing requires recognising specific town layouts or using sea direction"]},{"id":"guatemala","n":"Guatemala","f":"🇬🇹","co":"North America","qt":["Bars on the car roof + large visible black side mirrors — Guatemala's Google car has roof bars AND distinctly large, visible black side mirrors. The black mirrors with rounded edges are the key distinguisher from the Dominican Republic (which also has bars but NO visible side mirrors).","White plates with blue text — Guatemalan license plates have white backgrounds with blue lettering. Distinctive in Central America.","Blue kilometre distance markers on roads — Guatemala uses blue roadside distance markers, similar to Russia and some other countries","Spanish language + mountainous Central American landscape","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Guatemalan Spanish uses \"ALTO\" on stop signs (same as Mexico). Various indigenous Mayan languages (K'iche', Mam, Q'eqchi') appear on some signs in rural areas — these use Latin script but with unusual letter combinations. Spanish + Central American context + blue plates = Guatemala.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","ALTO on stop signs — shared with Mexico","White plates with blue text — unique combination in Central America","Blue distance markers on national highways","Road quality very variable — highways reasonable, mountain roads often rough","Green and white directional signs on main routes"],"landb":["Dramatically mountainous — Guatemala has some of the most spectacular mountain scenery in Central America. Towering active volcanoes (Volcán de Fuego, Acatenango, Santiaguito) are visible from many roads.","Active volcanoes with smoke/ash plumes visible in coverage — one of the most dramatic landscape tells","Lush tropical/subtropical highland — cool and green in highlands, hot and tropical in lowlands","Lake Atitlán area: breathtaking highland lake surrounded by three volcanoes — recognisable if you know it","Dense forest, colonial architecture in Antigua Guatemala (well-preserved Spanish colonial city — distinctive colourful buildings)","Pine forests at altitude — unusual for Central America, distinctive","Lowland areas (Petén): flat tropical jungle, similar to southern Mexico"],"car":"Bars on roof + large black rounded side mirrors — both visible simultaneously. The side mirrors have slightly rounder edges than the similar Kyrgyzstan car (which also has bars + mirrors but with different mirror shape). In a Spanish-speaking, mountainous tropical context with blue plates = Guatemala.","mu":[{"c":"Dominican Republic","k":"also has bars on the car. Key splits: DR has no visible side mirrors; Guatemala has large black side mirrors. DR is Caribbean flat urban; Guatemala is mountainous Central American."},{"c":"Mexico","k":"also \"ALTO\" signs, also Spanish, also Central American feel in southern states. Key splits: Mexico has octagonal poles, pink taxis in Mexico City, different car meta (no bars + mirrors)."},{"c":"Panama","k":"also Central American, also Spanish. Key splits: Panama has unique antenna (no bars + mirrors); Guatemala has bars + black mirrors."},{"c":"Costa Rica","k":"also Central American Spanish. Key splits: Costa Rica is footpath-only; Guatemala has full car coverage."}],"ex":["The large black side mirrors are the fastest Guatemala car confirm — commit when you see them in Spanish-speaking Central America","White plates with blue text are reliable and consistent across the country","Active volcano smoke/ash in the background is a spectacular and unique Guatemala landscape tell","Antigua Guatemala is one of the most recognisable colonial cities in GeoGuessr — colourful baroque buildings, cobblestone streets, volcano backdrop","The combination of volcanoes + pine forests + Spanish = central Guatemala highlands"]},{"id":"martinique","n":"Martinique","f":"🇲🇶","co":"North America","qt":["French language in a tropical Caribbean setting — the combination of French road signs (Rue, Route, Cédez le passage, signs in French) with lush tropical Caribbean landscape is the defining Martinique fingerprint. France in the Caribbean.","French infrastructure — French bollards (white cylindrical with red reflectors), French road sign conventions, French speed limit signs (km/h, triangular warning signs, French-style direction signs)","Volcanic tropical island — Martinique has a dramatic volcanic mountain (Mount Pelée, an active stratovolcano) at its north and lush tropical forest throughout","EU road conventions — Martinique is an integral part of France and the EU (not just an overseas territory)","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"French — fully French, an overseas department (département) of France. Road signs follow metropolitan French conventions exactly. \"Rue\", \"Route\", \"Cédez\", French place names (Fort-de-France, Le Lamentin, Sainte-Anne). French language + tropical Caribbean = Martinique or Guadeloupe. The same French infrastructure appears on both islands.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French road sign conventions — identical to metropolitan France","French bollards: thick white cylindrical posts with red reflectors","French speed limit signs, triangular warning signs, French-style direction signs","Road quality good — French standard maintained (EU funding)","European licence plates (French format: AA-123-BB or older regional)","Green directional signs (French motorway style), blue for national routes"],"landb":["Volcanic tropical island — lush, intensely green, mountainous","Mount Pelée (northern Martinique): large active stratovolcano, heavily forested slopes. Famous for the 1902 eruption that destroyed the former capital Saint-Pierre.","Southern Martinique: drier, more developed, beaches, resort areas","Fort-de-France (capital): largest French Caribbean city, dense urban, harbour","Sugarcane plantations historically — still some visible","Tropical rainforest on volcanic slopes — extremely lush and green","Caribbean Sea coastline visible from many roads"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4 — French coverage. No distinctive car meta. Martinique is identified by French language + Caribbean tropical landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Guadeloupe","k":"most similar. Also French Caribbean, also volcanic, also French infrastructure. Key splits: Guadeloupe is a different-shaped island (butterfly-shape, two main islands); Martinique is a single island. Landscape is slightly different — Basse-Terre (Guadeloupe) has La Soufrière volcano; Martinique has Mount Pelée. Hard to distinguish without signs."},{"c":"Réunion","k":"also French overseas department, also tropical volcanic. Key splits: Réunion is in the Indian Ocean (completely different geographic context). Réunion's car has bars and visible side mirrors with black tape on rear bar."},{"c":"France (metropolitan)","k":"same language, same signs. Key splits: France is temperate European; Martinique is tropical Caribbean. No pine forests or vineyards in Martinique."},{"c":"Saint Pierre and Miquelon","k":"also French territory. Key splits: Saint Pierre is cold Atlantic; Martinique is tropical Caribbean."}],"ex":["French language + tropical lush green volcanic island = Martinique or Guadeloupe (very hard to distinguish without specific signs)","Mount Pelée visible from much of northern Martinique — dramatic forested volcanic cone","Fort-de-France has good urban coverage — colourful French Caribbean city architecture","Martinique and Guadeloupe are not merely territories — they are full departments of France and therefore part of the EU, using euros and French law in every respect","If you see French signs in a lush volcanic Caribbean setting, commit to Martinique or Guadeloupe. If the island looks more butterfly-shaped with a very large volcano (La Soufrière), lean Guadeloupe. Single compact mountainous island = Martinique.","The combination of French infrastructure quality + tropical vegetation is striking — roads are better maintained than most Caribbean islands"]},{"id":"panama","n":"Panama","f":"🇵🇦","co":"North America","qt":["Unique antenna on the Google car — Panama has a distinctive thick antenna on its car that is found in no other country on Earth. It should be visible when panning down, though not always as clearly as in reference images.","Coloured strip at the top of license plates — Panamanian plates have a coloured strip (green, blue, etc.) running across the top. Some plates are entirely blue or red. Very distinctive.","Private cars only required to have rear plates — no front plates on many cars, similar to Puerto Rico","Yellow taxis with city/route painted on the side — very consistent taxi style throughout Panama City and the country","Utility pole plates: horizontal = west of Panama City, vertical = east — a deep meta for pinpointing location within Panama"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Panama uses standard Latin American Spanish. Key infrastructure words: calle, avenida, vía. The Panama City metro area has bilingual English/Spanish signage in some tourist/financial areas (Panama City is a major banking hub).","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Coloured-top license plates — green, blue, or red strip at top of plate, or entirely coloured plates","No front plates on private vehicles","American-influenced road conventions (Panama had deep US presence until 1999 canal handover)","Utility pole plates — horizontal orientation = west of Panama City; vertical = east. An extremely useful pinpointing meta.","Road quality good on main highways and in Panama City; rural roads variable","Thatched-roof huts visible in rural areas — Emberá and Guna indigenous architecture"],"landb":["Tropical Central America — lush, extremely humid, dense jungle","Panama City: modern, wealthy for the region, dramatic skyline visible from some coverage. Mix of glass skyscrapers and old colonial Casco Viejo district.","Interior: dense tropical rainforest, mountains (Chiriquí highlands with coffee plantations)","Caribbean coast: extremely rainy, dense jungle, Bocas del Toro islands","Pacific coast: drier, beaches","Panama Canal: some road coverage near the Canal, though actual canal views are limited. Ships visible in locks from some spots.","Indigenous thatched-roof settlements visible in some rural coverage"],"car":"Unique thick antenna — the Panama car has a distinctive thick, prominent antenna that is unlike the antenna style of any other country. When you pan down and see this specific antenna shape in a tropical Spanish-speaking context = Panama immediately. The blur can be large even when the antenna pole isn't clearly visible.","mu":[{"c":"Costa Rica","k":"most similar. Both tropical Central America, both Spanish, similar landscape. Key splits: Costa Rica has footpath-only trekker coverage (no car); Panama has car coverage with unique antenna. Costa Rica has no road driving available."},{"c":"Colombia","k":"also tropical Spanish, also similar landscape in northwestern regions. Key splits: Colombia has yellow plates; Panama has coloured-top plates. Different car meta."},{"c":"Guatemala","k":"also Central American Spanish. Key splits: Guatemala car has bars visible + black mirrors; Panama has unique antenna."}],"ex":["The unique antenna is THE fastest Panama car confirm — learn what it looks like","Coloured-top plates (especially the distinctive blue or green stripe) are very reliable","Yellow taxis with route information painted on the side are very consistent throughout Panama City","Panama City's skyline (visible from certain angles) is distinctive — modern skyscrapers on the Pacific coast","The Canal is historically visible at Miraflores Locks area — seeing a massive ship passing through a lock in a tropical setting = Panama","Utility pole plate orientation (horizontal/vertical) is one of GeoGuessr's more creative pinpointing metas","Panama is the southernmost country in Central America — it connects to Colombia/South America"]},{"id":"saint_pierre_and_miquelon","n":"Saint Pierre and Miquelon","f":"🇵🇲","co":"North America","qt":["French language + Canadian-feeling landscape — the combination of French signage (Rue, Route, French place names) with a cold, grey, sub-Atlantic island landscape that looks like Newfoundland is completely unique","No official car coverage — coverage is photospheres and limited trekker. You cannot move like a normal round.","French infrastructure in a North American setting — French-style utility poles, French road signs, French bollards (white cylindrical with red reflectors), tricolour flags — but surrounded by cold Atlantic bog and rocky terrain that feels like Atlantic Canada","Colourful houses on the islands — similar to Newfoundland outport architecture","Right-hand traffic (French convention)"],"ls":"French — fully French-speaking, part of France. Rue (street), Route, Chemin, French place names, French phone numbers. French language in a cold North Atlantic island context = Saint Pierre and Miquelon. The contrast between French civilisation and Atlantic Canadian wilderness is the defining character.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","French road sign conventions — same as metropolitan France","French bollards — thick white cylindrical posts with red reflectors","French utility poles — may carry blue plates (French territory indicator)","Reddish road surfaces in some areas","Very limited road coverage — small islands with minimal infrastructure"],"landb":["Cold, grey, sub-Atlantic — the dominant feel. Low boggy terrain, rocky coastlines, cold grey sea. Think Newfoundland/Atlantic Canada not tropical island.","Sub-arctic maritime climate — cold, windy, foggy much of the year","Saint-Pierre town (main settlement): small harbour town, colourful wooden houses, French infrastructure — feels like a Breton fishing village dropped in Atlantic Canada","Peat bogs, low hills, rocky outcrops","Miquelon island: even more desolate, connected to Langlade by a narrow sand bar","French tricolour flags visible on government buildings"],"car":"Photosphere and limited trekker only — no driving. You can pivot but typically cannot travel. This alone is a strong tell alongside the French + cold Atlantic island landscape.","mu":[{"c":"France (metropolitan)","k":"same language, same signs, same infrastructure. Key splits: France has car coverage and European landscapes; Saint Pierre is cold, bleak Atlantic Canada. No green fields or vineyards."},{"c":"Réunion","k":"also French territory. Key splits: Réunion is tropical (Indian Ocean); Saint Pierre is cold Atlantic. Very different landscapes."},{"c":"Canada (Newfoundland)","k":"same cold Atlantic landscape. Key splits: Canada has English (STOP signs, km signs in English); Saint Pierre has French (signs say Cédez in French). Different bollards and poles."},{"c":"Guadeloupe/Martinique","k":"also French Caribbean. Key splits: Those are tropical; Saint Pierre is cold."}],"ex":["The only remaining French territory in North America — a genuinely unique GeoGuessr location","Combination of French language + cold grey Atlantic landscape is globally unique","If you see French signs but the landscape looks like maritime Canada = Saint Pierre and Miquelon immediately","Very limited coverage — the handful of spots are all on Saint-Pierre island or the small roads of Miquelon","Population of only ~5,500 — one of the smallest GeoGuessr locations by population","French phone numbers on signs follow the French format: 05XX XX XX XX"]},{"id":"puerto_rico","n":"Puerto Rico","f":"🇵🇷","co":"North America","qt":["No front license plates on cars — Puerto Rico is one of very few places globally where cars commonly have NO front plate at all. Rear plates only. Immediately confirms PR.","Antenna on the FRONT of the Google car — the antenna is on the front of the car (not the back or hidden). Unusual and distinctive.","Rear plates: white with black lettering + light green strip along the bottom — very specific plate design","\"Clasificados Online\" red-and-white signs everywhere — a local classifieds website that advertises heavily on Puerto Rico roads. Red-and-white signs are plastered on poles, fences, and buildings across the island. Completely unique to PR.","Spanish language + US conventions (STOP signs, SPEED LIMIT)","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish + English — Puerto Rico is bilingual. Spanish dominates everyday signs and shop fronts. US road conventions (STOP, SPEED LIMIT, American highway shields) but Spanish city names and business names. This mix of Spanish language + American infrastructure is PR's fingerprint.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","No front plates — the most reliable confirm when you see a car","US-style road signs (STOP, SPEED LIMIT, green highway shields) in English","Spanish street names and local business names","Road quality reasonable — varies from excellent highways to rough municipal roads","Highway PR-XX numbering system","American-style road markings (yellow centre lines, white outer lines)"],"landb":["Tropical Caribbean island — lush, humid, tropical vegetation","Very hilly to mountainous in the interior (El Yunque rainforest)","Coastal areas: flat, urban, beaches","San Juan: large, dense, very urban — old San Juan (historic fortifications) and modern metro area","Tropical vegetation year-round — palms, tropical trees","Hurricane damage visible in some older coverage"],"car":"Antenna on the front of the car (not the back). This is the car meta tell — the antenna position is flipped compared to most other countries. Combined with no-front-plate cars = immediate Puerto Rico confirm.","mu":[{"c":"US Virgin Islands","k":"also Caribbean, also US territory, also English. Key splits: USVI drives left; PR drives right. USVI has English only; PR is bilingual Spanish/English. USVI has big pickup truck; PR has standard car with front antenna."},{"c":"Dominican Republic","k":"also Spanish, also Caribbean, similar landscape. Key splits: DR has green street signs with white border; PR has standard US-style signs. DR has Spanish only; PR has US conventions + Spanish."},{"c":"Cuba","k":"also Spanish, also Caribbean. But Cuba has almost no GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Mainland US","k":"also English, also US signs. Key splits: PR is tropical, has Spanish, has no front plates, has \"Clasificados Online\" signs."}],"ex":["\"Clasificados Online\" red-and-white signs are the fastest PR cultural confirm — once you know what they look like, you'll spot them instantly on any Puerto Rican road","No front plate on cars is extremely reliable — if you see a car with nothing on the front bumper in a tropical Spanish/English context = PR","PR has excellent coverage island-wide","Old San Juan is one of the most distinctive urban environments in GeoGuessr — cobblestone streets, colourful Spanish colonial buildings, blue painted road stones, massive Spanish fortifications","The island is medium-sized and quite mountainous in the interior"]},{"id":"u_s_minor_outlying_islands","n":"U.S. Minor Outlying Islands","f":"🇺🇲","co":"North America","qt":["Photosphere/trekker only — no Google car coverage. All coverage is photospheres or trekker walking. You cannot drive anywhere.","Flat coral atoll or low island — completely flat, low-lying terrain. Coral sand, scrubby low vegetation or bare rock, surrounding ocean in all directions.","Midway Atoll (most common): white sand, low buildings, albatross birds everywhere, some WWII-era structures. Very remote Pacific feel.","No road infrastructure — no road signs, no lanes, no vehicles. Paths and tracks only.","US flag sometimes visible — flags on buildings confirm US territory"],"ls":"English on any visible signage — US territory. But most coverage has no signs at all — just flat island terrain and wildlife.","landb":["Midway Atoll: flat sandy atoll in the middle of the Pacific. White sand, low palm/casuarina trees, old military/research buildings, and enormous albatross colonies — thousands of Laysan albatrosses visible, nesting everywhere. This is one of the world's largest albatross colonies. The bird density is unlike anywhere else in GeoGuessr.","Wake Island: slightly more barren, old military airstrip, minimal vegetation","General: crystal clear blue/turquoise lagoons, coral reef visible, flat as far as the eye can see, Pacific ocean horizon in all directions","Feels completely isolated and remote — no civilization for thousands of miles in any direction"],"car":"Trekker/photosphere only. You can pivot but not move like a normal round. This immediately tells you it's limited coverage. Combined with a flat tropical Pacific atoll landscape = US Minor Outlying Islands (most likely Midway).","mu":[{"c":"Midway vs. other Pacific atolls","k":"the albatross birds at Midway are so distinctive that if you see large white birds nesting everywhere on a flat sandy island, it's Midway"},{"c":"Other remote Pacific islands","k":"similar flat atoll geography but different territories (Kiribati, Marshall Islands, etc.)"},{"c":"Christmas Island","k":"also remote Pacific, also wildlife-heavy. Key splits: Christmas Island has car coverage and red crabs; Midway has trekker and albatrosses."}],"ex":["In practice, if you land here in GeoGuessr you're almost certainly at Midway Atoll","The albatross colony at Midway is one of the most immediately recognisable wildlife scenes in all of GeoGuessr — huge white birds sitting everywhere on flat white sand","WWII history is visible: old bunkers, aircraft hangars, memorials visible at both Midway and Wake","No permanent civilian population on any of these islands — completely surreal emptiness","If you see a flat sandy Pacific atoll with photosphere-only movement and birds everywhere = Midway, commit to US Minor Outlying Islands"]},{"id":"alaska","n":"Alaska","f":"","co":"North America","qt":["US road signs with dramatic subarctic/arctic landscape — the combination of American infrastructure (SPEED LIMIT signs, American stop signs, US highway shields) with an otherworldly tundra/boreal landscape is the defining Alaska tell","Vast wilderness, almost no buildings — Alaska has some of the emptiest road coverage in GeoGuessr. Main roads (Parks Highway, Richardson Highway) pass through enormous wilderness with nothing for miles.","Snow-capped mountains visible constantly — Alaska Range, Chugach, Kenai Mountains dominate the landscape","Boreal/taiga forest — dense black spruce forests with mountains behind. Very similar to northern Canada but with US signs.","Right-hand traffic, American conventions"],"ls":"English throughout — fully American state. US road signs, American conventions. Some Native Alaskan place names visible (Denali, Susitna, Matanuska, Chugach, Kenai — indigenous names with distinctive sounds). No foreign languages on road signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Full US road sign conventions — SPEED LIMIT, American-style highway shields","Alaska state route shields are distinctively shaped (Alaska state outline or standard shields)","Parks Highway (AK-3) and Richardson Highway (AK-4) are main coverage routes","Very few roads relative to the enormous land area — coverage is mainly along a handful of highways","Road quality reasonable on main highways; many roads become gravel in remote areas"],"landb":["Enormous, dramatic wilderness:","Southcentral (Anchorage area): lush, green, dramatic mountain backdrop (Chugach Mountains), relatively developed","Interior (Fairbanks/Denali area): boreal forest, tundra, extremely cold winters, open spruce forest","Kenai Peninsula: fjords, glaciers, fishing villages, spectacular scenery","Southeast (Panhandle): rainforest, extremely rainy, dramatic fjords","Denali (Mt. McKinley) — tallest peak in North America, visible from some road coverage","Tundra in northern/interior areas — open, treeless, mossy ground","Glacier coverage — some trekker coverage at glaciers","Very few people visible — the emptiness is striking"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4 — US coverage. No distinctive car meta. Alaska is identified purely by landscape + US road signs.","mu":[{"c":"Canada","k":"most similar. Both boreal forest, both vast wilderness, both North American feel. Key splits: Canadian signs say MAXIMUM for speed limits; US says SPEED LIMIT. American-style stop signs (hexagonal \"STOP\") vs Canadian. Highway shield shapes differ."},{"c":"Finland/Russia/Scandinavia","k":"also boreal forest, also dramatic wilderness. Key splits: Alaska has English American-style signs; those countries have different scripts/languages."},{"c":"Northern US states (Montana, Idaho)","k":"also mountains, also boreal-ish forests. Key splits: Those states have much more development, more towns, more traffic. Alaska has extreme emptiness and more dramatic/larger-scale mountains."},{"c":"New Zealand","k":"also dramatic scenery, also English, also right-hand traffic. Key splits: NZ has different road sign style (km not miles, different sign designs)."}],"ex":["The emptiness of Alaskan roads is itself a tell — if you're in what looks like North America but there are virtually no buildings, few cars, and enormous wilderness in all directions, lean Alaska","American road signs + subarctic landscape = Alaska or possibly northern Canada","SPEED LIMIT (not MAXIMUM) confirms USA over Canada","Anchorage is the largest city — relatively normal-looking American city but with mountain backdrop","The Palmer/Matanuska Valley area has distinctive large agricultural fields surrounded by mountains","Fairbanks is the interior city — boreal forest feel, colder, more remote","Many Alaskan roads have no cell service, no gas stations for 100+ miles — this remoteness is reflected in coverage quality"]},{"id":"hawaii","n":"Hawaii","f":"","co":"North America","qt":["Tropical volcanic island — lush, intensely green vegetation, volcanic black rock, palm trees, ocean visible. Completely unlike any other US state.","US road signs and conventions — SPEED LIMIT signs, American stop signs, American-style road markings. All in English.","Dark reddish/volcanic soil — Hawaii's soil is distinctive dark reddish-brown volcanic earth","Japanese and local Hawaiian language on some signs — Japanese (日本語) appears on many tourist signs alongside English due to the large Japanese-American and Japanese tourist population. Hawaiian words on street names (vowel-heavy like Kapi'olani, Likelike, Kamehameha).","Right-hand traffic, left-hand driving as everywhere in USA"],"ls":"English throughout as an American state. Hawaiian language appears on street names — Hawaiian words are phonetically spelled Latin alphabet, very vowel-heavy: Kamehameha, Kalakaua, Likelike, Ala Moana, Waikiki. Japanese appears on many tourist signs in Honolulu/Waikiki. Hawaiian addresses are a strong US + tropical island confirm.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Full US road sign conventions — SPEED LIMIT, American stop signs, American-style yellow/green highway signs","Hawaii uses its own state shield on highway signs","Road quality good — standard American infrastructure","Limited highway system given the island geography","Coverage mainly on O'ahu (Honolulu/Waikiki area) and other main islands"],"landb":["Tropical volcanic — the defining characteristic. Completely unlike continental US.","Lush green tropical vegetation — dramatic ferns, tropical flowers, palm trees, hibiscus","Volcanic black rock lava flows visible, especially on Big Island","Ocean everywhere — being islands, the ocean is never far from coverage","Dramatic mountainous terrain — steep green valleys, volcanic peaks","Big Island (Hawaiʻi): active lava flows visible in some coverage, barren black lava fields","O'ahu (Honolulu): dense urban, Waikiki beach, Diamond Head volcanic crater","Maui: green agricultural, resort areas, dramatic road to Hana"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4 — US coverage. No distinctive car meta. Hawaii is identified purely by landscape, tropical vegetation, volcanic terrain, and US road signs.","mu":[{"c":"Other tropical islands (Philippines, Indonesia, etc.)","k":"all have tropical vegetation but have completely different scripts and non-American road signs. Hawaii has full US road infrastructure."},{"c":"Réunion","k":"also volcanic tropical island. Key splits: Réunion has French signs; Hawaii has English/American signs."},{"c":"Puerto Rico","k":"also tropical US territory. Key splits: Puerto Rico uses Spanish on many signs; Hawaii uses English + Hawaiian. Puerto Rico's landscape is Caribbean; Hawaii is more lush volcanic Pacific."},{"c":"Florida","k":"also tropical in south, also palm trees. Key splits: Florida is flat; Hawaii is mountainous and volcanic. Florida has no volcanic rock."}],"ex":["Hawaiian street names (Kamehameha, Kalakaua, Likelike) are completely unique and immediately confirm the state","The dark volcanic soil is very distinctive — unlike the sandy Florida soil or red southern US clay","Big Island lava fields (barren black rock with sparse vegetation) are globally unique","Waikiki/Honolulu coverage: dense beach resort area, Japanese tourists, Diamond Head visible","O'ahu highway signs often show distances to places like Pearl Harbor, Waikiki","Being a US state, Hawaii uses miles, American speed limits, and American road markings despite being in the Pacific"]},{"id":"usa_mainland","n":"USA (Mainland)","f":"🇺🇸","co":"North America","qt":["\"SPEED LIMIT\" on white rectangular signs — Canada says \"MAXIMUM\"; USA says \"SPEED LIMIT\"","\"YIELD\" on inverted triangle signs — Canada says \"YIELD\" too but US version has the word; non-English countries don't","\"STOP\" on red octagons — universal in USA","Right-hand traffic + English","Interstate shields: blue with red crown top, route number inside. Even numbers = E-W routes, odd = N-S. Numbers get larger toward the northeast/north.","US Route shields: white shield shape with black number","State highway shields: every state has a unique shape — learning these is the key to US state identification","Yellow centre lines + white edge lines — standard throughout","Miles on speed signs, not km/h","Green street signs more common than blue (Canada uses more blue)","Metal sign poles more common than wood (Canada uses more wood)"],"car":"Standard Gen 1/3/4 — US is one of the original Gen 1 countries (very low quality blurry coverage in some areas, especially early suburban/rural). Gen 3/4 everywhere newer. No distinctive car meta. USA is identified by signs, plates, and landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Canada","k":"most similar. Key splits: SPEED LIMIT vs MAXIMUM, metal vs wood poles, green vs blue street signs, blue vs red mailbox."},{"c":"Australia","k":"both English, both developed, broadly similar infrastructure. Key splits: Australia is left-hand; USA is right-hand. Australia has eucalyptus; USA doesn't (outside CA)."},{"c":"UK/Ireland","k":"both English. Key splits: UK/Ireland drive left; USA drives right."}],"ex":["The USA is the hardest country to pinpoint in GeoGuessr — 50 states across a continent-sized country with enormous diversity","Highway shield shapes are THE most reliable state identification tool — dedicate serious study time to these","Landscape + vegetation is the fastest regional narrowing tool — learn the 5 regional biomes","Commercial signage (gas stations, fast food chains, regional brands) is often faster than infrastructure for state identification","The grid road system in the Midwest/Great Plains is one of the most distinctive geographic features in the world","Spanish moss = Deep South/Gulf Coast, immediately","Saguaro cactus = Southern Arizona, immediately","Concrete utility poles = Florida, immediately"]},{"id":"u_s_virgin_islands","n":"U.S. Virgin Islands","f":"🇻🇮","co":"North America","qt":["Bulky pickup truck (ute) visible when panning down — the USVI Google car is a large, distinctly bulky pickup truck with bars visible and a tray/bed at the rear. Much larger cab than other pickup-truck countries. Unique to USVI.","Left-hand traffic — despite being a US territory, USVI drives on the left. This is one of the most surprising GeoGuessr facts: American territory, English signs, US conventions, but LEFT-hand traffic.","English language + US conventions — American stop signs, US-style road markings, English only","Blue-tinted license plates — plates have a blue background element with black lettering. Varies in style but blue is the consistent colour.","Caribbean tropical landscape — turquoise sea, tropical vegetation, hills"],"ls":"English throughout — US territory. American road sign conventions, STOP signs, SPEED LIMIT signs. No Spanish (unlike Puerto Rico). The combination of English + left-hand traffic + Caribbean tropical setting is the USVI fingerprint.","rb":["Left-hand traffic — memorise this, it's the biggest USVI shock","American-style signage in English","Blue-tinted plates with black lettering (variety of designs)","Road quality reasonable for a Caribbean island","On the two northern islands (St. Thomas, St. John): white pickup truck","On the main southern island (St. Croix): red or white pickup truck, no black antenna holder"],"landb":["Three main islands: St. Thomas (most developed, Charlotte Amalie capital), St. John (lush, national park), St. Croix (largest, more rural)","Tropical Caribbean — turquoise sea visible from many roads, dense tropical vegetation","Hilly terrain — roads wind up and over steep tropical hills","St. John is predominantly national park — very lush, green","Beautiful Caribbean beaches visible in some coverage"],"car":"Large bulky pickup truck with visible bars and rear tray/bed. The cab is noticeably bigger and bulkier than Christmas Island's pickup (the main confusion point). White on St. Thomas and St. John; red or white on St. Croix with no black antenna holder. This is the fastest USVI confirm — the moment you see that big truck tray, commit.","mu":[{"c":"Puerto Rico","k":"also Caribbean, also US territory. Key splits: Puerto Rico is right-hand traffic; USVI is left-hand. Puerto Rico has Spanish on many signs; USVI is English only. Puerto Rico has no front plates; USVI has blue plates."},{"c":"Dominican Republic","k":"also Caribbean, similar tropical. Key splits: DR has Spanish, white car with black strip on roof rack. USVI has English, big pickup truck."},{"c":"Christmas Island","k":"also uses a pickup truck. Key splits: Christmas Island's truck cab is notably smaller. Christmas Island is in the Indian Ocean; context is completely different."},{"c":"Other Caribbean islands","k":"Jamaica (left-hand but very different look and plates), Cayman Islands (minimal coverage)"}],"ex":["Left-hand traffic in a US territory is the most reliable USVI fact — if you see left-hand driving + English American signs + tropical Caribbean = USVI immediately","The big pickup truck is globally distinctive — no other country has this exact vehicle","Charlotte Amalie (St. Thomas capital) has dense harbour-side coverage with cruise ships visible","USVI is a popular cruise destination — very tourist-oriented infrastructure"]},{"id":"canada","n":"Canada","f":"🇨🇦","co":"North America","qt":["Gen 2 / Gen 3 camera blur — Gen 2 is very common in rural Canada (extremely rare in USA). Gen 3 shows two peaks in the car blur vs. a single peak in the US. Either is a strong Canada signal.","\"MAXIMUM\" on speed signs — Canada says MAXIMUM (one line), USA says SPEED LIMIT (two lines). Canadian numbers are also metric (80, 100, 110 km/h vs. 55, 65, 70 mph in USA).","Diamond-shaped T-intersection signs — unique to Canada in the entire world. USA uses rectangular signs.","Single yellow centre line — Canada more commonly uses a single yellow centre line; the US more often has double yellow.","British English + metric — \"centre,\" \"colour,\" \"kilometre\" on signage. Metric units everywhere."],"lb":["English dominates most of Canada, with British spelling (colour, centre, fibre).","French only in Québec — stop signs say \"ARRÊT\", road signs are French-only.","Bilingual (French + English) in New Brunswick — stop signs say \"STOP / ARRÊT\", street signs bilingual. Also appears on federal infrastructure across Canada.","Federal bilingual signage (both languages) can appear anywhere on national roads/buildings.","Inuktitut syllabics appear in Nunavut settlements alongside English.","Québec's Fleurdelisé flag (blue with white fleurs-de-lis) is very commonly seen and immediately identifies the province.","The Acadian flag (tricolour with yellow star) identifies French communities in New Brunswick and parts of Nova Scotia/PEI."],"rb":["Speed signs: \"MAXIMUM\" in one line, metric numbers (50/80/100/110). USA uses \"SPEED LIMIT\" in two lines, imperial.","Diamond T-intersection signs — Canada-only. Québec omits the chequerboard pattern inside. Newfoundland adds a rectangular yellow border.","Less wordy signs — yield signs and railroad crossing signs are typically blank in Canada; US versions have the words printed on them.","Trans-Canada Highway shield — green maple leaf shield found in all 10 provinces. Each province also has its own highway shield design.","Single yellow centre line more common than in USA. Saskatchewan sometimes has white dashes between double yellow lines.","Province-specific bollards:","Alberta: black-and-white cylindrical, two thin black bands","Manitoba: black-grey with orange stripe","BC: thin black-and-white curved bollards","Québec: long thin white poles attached to guardrails, red/green reflector at top","New Brunswick (Trans-Canada): flat yellow bollards","Ontario guardrails: cylindrical wooden posts + exactly three metal wires; posts often have a white reflective band.","BC: concrete barriers common instead of guardrails; signs sometimes hung downward from unique overhead signposts; green sign backs (also on PEI).","Saskatchewan: white triangles on signposts (number varies).","Sign poles: typically wooden in Canada (sometimes white-painted); USA uses metal poles — a consistent background tell.","Street name signs are more often blue in Canada; USA defaults to green.","Québec stop signs say ARRÊT only. New Brunswick says STOP/ARRÊT.","Québec chevrons are red-and-white (rest of Canada: yellow-and-black).","Traffic cones: Ontario = orange-and-black stripes; Québec = orange-and-white stripes.","Transformers on poles: face the road in BC and New Brunswick; parallel to wires in other provinces; 45° angle in PEI and Nova Scotia (PEI ones have red numbers).","Ontario pole tops: two insulators to the side + one on top with a distinctive attachment.","Québec poles: insulators angled slightly upward; black-and-yellow label with small \"Q\"; yellow fire hydrant markers atop signposts.","Ontario: diamond-shaped road-side markers. Québec: rectangular road-side markers.","Alberta rural roads follow a numbered grid (Township Roads E-W, Range Roads N-S) — road signs alone can pinpoint exact location."],"landb":["West (BC, western Alberta, Yukon): Dramatic mountains, coniferous forest. BC interior (Kamloops/Kelowna area): arid brown grasslands, pine forests on hillsides.","Great Plains (Alberta, Saskatchewan, Manitoba): Flat, vast agriculture, very sparse trees. Grain elevators visible on the horizon. Canola fields (bright yellow flowers) in central-southern prairies.","Canadian Shield: Exposed bedrock visible along roadsides across Ontario, Québec, and parts of Atlantic provinces.","PEI: Distinctive red soil, potato farms everywhere.","Yukon: Boreal, hilly, short coniferous trees that get thinner further north. Gen 2 still common.","Manitoba: Aspen trees with white birch-like trunks common in forested areas; turn bright yellow in autumn.","Newfoundland: Balsam fir trees (Christmas-tree shape) dominate. Wooden octagonal bins on driveways. Pyramid-topped wooden guardrail posts.","Atlantic Canada (Nova Scotia, NB): Rectangular lampheads. Nova Scotia lamp arms are unusually short and curved.","Architecture: Colourful wooden houses common in Atlantic provinces and northern communities."],"carb":["Gen 2 — large circular car blur + halo-like colour distortion in the sky. Very common in rural/remote Canada. Extremely rare in USA — if you see Gen 2, strongly lean Canada.","Gen 3 — two peaks in the car blur (USA Gen 3 shows a single peak). This is one of the most reliable Canada-vs-USA tells in ambiguous situations.","Gen 4 Smallcam — mounted lower than standard Gen 4. Big circular blur with a small protrusion at front. Sometimes blur is fully transparent; right-side mirror visible when blur fails.","Special coverage: Dempster Highway (Gen 2, unpaved, dark soil, tundra), Trans-Labrador Highway (Gen 4, remote pine forest), Iqaluit (trekker, turquoise bilingual street signs)."],"mu":[{"c":"USA","k":"Gen 2 (Canada only), two-peaked Gen 3 blur, \"MAXIMUM\" vs \"SPEED LIMIT,\" diamond T-intersection signs, metric numbers, single yellow centre line, communal mailboxes, British spelling"},{"c":"USA (French area)","k":"Louisiana has French but uses US sign conventions, imperial units, \"SPEED LIMIT,\" rectangular T-signs"},{"c":"Québec vs France","k":"Québec uses North American sign formats, metric but MAXIMUM not \"Vitesse limitée,\" French road names, North American road width/infrastructure feel"},{"c":"BC/Alberta vs Pacific NW USA","k":"Check speed signs (MAXIMUM + metric), Gen 2/3 blur, highway shields, bollard style"},{"c":"Manitoba/Saskatchewan vs Montana/North Dakota","k":"Canada has \"MAXIMUM,\" diamond T-signs, metric; canola fields appear on both sides of border"}],"ex":["Canadian brands: Tim Hortons (coffee), Petro-Canada (gas stations), Canadian Tire (retail), LCBO (Ontario liquor stores), Loblaws/Sobeys (groceries) — any of these instantly confirm Canada.","Québec architecture: Large white/grey stone Catholic churches with prominent steeples are very common and distinctly Québécois.","Area codes: Canadian phone numbers formatted XXX-XXX-XXXX. Area codes on signs/ads can help identify province — each province has its own set.","Provincial flags appear frequently; the Québec Fleurdelisé (blue + white fleurs) is especially common and unmistakable.","Canola fields (bright yellow) appear in central-southern prairies — also in North Dakota, so not Canada-exclusive.","Saskatchewan road grid: rural roads numbered by compass direction and distance; can be very useful for pinpointing location.","Manitoba rural roads: numbered by distance from US border (N roads) and from principal meridian west of Winnipeg (E/W roads).","Nunavut settlements accessible via trekker; most have unique characteristics (Iqaluit: turquoise bilingual signs; Grise Fiord: northernmost covered town, unique mountains + ice floes).","Dempster Highway (Yukon/NWT): instantly recognizable — unpaved Gen 2, dark brown soil, tundra, short trees, mountainous."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_1.png"},{"l":"Diamond T-intersection sign","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_2.png"},{"l":"Maximum speed sign","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_3.png"},{"l":"Road lines","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_7.png"},{"l":"Highway shields","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_6.png"},{"l":"Gen 3 two-peaked blur","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_4.png"},{"l":"License plates by province","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_5.png"},{"l":"Communal mailbox","f":"NorthAmerica_ca_Canada_8.png"}]},{"id":"mexico","n":"Mexico","f":"🇲🇽","co":"North America","qt":["Octagonal concrete utility poles — the single most distinctive infrastructure tell. Most poles are concrete, eight-sided, often with engravings on the side. Also common in Colombia, but rare elsewhere.","\"ALTO\" stop signs — Mexico and all Central American countries use ALTO. USA/Canada use STOP. All of South America uses PARE. Seeing ALTO rules out South America and USA, but doesn't alone distinguish Mexico from Central America.","Cylindrical white bollards with a black base — unique to Mexico. Sometimes have a yellow reflector or appear in a flat version.","Yellow center road line + white outer lines — solid white outer lines with a single unbroken yellow center line is the default. Yellow anywhere on the road = not USA (which uses yellow too but differently) and not most of South America.","Black or white cylindrical water tanks on rooftops — extremely common. Nearly every building has one. Rare in the USA and most other Latin American countries.","VeTV blue satellite dishes — small bright-blue satellite dishes mounted on house walls or rooftops. Branded with \"VeTV\" logo. More distinctive than water tanks as a Mexico-only signal."],"lb":["Spanish with many place names of Nahuatl origin — lots of 'x', 'tl', suffixes '-ec' and '-tlan' (e.g. Oaxaca, Tlaxcala, Xochitlan, Teotihuacan). This distinguishes Mexico from other Spanish-speaking countries instantly when you can read a place name.","No ñ quirks vs. Portugal/Brazil, but Nahuatl toponyms are the key tell.","\"ALTO\" on stop signs (not STOP, not PARE).","Directional signs have a distinctly large, all-caps white font — bigger and bolder than most Latin American countries.","OXXO (convenience store) and Pemex (gas station) brand signage is ubiquitous and confirms Mexico immediately.","Telcel / Telmex telecom branding on street cabinets and signs — Mexico's dominant carrier. CEMEX (cement company) and Grupo Modelo / Corona advertising also confirm Mexico.","Speed limit signs: large number inside a red circle with \"km/h\" written below — distinct from USA's white rectangle.","Mexico City taxis: white lower half, pink upper half — very distinctive."],"rb":["Road lines: solid white outer lines + single yellow center line (standard). Broken yellow or double yellow center lines also common. White center lines are most common in Tabasco.","Bollards: small cylindrical white bollards with a black base — unique to Mexico. Nayarit adds a red band near the top; Jalisco bollards say \"Jalisco\" with a crown.","Yellow accents on kerbs and bridge barriers — very common throughout the country.","Highway shields: \"MEXICO\" written at the top on national highway shields (curvy design). State road shields have straight borders with state initials at top.","Kilometre markers: white with black font and outline.","Arrows on signs are very thick — noticeably chunkier than other countries.","Sign cross on back: Chihuahua state has a thick cross visible on the back of road signs.","Road lines by state: Black tar on both sides of the yellow center line = Sinaloa, Durango, or Guerrero. Grainy blue-grey pavement = Tamaulipas or Nuevo León. Dashed outer lines common in Tamaulipas.","Cobblestone pavement: disorganised irregular tiles common in Nayarit, Jalisco, Colima, Queretaro. Hexagonal tiles = Puebla/Tlaxcala. Three-line pattern = Oaxaca."],"landb":["Cacti are everywhere across Mexico in enormous variety — a strong immediate signal vs. USA (where cacti are limited to the southwest) and all of South America (where cactus diversity is lower).","Mexican Giant Cardon (large sprawling arms from single trunk, ribbed) = Baja California","Saguaro (short curving arms) = western Sonora","Organ Pipe (long thin stems from near ground level) = Sonora, Baja California Sur","Prickly pear (flat oval pads) = central Mexico, rare in south/coast","Blue agave fields (tequila) = Jalisco, Nayarit","Pulque agave (crown-like, wide smooth curling leaves) = central valley, San Luis Potosí","Tree yucca (oblong rosettes branching from single trunk) = San Luis Potosí, Zacatecas","Boojum tree (alien tentacle-like) = southern Baja California","Architecture: Rooftop water tanks (black or white cylinders) nearly universal. Construction style varies significantly by region:","North: Pastel/light coloured houses, gated, front yards, US bungalow influence, orange Spanish colonial tiles","West of CDMX (Jalisco, Michoacán, Guanajuato): Red brick buildings dominant","Around CDMX + east: White concrete block buildings","Dry northern states: Mud brick construction","Yucatán: Light-coloured rock walls, thatched roofs, thin white-barked trees","Pickup trucks everywhere — US brands (Ford, Chevrolet, RAM) dominate Mexican roads.","Vegetation zones:","Dense tropical forest + palm variety = southeast (Veracruz, Tabasco, Chiapas, Yucatán)","Pine forest = Sierra Madre (Chihuahua, Durango) and central highlands","Arid scrub/desert = north (Sonora, Chihuahua, Baja)","Sugarcane = Veracruz (most common)","Coconut palms in groups = Guerrero, Colima coast","Mountains: Monterrey surrounded by dramatic tall mountain ranges. Twin volcanoes (Iztaccíhuatl & Popocatépetl) visible near Mexico City–Puebla border."],"carb":["Gen 2 coverage exists in Mexico — very rare in Latin America (Brazil has a little; most countries have none). Seeing Gen 2 in a Spanish-speaking context strongly suggests Mexico.","Gen 3: Two distinctive cars:","White car with a stubby antenna wrapped in a diagonal coil","White car with a visible back and a long red brake light (no antenna)","Gen 4: Three common car types — blue, white with blue stripe, and black. Various color patterns with or without a visible antenna.","Special cars: Yellow-hood car near La Malinche volcano (Tlaxcala); white truck with visible mirrors in Cofre de Perote park; red car with black roof in La Seca, Sinaloa."],"mu":[{"c":"USA","k":"Mexico: ALTO stop signs, yellow center road line, octagonal concrete poles, water tanks on roofs, cacti (outside US southwest), Nahuatl place names, OXXO/Pemex, Spanish language"},{"c":"Guatemala","k":"Both use ALTO (as do all Central American countries); Guatemala camera car has a roof rack, visible bars, and black side mirrors — Mexico's car is a clean white car with stubby coiled antenna. Guatemala has much denser jungle, lower infrastructure quality, fewer octagonal poles."},{"c":"Colombia","k":"Also has octagonal concrete poles — rely on language (Nahuatl toponyms = MX), plates, ALTO vs PARE"},{"c":"Other South America","k":"All use PARE on stop signs, not ALTO — instant differentiation"},{"c":"US–Mexico border zone","k":"Can look very similar; check road lines (yellow center = MX), ALTO sign, water tanks, Spanish language"}],"ex":["Area codes: First digit is regional — see plonkit map. Postal codes first digits are alphabetical by state name and often appear at the bottom of street signs.","License plates: Every state has unique designs. Front plates required nationally. Short plates vs. long European style.","Circular electricity meters on poles (also in US/Philippines/Guatemala — not Mexico-exclusive).","Utility pole regional tells (useful for advanced region-guessing):","Asymmetric crossbar + double-stacked insulators = Mexico City, State of Mexico, Hidalgo, Morelos","Wooden poles with lowered crossbar = Sinaloa, Sonora","Concrete poles with insulators suspended below crossbars = Yucatán peninsula","Poles with mesh body = San Luis Potosí, Guanajuato, Querétaro","Single support beam from crossbar end = Durango","Regional road lines: White center line = Tabasco (only state); black tar flanking yellow = Sinaloa/Durango/Guerrero.","Red dirt roads/fields = Zacatecas. Dark fields = Guanajuato. Near-white soil = Quintana Roo (Gen 3).","Taxis: Pink-and-white = Mexico City area."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_1.png"},{"l":"ALTO stop sign","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_3.png"},{"l":"Cylindrical bollard with black base","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_4.png"},{"l":"Road lines: white outer, yellow center","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_5.png"},{"l":"Octagonal concrete poles","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_2.png"},{"l":"Water tanks on rooftops","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_6.png"},{"l":"Cacti","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_7.jpg"},{"l":"Gen 3 car: stubby coiled antenna","f":"NorthAmerica_mx_Mexico_8.png"}]},{"id":"american_samoa","n":"American Samoa","f":"🇦🇸","co":"Oceania","qt":["Right-hand traffic — rare for a Pacific island. Most Pacific islands (including neighbouring independent Samoa) drive on the left. American Samoa drives on the right due to US administration. This is immediately surprising.","Blue license plates — American Samoa uses blue-background plates. Distinctive in the Pacific.","Black ute/pickup truck visible at the rear — when panning down in Tutuila coverage, you commonly see the back of a black ute (pickup truck). Other American Samoa locations have a person holding the camera instead.","US conventions + Samoan tropical setting — English signs, US-style SPEED LIMIT, American infrastructure quality, but in a lush tropical Pacific island environment","Double yellow centre line on roads (right-hand)"],"ls":"English throughout as a US territory. Samoan language may appear on some local signs (Latin script, vowel-heavy, distinctive). American road sign conventions (SPEED LIMIT, STOP, US highway shields). The combination of US infrastructure + lush tropical Pacific island = American Samoa.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Double yellow centre line on main roads","US-style road signage in English","Blue license plates","Road quality reasonable — varies by area"],"landb":["Tutuila (main island): dramatic, mountainous, densely forested. Steep green volcanic mountains rising directly from the sea. One of the most dramatic island landscapes in GeoGuessr.","Very lush tropical vegetation — extreme rainfall keeps the island deeply green","Pago Pago harbor: dramatic deep natural harbor surrounded by mountains — recognisable if you know it","Small, dense island — ocean is visible from many points","Some coverage on outer islands (Manu'a group) — even more remote, trekker coverage"],"car":"Black ute (pickup) visible from rear on Tutuila road coverage. In other locations a person is holding the Street View camera (trekker-style). The black ute back is the primary car meta for standard road coverage.","mu":[{"c":"Independent Samoa","k":"neighbouring island nation. Key splits: Independent Samoa drives on the left (switched in 2009); American Samoa drives on the right. Independent Samoa has minimal GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Hawaii","k":"also US territory, also Pacific, also tropical. Key splits: Hawaii is much more developed and flat in places; American Samoa is dramatically mountainous. Hawaii has more coverage and more English-only signage."},{"c":"Guam","k":"also US Pacific territory, also right-hand, also English. Key splits: Guam has octagonal utility poles + blue \"Guam\" highway shields; American Samoa has blue plates + black ute. Different landscape (Guam is flatter)."}],"ex":["Right-hand traffic is the fastest American Samoa split from most Pacific islands","Blue plates are distinctive and consistent","The Tutuila landscape (dramatic mountains + deep harbour + dense jungle) is one of the most visually striking in the Pacific","Pago Pago is one of the deepest natural harbors in the South Pacific — visible from some coverage","American Samoa is the only US territory in the Southern Hemisphere"]},{"id":"australia","n":"Australia","f":"🇦🇺","co":"Oceania","qt":["Eucalyptus (gum) trees everywhere — tall trees with white/pale bark and distinctive drooping leaves. No other country on Earth has eucalyptus as the dominant roadside tree. If you see them = Australia.","Left-hand traffic + English — immediately narrows to UK/Ireland/NZ/Australia","GIVE WAY in black text (not red = NZ) and SPEED LIMIT on white rectangle signs (not circular = NZ)","Black-on-yellow chevrons without border — Australia's corner warning chevrons","State-specific pole/infrastructure tells for pinpointing within Australia"],"ls":"English throughout. Australian spelling and terminology on signs. Key infrastructure words: Give Way (not Yield), Speed Limit (on rectangular white sign). Road numbers use national and state numbering systems. The combination of English + left-hand + eucalyptus = Australia.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","GIVE WAY in black text on white/red sign (NZ uses red text)","SPEED LIMIT on white rectangular plates — contrasts NZ's circular speed signs","Black-on-yellow chevrons without border — unique style","Green directional signs on national highways","Road quality excellent on highways, variable on outback tracks","South Australia: Stobie poles — unique dual-steel + concrete utility poles found ONLY in SA. Two steel channels with concrete between. Instantly identifies SA.","Western Australia: Yellow sign posts — sign poles are painted yellow. Rest of Australia uses silver/grey poles.","Northern Territory: Metal utility poles with holes in them. NT also has reddish-tinted license plates.","Tasmania: Some poles have olive-coloured metal wrappings ~2m above ground.","Queensland: Black-painted numbers, blue circular markers, slightly tilted horizontal insulators on poles.","New South Wales: Some cars have yellow license plates (both front and rear)."],"landb":["Enormous diversity across the continent:","Western Australia: vast flat red outback, sparse scrub, huge distances","Queensland: tropical north (rainforest, Great Barrier Reef coast), subtropical south","New South Wales / Victoria: temperate, green, rolling hills (especially Tasmania and Victoria)","Northern Territory: red desert, Uluru, dramatic rock formations","South Australia: flat, dry wine regions, Flinders Ranges","Tasmania: cool, green, mountainous, forested — looks more like New Zealand or Scotland","Eucalyptus/gum trees the dominant vegetation across almost all regions","Outback: vast, flat, red-orange dirt, sparse scrubby vegetation, blue sky","Rolling hills = likely Tasmania or Victoria"],"car":"Standard Gen 1/3/4. Australia has Gen 1 coverage in some early areas (very low quality). Gen 3/4 everywhere else. No distinctive car meta beyond generation. Left-hand traffic is the primary car-perspective confirm.","mu":[{"c":"New Zealand","k":"most similar. Both left-hand, both English, both similar road sign styles. Key splits: NZ uses red text on Give Way signs (Australia uses black). NZ uses circular speed limit signs (Australia uses rectangular). NZ has green directional signs with red highway number shields (Australia has green with white). NZ has a metal ring on utility poles. Eucalyptus = Australia; NZ has more fern/podocarp trees."},{"c":"South Africa","k":"also left-hand, also English partially, also some eucalyptus. Key splits: SA has both English and Afrikaans on signs; Australia is English only. SA road sign fonts are more angular. SA has different vegetation patterns."},{"c":"UK/Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also English. Key splits: completely different landscape and vegetation."}],"ex":["Eucalyptus trees are THE fastest Australia confirm globally — no other country has them as dominant roadside flora","Stobie poles = South Australia, always. No exceptions worldwide.","Yellow sign posts = Western Australia, always.","Mobile numbers beginning with 04 visible on business signs are Australian","Area codes on business signs: 02 = NSW/ACT, 03 = VIC/TAS, 07 = QLD, 08 = WA/SA/NT","Australia has extensive coverage nationwide including very remote outback roads","The outback coverage (flat red dirt, sparse scrub, no buildings for hundreds of km) is one of the most distinctive landscapes in GeoGuessr"]},{"id":"cocos_keeling_islands","n":"Cocos (Keeling) Islands","f":"🇨🇨","co":"Oceania","qt":["Flat tropical coral atoll — two low-lying atolls in the Indian Ocean. Completely flat, coral sand, dense coconut palms, turquoise lagoon. No hills, no mountains, nothing above 5 metres elevation.","Very limited coverage — only West Island and Home Island have coverage. Coverage is extremely sparse — just a handful of roads/paths on tiny islands.","Australian territory — English on any signage, Australian conventions, left-hand traffic","Coconut palm-dominated vegetation — the entire island is covered in coconut palms (historically planted for copra production). Dense palm groves everywhere.","Malay cultural influence on Home Island — the Cocos Malay community on Home Island gives it a distinctly different feel from West Island (which has more Australian-style infrastructure)"],"ls":"English for official signage (Australian territory). The local Cocos Malay population speaks a dialect of Malay — Malay-influenced signs or place names may appear on Home Island. West Island has Australian-style English infrastructure. The combination of English + Indian Ocean coral atoll + coconut palms = Cocos Islands.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (Australian)","Australian road sign conventions","Extremely minimal road network — the islands are tiny (14 sq km total)","Coverage dead-ends very quickly — island roads are short"],"landb":["Flat coral atoll — absolutely flat. If you see completely flat terrain with coconut palms and turquoise water = strong Cocos indicator","Coconut palms completely dominate the vegetation — dense, uniform, plantation-style","Turquoise Indian Ocean lagoon — stunning blue/green water visible from all coastal roads","White coral sand paths and roads","Home Island: denser, more residential, Cocos Malay community, mosque visible, more tropical village feel","West Island: more Australian-style, airstrip, Australian government facilities"],"car":"Very limited road coverage. Australian-style car where it exists. The extreme flatness + coconut palm monoculture + Indian Ocean setting is more identifying than any car meta.","mu":[{"c":"Christmas Island","k":"also Australian Indian Ocean territory, also tropical, also limited. Key splits: Christmas Island is mountainous/hilly with tropical rainforest (not flat); Christmas Island has red crabs and crab warning signs; Christmas Island has a silver ute tray visible. Cocos is flat atoll with palms."},{"c":"Maldives","k":"also flat coral atoll, also turquoise lagoon. Key splits: Maldives uses Dhivehi script (Arabic-derived), right-hand traffic; Cocos uses English, left-hand traffic."},{"c":"Other Pacific atolls","k":"similar geography but different territories."}],"ex":["If you land here in GeoGuessr: flat + coconut palms + Indian Ocean turquoise water + Australian English signage = Cocos Islands, commit","Coverage is so limited that once you recognise the flat atoll + palm landscape you've essentially identified it","The Cocos (Keeling) Islands are closer to Indonesia than to Australia — located NW of Perth near Java","Population of only ~600 people — one of the most sparsely populated places in GeoGuessr","Charles Darwin studied coral atoll formation here during the Beagle voyage — scientifically historic location"]},{"id":"christmas_island","n":"Christmas Island","f":"","co":"Oceania","qt":["Silver ute (pickup truck) tray visible when panning down — Christmas Island's Google car is a pickup truck with a distinctive light silver/metallic tray (bed) visible. The tray is a lighter silver colour. This is the primary car meta.","Red crab warning signs — Christmas Island is famous for its tens of millions of red land crabs that migrate annually. Crab warning signs along roads and special crab bridges (elevated walkways over roads for crabs) are completely unique globally.","Trekker coverage near Ethel Beach showing literally hundreds of red crabs — if you see a walking person perspective surrounded by red crabs, you're at Ethel Beach, Christmas Island.","Australian territory — English signs, left-hand traffic","Tropical rainforest — hilly, lush, green — very different from the flat Cocos Islands"],"ls":"English throughout — Australian external territory. Australian road conventions. Some Chinese signage visible (significant Chinese-Australian population on the island). English + crab signs + tropical forest hills = Christmas Island.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (Australian)","Australian-style road signs in English","Crab warning signs — bright red/orange warning signs with crab imagery. Unique in the world.","Crab bridges/underpasses — elevated structures built over roads to allow crabs to cross safely during migration. Globally unique infrastructure.","Road quality reasonable — Australian territory standards","Very limited road network (small island)"],"landb":["Tropical rainforest covering volcanic hills — unlike the flat Cocos Islands, Christmas Island is mountainous and densely forested with tropical jungle","The island is largely a national park","Ethel Beach area: the famous crab migration site — trekker coverage here shows hundreds of bright red land crabs","Settlement of Flying Fish Cove (main town): small, compact, Australian-style tropical town","Dense tropical forest on steep hillsides — similar feel to Borneo in some respects","Indian Ocean setting — turquoise water visible on coastal roads"],"car":"Silver/metallic pickup truck tray visible when panning down — the tray is a light silver colour. Smaller and less bulky cab than the USVI pickup truck (the main confusion point). Christmas Island = silver tray; USVI = large bulky cab.","mu":[{"c":"Cocos Islands","k":"also Australian Indian Ocean territory, also tropical, also limited coverage. Key splits: Cocos is flat atoll with coconut palms (no hills); Christmas Island is hilly with tropical rainforest. Christmas Island has silver ute tray + crab signs; Cocos has flat landscape + no crab signs."},{"c":"US Virgin Islands","k":"also uses a pickup truck. Key splits: USVI truck has a much larger, bulkier cab; Christmas Island truck has a silver tray with smaller cab. USVI is Caribbean with English + left-hand; Christmas Island is Indian Ocean."},{"c":"Australia (mainland)","k":"also left-hand, also English. Key splits: Christmas Island has crab warning signs, tropical dense rainforest, very limited coverage — context is completely different."}],"ex":["Red crab warning signs are THE fastest Christmas Island confirm — nothing else in the world has crab crossing signs","The red land crabs themselves are visible in some coverage — bright red against green forest","Trekker coverage at Ethel Beach surrounded by hundreds of red crabs is one of the most memorable and unique locations in all of GeoGuessr","Christmas Island is closer to Indonesia than to Australia — located in the Indian Ocean south of Java","Population of ~1,700 — very small community","If you see Australian infrastructure + tropical hilly rainforest + red crab signs = Christmas Island immediately"]},{"id":"guam","n":"Guam","f":"🇬🇺","co":"Oceania","qt":["Large octagonal concrete utility poles — Guam has large octagonal-shaped concrete utility poles. These are distinct from the wooden poles of the Northern Mariana Islands. Unique in the Pacific.","Blue highway shields that literally say \"Guam\" — Guam's highway route markers are blue shields with the word \"Guam\" written on them. You cannot miss this if you see a highway sign.","Long antenna on front-right of Google car — Guam, Northern Mariana Islands, and Puerto Rico all share the same front antenna car meta. Guam vs NMI split: look at rear-left of car — a tiny bit of bar sticking out = Guam (NMI lacks this).","US conventions throughout — SPEED LIMIT, English, right-hand traffic","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"English throughout — US territory. Also Chamorro (indigenous language) may appear on some signs alongside English. Standard American road sign conventions. The combination of English + US-style infrastructure + tropical Pacific island = Guam, NMI, or American Samoa. Octagonal poles + blue Guam shields = Guam specifically.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Blue \"Guam\" highway shields — route markers explicitly say \"Guam\", making identification trivially easy if visible","US-style road signs (SPEED LIMIT, STOP)","Narrow white plates with black lettering — standard; yellow plates also possible","Road quality good — Guam is the most developed US Pacific territory","Larger, busier streets than Northern Mariana Islands","American-style commercial strip development (fast food, shopping malls) similar to US mainland"],"landb":["Tropical Pacific island — lush, green, humid, palm trees","Relatively flat in the south, hillier in the north","Tamuning/Tumon area: heavily developed tourist and commercial zone — almost feels like a US city","Military presence visible — large US military installations occupy significant portions of the island (Anderson AFB, Naval Base Guam)","Beautiful tropical beaches and coastline","Dense tropical vegetation in undeveloped areas","About 2.5x the size of Guam compared to Northern Mariana Islands"],"car":"Long antenna on the front-right corner of the car — shared with Northern Mariana Islands and Puerto Rico. The split from NMI: look at the rear-left of the car (right side in the actual image) — you should see a small bit of bar sticking out in Guam. NMI does not have this. Puerto Rico split: PR uses Spanish; Guam uses English.","mu":[{"c":"Northern Mariana Islands","k":"most similar. Both US Pacific territories, both English, both right-hand, both tropical, same front antenna car. Key splits: Guam has octagonal concrete poles (NMI has wooden poles). Guam has blue \"Guam\" highway shields. Guam is larger and more developed. Tiny bar visible at rear-left of Guam car."},{"c":"Puerto Rico","k":"also same front antenna car, also US territory. Key splits: Puerto Rico uses Spanish on many signs; Guam uses English. Puerto Rico is Caribbean; Guam is Pacific. Very easy split."},{"c":"American Samoa","k":"also US Pacific, also English. Key splits: American Samoa has blue plates + black ute rear; Guam has octagonal poles + front antenna + Guam highway shields."}],"ex":["Blue \"Guam\" highway shields are the most explicit country confirm in GeoGuessr — the sign literally tells you where you are","Octagonal concrete poles are very distinctive and consistent","Guam is strategically important US military territory — military vehicles, bases, and infrastructure visible in coverage","The Tumon tourist strip looks remarkably like a US beach resort strip — Japanese tourists are a large demographic","Anderson Air Force Base is one of the largest US overseas military installations","Guam is located in the western Pacific, east of the Philippines — 13 hours ahead of US East Coast"]},{"id":"northern_mariana_islands","n":"Northern Mariana Islands","f":"🇲🇵","co":"Oceania","qt":["Thick blur beneath you + long antenna on front-right of car — when panning down you see a notably thick/large blur beneath the car. There is also a long antenna extending from the front-right section of the car. This is shared with Guam, but NMI has the thick blur; Guam has a slight unblurred roof rack bar sticking out at the rear-left.","Wooden utility poles — NMI predominantly uses wooden poles, in contrast to Guam's large octagonal concrete poles. This is the fastest Guam vs NMI split.","Smaller, quieter, less developed than Guam — NMI feels more rural and less built-up than Guam's commercial strips","Right-hand traffic — rare for Pacific islands","English language + US conventions"],"ls":"English throughout — US Commonwealth territory. US-style road signs (SPEED LIMIT, STOP), American highway shields. Chamorro and Carolinian languages may appear on some signs alongside English. Standard American infrastructure conventions. Like Guam: English + US signs + tropical Pacific island + right-hand driving.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","US-style road signs (SPEED LIMIT, STOP) in English","Route shields with numbers (route 308, etc.) — US-style numbered shields visible on signs","Tall narrow white plates with black or blue lettering — distinctive plate shape","Wooden utility poles — the key Guam vs NMI infrastructure split","Smaller streets and quieter roads than Guam overall","Some trekker coverage on Tinian Island (WWII ruins, Lasso Shrine)"],"landb":["Tropical Pacific island — lush, green, humid, palm trees throughout","Saipan (main island): limestone terraces, relatively flat in south, hilly in north; most coverage is here","Tinian: flatter, WWII historical sites (atomic bomb loading pits from 1945), ruins visible","Rota: more remote, lush, quieter","Large number of palm trees — very tropical feel","Hills nearby in most of the landscape","Japanese WWII ruins visible in some coverage (the Mariana Islands were a major WWII Pacific theatre)"],"car":"Thick blur beneath car + long antenna at front-right — shared with Guam and Puerto Rico as a car family. NMI split from Guam: NMI has thick featureless blur (no roof rack bar visible); Guam has a tiny bit of bar sticking out at rear-left. NMI split from Puerto Rico: Puerto Rico uses Spanish; NMI uses English.","mu":[{"c":"Guam","k":"most similar. Both US Pacific, both right-hand, both English, both same front antenna. Key splits: Guam has large octagonal concrete poles; NMI has wooden poles. Guam has blue \"Guam\" highway shields; NMI has standard numbered shields. Guam is larger and more developed. Tiny bar at Guam's rear-left vs thick featureless blur at NMI."},{"c":"Puerto Rico","k":"also same front antenna car family, also US. Key splits: Puerto Rico uses Spanish; NMI uses English."},{"c":"American Samoa","k":"also US Pacific, also tropical. Key splits: American Samoa has blue plates + black ute rear; NMI has white/narrow plates + antenna car."}],"ex":["Wooden poles are the fastest and most reliable Guam vs NMI split — learn to distinguish octagonal concrete (Guam) from wooden (NMI) immediately","The WWII history is significant on these islands — if you see Japanese ruins, bomb pits, or WWII memorials in a tropical US territory = NMI (Saipan/Tinian)","NMI is notably quieter and less commercial than Guam — smaller roads, fewer big stores","Coverage is mainly on Saipan with some on Tinian and Rota","Japanese tourists are a significant presence in NMI as in Guam — Japanese signage on some shops"]},{"id":"new_zealand","n":"New Zealand","f":"🇳🇿","co":"Oceania","qt":["GIVE WAY in red text (Australia uses black) — the single fastest NZ vs Australia split on any Give Way sign","Circular speed limit signs (Australia uses white rectangular signs) — round speed discs = NZ immediately","Green directional signs with red highway number shields — NZ highway markers are red shields on green signs. Australia uses green shields. Completely different.","Metal ring/band on utility poles — most NZ utility poles have a lone silver/white metal ring or band wrapping around them partway up. Very distinctive and consistent.","Left-hand traffic + English"],"ls":"English throughout. Māori language also official — appears on many signs (bilingual English/Māori), place names, and road signs. Māori words: Rotorua, Whanganui, Tāmaki Makaurau (Auckland), Te Whanganui-a-Tara (Wellington). The presence of Māori place names alongside English on directional signs is a strong NZ tell. Māori uses macrons (ā, ē, ī, ō, ū) on vowels.","rb":["Left-hand traffic","GIVE WAY in red text — not black (black = Australia)","Circular speed limit signs — round white disc with red border and number. Not rectangular like Australia.","Green directional signs with red highway shields — red shield containing a number = NZ state highway","White give-way triangle painted on road surface at many intersections — unique","Black-on-white chevrons with thin black outline border — NZ chevron style, different from Australian black-on-yellow","Road lines: white centre and edge lines standard; yellow regulatory lines also used","Street signs: blue or green backgrounds"],"landb":["Dramatically diverse across two islands:","North Island: Volcanic plateau (Ruapehu, Tongariro, Taranaki), geothermal areas (Rotorua), rolling green pasture, subtropical north (Auckland/Northland), Wellington coast","South Island: dramatic alpine spine (Southern Alps/Kā Tiritiri o te Moana), fjords (Fiordland), Canterbury Plains (flat farmland), subtropical Marlborough, Otago/Southland (cold, rolling)","Extremely green pasture everywhere — over 40% of NZ is pasture, kept lush by year-round rainfall. If you see intensely green rolling hills = likely NZ.","Sheep and cattle very common roadside — NZ has more sheep than people","Ferns (silver fern and tree fern) visible in forested areas — iconic NZ vegetation","No eucalyptus dominance — unlike Australia, NZ has native podocarp/beech forests and exotic pine plantations","If it looks like Middle Earth, it's probably New Zealand"],"car":"Standard Gen 3/4. No distinctive car meta. Left-hand traffic is the primary orientation confirm. NZ is identified by signs, poles, and landscape.","mu":[{"c":"Australia","k":"most similar. Both left-hand, both English, both similar road conventions. Key splits: NZ has red Give Way text (AU black), circular speed signs (AU rectangular), red highway shields (AU green), metal ring on poles (AU doesn't have this), no eucalyptus dominance. Landscape: NZ is more dramatically mountainous and green; Australia has more flat outback and distinctive eucalyptus."},{"c":"Ireland","k":"also left-hand, also English, also green rolling hills. Key splits: Ireland has metric speed signs showing km/h (NZ signs don't show km/h). Irish signs are in English and Irish (Gaeilge). Very different road sign styles."},{"c":"Scotland/UK","k":"also left-hand, also English, also hilly green. Key splits: UK has completely different road sign design (yellow diamond warnings, etc.)."}],"ex":["Red Give Way text = NZ immediately, never Australia — memorise this split","Circular speed signs = NZ, rectangular = Australia — one of the most reliable AU/NZ splits","Red highway number shields on green signs = NZ — check any directional sign for this","Metal ring on poles is very consistent across the country","Māori place names (long vowel-heavy words with macrons) on bilingual signs are a strong supporting tell","NZ has excellent coverage nationwide including very remote South Island roads and mountain passes","The Queenstown/Fiordland area has some of the most dramatic scenery in all of GeoGuessr — dramatic fjord/mountain landscape that looks completely unlike Australia","North Island vs South Island pinpointing: volcanic peaks + geothermal steam = North Island. Dramatic Alps + glaciers + fjords = South Island. Canterbury flat plains = South Island east coast."]},{"id":"pitcairn_islands","n":"Pitcairn Islands","f":"🇵🇳","co":"Oceania","qt":["Trekker only — no car. Walking perspective on dirt paths through dense tropical vegetation and a tiny settlement.","The \"Adamstown hair\" — the trekker on Pitcairn Island itself has a distinctive hairstyle/appearance. Once you've seen it, it's recognisable.","Henderson Island trekker — has a light grey/tan hat that almost blends with the sandy soil. Mostly beach coverage with some interior paths.","Tiny settlement (Adamstown) — the only inhabited settlement. Wooden directional signs pointing to local landmarks (rather than proper road signs).","British Overseas Territory — Union Jack visible on flags where present. English language."],"ls":"English + Pitkern (a creole of English and Tahitian spoken only on Pitcairn). Pitkern may appear on some signage. The combination of remote South Pacific island + trekker + tiny community + English = Pitcairn. There are essentially no road signs — just the occasional wooden directional post and some guardrails.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (British territory)","No real roads — just dirt paths and tracks through the settlement and jungle","Wooden directional signs pointing to local landmarks","Standard guardrail visible occasionally","Small concrete and wooden utility poles — shorter than typical utility poles","No road markings"],"landb":["Pitcairn Island: Volcanic, extremely rugged and remote. Dense tropical/subtropical vegetation on steep terrain. The only town is Adamstown, perched on a central ridge. Very green, lush, isolated.","Henderson Island: UNESCO World Heritage uninhabited coral island. Mostly beach coverage with some interior. Sandy soil, coral rock, seabirds. Tan/grey sandy landscape.","Two very different landscapes across the group — Pitcairn is green/volcanic; Henderson is flat/sandy/coral","Located in the remote south Pacific — one of the most isolated inhabited places on Earth","Population of Adamstown: fewer than 50 people — the least populated jurisdiction in the world"],"car":"Trekker only throughout. Pitcairn Island has the distinctive Adamstown trekker with recognisable hair/appearance. Henderson Island has a different trekker with a light grey/tan hat. No road driving anywhere in the territory.","mu":[{"c":"Other remote Pacific trekker locations","k":"the combination of British territory + tiny English-speaking settlement + extreme isolation + trekker narrows it significantly."},{"c":"Vanuatu","k":"also Pacific trekker. Key splits: Vanuatu's trekker has a guide with a machete and coconut; Pitcairn has the Adamstown hair trekker. Very different settlements."},{"c":"Falkland Islands","k":"also British territory, also trekker, also remote. Key splits: Falklands is cold/windy grassland in South Atlantic; Pitcairn is lush tropical/warm Pacific."}],"ex":["Pitcairn is famous as the refuge of the Bounty mutineers — settled in 1790 by Fletcher Christian and the mutineers along with Tahitian companions","Population has been declining for decades — fewer than 50 people remain","Coverage is so limited that once you recognise the trekker appearance, pinpointing is straightforward","Henderson Island (uninhabited) appears in GeoGuessr on some world maps — recognisable by flat sandy coral landscape with seabirds","Pitcairn is one of the rarest spawns in GeoGuessr — if you get it, the trekker appearance is the primary tell","Geographically closer to French Polynesia than to any other populated territory"]},{"id":"vanuatu","n":"Vanuatu","f":"🇻🇺","co":"Oceania","qt":["Trekker with a local guide carrying a machete and coconut — Vanuatu's coverage was captured on foot, and the person has a local guide alongside them. The guide is often visible carrying a machete and a coconut. Completely unique.","Only one island covered: Ambrym — coverage is limited to a single village (Endu Pahakol) on the eastern end of Ambrym Island, south of the main island Efate","Active volcano visible — Ambrym has an active volcano. Coverage near the volcano shows dark volcanic soil and lava imagery. One of the most dramatic close-up volcano views in all of GeoGuessr.","Thatched-roof huts — traditional Melanesian architecture. Woven thatch with distinctive weave patterns on the walls.","English language (Vanuatu is officially English/French/Bislama)"],"ls":"English and/or French and Bislama (a creole). Bislama is a unique contact language combining English vocabulary with Melanesian grammar — words like \"ples\" (place), \"man\" (person/man), \"nomo\" (only). If you see a shop or sign in Bislama = Vanuatu. The general store visible in the coverage has some text. The combination of trekker + machete guide + thatched huts + English/Bislama = Vanuatu.","rb":["Right-hand traffic (where applicable — coverage is essentially a footpath through a village)","Dirt road/path — the coverage follows a dirt track through Endu Pahakol village","No road markings, no formal signs","Cinderblock and sheet metal buildings also visible alongside traditional thatched huts"],"landb":["Ambrym Island landscape:","Eastern coastal village: flat, tropical, coconut palms, lush green vegetation","Toward the volcano (west): terrain rises, vegetation changes, dark volcanic soil appears","Active volcano (Ambrym Volcano): one of the most active volcanoes in the world. Coverage near it shows dramatic dark lava fields and volcanic landscape. Extraordinarily rare to have GeoGuessr coverage this close to an active caldera.","Dense tropical Pacific vegetation throughout","Feels very remote and traditional — one of the most ethnographically distinctive locations in GeoGuessr","Dark volcanic soil near the volcano contrasts sharply with the green vegetation"],"car":"Trekker — person on foot with a local guide. The guide with machete and coconut is the most distinctive element of all Vanuatu coverage. You cannot drive anywhere. Coverage is extremely limited to this one village and the path toward the volcano.","mu":[{"c":"Pitcairn Islands","k":"also Pacific trekker, also remote. Key splits: Pitcairn has the Adamstown hair trekker; Vanuatu has the machete/coconut guide. Very different landscapes (Pitcairn is British/European-influenced; Vanuatu is traditional Melanesian village)."},{"c":"Papua New Guinea","k":"similar Melanesian feel. But PNG has almost no GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Solomon Islands / Fiji","k":"also Pacific Melanesian. But those have different or minimal coverage."}],"ex":["The machete and coconut-carrying guide is THE Vanuatu tell — globally unique","Active volcano imagery (dark lava fields, volcanic soil, dramatic scenery) is one of the most spectacular GeoGuessr locations in Oceania","Coverage is so limited (~1 village + volcano path on 1 island) that once you know what it looks like, you'll always identify it","Thatched wall weave pattern is distinctive — traditional Melanesian ni-Vanuatu construction style","Vanuatu is one of GeoGuessr's rarest spawns — if you get the machete guide, commit immediately","The country ranks among the world's happiest countries per capita and has one of the lowest carbon footprints"]},{"id":"argentina","n":"Argentina","f":"🇦🇷","co":"South America","qt":["Black ghostly front of the Google car — when panning forward you see a dark/black ghostly car front. Argentina, Uruguay, and some of Peru share the black car, but Argentina is the most common.","Red-on-white chevrons — Argentina uses red chevrons on a white background. Unique in South America (Brazil uses yellow-on-black, most others use different styles).","Small black and white milestone markers on small posts showing kilometre + road number (RN = national road, RP = provincial road)","Double concrete poles — pairs of utility poles mounted together, a distinctive Argentine infrastructure pattern","YPF gas stations — Argentina's dominant fuel brand, a reliable commercial tell"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Argentine Spanish has distinctive features — the voseo (using \"vos\" instead of \"tú\") appears on signs targeting locals. Street suffix words: calle, avenida, ruta, autopista. Road numbers RN (Ruta Nacional) and RP (Ruta Provincial) are Argentina-specific prefixes visible on milestone markers.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow centre lines + white outer lines — standard for the Americas","Red-on-white chevrons at road bends — unique in South America","Small black-and-white milestone signs on small posts: show kilometre number, sometimes RN/RP road designation","Road quality decent on national routes, variable on provincial roads","Argentine cities often have trees planted between footpath and road — a consistent urban tell shared with Uruguay"],"landb":["Enormous country with extreme regional diversity:","Patagonia (south): flat, windswept, desolate steppe, dramatic sky, very sparse — one of the most distinctive landscapes in GeoGuessr","Pampas (central): vast flat agricultural grassland, cattle, soybeans","Northwest (Jujuy/Salta): dramatic Andean highlands, coloured rock formations, similar to Bolivia","Misiones (northeast): red soil, rolling hills, tropical, near Iguazú Falls","Mendoza (west): vineyards, Andes backdrop","Buenos Aires province: flat, green, agricultural"],"car":"Black car — the front of the car appears as a dark ghostly black shape when panning forward or down. Shared with Uruguay and some Peru, but Argentina is the dominant black-car country in South America.","mu":[{"c":"Uruguay","k":"also black car, also Spanish, also flat grassland. Key splits: Uruguay has green stone kilometre markers; Argentina has black-and-white milestone posts. Uruguay has triple road lines (double yellow + white dashes); Argentina doesn't. Uruguay is much smaller."},{"c":"Chile","k":"also Spanish, also South America. Key splits: Chile has a white rear visible on its car; Argentina has black front. Chile has thin-slotted sign poles; Argentina doesn't."},{"c":"Brazil","k":"Portuguese language (immediate split from Spanish Argentina)"},{"c":"Bolivia","k":"similar northwest Argentina/Bolivian highlands landscape. Check plates: Bolivia has faint blue-tinted plates; Argentina has white plates."}],"ex":["YPF gas stations (blue-yellow branding) are everywhere in Argentina — strongest commercial tell","Patagonian steppe is one of the most recognisable and dramatic landscapes in GeoGuessr — vast empty flatness, sparse scrubby vegetation, massive sky","The double concrete pole pairs are distinctive and consistent across the country","Buenos Aires city: European-feel wide boulevards, French-influenced architecture, very cosmopolitan","Argentine houses often have flat roofs and are painted in pastel colours"]},{"id":"bolivia","n":"Bolivia","f":"🇧🇴","co":"South America","qt":["Faint blue-coloured license plates — Bolivia's plates have a distinctive light blue/pale blue tint, unlike the white plates of most South American countries. Visible even through blur.","White car rear visible, no antenna — the Bolivia Google car has a white back and no antenna, a specific car meta","Dramatic high-altitude Andean landscape — the Altiplano (high plateau at 3,500–4,000m) is flat, barren, and surrounded by snow-capped volcanic peaks. Completely unique landscape.","Thick unpainted sign posts on many roads — rough, unfinished wooden or concrete posts without paint","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish throughout, plus Quechua and Aymara on some signs (indigenous languages). Aymara uses Latin script but with distinctive word patterns. The combination of Spanish + indigenous language text on the same sign is a strong Bolivia tell in some areas.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow centre lines — standard Americas convention","Thick, unpainted road sign posts in many areas — rough, unfinished look distinguishes from neighbouring countries","Various bollard styles with rounded tops and different coloured reflectors — region-specific","Road quality very variable — main paved roads decent, many rural roads unpaved/rough","Bolivia has some extremely high-altitude roads — if you see paved road at altitude with snow-capped peaks = Bolivia/Peru"],"landb":["Altiplano — the defining Bolivia landscape. Vast flat high-altitude plateau at 3,500–4,000m elevation, brown/tan soil, almost no vegetation, surrounded by volcanic peaks. The most iconic Bolivia landscape — one of the most dramatic in GeoGuessr.","Salar de Uyuni (salt flat): brilliant white flat expanse, hexagonal salt patterns, surreal","Lake Titicaca area: deep blue lake at high altitude, Aymara communities on shores","Amazon basin (northeast): tropical jungle, completely different from the highlands","Yungas: dramatic transition between highlands and jungle — very steep green mountain roads","Snow-capped Andean volcanic peaks visible from many highland areas"],"car":"White back visible, no antenna — the Bolivia car shows its white rear section when panning down, and notably has no antenna. This distinguishes it from some other South American cars.","mu":[{"c":"Peru","k":"most similar. Both Andean highlands, both Spanish + indigenous languages, both high altitude. Key splits: Bolivia has faint blue plates; Peru has white plates. Peru has tuk-tuks (Bolivia doesn't). Landscape is similar but Bolivia's Altiplano is even higher and flatter."},{"c":"Argentina (northwest)","k":"similar arid highland landscape in Jujuy/Salta. Key splits: Argentina has white plates, red-on-white chevrons, different car meta."},{"c":"Chile (north)","k":"also Andean, also arid. Key splits: Chile has thin slotted sign poles, white car rear visible, orange commercial plates."}],"ex":["The blue plate tint is subtle but the most reliable Bolivia plate confirm at blur distance","The Altiplano flat+volcanic peaks landscape is extremely distinctive — nothing else looks quite like it","La Paz/Sucre coverage: chaotic hillside cities with colonial architecture","Bolivia has some of the most dramatic road coverage in GeoGuessr — narrow mountain roads with sheer drops","The Death Road (Yungas Road) has some coverage — extremely steep, dramatic"]},{"id":"brazil","n":"Brazil","f":"🇧🇷","co":"South America","qt":["Portuguese language — the ONLY South American country using Portuguese. Distinctive characters: ç (c-cedilla), ã/õ (tilde vowels), â/ê/ô (circumflex vowels). Words ending in -ção (like nation in Portuguese). Immediate continent-level confirm.","Yellow-on-black chevrons — Brazil uses yellow chevrons on black backgrounds at road bends. Unique combination in South America (Argentina uses red-on-white).","Black-backed road signs — the backs of road signs are painted black in Brazil. Very consistent and distinctive when seen from the side or back.","Ladder-style utility poles — the bottom half of Brazilian poles has wide indented ladder segments (not holes), top has small circular holes. Wider at bottom than top.","Red/reddish soil visible in many regions — similar to Uganda/Kenya but in a Latin American context"],"ls":"Portuguese — the definitive Brazil confirm in South America. Key Portuguese features: ç (cedilla), ã/õ (nasal tilde vowels), â/ê (circumflex), articles o/a/os/as, word \"Rua\" (street), \"Avenida\", \"Centro\". Highway signs show BR-XXX for federal highways and XX-XXX for state highways (XX = state abbreviation). No other South American country uses Portuguese.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow inner lines (single or double) + white outer lines — standard Americas convention","Black-backed road signs — flip or view from the side = black back, very consistent","Highway numbering: BR-XXX for federal, state abbreviation-XXX for state roads (e.g. SP-XXX for São Paulo state)","Yellow-on-black chevrons at bends","Road quality very variable — southeast Brazil (São Paulo/Rio) excellent; northeast/rural much rougher","Commercial vehicles have red license plates — useful for trucks on remote roads"],"landb":["Enormous country with extreme diversity:","Amazon rainforest (north/west): dense tropical jungle, rivers everywhere, some remote roads","Cerrado (central): savanna/woodland, dry season yellows the vegetation","Northeast/Nordeste: arid semi-desert (Sertão), very dry, rock formations, reddish soil","Southeast (Rio/São Paulo): tropical coastal mountains, dense urban, Atlantic Forest","South (RS/SC/PR): temperate, green, European-influenced, resembles southern Europe","Pantanal: vast wetland, flooded in wet season","Red/reddish soil common across many regions, especially southeast and west"],"car":"Standard Gen 3 — much of Brazil has a white car with only a small silhouette visible. No distinctive special car meta. Newer coverage has white/silver cars. Brazil is identified primarily by language and infrastructure rather than car.","mu":[{"c":"Portugal","k":"also Portuguese! Key splits: Portugal is in Europe, left-hand traffic historically was right-hand now right, completely different landscape. Totally different context."},{"c":"Argentina","k":"same continent but Spanish language (immediate split). Argentina has red-on-white chevrons; Brazil has yellow-on-black."},{"c":"Colombia","k":"also tropical, also Spanish. Portuguese ç/ã letters immediately split from Spanish."},{"c":"Mozambique/Angola","k":"also Portuguese but completely different African context, different landscape"}],"ex":["ç and ã are the fastest language confirms — no other South American country has these","Black sign backs are incredibly consistent — if you see a sign back and it's black, commit to Brazil","YBrazilian highways BR-XXX are shown on the map and can be used to pinpoint location significantly","São Paulo is one of the largest cities in the world — absolutely massive urban coverage","Rio de Janeiro has iconic Christ the Redeemer visible in some coverage","The Amazon coverage is minimal but exists — if you're in an utterly remote tropical jungle with Portuguese signs, it's Brazil","Brazilian Portuguese has distinctive nasal sounds reflected in ã/õ — once you know it, it's unmistakable"]},{"id":"colombia","n":"Colombia","f":"🇨🇴","co":"South America","qt":["Yellow license plates — Colombia uses yellow plates for all vehicles (similar to Colombia-specific yellow). One of the most reliable Colombia tells in South America.","Very narrow white sign poles — Colombian road signs are mounted on extremely thin, narrow white poles. Distinctive and consistent throughout the country.","Octagonal utility poles — Colombia is the only Latin American country (besides Mexico and occasionally Ecuador) with octagonal-shaped poles","Reddish tile sidewalks — sidewalks in Colombian cities often feature red/terracotta ceramic tiles. Consistent urban tell.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Colombian Spanish uses standard Latin American Spanish conventions. Key infrastructure words: carrera (numbered N-S streets), calle (E-W streets), transversal, diagonal — the Bogotá grid system uses these terms uniquely. \"Pr\" visible on green kilometre markers. Colombian addresses often include both carrera and calle numbers.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Yellow centre lines — standard Americas","Very narrow, thin white sign poles — one of the most distinctive infrastructure tells in Latin America","Octagonal utility poles — shared only with Mexico in Latin America","Two types of km markers: tall green post with \"Pr\" at top, OR traditional stone marker with black lettering","Wooden fences — rudimentary wooden fence style common along rural roads","Licence plates printed on taxi sides — Colombian taxis often have their plate number painted on the car door","Road quality reasonable on main roads; very rough in rural areas"],"landb":["Extremely mountainous — three Andean ranges (Cordilleras) run north-south through the country","Very green and lush — Colombia has year-round tropical growing conditions","Coffee-growing regions: steep green mountain slopes with coffee plantations, banana trees","Bogotá and other major cities at high altitude (Bogotá 2,600m) — cooler than expected for tropical latitude","Caribbean coast: flat, tropical, palm trees","Amazon jungle in south","Pacific coast: one of the wettest places on Earth, dense rainforest","Yellow soil/clay common in many areas"],"car":"Standard Gen 3. No distinctive car meta. Colombia is identified by plates, poles, and urban infrastructure.","mu":[{"c":"Ecuador","k":"most similar. Both Andean, both Spanish, both mountainous. Key splits: Ecuador has distinctive red-stripe bollards; Colombia has yellow plates. Ecuador uses double guardrails on many roads. Ecuador's sign poles are not as narrow as Colombia's."},{"c":"Venezuela","k":"also Spanish, also Andean/Caribbean. But Venezuela has almost no GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Peru","k":"also Andean, also Spanish. Key splits: Peru has white plates (Colombia has yellow). Peru has tuk-tuks; Colombia doesn't."},{"c":"Brazil","k":"Portuguese language (immediate split from Spanish)"}],"ex":["Yellow plates are the single fastest Colombia confirm — visible at blur distance across the whole country","The narrow thin white sign poles are very distinctive once you notice them","Colombian taxis with plate numbers painted on doors are a strong urban tell","Colombia's road network includes some of the most dramatic mountain roads in GeoGuessr — narrow roads on sheer cliff faces in the Andes","Cartagena coverage: colonial Caribbean city with colourful buildings, very distinctive","\"Pr\" markers are visible on main highways and a reliable Colombia confirm"]},{"id":"cura_ao","n":"Curaçao","f":"🇨🇼","co":"South America","qt":["Brightly coloured Dutch colonial houses — Curaçao's architecture is iconic: vivid orange, yellow, blue, green, pink buildings in Dutch gabled style. The most visually distinctive architecture in the Caribbean.","Dutch language on signs — ONLY Caribbean island with Dutch as its national language. If you see Dutch words in a tropical Caribbean setting = Curaçao.","Black car bonnet (hood) visible + visible roof rack bars — Curaçao's Google car has a distinctly visible black bonnet/hood at the front, unique to Curaçao. No black strip on rack (unlike Dominican Republic).","White base on wooden utility poles — poles are wooden with the lower section painted white, upper section unpainted. Distinctive two-tone pole style.","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Dutch (Papiamentu also spoken locally). Dutch is immediately recognisable by words like straat (street), weg (road), haven (harbour), ingang/uitgang (entrance/exit). The combination of Dutch text + tropical Caribbean island = Curaçao only. No other Caribbean or Latin American island uses Dutch on road signs.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Dutch road sign conventions (same style as Netherlands)","Road quality reasonable — small island, well-maintained main roads","Wooden poles with white-painted base — very consistent","General infrastructure is well-maintained for a Caribbean island — reflects Dutch investment"],"landb":["Small arid Caribbean island — Curaçao is notably drier than most Caribbean islands. Scrubby cacti and thorny bushes rather than lush tropical jungle.","Flat to gently hilly terrain","Caribbean Sea surrounding — turquoise water visible from coastal roads","Willemstad: the capital is iconic — Handelskade waterfront with colourful Dutch gabled buildings is one of the most photographed urban scenes in the Caribbean","Cacti common on roadsides — arid landscape unlike most Caribbean islands people imagine"],"car":"Visible black car bonnet (hood) at the front, visible roof rack bars. The black front hood is the key car meta — unique to Curaçao. No black strip on the roof rack bars (the Dominican Republic has a black strip on its rack; Curaçao does not).","mu":[{"c":"Dominican Republic","k":"also Caribbean, also tropical. Key splits: DR has Spanish (not Dutch), DR car has black strip on roof rack bars; Curaçao car has black bonnet but no strip on bars."},{"c":"Netherlands (mainland)","k":"also Dutch language. Key splits: Netherlands is in Europe, flat, temperate climate; Curaçao is a tropical arid Caribbean island with colourful colonial architecture."},{"c":"Aruba","k":"neighbouring ABC island, also Dutch-influenced, also arid. But Aruba has very limited GeoGuessr coverage."},{"c":"Other Caribbean islands","k":"all use English, French, Spanish or Creole. Dutch = Curaçao only."}],"ex":["The colourful Dutch colonial architecture is one of the most immediately recognisable scenes in all of GeoGuessr — if you see a row of brightly painted gabled buildings in a tropical setting, it's Willemstad, Curaçao","Dutch language + tropical Caribbean = only Curaçao. This combination is globally unique.","The white-based wooden poles are very consistent and a good supporting tell","Black car bonnet visible from the front — learn this as the primary car meta","Curaçao is a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands — technically part of the Dutch realm despite being in the Caribbean","The island is surprisingly arid — cacti and dry scrub rather than jungle, quite different from what people expect from the Caribbean"]},{"id":"ecuador","n":"Ecuador","f":"🇪🇨","co":"South America","qt":["Stubby/thick short antenna on the white Google car — Ecuador has a white car with a distinctive short, thick stubby antenna. Visible when panning down or forward.","Double guardrails on mountain roads — Ecuador frequently uses double guardrails on road edges, unique in Latin America","Red-stripe bollards — round bollards with two red stripes, OR flat bollards with two red reflectors on black background. Very consistent throughout the country.","Ladder-style utility poles with many small indents resembling ladder steps — similar to Brazilian poles but with more, shallower holes/indents","Square white-background road signs — Ecuador uses square signs with white backgrounds frequently, unusual in the region","Right-hand traffic"],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Quechua (Kichwa) may appear on some signs in indigenous areas. Standard Latin American Spanish signage conventions. Ecuador uses metric distances.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Double guardrails on mountain roads — a strong Ecuador tell in Andean areas","Square white-background road signs — more common than in neighbouring countries","Orange commercial vehicle plates — commercial vehicles have solid orange plates or white plates with an orange bar at top","White standard plates for private vehicles","Road quality varies — main Pan-American Highway and city roads decent, mountain/rural roads rough","Galapagos Islands: trekker coverage on some islands"],"landb":["Extremely diverse in a tiny country:","Sierra (Andes): dramatic volcanic peaks, including active Cotopaxi and Chimborazo. Quito sits at 2,850m altitude in a beautiful valley.","Costa (Pacific coast): flat, tropical, banana plantations, humid","Oriente (Amazon): jungle, remote, some coverage along main roads","Galapagos: unique volcanic islands with trekker coverage and sometimes Galapagos tortoises visible","Very mountainous overall — coverage in highlands shows dramatic Andean volcanic landscape","The Pan-American Highway runs north-south through the Sierra region"],"car":"White car with a short stubby thick antenna — the antenna is notably shorter and thicker than typical European-style antennas. This is the primary Ecuador car tell, though the same style appears in Mexico, Brazil, and Colombia too. Combined with other clues it helps confirm Ecuador.","mu":[{"c":"Colombia","k":"most similar. Both Andean, both Spanish, both mountainous. Key splits: Colombia has yellow plates; Ecuador has white plates. Colombia has very narrow sign poles; Ecuador has more standard poles. Ecuador has distinctive red bollards; Colombia doesn't."},{"c":"Peru","k":"also Andean, also Spanish. Key splits: Peru has tuk-tuks (Ecuador doesn't). Ecuador has double guardrails more consistently than Peru."},{"c":"Bolivia","k":"also Andean highlands. Key splits: Bolivia has faint blue plates; Ecuador has white plates. Bolivia's Altiplano is flatter; Ecuador is more dramatically volcanic."}],"ex":["The double guardrails on mountain roads are the most reliable Ecuador infrastructure tell","Red bollards (two red stripes) are very consistent and distinctive — few other countries in South America have bollards this consistently","Galapagos Islands trekker coverage is unique — giant tortoises occasionally visible, completely unlike mainland Ecuador","Quito's colonial centre (UNESCO heritage) has distinctive Spanish colonial architecture","The active volcanos visible in Andean coverage (Cotopaxi with its perfect cone shape) are sometimes recognisable landmarks"]},{"id":"falkland_islands","n":"Falkland Islands","f":"🇫🇰","co":"South America","qt":["Trekker + boat coverage — no Google car. All coverage is on foot (trekker) or from a boat. You will see the person walking or be on a boat on the ocean.","Sub-Antarctic island landscape — dark soil, tussock grass and low vegetation, windswept, grey skies. Cold, bleak, and remote.","Yellow rear + white front plates — British territory uses UK-style plates","British English — all signage in English where visible, British conventions","Extremely limited coverage — only a handful of locations on the western island (West Falkland)"],"ls":"English throughout — British Overseas Territory. No Spanish despite being surrounded by Argentina. British road conventions, left-hand traffic.","rb":["Left-hand traffic (British)","Very few roads — the islands are largely trackless grassland","Coverage is trekker/boat only — no car driving along roads","Yellow rear plates visible on vehicles when they appear"],"landb":["Windswept sub-Antarctic grassland — tussock grass, low scrubby vegetation, dark peaty soil","Rocky outcrops, dramatic coastlines","Grey/overcast skies typical — very bleak and remote feel","Penguins sometimes visible — Falklands has significant penguin populations. Seeing penguins in this context (rocky grassland island) helps confirm Falklands vs Antarctica","Colourful British-style houses — distinctive architecture similar to what you'd find in remote British communities","The research vessel used to cover surrounding waters is sometimes visible"],"car":"Trekker only + some boat coverage. Three specific locations on West Falkland island make up most of the coverage: New Island, West Point, and Carcass Island. If you land here, it will be one of these.","mu":[{"c":"South Georgia","k":"also sub-Antarctic, also British, also penguins + tussock grass. Key splits: South Georgia has more dramatic mountains/glaciers and much larger penguin/seal colonies. Falklands feels more like windswept lowland farmland/grassland. South Georgia has more dramatic scenery."},{"c":"Antarctica","k":"also cold, also trekker. Key splits: Antarctica has no vegetation at all; Falklands has tussock grass and green vegetation."},{"c":"Patagonia (Argentina/Chile)","k":"also windswept, also cold. Key splits: Falklands is an island (ocean visible), no cars, trekker only. Patagonia has road coverage and Spanish."}],"ex":["The Falklands/Malvinas are disputed between UK and Argentina — the Argentine flag is visible in some coverage as a political statement","Coverage is so limited (~3 locations) that memorising the specific spots is a valid strategy","The Falklands look similar to a very remote, windswept British farm — rolling grass hills, colourful wooden houses","Penguin encounters in trekker coverage are a strong Falklands tell — combined with tussock grass and British houses","Left-hand traffic + English + South Atlantic island = Falklands"]},{"id":"uruguay","n":"Uruguay","f":"🇺🇾","co":"South America","qt":["Trident utility poles — the most common Uruguayan utility pole has three upward-facing bulbs at the top, making it look like a trident. Unique and distinctive — the fastest Uruguay confirm.","Triple road lines — roads often feature double yellow lines in the centre with white dashes between them. This three-line road marking is not found elsewhere in the Americas.","Green painted stone kilometre markers — Uruguay uses distinctive green-painted stone posts as kilometre markers on highways. Unique in South America.","Black ghostly car front — same black car as Argentina. Combined with other tells.","Overcast, grey weather — Uruguay typically has overcast skies and a generally gloomy grey atmosphere. More cloudy than Argentina."],"ls":"Spanish throughout. Rioplatense Spanish (same dialect as Argentina). Standard Latin American signage conventions. Cities tend to have trees planted between footpath and road — consistent urban tell shared with Argentina but very distinctive.","rb":["Right-hand traffic","Triple road lines (double yellow + white dashes in centre) — unique in the Americas, fastest road marking confirm","Black-and-white or black-and-yellow striped traffic light poles — traffic lights mounted on distinctively striped poles","Black and white arrows on walls and poles in cities — directional arrows painted on urban infrastructure","Thick white wooden sign posts — Uruguay's road signs are mounted on thick, white, wooden posts. Different from Argentina's concrete poles.","Road quality generally poor — notably worse than Argentina or Brazil","Green stone km markers on national highways"],"landb":["Flat, open grassland (campo) — Uruguay is one of the flattest countries in South America. Gentle rolling hills, open pasture, cattle everywhere.","Overcast grey atmosphere — a notable sub-tell. Uruguay consistently has more cloud cover and grey skies than neighbouring Argentina.","Trees planted in lines along urban roads and footpaths","Some eucalyptus plantations","Coastal areas (Montevideo, Punta del Este): beaches, urban developments","Generally feels like a quieter, greyer, more agricultural version of Buenos Aires"],"car":"Black car front — same as Argentina. The front of the car appears as a ghostly black shape. Uruguay and Argentina share this car, so other tells (poles, road lines, km markers) are needed to distinguish them.","mu":[{"c":"Argentina","k":"most similar. Both black car, both Spanish, both flat grassland, both tree-lined city streets. Key splits: Uruguay has trident poles (Argentina has double concrete poles). Uruguay has triple road lines (Argentina has different markings). Uruguay has green stone km markers (Argentina has black-white milestone posts). Uruguay is overcast more frequently."},{"c":"Brazil","k":"Portuguese language (immediate split)"},{"c":"Paraguay","k":"adjacent country but Paraguay has almost no GeoGuessr coverage"}],"ex":["Trident poles are THE fastest Uruguay confirm — three upward bulbs = Uruguay, commit immediately","Triple road lines (if you can see them clearly) are equally reliable","The generally poor road quality relative to Argentina is a supporting sub-tell","Montevideo: grey, European-influenced port city — one of the more recognisable South American capitals","Uruguay is geographically tiny and very consistently flat — if you're in a flat, grey, grassy South American landscape with no mountains on the horizon and a black car, it's probably Uruguay","Black-and-white arrows painted on urban walls/poles are a distinctive urban Uruguay tell"]},{"id":"chile","n":"Chile","f":"🇨🇱","co":"South America","qt":["All-white or all-yellow road lines — Chile almost never mixes the two colours. All-white is the default; all-yellow appears in national parks and high snowfall zones and is essentially unique to Chile within the Americas.","Square concrete utility poles with an indent on both sides — the indent runs the full length of the pole with small pinholes at the top. Looks similar to Brazilian poles but with fewer horizontal supports inside.","Slots at the top of signposts — a thin rectangular slot near the top of the post, visible from behind or at an angle. Very common and distinctive.","White (private) and orange (commercial/taxi) license plates — the combination is distinctive; most of South America uses white-only or yellow plates.","Red painted fence posts on bridges — very common across the country, rarely seen elsewhere in South America.","Copec gas stations (green logo) — Chile's dominant fuel brand with ~53% market share. Seeing \"Copec\" is an instant confirm. Argentina has YPF (yellow/blue), Brazil has Petrobras.","Walmart (branded Lider) — Chile is the only country in South America where Walmart operates. A Walmart or Lider sign = Chile confirmed."],"lb":["Spanish — no unique language tell vs. other South American countries, but Nahuatl-style names are absent (contrast with Mexico).","PARE on stop signs — like all of South America. Not ALTO (Central America/Mexico), not STOP (North America).","Road naming system: Regional letters A–Y increase from north to south. Road names with the letter prefix (e.g., B-710, D-55) reveal the approximate latitude.","Phone area codes: Two-digit prefix + seven digits. Regional patterns are learnable for precise region-guessing.","Ñuble, Aysén, Magallanes, Araucanía — distinctive Chilean region names that may appear on road signs."],"rb":["Road lines: All-white (most common) or all-yellow (national parks, Magallanes, high altitude). Triple yellow lines appear on some southern and Atacama-region roads — essentially unique to Chile.","Concrete road + all-yellow lines = strong indicator of Magallanes (far south) — barren, grassy, treeless landscape.","Bridges: Red painted fence/guardrail posts, very common.","Slots on signposts — thin rectangular slot at the top of the post. One of the most reliable infrastructure tells.","Bollards: Spanish-style (white front reflector, yellow-orange rear), not very common. Temporary bollards are orange with two white stripes at top.","Speed limit signs: White rectangle with red border and black number — same European/international style as Argentina, Peru, and most of South America."],"landb":["Far north (Atacama, Arica y Parinacota): Extreme desert. Almost no vegetation — bare sand and rock. Atacama region has brownish-red soil. Arica has smooth/sandy eroded mountains with valleys. Candelabrum cactus (Browningia candelaris — tall branching columnar) appears at higher altitude. Salt flats and volcano silhouettes on the horizon. The Atacama Desert extends into southern Peru and western Bolivia.","Central (Santiago metro, Valparaíso, O'Higgins): Semi-arid Mediterranean. Dry brown hills with sparse shrubby vegetation; vineyards common in Maule. Eucalyptus plantations = southwestern Valparaíso.","South-central (Bio Bío, Araucanía): Dense green forest. Concepción pines (puffy Pinus radiata) = Bio Bío. Monkey puzzle trees (Araucaria araucana — spiky candelabra shape) = eastern Araucanía. Narrow tree-lined roads.","Lake District (Los Lagos) / Chiloé: Rolling green agricultural landscape. German-influenced architecture in Frutillar and Puerto Varas (Bavarian-style buildings). Chiloé island: colorful palafitos (wooden stilt houses over water) in Castro/Chonchi — immediately distinctive. Wooden shingle-clad churches (16 UNESCO-listed). Chilean rhubarb (giant cabbage-like plant) on Chiloé and adjacent mainland.","Far south (Aysén, Magallanes): Barren, treeless grasslands, rocky peaks, overcast. Aysén has autumn orange/red coverage. Torres del Paine: sharp peaked granite towers.","Architecture: San Pedro de Atacama — distinctive clay brick walls with triangles at top. O'Higgins village — orange-stained wooden structures."],"carb":["Gen 3: Solid white car with no antenna — two variants:","Plain white car (also seen in Peru and Bolivia)","White car with a visible black section at the back — unique to Chile. The strongest Gen 3 car tell.","Gen 4: Blue car (standard).","Special vehicles:","Grey Toyota Hilux with snorkel = Baños Morales area","White truck with visible side mirrors = Conguillio NP and Puerto Williams","Horse trekker = northeast of San Felipe"],"mu":[{"c":"Argentina","k":"Argentina uses red-and-white chevrons (unique in the Americas) — if you see them, it's Argentina. Chile has no chevrons. Also: Argentina = YPF gas stations, all-white plates; Chile = Copec, orange commercial plates. Patagonian landscape is shared — rely on road markings and poles."},{"c":"Peru","k":"Tuk-tuks (auto-rickshaws) are Peru-only in South America — instant confirm. Peru has black-and-white striped poles set in raised concrete blocks; Chile has square indented poles. Peru roads often have a yellow center line."},{"c":"Bolivia","k":"Similar altiplano landscape in north — Bolivia has very poor road quality, different poles, white center lines on many roads"},{"c":"Argentina (Patagonia)","k":"All-yellow lines on concrete = Chile Magallanes (Argentina uses white lines in Patagonia). Monkey puzzle trees grow on both sides of the border."}],"ex":["Road letter codes go A (northernmost) → Y (southernmost) — a quick latitude fix when you can read a road sign.","City lamp tells: Green dome lamps = Copiapo; blue rectangular lamps with yellow stripe = Concepción; photocell lamps = Santiago; silver-top/grey-bottom = Puerto Montt/Temuco; orange lamps = Calama/Chañaral.","Arica poles: White painted. Other Atacama cities: yellow painted poles (may be faded).","Orange street signs at intersections = city of Lanco (Los Ríos region).","Ruta 1 is a coastal road with Pacific to the west and a wall of mountains to the east — very recognisable when seen.","ALMA radio telescopes in the Atacama (barren, snowy high plateau) are unique to Chile.","Torres del Paine trekker = sharp granite peaks + glacier walking with orange-helmeted people."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_1.png"},{"l":"Road lines: all white or all yellow","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_2.png"},{"l":"Square concrete poles with indent","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_4.png"},{"l":"License plates: white and orange","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_5.png"},{"l":"Slotted signposts","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_6.png"},{"l":"Atacama desert","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_7.png"},{"l":"Southern Chile: yellow lines on concrete road","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_8.png"},{"l":"Google car: white Gen 3 variants","f":"SouthAmerica_cl_Chile_3.png"}]},{"id":"peru","n":"Peru","f":"🇵🇪","co":"South America","qt":["Black-and-white striped signposts — the single most distinctive infrastructure tell. No other South American country uses this. Sometimes black-and-yellow instead.","Concrete blocks at the base of metal signposts — unique to Peru in South America. The post sits in a rectangular concrete base at ground level.","Tuk-tuks (mototaxis) — three-wheeled motorized rickshaws, extremely common in cities and rural areas. Unique to Peru in South America. Open-front variants = northern Peru.","Orange painted bridges — bridges throughout the country are commonly painted orange, a strong secondary tell.","Black-and-yellow striped guardrails — outer stripe is black (Bolivia's is yellow — the key differentiator between the two).","Inca Kola branding (bright yellow soda, Peru's dominant drink) — wall murals, fridge stickers, and signs appear everywhere. Seeing \"Inca Kola\" = Peru confirmed."],"lb":["Spanish is dominant on signs. Quechua is co-official and appears in the highlands — place names (Huancayo, Cusco, Ayacucho, Puno, Machu Picchu) and business signs (words like Killa, Kusi, Ayllu, Tahuantinsuyu). Quechua on a sign = Peruvian highlands confirmed (not Bolivia).","PARE on stop signs (like all South America).","S/ symbol for the sol (Peru's currency) — unique to Peru. May appear on price signs, storefronts.","Peruvian political party logos are highly distinctive and unique to Peru — colourful stencil-style logos painted on walls.","Highway numbering: Numbers increase from north to south on coastal Route 1 (1N/1S). Highways 1, 3, and 5 are the longest. Road numbers on signs can give an approximate latitude."],"rb":["Road lines: White outer lines always. Center line is either single yellow dashed or double yellow on highways. Mountain roads often have no center line at all. Divided highways may be completely white.","Signposts: Black-and-white or black-and-yellow diagonal stripes — unique in South America. Always check the posts.","Concrete blocks at post bases — unique to Peru in SA.","Guardrails: Black-and-yellow stripes. Outer stripe is black (Bolivia's outer stripe is yellow — crucial differentiator).","Kilometre markers: Concrete, painted black and white.","Bollards: Triangular concrete, painted red or yellow. Moquegua state has a unique cylindrical bollard with black-and-yellow stripe at top.","Utility poles: Concrete or wood. Many poles have 3 horizontal arms/crossbars all extending in the same direction — distinctive within South America. Some poles have painted bases — black or black-and-yellow — unique to Peru in SA.","Speed signs: White rectangle with red border (international standard, same as Chile/Bolivia)."],"landb":["Coast: Extremely dry desert. Near Lima and south of Ica: barren flat desert with red/orange soil, mountains visible to east. Near Arequipa and Tacna: similar but with volcanoes visible (volcanoes only in southeast Peru). Agricultural valleys — green strips sandwiched between dry mountains — run SW–NE.","North coast: Flatter desert with shrubs; coconut palms near coastal cities north of Lima; sugar cane and banana plantations near Chiclayo and Trujillo.","Highlands (Sierra): Semi-arid mountain ranges and valleys. Rocky outcrops on hillsides (central highlands). Pine plantations at higher elevation. Lichen patches (light green) on rocks = central/southern highlands. Dark red soil = areas near Cusco, Ayacucho, Cajamarca.","Lake Titicaca area (Puno): Flat grasslands with brown brick buildings and stone walls. Looks similar to Bolivia — use infrastructure tells.","Amazon (selva): Dense rainforest. Iquitos (isolated, Gen 3 only) has overcast skies and rolling jungle landscape.","Architecture: Red brick buildings become more common near Lake Titicaca. Colonial style = Cusco area. Overhanging roofs with wooden supports = northern Peru. Lima boulevards: long straight streets divided by concrete or grassy berms.","Cusco: Red brick + Spanish colonial buildings, airport in the middle of the city, surrounded by mountains on all sides."],"carb":["Gen 3: Either solid black or solid white car, no antenna.","Black car = only Peru, Argentina, Uruguay in South America","White car = only Peru, Bolivia, Chile in South America","Gen 4: Dark gray car. Peru has Gen 4; Bolivia does not. Ecuador has Gen 4 but always in a large pickup truck — easily distinguishable.","Gen 4 Smallcam: Lower-mounted, large circular blur, small front protrusion. Only Peru, Brazil, and Argentina have smallcam in South America.","Special vehicles:","White car from Aguas Calientes up to Machu Picchu (central Cusco area)","Trekker on train track between Aguas Calientes and Cusco"],"mu":[{"c":"Bolivia","k":"No tuk-tuks in Bolivia. Bolivia has NO Gen 4 coverage. Guardrail outer stripe: Peru = black, Bolivia = yellow. Black-and-white signposts = Peru only. Bolivia road lines may also differ."},{"c":"Ecuador","k":"Ecuador Gen 4 = large pickup truck (Peru = dark gray car). Ecuador has double guardrails (nearly unique to Ecuador in Latin America — Peru has single). Ecuador \"ladder poles\" (many small indents like rungs). No tuk-tuks in Ecuador. Black-and-white striped signposts = Peru only."},{"c":"Chile (north)","k":"Both have dry desert coast. Chile: square indented concrete poles, all-white road lines, no tuk-tuks, Copec gas stations, orange commercial plates. Peru: striped signposts, concrete block bases, tuk-tuks, yellow/white plates."},{"c":"Bolivia (altiplano)","k":"Flat highland lake landscape is shared. Rely on signpost stripes, guardrail outer stripe color, and presence/absence of tuk-tuks."}],"ex":["Electricity counters: Rectangular metallic boxes with 2–3 horizontal slits — distinctive Peruvian design.","Taxi stickers: Wide red-and-white sticker on the side of taxis and commercial vehicles.","Lima lamp posts: Sweeping inverted \"J\" shape at the top — common in Lima Department, occasionally Iquitos/Pucallpa.","Petroperu fuel stations — national oil company, appears on gas stations throughout Peru.","Ruta 1 (Pan-American): Divided highway section near Piura/Lambayeque border — the only divided highway outside cities.","Ruta 30C (east): Gen 3 white car, dense Amazon forest, resembles Brazil interior. Some Gen 4 overlay.","Iquitos: Isolated city in northeast, Gen 3 only, overcast, three-wheeled tuk-tuks, jungle surroundings.","Olive plantations = far south, Tacna region only.","Arequipa volcanoes = only found in the southeastern corner of Peru."],"imgs":[{"l":"Overview","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_1.png"},{"l":"Black-and-white striped signposts","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_2.png"},{"l":"Concrete blocks at signpost bases","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_3.png"},{"l":"Road lines: white outer + yellow center","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_6.png"},{"l":"Black-and-yellow guardrail markings","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_7.png"},{"l":"Orange bridges","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_8.png"},{"l":"Google car: black and white Gen 3","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_4.png"},{"l":"Tuk-tuks / mototaxis","f":"SouthAmerica_pe_Peru_5.png"}]}];

// Normalize compact keys to readable names
const COUNTRIES = RAW.map(d => ({
  id: d.id || d.n?.toLowerCase().replace(/[^a-z0-9]/g,'_'),
  name: d.n || '',
  flag: d.f || '',
  continent: d.co || '',
  quickTells: d.qt || [],
  languageScript: d.ls || '',
  languageBullets: d.lb || [],
  roadsBullets: d.rb || [],
  roadsScript: d.rs || '',
  landscapeBullets: d.landb || [],
  landscapeScript: d.land || '',
  googleCar: d.car || '',
  carBullets: d.carb || [],
  mixups: (d.mu || []).map(m => ({ country: m.c || '', clue: m.k || '' })),
  extraNotes: d.ex || [],
  images: d.imgs || [],
}));

